[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Game 3"]
[Result "*"]

{ José Raúl Capablanca-Otto Tipal, London 1911 } 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Bg4
{ In view of previous games in which White played Ne5 and this bishop remained passive, Black develops it quickly. }
6. c3 e6 7. h3
{ A good move, forcing the black bishop to commit itself and at the same time opening an escape route for White's own bishop on f4. }
7... Bh5 8. Qb3
{ The usual plan for White  (which remains applicable today)  when Black's bishop is not on c8 is to put pressure on the b7-pawn. Black can do likewise with Qb6, attacking b2. }
8... Qb6 9. Ne5
{ 9.Qxb6  axb6  10.Bb5  was a good alternative, with a slight advantage to White. }
9... Nxe5 10. Bxe5
{ Again it was good to play   10.Qxb6  axb6  11.dxe5  Nd7  12.Bb5 } 10... Nd7
{ It was better to play   10...c4  11.Qxb6  axb6  12.e4  b5  13.g4  Bg6  14.Bxf6  gxf6  15.exd5  exd5  16.Bg2  O-O-O  with possibilities for both sides. White has the better structure, while Black has doubled pawns and a weakness on d5, but the bishop pair and the open character of the position provide more than sufficient compensation. }
11. Bb5 f6 12. Bh2 c4 13. Qa4
{ The pin is unpleasant and the bishop on h5 plays a passive role. } 13... Rd8
14. b3
{ The typical break when Black plays c5-c4. This plan is still considered the correct one today. }
14... a6
{ It was better to play   14...cxb3  15.Rb1 !?   15.axb3  a6  16.Bd3  +=  15...Bg6  16.Rb2   16.Rxb3  Bc2  16...a6  17.Be2  e5  18.Rxb3  Qc7  19.O-O  += }
15. Bxd7+ Rxd7 16. bxc4 Qb2
{ Here it was better to play   16...Bg6  17.e4  dxe4  18.Rb1  Qc6  19.Qxc6  bxc6  20.Rb8+  Kf7  21.Nb3  ± }
17. Rb1 Qxc3 18. g4 b5 { If   18...Bg6  then  19.Rxb7  +- } 19. cxb5 Bg6 20.
bxa6 { An attractive finish; the white pawn will soon queen. } 20... Bxb1
{ If   20...Bc2  then  21.a7  Bxa4  22.a8=Q+  Kf7  23.Qxa4  +- } 21. a7 Bd3 22.
a8=Q+ Kf7 23. Qxd7+ Kg8
{ A blunder, allowing mate in one. It was essential to play   23...Be7  24.Qac6  Qa1+  25.Nb1  Qxb1+   25...Qb2  26.Nc3  +-  26.Kd2  although White still wins. }
24. Qxe6#
{ A good game by Capablanca, illustrating some ideas such as Qb3 and the b2-b3 break, which are still relevant today. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Game 4"]
[Result "*"]

{ Alexander Alekhine-Max Euwe, London 1922.  King's Indian } 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
g6 3. Bf4 { The London System against Black's kingside fianchetto. } 3... Bg7
4. Nbd2 c5 5. e3 d6 6. c3 Nc6 7. h3
{ Providing the f4-bishop with an escape hole in the event of ...Nh5. } 7...
O-O 8. Bc4
{ This is not the usual square for this bishop. These days, against defences such as the Grünfeld or the King's Indian, it is usual to develop it to e2. }
8... Re8 9. O-O
{ Nowadays we would prefer   9.dxc5  dxc5  10.O-O  with a slight advantage to White. }
9... e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5
{ A serious positional error that leaves White with a clear, even decisive, advantage.  It was necessary take with the pawn:   10...dxe5  11.Bh2  += }
11. Bxe5 dxe5 12. Ng5 Be6
{ It was slightly better to play   12...Rf8  13.Nde4  Qxd1  14.Rfxd1  Nxe4  15.Nxe4  although White still has a clear advantage: the black bishop on g7 is out of play, while its white counterpart on c4 and the white knight  (which can go to d6)  , are strong pieces. In addition, White dominates the d-file. }
13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Nde4
{ The doubled pawns and passive bishop add up to a clear disadvantage for Black. White will exploit these in masterly fashion in the endgame. }
14... Nxe4
{ If   14...Qb6  then after  15.Qd6  Nxe4  16.Nxe4  Qxd6  Or   16...Qxb2 ?  17.Rab1  Qc2  18.Rxb7  Qxe4  19.Qd7  and White wins  17.Nxd6  Re7  18.Rad1  White maintains a clear advantage. }
15. Qxd8 Rexd8 16. Nxe4 b6 17. Rfd1 Kf8 18. Kf1 Ke7 19. c4
{ A good move: White fixes the enemy pawns on dark squares, thus restricting the bishop, and clears the third rank for the white rook. We have an endgame of good knight versus bad bishop. }
19... h6 20. Ke2 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Rb8
{ Black cannot exchange rooks because the ending is lost after   21...Rd8  22.Rxd8  Kxd8  23.h4  White will advance with g4-g5, then bring the king to e4 and the knight to f3, with a winning endgame }
22. Rd3 Bh8 23. a4 Rc8
{ If   23...a5  then  24.Rb3 !  and White wins a pawn with the unstoppable threat of Nxc5. }
24. Rb3 Kd7 25. a5 Kc6 26. axb6 axb6 27. Ra3
{ White finally gains a file along which his rook can invade. Black is passive and can only await events. }
27... Bg7 28. Ra7 Rc7
{ Black now offers the exchange of rooks, but White rejects this because he considers, with good judgement, that his rook is better and his advantage greater with the rooks still on the board }
29. Ra8 Re7 30. Rc8+ Kd7 31. Rg8 Kc6 32. h4 Kc7 33. g4 Kc6 34. Kd3 Rd7+ 35. Kc3
Rf7 36. b3 Kc7 37. Kd3 Rd7+ 38. Ke2 Rf7 39. Nc3
{ The game is decided. Also winning was   39.g5  h5  40.Nc3  Re7  41.Nb5+  Kd7  42.Kd3  Kc6  43.Ke4  Rb7  44.Rd8  Re7  45.Rb8  and Black is in zugzwang: if  Rd7  then  46.Re8  and the pawn on e6 falls, with a decisive advantage to White. }
39... Re7 40. g5 hxg5 41. hxg5 Kc6 42. Kd3 Rd7+ 43. Ke4
{ White now has his king active. Black will soon be in zugzwang. } 43... Rb7
44. Nb5 Re7 45. f3 Kd7 { If   45...Kb7  then  46.Nd6+  Kc6  47.Ne8  wins. } 46.
Rb8 Kc6 47. Rc8+ Kd7
{ Again if   47...Kb7  then after  48.Nd6+  Ka7  49.Rd8  Black is once again in zugzwang:  Ka6  50.Ra8+  Ra7  51.Rxa7+  Kxa7  52.Ne8  Bh8  53.Nc7  and White wins. }
48. Rc7+ Kd8 49. Rc6 Rb7 50. Rxe6
{ And Black resigned. A great lesson in strategy from Alekhine, who played well to exploit the opponent's doubled pawns. Up to the 1940s the London System continued to be played by great masters, such as Capablanca and Alekhine. Around 1950 Bondarevsky included it in his repertoire, popularising it in the USSR. We then begin to see this opening in the hands of the elite of the time: Kotov, Smyslov, Ragozin, Bronstein, Keres  (we shall see a game of his from 1959 in Chapter 2)  and various non-Soviet players, such as Larsen and Benko. Also around the start of the 1950s, in South America, the Argentinean player Manuel Pereyra Puebla came on the scene and began to play the London System on a regular basis. Manuel Pereyra was a strong player who gained his greatest successes in correspondence chess but he also had good results over-the-board, although he never played as a professional. Pereyra began to develop new lines and variations that differed from the known lines of the London System, so that for the Argentineans it began to be known as the Pereyra System or Attack. His line of attack gained its greatest successes when Black played the orthodox defence with ...d7-d5 and ...e7-e6: Pereyra developed the plan with Ne5 and h2-h4, followed by the sacrifice Bxh7+, with a decisive attack. He had many followers in Argentina and other strong players employed it on a regular basis, such as Guimard, Bauza, Rossetto, Panno and Bolbochan. Pereyra played his opening for more than forty years until his death in 1998. Pereyra was an International Master of the ICCF  (International Correspondence Chess Federation)  . His highest Elo rating, according to the public archives of the ICCF, was 2321. His last game dates from 1998, but his Elo was acquired a lot earlier, when there were no electronic analysis engines, or only very weak ones, thus his rating corresponds to that of a really strong player. He played in the 11th World Championship Final for correspondence chess, in which he finished in a creditable 7th place out of 17 players. Among the contestants were two former World Correspondence Champions. In an extra chapter in the back of the book we provide further information about him. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Game 5"]
[Result "*"]

{ Manuel Pereyra Puebla-Juan Cassani, cr Argentina 1982 } 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6
3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 e6 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Ne5
{ The early knight jump to e5 was Pereyra's preference, combined with h2-h4 and an attack on the black king, but he also played 7. dxc5 here, which is an interesting alternative. Another idea, which is more normal in our day, is 7. Bg3, so that if Black exchanges on g3 the h-file is opened, while if Black declines the exchange, White reinforces the e5-square with moves such as f2-f4 or Ndf3. }
7... Bxe5
{ Exchanging on e5 so quickly is not Black's best course of action, especially if he has already castled on the kingside. It is more appropriate to play   7...Qc7  8.Ndf3  O-O  9.Bd3  with much play ahead. }
8. dxe5 Nd7 9. Nf3 { The immediate   9.Qg4  was also good. } 9... O-O
{ Here it was better to play 9... h6 or 9... Qc7 } 10. Bd3 Qc7
{ But now this is a decisive error: it is very dangerous for Black when there is a white pawn on e5 and the f6-knight has had to move, because it leaves Black's castled position vulnerable and White has attacking possibilities. Black needed to play 10... h6 or 10... g6. It is White's move now: how should he begin the attack ? }
11. Bxh7+
{ A classic and thematic sacrifice which leaves White with a decisive advantage. The reader should familiarise himself with this idea, which we shall examine in greater depth in the theoretical section. This is the Pereyra Attack in its purest form. }
11... Kh8
{ Capturing the bishop fails to solve the problem:   11...Kxh7  12.Ng5+  Kg6   12...Kg8  13.Qh5  Rd8  14.Qxf7+  Kh8  15.Qh5+  Kg8  16.Qh7+  Kf8  17.Qh8+  Ke7  18.Qxg7+  Ke8  19.Qf7#  13.Qc2+  f5  the only move   13...Kh5 ?  14.Qh7+  Kg4  15.f3#  15. Qh3#; 15. h3#   13...Kh6 ?  14.Qh7#  14.exf6+  Kxf6  15.Nh7+  Kf7  16.Bxc7  winning. }
12. Ng5 { 12.h4  g6  13.h5  also wins. } 12... Ncxe5
{ 12...g6  was the most tenacious move, but after  13.h4  Ndxe5  14.h5  f6  15.hxg6  fxg5  16.Bxg5  the white attack is winning. }
13. Bxe5 Nxe5
{ If   13...Qxe5  then  14.Qh5  Qxg5  15.Qxg5  Kxh7  and White is left with a decisive advantage. }
14. Qh5 g6 15. Qh6
{ It is mate in four. An attractive miniature by Manuel, demonstrating the dangerous attacking possibilities that White can create in this variation. The idea of the sacrifice on h7 should always be kept in mind. Pereyra won many games with such attractive attacks. At the end of the 1970s and the start of the 1980s the system continued to be played by strong players, such as the young Garry Kasparov in 1977. Special mention should be made of the Yugoslav Vlatko Kovacevic, who was one of the greatest specialists in the 1980s and was the author of a book on the London System in 2005. Other compatriots of his, such as Nikolic or Knezevic, have also played it. In Spain, Bellon and Rivas began to play it. Let's look at an example from the young Kasparov. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Game 6"]
[Result "*"]

{ Garry Kasparov-Edvins Kengis, Riga ch-URS U20, 1977 } 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 b6 3.
Bf4 Bb7 4. e3 c5 5. Nbd2 g6 6. c3 Bg7 7. h3 O-O 8. Be2 Nc6 9. O-O d6 10. a4
{ By transposition we have reached a line of the King's Indian. Black can also develop the knight at d7 instead of c6. The thematic move a2-a4 gains space on the queenside. }
10... a6 11. Nc4
{ An interesting idea. Kasparov wants to play a4-a5 at some point to weaken the enemy queenside and if Black then plays ...b6-b5, White could bring the knight to b6. The text move invites Black to advance with ...b6-b5 or ...d6-d5. Alternatives in this position include 11. Bh2 and 11. Re1. }
11... b5 12. Na3
{ This is better than   12.axb5  axb5  13.Qb3   13.Na3  b4 =  13...bxc4  14.Qxb7  Na5  15.Qb5  cxd4  16.cxd4  Qc7  with an equal position. }
12... b4 13. cxb4 Nxb4
{ A dubious move.  It was better to play the natural   13...cxb4  14.Nc4  Na5  15.Nfd2  and the position is equal. }
14. dxc5 Nfd5
{ Kengis enters complications, but even against a young Kasparov this was a risky thing to do. Quieter play follows after   14...dxc5  15.Nc4  although White is better in view of the weakness on c5. }
15. cxd6 Bxb2 16. Bh6
{ Here   16.Bg5  Qxd6  17.Nc4  Qc5  18.Nxb2  was good, when White wins a piece but Black is able to recover it after a long sequence, which would have been difficult to calculate; even so, White emerges with an advantage after  Nc3  19.Rc1  Nba2  20.Rc2  Rfc8  21.Nd3  Qf5  22.Qe1  Nxe2+  23.Qxe2  Rxc2  24.Qxc2  Bxf3  25.Bxe7 }
16... Re8
{ A blunder by Kengis; it was essential to play   16...Nc3  17.dxe7  Qxe7  18.Bxf8  Rxf8  19.Qd2  Bxa1  20.Rxa1  Nxe2+  21.Qxe2  Rc8  and Black has compensation, thanks to the strong bishop on b7. }
17. d7 { The future World Champion does not pass up the opportunity. } 17...
Qxd7 18. Nc4 Bxa1 19. Qxa1
{ White has a clear advantage; he has sacrificed the exchange but has very direct threats against Black's castled position, weakened by the absence of Black's dark-squared bishop. }
19... e5
{ This loses, because White takes on e5 and then the diagonal a1-h8 decides the game,  but   19...f6  would not save Black in any case after  20.e4  Nc7  21.Nb6  The best defence was to return some material with   19...Nf6  20.Nb6  Qf5  21.Nxa8  Bxa8  22.Rc1  but White is left with an advantage, thanks to his pair of bishops, especially the one on h6, which has no opponent. }
20. Ncxe5 Qe6 21. Ng4 f6 { The only defence against the mate on g7 } 22. Bc4
{ The pin by this bishop proves decisive; Black has no satisfactory defence. }
22... Rf8 23. e4 { Black resigned, because after } 23... Qxe4 24. Nxf6+ Rxf6
25. Qxf6
{ he is unable to prevent mate.  By the 1990s many masters were playing the London System, among whom we might single out the English grandmasters Hebden  (the great specialist in the Barry Attack)  and Hodgson, the Czech grandmaster Blatny, who introduced new ideas in some lines, the Serbs Vlatko and Slobodan Kovacevic, and many others, too numerous to mention.  The quantity of games from the middle of the 1990s till the present day has grown exponentially, since there are more and more active players and thus more games played.  Game databases have also played an important role, thanks to the arrival of computers. As we noted at the start of this book, nowadays it is a very popular opening, both among club players and strong masters, who continue to use the London System as an opening which is solid yet does not renounce the struggle to gain an opening advantage.  We now close this brief historical survey with a game featuring a mixture of the London System and the Barry Attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Game 7"]
[Result "*"]

{ Markus Bawart 2330-Manfred Schumi 2260, Austria Bundesliga 1998/99 } 1. Nf3
Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. Nbd2 d5
{ Black renounces the King's Indian setup, which we shall examine in greater detail in Chapter 2. }
5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 b6 7. Ne5 Bb7 8. h4
{ White uses an idea from the Barry Attack, Ne5 and h2-h4, but with the knight on d2 instead of c3, which is its natural post in the Barry. }
8... Nbd7 9. h5 Nxe5
{ This is an error.  Also bad is   9...Nxh5  which leaves White with a decisive advantage after the thematic exchange sacrifice on h5:  10.Rxh5 !  gxh5  11.Qxh5  Nf6  12.Qh4  c5  13.Bg5  Ne4   13...c4  14.Bf5   13...Re8  14.Bh6  Bxh6  15.Qxh6  c4  16.Bxh7+  Nxh7  17.Qh5  Qd6  18.Qxf7+  Kh8  19.Ng6+  Qxg6  20.Qxg6  +-  14.Bxe7  Qc7  15.Nxe4  dxe4  16.Ng4 !  Kh8   16...exd3  17.Nf6+  Bxf6  18.Qg4+  Bg7  19.Bf6  with unstoppable mate  17.Nf6  h6  18.Nxe4  The correct move was   9...c5 !  10.hxg6  hxg6  11.c3  and White's advantage is only slight. }
10. dxe5 Ne4
{ Once again   10...Nxh5  is bad on account of  11.Rxh5 !  gxh5  12.Qxh5  f5  13.exf6  Rxf6  14.Qxh7+  Kf8  15.Nf3  and White has a winning attack.  If   10...Nd7  then  11.hxg6  hxg6  If   11...fxg6  12.Rxh7 !  wins.  12.e6  and White again has a decisive advantage. }
11. hxg6 fxg6
{ Or   11...hxg6  12.Qg4  Re8  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Qh3  e6   14...exd3  15.Qh7+  Kf8  16.Bh6  +-  15.Qh7+  Kf8  16.Bh6  Bxh6  17.Qxh6+  Ke7  18.Bb5  Rg8   18...c6  19.Qh4+  Kf8  20.Qh8+  Ke7  21.Qf6+  Kd7  22.Rd1+  +-  19.Rd1  and White wins. }
12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bc4+ Rf7
{ A sad necessity:  If   13...Kh8  14.Qg4  with the immediate threat of 15. Qxg6. The apparent defence  Qe8  is refuted with the sacrifice  15.Rxh7+ !  Kxh7  16.Qh4+  Bh6  17.Qxh6# }
14. Bxf7+ Kxf7 15. Rxh7
{ White is the exchange and a pawn up, so that the win is now only a question of technique. }
15... Kg8 16. Qxd8+ Rxd8 17. Rh1 Kf7 18. Rd1 Rxd1+ 19. Kxd1 c5 20. Kc1 Bd5 21.
e6+ { Many moves win, such as the quiet 21. a3 } 21... Kxe6 22. Bb8 Kd7 23. Rd1
Kc6 24. Bxa7 Bxa2 { If   24...Be6  then  25.Rd8  with an easy win for White. }
25. Rd8 Be5 26. b3 c4 { If   26...Kb7  then  27.Rd7+  +- } 27. Rc8+
{ Black resigned. After } 27... Kb7 28. Rxc4 Kxa7 29. Ra4+ { White wins. } *

