[White "Introduction"]
[Black "How This Book Is Organized"]
[Result "*"]

{ Following the introduction and our brief historical survey of the opening, the book is divided into chapters according to Black's responses, with the most typical defences being the Indian defences, the Grünfeld, the Benoni etc.  There is also a division according to whether Black plays ...d7-d5 or not. Finally we shall cover Black's less frequent replies. We shall present the material in the form of complete, annotated model games, not only to illustrate the different variations that can arise but also to study the middlegames and endgames.  In the notes to each game we shall cover the theory of the opening and provide brief references to other relevant games. We shall round off the book with sixty thematic exercises, both tactical and strategic, to test the knowledge acquired from reading the book.  The London System can usually be found in the Encyclopaedia of Chess Openings under the codes A45-48, D00-D02 and D10. Finally we should like to thank all the many club players who inspired us to write this book.  @@HeaderStart@@GM Alfonso Romero and FM Oscar de Prado, 2016@@HeaderEnd@@ }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Grünfeld"]
[Black "The London System vs. versus the GrÃ¼nfeld"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 O-O 5. Be2 { 5.Nbd2   5.Bd3 } 5... d5
{ 5...Nh5 } 6. O-O { 6.Nc3   6.h3 } 6... c5 7. c3 Nc6
{ 7...b6   7...cxd4   7...Qb6 } 8. Nbd2 { 8.dxc5 } 8... Qb6
{ 8...b6   8...cxd4 } 9. Qb3 c4 10. Qa3
{ We begin the analysis of the various Indian defences against the London System with the Grünfeld, which is characterised by Black's kingside fianchetto  (... g7-g6)  and the move ...d7-d5. This can be reached via 1... d5 or 1... Nf6.  As we shall see, the presence of the pawn on d5 makes quite an important difference in comparison with the King's Indian, in which Black plays ...d7-d6, since now the advance ...e7-e5 by Black isn't as strong and is less of a worry to White.  In addition, the bishop on f4 has an open diagonal, which increases its power. There are various plans available: White can play c2-c3 and Qb3, or else play c2-c4. Normally the king's bishop goes to e2, which seems best against the lines with ...g7-g6, but White can also develop the bishop to d3, with the idea of advancing with e3-e4.  If Black exchanges on d4 soon and we recapture with the e-pawn, we reach positions from the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann, normally arising from 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4, where now the line with ...g7-g6 is one of Black's options.  Finally White has the option of transposing to the Barry Attack by playing Nc3, which was very popular a few years ago, especially with English players such as Hebden, and which is still played today. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Grünfeld"]
[Black "Game 8 - de Prado Rodriquez vs. Pazos Porta"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 O-O 5. Be2 d5
{ The Grünfeld Defence against the London System.  Instead,   5...d6  would lead to the King's Indian.  If   5...Nh5  a thematic idea, harassing the bishop then  6.Bg5  h6  7.Bh4  g5  and now White emerges in good shape after the alternatives:  8.Nfd2   8.g4 !  Nf6  9.Bg3  Ne4   9...Nxg4  10.h4  ±  10.Nc3   10.h4  Nxg3  11.fxg3   10.Qd3  10...Nxg3  11.hxg3  +=  8...Nf6   8...Nf4  9.exf4  gxh4  10.c3   8...gxh4  9.Bxh5  9.Bg3 }
6. O-O
{ Here   6.Nc3  is also possible, transposing to the Barry Attack, which we shall examine later.  Another alternative is   6.Nbd2  c5   6...Nh5  7.Bg5  h6  8.Bh4  g5  9.Ne5  Nf6  10.Bg3  7.c3  Nc6  8.h3  , while 6. h3 is also playable. }
6... c5
{ Other options for Black on move 6 leave White with some advantage:   6...Bg4 ?!  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Bxf3  c6  9.Nd2  Nbd7  10.c4  +=   6...b6  7.c4  Bb7  8.Nc3  += }
7. c3 Nc6 8. Nbd2
{ The alternative in this move order is to play 8. dxc5 ! a move which we shall also see in the following game. }
8... Qb6
{ The most incisive.  Again   8...b6  is also possible  Also   8...Nd7  9.Qb3  c4   9...e5 !?  10.dxe5  Ndxe5  11.Rad1  +=  10.Qb5  Nf6  11.b3  +=   8...cxd4  9.exd4  will be examined in another game.  Let us consider the critical move   8...Nh5  once more:  9.Bg5   9.dxc5 !?  Nxf4  10.exf4  d4  11.cxd4  Nxd4  12.Nc4  Nxf3+   12...Nxe2+  13.Qxe2  +=  13.Bxf3  Qc7  14.Ne3  Bxb2   14...Qxc5  15.Rc1  Qa5  16.Nd5  +=   14...Qxf4  15.Nd5  +=  15.Rb1  Bg7  16.Qc1  +=  9...h6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Ne1  Nf6  12.Bg3  and now:  cxd4   12...Nd7  13.Bf3  cxd4  14.cxd4  e6  15.Nd3  13.exd4  Bf5  14.Qb3  Qb6  15.Qxb6   15.h3  15...axb6  16.a3  += }
9. Qb3 c4
{ There is no need to fear   9...Qxb3  10.axb3  since White has the better ending, thanks to the half-open a-file and his superior pawn structure on the queenside, e.g.  cxd4  11.exd4  Bf5  12.b4  a6  13.h3  +=  Black has also tried   9...Qa5 !?  10.Rfc1   10.dxc5  Qxc5  11.h3  and   10.Qb5  Qxb5  11.Bxb5  cxd4  12.exd4  are better.  10...Nh5 !?  11.Bg5 ?!   11.Qxd5  11...h6  12.Bh4  g5  13.Bg3 ?   13.Nxg5  hxg5  14.Bxg5  is better for Black but White has some compensation  13...Nxg3  14.hxg3  g4  ∓  Burmakin-Razmyslov, Seville 2012.  If   9...Re8 ?!  then  10.Qxb6  axb6  11.Bc7  Nd7   11...cxd4  12.exd4  Bf5  13.Bxb6  +=  12.a4  +=  Or   9...Bf5 ?  10.h3 ?   10.dxc5  ±  10...cxd4  11.Qxb6  +=  De Prado-Rodriguez, Ferrol 2013. }
10. Qa3
{ White cannot usually play this move in lines where Black has his king's bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal, but here it is possible, with the idea of playing a quick b2-b3 and gaining the advantage on the queenside.  It is also possible to exchange on b6:   10.Qxb6  axb6  and now:  11.Ne5   11.h3  b5  12.a3  Bf5  13.g4  Be6  14.Ne5 =  Thejkumar-Sriram, Chennai 2008   11.b3 !  b5  12.a4  b4 !   12...Ne4  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Nd2  ±   12...bxa4  13.bxc4  dxc4  14.Bxc4  and although the position is equal I prefer White  13.Rfc1  cxb3  14.Nxb3  bxc3  15.Rxc3  Bf5  16.Nfd2  with equality in an interesting position.  11...Nxe5   11...b5  12.Bxe5  Bd7  13.Bf3  Bc6 =  Wang-Li, Tianjin 2001; }
10... Qa5
{ This move is a recent novelty.  Other options include:   10...h6  This move was played against me the previous day by another player belonging to the same team as my present opponent; it would seem that they had prepared this line together.  11.b3   11.h3  g5  12.Bh2  a6  13.b3   13.e4 !  ±  13...cxb3  14.axb3  with a clear advantage to White, De Prado-Ines Prado, Puentedeume 2013.  11...cxb3   11...Nh5  12.bxc4  Nxf4  13.exf4  ±  12.axb3  Nh5  13.Be5  Nxe5  14.dxe5  Qc7  15.c4  Bxe5  16.Nxe5  Qxe5  17.cxd5  Qxd5  18.Nc4  +=  The familiar   10...Nh5  is again possible, and after  11.Bg5    A  11...f6  12.Bh4  and now:   A1  12...g5  A2   12...e5  13.b3  cxb3   13...e4  14.Ne1  14.axb3  g5  15.Bg3  Nxg3  16.hxg3  e4  17.Nh2  f5  18.c4  f4  19.cxd5  fxe3  20.Nc4!  Black now gets three pawns for the piece, but White retains the advantage:  20...exf2+  21.Kh1  Qc7  22.dxc6  Bxd4  23.Rad1  Be5  24.Nxe5  Qxe5  25.Bc4+  Kg7  26.cxb7  Bxb7  27.Rd7+  Kg6  28.Rxb7  Rad8  29.Qxa7  1-0, S.Kovacevic-McMahon, Massy 1993.  13.Ne1!  Keep in mind that White almost always has the possibility of attacking the black knight in order to prevent the capture of the bishop   13.Bg3  Nxg3  14.hxg3  , followed by b2-b3, with the better game for White  13...gxh4   13...Nf4  14.exf4  gxh4  14.Bxh5⩱  B   10...Nh5  11.Bg5  h6  and now:  ()  B1 Taking on e7 leads nowhere:  12.Bxe7  B2   12.Bh4  g5  13.Ne1!  It is important to remember this idea!  13...Nf6   13...gxh4  14.Bxh5   13...Nf4  14.exf4  gxh4  and in both cases I prefer White’s position  14.Bg3  Re8  15.b3  e5  and now:  ()  B21  16.dxe5  B22   16.bxc4  Bf8  17.c5  exd4  18.cxd4  Nxd4  19.exd4  Rxe2  20.Nef3  and the play is complicated, with chances for both sides.  16...Nxe5  17.bxc4   17.Bxe5  Rxe5  18.bxc4  dxc4  19.Nxc4  Qc5  and Black has compensation  17...Nxc4  18.Nxc4  dxc4  19.Bxc4  Ne4=  12...Nxe7  13.Qxe7  Qxb2  14.a3   14.Rab1  Qxa2  15.Ra1  Qb2  16.Rfb1  Qxc3  17.Rc1  Qb2  18.Rab1  Qa2  with a draw  14...Nf6  15.Qb4  Qxb4  16.axb4=  The move   10...Qd8  has also been played:  11.b3   11.Ne5   11.h3  11...b5  12.Qc5  Qb6  The only move  13.Qxb6  axb6  14.a4  cxb3?   14...bxa4  15.bxc4  dxc4  16.Bxc4  reaching the same ending that we saw in an earlier variation; it can be evaluated as equal but I prefer White on account of his structure  15.axb5  ±  Olbrich-Koglin, Dresden 1998. }
11. Qxa5 Nxa5 12. b3
{ Implementing White's thematic idea of breaking quickly on b3.  Other good options were   12.Ne5 !  Bf5  13.g4  Be6  14.b3  +=  And   12.Rfe1 !  Bf5  13.Ne5  Rac8  14.g4  Be6  15.g5  += }
12... Bf5 { If   12...cxb3  then  13.axb3  += } 13. Ne5
{ There is no advantage in   13.bxc4  Nxc4  14.Nxc4  dxc4  15.Bxc4  Rac8  16.Bb3  Rxc3  and Black is at least equal.   13.Rfe1  was also interesting. }
13... Rac8 { 13...Nh5  14.Bxh5  gxh5  15.e4  += } 14. bxc4 dxc4 15. Rfc1
{ White can maintain the advantage with   15.Bf3 !  The idea is to create a strong centre, while the knight on a5 remains passive, defending the pawn on c4. A possible continuation is  Nd7  16.Nxd7  Bxd7  17.Rab1  b6  18.h3  The idea seen earlier of   15.g4  Be6  16.e4  is also good. }
15... Ne4
{ The Houdini engine prefers   15...Nd5  16.Bg3  Bxe5 !?  a difficult move for a human player to make  17.Bxe5  Bd3  18.Bf3  with equality, although after  Rfd8  19.e4  Nf6  20.h3  I prefer White. }
16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. f3 Bxe5
{ This move is now necessary.  After   17...Bf5  18.e4  Be6   18...f6  19.Nxc4  Nxc4  20.exf5  gxf5  21.Rab1  +=  19.d5  Bxe5  20.Bxe5  Bd7  21.Rab1  White has a clear advantage. }
18. fxe4
{ At first it seemed best to take on e5:   18.Bxe5  Bd3 !  19.Bxd3   19.Kf2 =  19...cxd3  20.d5  Nc4  21.Bd4  and I thought now the pawn would soon fall, but this is not the case. Black has the advantage here:  e5   21...d2  22.Rd1  Rfd8  23.e4  e6  24.dxe6  fxe6  =+  22.dxe6  fxe6  23.f4   23.Bxa7  b6  23...b6  24.Rd1  d2  =+ }
18... Bxf4 19. exf4 b5
{ After the exchanges we have reached this position, where White is better, thanks to his strong centre and the fact that the bishop is superior to the knight. }
20. Rcb1
{ Here there were better moves, such as   20.Rab1  a6  21.e5  Rb8  22.Rd1  e6  23.Bf3  Or   20.e5  e6  21.Bf3  with a comfortable advantage to White in both cases. }
20... Rb8 21. a4
{ This move is dubious;  I considered only a tactical idea that would lead to the win of a pawn and an exchange sacrifice. Instead,   21.e5  maintains the advantage, as does 21. Rb2 +/=. }
21... Nb3 22. Ra2
{ My first idea was to sacrifice the exchange, which looked promising, but concrete analysis does not support this. After   22.Rxb3  cxb3  White has two ways to take the pawn:  23.axb5   23.Bxb5  Rfc8 !  24.c4  Rxb5  25.axb5  Rxc4  26.Rb1  Rb4  27.Kf2  Rxb5  28.Ke3  a5  29.Kd2  a4  and this ending should be winning for Black.  23...Rfc8 !  24.Rc1   24.c4  was my original idea, but this fails to  b2  25.Rb1  Rxb5 !  -+  24...b2  25.Rb1  Rxc3  26.Rxb2  a6  ∓ }
22... Rfc8
{ A blunder caused by time pressure.  Black could equalise with   22...b4 !  23.cxb4   23.Bxc4  Na5  24.Bb5  bxc3  25.Rd1 =  23...Rxb4   23...Rfc8  24.Bxc4  Rxc4  25.Rxb3  Rxd4  26.Rb7  Ra8  27.Rxe7  Kf8  28.Re5  Re8  29.Rxe8+  Kxe8  30.Kf2  Rxe4 = }
23. axb5 Rxb5 24. Rab2
{ Returning the favor.  White could retain his clear advantage with   24.Rd1  Black will be unable to defend his weaknesses on a7 and c4, whereas White maintains a good pawn structure in the event of:  Rc7   24...Rb7  25.Ra4  Rbc7  26.Kf2  ±   24...Ra5  25.Rxa5  Nxa5  26.Ra1  Nb3  27.Rxa7  ±  25.Kf2  ±   25.Ra4 }
24... Ra5 { 24...Nc1 ?  25.Rxb5  Nxe2+  26.Kf2  Nxc3  27.Rb8  and White wins. }
25. Bxc4
{ Finally White wins a pawn, but this is not sufficient to gain the advantage in the rook ending.  It was better to play   25.f5  gxf5  26.exf5  Kg7  +=  Or   25.Kf2  += }
25... Rxc4 26. Rxb3 Ra2
{ One black rook is active on the seventh rank and the other one putting pressure on c3, meaning that White is unable to exchange a pair of rooks without losing a pawn. The game should now be a draw. }
27. h3 a5 28. Rc1 Re2 { Or   28...a4  29.Rb8+  Kg7  30.Rb7  a3  31.Ra7 = } 29.
e5 Ra4 30. c4 Raa2 31. Rg3 Kf8 32. c5
{ Or   32.d5  Rec2  33.Rxc2  Rxc2  34.Ra3  Rxc4  35.Rxa5  Rxf4 = } 32... e6 33.
c6 Rac2 34. Rxc2 Rxc2 35. Ra3 Rxc6 36. Rxa5 Rc4 37. Ra8+ Ke7 38. Ra7+ Ke8
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw that it is not essential for White to play h2-h3, although it is simpler to play with h2-h3 to prevent the lines with ...Nh5.  The idea of Qa3 ! is very 39 interesting, taking advantage of the absence of the black bishop from the a3-f8 diagonal. Black gains some space with ...c5-c4, but with the thematic break b2-b3 White either gains some advantage or else reaches a very comfortable endgame.  The idea of ...Qa5 does not appear to be unpleasant for White, who is able to maintain some advantage at no risk. }
*

