{ Tomasz Markowski, 2558-Grzegorz Gajewski, 2653 Chorzow ch-POL 2013  (7) } 1.
d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c3
{ An interesting move order, aimed at preventing some of Black's lines with c7-c5 and a quick Qb6. }
3... g6 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2
{ The variation that we shall see in this game is even better for White with the inclusion of the move h2-h3:   6.h3  c5  7.Nbd2  Nc6  to avoid this line Black should play Qb6 first  8.dxc5 !  and now  a5   8...Re8  9.Bb5 !  Nd7  10.Nb3 !  a6   10...e5  11.Bg3  +=  11.Be2   11.Ba4 !?  +=  11...e6  12.Bd6  +=  Alcaraz Ortega-Cruz Lledo, Cullera 2012   8...Ne8 !?  Morozevich's move  9.Be2  Nc7  and now:  The right move is  10.Bh2 !   10.Nb3 ?  e5  11.Bh2  a5 !?   Black could now regain the pawn with the simple  11...Qe7=  12.a4  Qe7  13.Bb5  +=  Jadrijevic-Morozevich, Zurich 2009  10...e5   10...Ne6  11.Nb3  ±  and it is not clear how Black is going to regain the pawn. If  a5  12.a4 !  11.O-O  Ne6  12.b4  ±  Again it is not easy for Black to regain his pawn, since if  e4  13.Nd4  with a clear advantage to White;   8...Nd7  9.Nb3  e5  10.Bg5  Nf6   10...f6 ?  11.Qxd5+  11.Bb5  h6  12.Bh4  g5   12...Re8  +=  13.Bg3  Ne4  14.Bxc6 ?   14.Bh2  ±  14...Nxg3  15.Bxb7  Bxb7  16.fxg3 =  P.S.Nielsen-H. Olsen, Copenhagen 1993;   8...Nh5 ?!  9.Bh2  f5 ?!  10.Bb5  f4  11.exf4   11.O-O  ±   11.e4  ±  11...Nxf4  12.Bxf4  Rxf4  13.Qe2   13.O-O  13...e5  Sedlak-Brenjo, Vrnjacka Banja 2013.  9.a4  Nd7  10.Nb3  e5  11.Bg3   11.Bg5 !  as we shall see in another game, it is better to move the bishop to g5 rather than g3  Nf6  12.Bb5  Qc7  13.O-O   13.Bh4  Be6  14.O-O  +=  Ghane Gardeh-Mallahi, Iran Championship 2000.  Also good is   13.Nfd2 !  +=  13...Be6  14.Nbd2 ?!  Nd7 =  Pomes Marcet-Lautier, Terrassa 1991;  11...e4  12.Nfd4  Be5  13.Bxe5  Ndxe5  14.Bb5  Qg5  15.Kf1  Rd8  16.Ne2  Nc4  17.Nbd4 ?!   17.Qc2 !  +=  17...Nxb2  Garcia Palermo-Adorjan, Germany Bundesliga 1989/90; }
6... c5 7. Nbd2 Nc6
{ To prevent the line in the game, Black should play   7...Qb6  right away. }
8. dxc5
{ In this move order, this capture is not only possible but good, since even though it gives up the centre and allows Black to play e7-e5, the pawn is not easy to regain for Black, because White has moves such as b2-b4 or Nb3. It also contains the idea of Bb5, to put pressure on e5, so I recommend this capture, which furthermore could well take the opponent by surprise. }
8... a5
{ A move to prevent b2-b4 or deter Nb3, in view of the reply a5-a4.  Here   8...Re8  9.O-O  e5  has also been played, and now:  10.Bg3   10.Bg5 !  we have already seen in the analysis of the line with h2-h3 above  (the game Pomes Marcet-Lautier)  that it is better to move the bishop to g5 rather than g3  10...h6  11.Bxf6  Qxf6  12.e4 !  Be6   12...d4  13.Rc1  +=  13.exd5   13.Qb3 !  +=  13...Bxd5  14.Bc4  Ne7   14...Rad8 !  +=  15.Re1  ±  Megaranto-Chu Wei Chao, Shijiazhuang 2013  10...a5  11.Qa4   11.Bb5 !  +=  again this is a thematic idea to put pressure on the c6-knight and attack e5  11...Bd7  12.Bb5  Qe7  13.Nb3  Ne4  14.Rfd1  Nxc5  15.Nxc5  Qxc5  16.e4  d4  Miles-Lautier, Ohrid 2001;  Perhaps the best move is   8...Nh5 !?  which works best when White has not played h2-h3:  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Nd4  e5  and now  12.Nb5 !   12.N4b3  Nf6  13.Bg3  Bf5  14.h4  with a complicated position. Black has a fine pair of centre pawns, but White is a pawn up.  12...gxh4   12...Nf6  13.Bg3  +=   12...b6 !?  13.Bxh5  gxh4  14.c4  +=  13.Bxh5  Be6  14.Nd6  b6  15.c4  bxc5  16.cxd5  Bxd5  17.N2c4  and White has the advantage, on account of his better pawn structure and strong knight on c4; }
9. a4 Nh5
{ Here   9...Re8  has been played, but this is inferior on account of  10.Bb5 !  again we see this move, fighting for the e5-square   10.Bg5  h6  11.Bxf6  Bxf6  12.O-O  e5  13.e4  +=   13.Qb3  ±  Vojinovic-Ziaziulkina, Athens 2012  10...Nh5  11.Bg5  h6  12.Bh4  Bf5   12...g5 ?  13.Nd4  ±  again this thematic move, to prevent Black from being able to exchange Whites dark-squared bishop without making some concession  13.O-O  ±  Torre-Vidit, Subic Bay 2009. }
10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 g5
{ 11...b6 !?  is a thematic idea in some variations. It sacrifices a pawn to open the b-file, but in this position it does not work very well because of  12.cxb6 !  better than   12.Nb3  bxc5  13.Nxc5  Qb6  14.Qxd5  Rd8  which gives Black excellent compensation.  Also good is   12.Bb5 !  Na7  13.c6  Qc7  14.O-O !  e5   14...Nxc6  15.Bxc6  Qxc6  16.Bxe7  +=  15.Rc1  Nxc6  16.c4 !  d4  17.c5 !  ±  12...Qxb6   12...g5  13.Nd4  Nxd4  14.cxd4  gxh4  15.b7  Bxb7  16.Bxh5  +=  13.Nd4  Nxd4  14.cxd4  g5   14...Qxb2  15.Bxe7  ±  15.Bxg5  hxg5  16.Bxh5  Qxb2  17.Rb1  Qa2  18.Qb3  Qxb3  19.Rxb3  with advantage to White. }
12. Nd4
{ The thematic idea against the persecution of the bishop with h7-h6 and g7-g5. It is important to always remember this idea, which can involve the knight moving to various different squares, such as d2, e1, e5 or d4, as in this game, which shows another advantage of playing 8. dxc5 !. }
12... gxh4
{ If   12...Nf6  then  13.Bg3  with a healthy extra pawn and a clear advantage to White. }
13. Bxh5 e5
{ If   13...Nxd4 !?  White can play:  14.exd4   14.cxd4  e5  15.Nb3   15.dxe5  Bxe5  16.O-O  Bxb2  17.Rb1  Bg7  18.Bf3  +=  15...Qg5  16.g3  exd4  17.Nxd4  Bxd4  18.gxh4  Qxh4  19.Qxd4  Qxd4   19...Qxh5  20.Rg1+  20.exd4  with advantage to White;  14...b6   14...e5  15.dxe5  Bxe5  16.O-O  ±  15.c6  Qc7  16.O-O  Qxc6  17.Re1  += }
14. Nb5 { White has a clear advantage in this position. } 14... Qe7 15. O-O
{ White completes his development. If Black takes the pawn on c5, White wins the one on d5. Here   15.Nd6  Be6  16.e4  dxe4   16...d4  17.O-O  17.Qe2  +=  also looks interesting.   15.Nb3  Be6  16.O-O  ±  is also good. }
15... Be6
{ Inferior is   15...Qxc5  16.Nc7  Rb8  17.Nb3  Qd6  18.Nxd5  with a clear advantage to White. }
16. e4
{ Opening up the game right now does not seem best. Instead,   16.Nb3  was the best move, and White maintains a clear advantage, while it is not clear whether Black will be able to regain the pawn. If  Rad8  17.Bg4  f5  18.Bh3  Rd7  19.Re1  ± }
16... Rad8 17. exd5
{ Another error. It was better to play   17.Bg4 !  Qxc5   17...dxe4  18.Bxe6  Qxe6  19.Qe2  ±  18.Bxe6  fxe6  19.Qg4  += }
17... Rxd5 18. Bf3
{ White has lost the thread of the game and starts to play badly; 18. Qe2 maintains equality. }
18... Rxc5 19. Qe2 f5
{ What a reversal ! The black pieces are now extremely active; the rook on c5, the bishop pair and the two strong pawns on e5 and f5 mean that the black position is now to be preferred. }
20. Qe3 Bf6
{ An interesting move, which creates complications. The natural 20... Rd8 was good. }
21. Rfd1
{ It was possible, although risky, to take the pawn:   21.Qxh6 !?  Bg5  22.Qg6+  Kh8  23.Bxc6 !   23.Qh5+  Kg7  =+  with the threat of 24Rh8  23...bxc6   23...Rxc6 ?  24.Nf3  ±  24.f4 !?   24.Nf3  Bf4   24...Bf6  25.Qh6+  Kg8  26.Qg6+  Qg7  27.Qxg7+  Kxg7  28.Nc7  Bc8  25.b4  Rc4  26.Rfe1 !   26.Qh5+  Kg7  27.Nxh4  Bxh2+  -+  26...cxb5  27.Nxe5  Bf7  28.Qxf5  Bxe5  29.Rxe5  Bg6  30.Rxe7  Bxf5  31.axb5  axb4  32.cxb4  Rxb4  and White has sufficient compensation.  24...Bf6 !   24...exf4  25.Rae1 !  +=   24...Bxf4  25.Rxf4  exf4  26.Qh6+  Kg8  27.Qg6+  and perpetual check.  25.Na3  e4  =+ }
21... e4
{ It was slightly better to play   21...Bg5 !  22.Qe2  e4  23.Bh5  h3  with a clear advantage to Black. }
22. Be2
{ Another error. It was essential to play   22.Bh5  Bg5  23.f4  exf3  24.Qxf3  Re5  although Black is still better. }
22... Bg5 23. Qh3
{ The queen is very insecure here.   23.f4  exf3  24.Qxf3  Bd5  25.Qf1  h3  also gave Black a clear advantage, but this was the lesser evil. }
23... Ne5
{ Black now has an almost decisive advantage; the white pieces are very passive. }
24. Nd4 Bc8 25. f4
{ Desperation, in view of the threat of 25... f4, winning the white queen;  If   25.c4  e3  -+  but not   25...f4 ?  26.Qc3 }
25... Bxf4
{ The white position is in ruins and Black won without any problems in a few more moves. }
26. N2b3 Rc7 27. Nb5 Ng4 28. Rf1 Bxh2+ 29. Kh1 Bg3 30. N3d4 Nf2+ 31. Rxf2 Bxf2
32. Nxc7 Qxc7 33. Rf1 Qg3 34. Bc4+ Kh8 35. Ne6 Bxe6 36. Bxe6 e3
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@It is a good idea for White to take with 8. dxc5 in the variation with Nc6. For Black it is better to play 7. Qb6 first. With the move order involving an early h2-h3 instead of Be2, the capture on c5 is even better for White.  It is not easy for Black to regain the pawn, although White temporarily gives up the centre. Remember that the white bishop should go to g5 and not g3 when Black plays e7-e5.  The manoeuvre Nd4 is key when Black plays g7-g5. Another good idea is Bb5, to attack the c6-knight and put pressure on e5. To defend the pawn on c5, remember the moves b2-b4 and especially Nb3.  In this game White had a clear advantage but then lost the thread and ended up losing the game. }
*

