[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Grünfeld"]
[Black "Game 9 - Markowski vs. Gajewski"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c3
{ An interesting move order, aimed at preventing some of Black's lines with c7-c5 and a quick Qb6. }
3... g6 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3 O-O
{ The variation that we shall see in this game is even better for White with the inclusion of the move h2-h3: }
6. h3 c5 7. Nbd2 Nc6 { to avoid this line Black should play Qb6 first } 8. dxc5
{ and now } 8... Ne8 { Morozevich's move } 9. Be2 Nc7
{ and now: The right move is } 10. Bh2 e5 11. O-O Ne6 12. b4
{ Again it is not easy for Black to regain his pawn, since if } 12... e4 13.
Nd4 { with a clear advantage to White; } *

