[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Grünfeld"]
[Black "Game 10 - Grachev vs. Rakhmanov"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 d5 6. h3
{ In this game we see White playing h2-h3, completely ruling out all Black's lines with Nh5, trying to hunt down the bishop. Knowing in which variations it is appropriate to play h2-h3 or not is one of the keys, because against certain defences playing an early h2-h3 can be bad, since it wastes time. }
6... c5 7. c3 Qb6
{ The alternative is   7...Nc6  which will normally transpose:  8.Nbd2   8.O-O  8...Qb6  9.Qc1   9.Qb3  9...Bf5  10.O-O  Rfc8  11.Nb3   11.dxc5  11...Ne4  12.Nfd2 ?   12.Rd1  12...cxd4  ∓  Eljanov-Kramnik, Moscow blitz 2008. }
8. Qb3 Nc6
{ Also played here is   8...c4  9.Qa3  Re8   9...Bf5 !?  10.b3  cxb3  11.axb3  Rc8  12.c4  +=   9...Qd8  transposes to the game.  10.b3  Bf8  11.Qb2   11.Qc1  +=   11.Ne5  +=  11...a5  12.Nbd2  a4  13.O-O  Nc6  +=  Zowada-Jasnikowski, Katowice 1995. }
9. Nbd2 c4 { After   9...Qxb3  10.axb3  b6  11.O-O  White is a bit better. }
10. Qa3
{ Again this is the best way to fight for the advantage. White can also exchange queens, but this is more drawish.  One of the specialists in this system, Grachev, has tried the dubious   10.Qc2 ?!  Bf5  11.Qc1  Qa5   11...Rac8   11...Ne4  12.Nxe4  Bxe4  13.O-O  Qd8   11...Nd7  =+  12.O-O  b5  Grachev-Kramnik, Moscow blitz 2008.  Practice has also seen   10.Qxb6  axb6  11.O-O   11.Ne5  b5  12.a3  11...b5  12.a3  Re8   12...Bf5  lets look at a couple of interesting examples of this endgame:  13.Rfe1   13.g4  Be6  14.Ne5  Nd7  15.Nxd7  Bxd7  16.Bf3  e6  17.Bd6  Rfd8  18.e4  Bh6  19.Rad1  Be8  20.Bg3  +=  Thejkumar-Sriram, Chennai 2008  13...h6   13...Ne4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.Nd2  Bf5  16.Bf3  Rad8  17.e4  dxe4  18.Nxe4  e5  19.dxe5  Nxe5  20.Nf6+  +=  14.g4  Be4  15.Bh2  Rfe8  16.Rad1  Rad8  17.Nxe4  Nxe4  18.Nd2  +=  Nf6   18...Nxd2  19.Rxd2  e6  20.Bf3  f5  21.Kg2  19.Bf1 =  Kosic-Pavlovic, Herceg Novi 2001;  13.Bh2   13.Ne5   13.Rfe1  13...Ra6  14.Rfe1  h5 =  Apicella-Nyzhnyk, Haguenau 2013; }
10... Qd8
{ The black queen retreats, in order to allow b7-b5 in support of the c4-pawn, an idea which is Blacks best defence, as we can see from other variations such as   10...Bf5  11.b3  cxb3   11...Qa5 !?  12.Qxa5  Nxa5  13.g4  Be6  14.Ne5  +=  12.axb3  +=  The opening of the a-file favours White, as well as enabling him to continue with c3-c4 or b3-b4, as appropriate, e.g.  Nd7 ?!  13.g4 !  Be4  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Nd2  with a clear advantage to White, Kolev-Laylo, Las Vegas 2008. }
11. b3 b5 12. O-O
{ After   12.bxc4  bxc4   12...dxc4 ?!  13.Qb2  +=  13.Rb1  Bf5  14.Rb7  +=  I prefer White, in view of his control of the b-file. The difference is that the bishop on f4 denies the b8-square to the black rooks, whereas the f5-bishop can be dislodged with g2-g4 and so it is not easy for Black to contest the b-file. 12. Qb2 is also a good option, preparing a2-a4. }
12... Nd7
{ A dubious move. The best defence was   12...Bf5  although White maintains the advantage:  13.g4   13.Qb2  is another good option, preparing a2-a4:  Qd7  14.a4  a6  15.Ra2  +=  13...Bd3   13...Bd7  14.Ne5  +=   13...Be6  14.Qb2  +=  14.Bxd3  cxd3  15.c4  bxc4   15...Qb6  16.Rac1  +=  16.bxc4  dxc4  17.Nxc4  +=  White stands better, due to the weakness of the d3-pawn; }
13. bxc4 bxc4
{ It is not good for Black to recapture with the d-pawn:   13...dxc4 ?  14.Rab1   14.Qb2  e5  15.Bg3  a6  16.a4  Rb8  17.Rfb1  14...e5   14...a6  15.Rxb5  axb5  16.Qxa8  15.dxe5  in all cases with a clear advantage to White. }
14. e4
{ Grachev decides to open the centre immediately but perhaps it made more sense to wait and improve the position of his pieces with   14.Qa4 !  Bb7  15.Rab1  Nb6  16.Qb5  +=  which gives White a comfortable advantage: he has control of the b-file, his pieces are more active and he can break with e3-e4 at an opportune moment. }
14... e6
{ Better is   14...Nf6 !  15.exd5   15.e5  Ne8  15...Nxd5  16.Bh2  Qa5  17.Qxa5  Nxa5  18.Rfc1  Bh6 !  19.g4  Bf4 !  20.Bf1  Ba6  and it seems that Black is holding, but White maintains his advantage. }
15. Qd6
{ There were several moves leading to an advantage for White, such as 15. Rab1, 15. Rfe1 or 15. Bd1. }
15... Ndb8
{ Another dubious move and a very passive one. It was better to play   15...Bb7  16.exd5  exd5  17.Rfb1   17.Qxd5 ?  Nxd4  =+  17...Nb6  18.a4  although White retains the advantage. }
16. Qxd8
{ Simplifying into a favourable endgame, but this was not forced. White could also gain a clear advantage with moves such as   16.exd5  exd5  17.Rfe1   16.Rab1   16.Rfe1  The position is so healthy that it allows White a wide range of good moves. }
16... Rxd8 17. Rfb1
{ It was better to move the bishop immediately with 17. Bd1 !, because the rook can go to either the e-file or the b-file. It is clear that the bishop should head for a4, so it was better to move it right away. }
17... Ba6
{ After   17...Nd7  18.Bc7  Re8  19.Bd1 !  heading for a4, maintains Whites advantage }
18. Bd1
{ The alternative   18.exd5  exd5  19.Nf1 !  Nd7  20.Ne3  was a good idea; the knight is better on e3, putting pressure on d5 and c4, and White retains his advantage. }
18... Nd7 19. exd5 exd5 20. Ba4 Rac8 { How should White continue ? } 21. Bb5
{ A good idea, even though it appears that we are exchanging the opponent's bad bishop. The idea is to attack d5 and gain the square b7 for the rooks. It should be mentioned that 21. Re1 was also possible, with advantage to White. The poor contribution of the black bishops is worth noting. }
21... Bxb5 22. Rxb5 Nf8 23. g4
{ This move is not good because it weakens both the f4-square and the knight on f3, which will prove important later. Instead, a good continuation was   23.Bh2  Ne6  24.Rb7  Re8  25.Nf1  Bh6  26.Rb5  Rcd8  27.Ne3  Bxe3  28.fxe3  with a slight advantage to White. }
23... Ne6
{ Black equalises with this move, because there are also some tactical ideas present. }
24. Bg3
{ It was better to play   24.Be3  a6  25.Rb7  Rb8  26.Rab1  Rxb7  27.Rxb7  Rb8  with equality.  How should Black play now ? }
24... Rd7
{ A pity; Black misses a good tactical opportunity with   24...Bxd4 !  25.cxd4  Ncxd4  26.Rb7   26.Nxd4  Nxd4  27.Rb7  transposes  26...c3  27.Nxd4  Nxd4  28.Nb3  Ne2+  29.Kg2   29.Kf1  Nxg3+  30.fxg3  d4  =+  29...d4  and Black is at least equal. The black pawns are dangerous. }
25. Re1 { 25.Rab1  is better, preventing the sacrifice. } 25... h6
{ Another wasted opportunity. Here   25...Bh6 !?  was interesting  but the sacrifice on d4 was still good:   25...Bxd4 !  26.cxd4  Ncxd4  27.Ne5  Nxb5  28.Nxd7  Nbd4  with very good compensation for Black. }
26. Nf1
{ 26.Kg2  defending f3, was necessary, to prevent the sacrifices on d4. } 26...
Kh7
{ Once again Black lets slip the tactical resource of the sacrifice on d4, which this time even gives Black the advantage after   26...Bxd4 !  27.Rxe6   27.cxd4 ?  Nexd4  28.Nxd4  Nxd4  and Black wins, with the double threat of taking the b5-rook and forking the e1-rook with a check on f3  27...fxe6 !  much better than   27...Bxf2+  28.Kxf2  fxe6  29.Ne5  Nxe5  30.Bxe5  Rf7+  31.Ke2  Rcf8  with a complex position  28.cxd4   28.Nxd4  Nxd4  29.cxd4  c3  =+  28...c3  29.Rb3  c2  30.Bf4  Rf7  31.Bc1  Rxf3  32.Rxf3  Nxd4  and Black is better. }
27. Kg2
{ Finally preventing the sacrifice by defending f3. Here 27. Ne3 was also good. }
27... Bf6 28. Ne3 Rcd8 29. Nc2
{ 29.h4 !  was the best move for White, gaining a clear advantage: it prevents g6-g5 and threatens g4-g5 or h4-h5, as appropriate. The idea is to gain the e5-square later. }
29... Re8 30. a3
{ White wants to play Nb4 and force Black to capture, in order to improve the white structure after axb4 and open the a-file for the rook. }
30... Be7 31. Nb4 { Again   31.h4  ±  was good. } 31... Bxb4 32. axb4
{ White has improved his structure: he has the half-open a-file and can put pressure on the a7-and d5-pawns. However, at the moment his rook on b5 has no moves. }
32... f6 33. Ra1 Kg7 34. h4
{ Finally White decides to make this advance, which is a natural one in the position, although now it is not as strong as before. }
34... Kf7
{ 34...g5 !  was absolutely necessary for Black and although White maintains the advantage, it is not easy to see how he is going to make progress. }
35. Ra6 Rc8 { In this position White has a very strong move what is it ? } 36.
g5 { White sacrifices a pawn in order to gain the e5- or c5-square. } 36...
hxg5 37. hxg5 Nxg5
{ Black cannot take with the pawn or advance with f6-f5 on account of the combination on c6: if   37...fxg5 ?  38.Rxc6 !  Rxc6  39.Ne5+  winning the rook on c6. }
38. Nxg5+ fxg5 39. Rc5
{ This rook, which was active but could not move, is finally liberated, with decisive effect. }
39... Ne7 40. Be5
{ Despite being a pawn down White has a clear advantage; his bishop dominates the knight and Blacks pawns are weak. The black king can come under attack from the rooks and the bishop. }
40... Rf8 41. Rca5 Ra8
{ If   41...Nc8  42.Rf6+  Ke8  43.Rxg6  with a decisive advantage to White. }
42. Ra1 { Here   42.Kg3  Rb7  43.Kg4  Rd7  44.Kxg5  was a simpler way to win. }
42... Rb7
{ Black does not sense the danger and makes another error. It was necessary to play   42...Rad8  43.Rh1  Rf8  although White retains a clear advantage. }
43. Rh1
{ There was an immediate win with   43.Rf6+ !  Ke8   43...Kg8  44.Rh1  +-  44.Rh1 !  Kd7  45.Rd6+  Kc7  46.Rxg6+  Kd7  47.Rd6+  Kc7  48.Re6+  Kd7  49.Rxe7+  Kxe7  50.Rh7+  Ke6  51.Rxb7  +- }
43... Rb6 44. Rha1 { White again applies pressure to the a-pawn. } 44... Nc8
{ 44...Rxa6  45.Rxa6  fails to ease the defence. White can win, either by bringing his king to g5, or by playing b5-b6 to capture on a7. }
45. R6a5 Ke6 46. Re1 Nd6 47. Bxd6+
{ Here   47.Bg3+  Kf7  48.Rxd5  +-  was also winning. } 47... Kxd6 48. Re5
{ The black pawns are about to fall like ripe fruit. } 48... Rf8 49. Rxg5 Kc7
50. Rgxd5 Rbf6 51. Ra2
{ It was better to play   51.Rxa7+ !  Kc6  52.Rc5+  Kb6  53.Ra2 } 51... Kb6 52.
Rc5
{ And, faced with the loss of another pawn, Black resigned.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw that the line in which White plays h2-h3 has some advantages, especially by preventing any Nh5 ideas by Black.  We also saw that after Black plays c5-c4 White's best plan is to respond quickly with b2-b3, while Black's best defence is to play Qd8 and support c4 with b7-b5, although White maintains some advantage: his bishop on f4 is better than the one on g7 throughout the game and he can use the b- and e-files for his rooks.  It is also worth noting the manoeuvre Bd1, with idea of bringing the bishop to a4 and then exchanging it for the opponents bishop. }
*

