[Black "Game 11 - Keres vs. Bronstein"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. Nbd2 d5 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 c5 7. O-O
{ Nowadays it is more common to play   7.c3  first. } 7... cxd4
{ This exchange can be made now or on the following move, after 7. Nc6. It was also possible to play   7...Qb6  taking advantage of White's move order, since he cannot respond with Qb3; then a possible continuation is  8.dxc5   8.Qc1   8.c4 !?  are playable  8...Qxb2  9.Be5  with equality. }
8. exd4 Nc6 9. c3 Nh5
{ Blacks idea is to gain control of the f4-square and neutralise the strong white bishop. It is less common for Black to play for e7-e5, because this leaves the d-pawn weak after the exchange on e5  (one cannot have everything)  .   9...Bf5  is an alternative tried by the strong grandmaster Nepomniachtchi recently; lets take a look at it:  10.Re1   10.a4  a6   10...Nh5 !?  11.Be3  Nf6   10...Qb6 !?  11.h3  Ne4  12.Re1  Rc8  13.Bf1  Qb6  14.Qb3  Qxb3  15.Nxb3  Shimanov-Nepomniachtchi, Warsaw Ech blitz 2011;   10.h3 !  looks best to me. After  Ne4  11.Re1  h6   11...Rc8  12.Bf1  +=  12.Bf1  g5  13.Bh2  e6  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.Nd2  White had the advantage and managed to win the game:  Bg6  16.Nb3  Qe7  17.f4 !?   17.a4 !  +=   17.Bb5  +=  17...Be4  18.fxg5   18.Qd2  +=  18...hxg5  19.Nc5  +=  Vl.Kovacevic-Mikhalchishin, Pula 1980.  10...Rc8  11.Ne5 ?  This move, which is an error   11.Nf1  or  11.Qb3  are better  , was recommended by grandmaster Danielsen in a DVD on the London System; I suspect that he had this game in mind. My advice is to trust no-one 100% and check all the variations for oneself. Danielsen gives  Nd7 ?!  Black could already force a draw with   11...Nxd4 !  but this passed unnoticed by Danielsen:  12.cxd4  Bc2  13.Qc1  Bf5  14.Qd1  Bc2  and the white queen can escape only by returning the piece and remaining a pawn down  12.Nxc6  Rxc6  +=  Zilberman-Kantsler, Tel Aviv ch-ISR 2002;  An idea which has hardly been tested but which is interesting is   9...Re8  10.h3   10.Re1  10...Qb6   10...Nh5  11.Bh2  Bh6  12.Re1  Bf4  13.Ne5  +=  11.b4   11.Qb3  +=  11...Bf5  12.a4  Rac8  13.a5  Qd8  14.a6  b6  Saud-Yang Jiunn, Singapore 1995 }
10. Be3
{ White takes advantage of the exchange of pawns on d4 to use the e3-square, which is usually occupied. The disadvantage is that White has to abandon the h2-b8 diagonal, which is key in the London System for White's dark-squared bishop. }
10... Qc7
{ Bronstein's original idea is also the first choice of Houdini, 54 years later ! It would appear that the masters of the past were not at all bad players and were able to work things out in their heads without the electronic aids available to us today, for which they deserve great credit.   10...Qd6  11.Re1  has also been played here:  Bd7   11...Nf6  12.h3  Bd7  13.Nb3  b6  14.Qc1  +=  This plan is very common in such positions, lining up the queen and the bishop, either to play Bh6 and exchange the bishop on g7 or else to return the bishop to f4;   11...f5 !?  is a risky move; the idea is to trap the white bishop with f5-f4, but it creates some weaknesses:  12.Nb3  f4   12...b6  13.Bd2  +=  13.Bd2  and now:  Kh8   13...b6  14.c4 !  opening the position, despite leaving the d4-pawn isolated  e6   14...dxc4  15.Bxc4+  Kh8  16.d5  ±  15.cxd5  exd5  16.Ne5  +=  Nxe5 ?  17.dxe5  Qxe5  18.Bf3  Qf5  19.Bb4  and White wins;   13...Nf6  14.c4 !  again we see that opening the position is advantageous for White and the isolation of the d4-pawn is unimportant;  dxc4   14...Kh8  15.Rc1  Rb8  16.Na5  and now:  Nxa5   16...Bg4  17.cxd5   17.a3 !  +=  17...Nxd5  18.Nc4   18.Nxc6  bxc6  19.Ne5  Bxe2  20.Qxe2  Bxe5  21.dxe5  Qe6  18...Qd8  Winants-Kobese, Turin ol 2006.  17.Bxa5  dxc4   17...b6  18.c5 !  18.Bxc4  b6  19.Bc3  +=  15.Bxc4+  Kh8  16.Rc1  ±   16.Ng5 !?  14.Bd3  Bg4  15.Be2  Rae8  +=  Turov-Burmakin, Moscow 1994;  12.Nb3  Nf6  13.Nc5  +=  Kachko-Deviatkin, Moscow 2007;  Retreating the knight should not be ruled out: after   10...Nf6  11.Ne5  Bf5  12.h3  Qc7  13.Ndf3  Ne4  14.Bf4  the position is unclear; both sides have strong knights. }
11. Re1 Bg4
{ With the passing of the years, Black has tried to improve on Bronstein's play, for example with   11...Nf6  and now:  12.h3   12.g3 !?  is an interesting idea to enable the bishop to return to f4:  Bg4  13.Bf4  Qd8  14.Ne5  Bxe2  15.Nxc6   15.Qxe2  e6  16.h4  Rc8  17.Ng4   17.Nd3  b6  18.Bg5  is interesting  17...Nxg4  18.Qxg4  Re8  19.Nf3  Qf6   19...h5  20.Nh2   20.h5 !  +=  20...Qf5  21.Qf3   21.Qxf5  +=  21...h5  22.Re2 ?  Bxd4  23.cxd4  Nxd4  24.Qe3  Nxe2+  25.Qxe2  e5  -+  Renner-Gyimesi, Germany Bundesliga 2010/11.  15...Bxd1   15...bxc6  16.Rxe2  +=  16.Nxd8  Raxd8  17.Raxd1  e6  with equality;  12...Bf5  13.Nb3  b6  this idea is thematic, to prevent the white knight from occupying c5;  Black has also tried   11...a6  12.Nb3  Nf6   12...b6  13.Qc1 !  +=  13.Nc5   13.Qc1 !?  13...Bf5   13...b6  14.Nd3  14.h3   14.Bd3 !  Bxd3  15.Nxd3  e6  16.Bf4  +=  with great control of the e5-square  14...Nd7  15.Nd3  Bxd3  16.Qxd3  +=  Pinheiro-Frois, Lisbon 1996. }
12. Nb3
{ Here it was good to put the question to the bishop with   12.h3  to sound out Black's intentions, because it seems that if he takes on f3 White stands better:  Bd7  perhaps Bronstein was intending to play this, since h3 can be a weakness, and then fight for the f4-square; but after   12...Bxf3  13.Nxf3  Rac8   13...Nf4  14.Bf1  14.Qd2  and White is better.  13.Nf1   13.Nb3  13...Nf4  14.Qd2  Nxe2+  15.Rxe2  Rfe8  16.Bf4  Qb6  17.Ne3  e6  18.Ng4  White has a strong initiative on the kingside; }
12... Nf4
{ Black has completed the plan started with Nh5: placing the knight on f4, where it has both defensive and offensive functions and in particular restricts the activity of the white bishop on e3. But now White springs a surprise. }
13. Bb5
{ With the unpleasant threat of winning the pawn on e7 after the exchanges on c6 and f4; it is not easy for Black to find a good move now. }
13... Nh5
{ Bronstein decides to retreat, acknowledging his error.  I think that it was better to defend the pawn another way, such as   13...Bf6  14.h3  Bf5   14...Bxf3  15.Qxf3  ±  15.Bxc6   15.Nc5  Ne6  16.Nxe6  Bxe6  17.Qd2  +=  15...bxc6  16.Bxf4  Qxf4  17.Nc5  Qd6  and we have a very interesting situation with a knight pair vs. a bishop pair, which seems slightly better for White, with his strong knight on c5.  Sacrificing the pawn with   13...a6  14.Bxc6  bxc6  15.Bxf4  Qxf4  16.Rxe7  Rfe8  seems to offer Black counterplay, but in fact White stands better in the endgame arising after  17.Rxe8+  Rxe8  18.h3  Bxf3  19.Qxf3  Qxf3  20.gxf3  Re2  21.Rb1  Bf8  22.Kf1  Re8   22...Rc2  23.Na1  ±  23.Na5  Rc8  24.b4  +=  with good winning chances, since the knight is better than the bishop and also White has an extra pawn. }
14. h3 Bd7 { 14...Bxf3  15.Qxf3  is also advantageous to White. } 15. Qc1
{ It is better to play   15.Nc5  +=  immediately. } 15... Rfe8 16. Bh6
{ The thematic idea of exchanging the fianchettoed bishop usually favours the attacking side. }
16... Bh8
{ Black evades the exchange, although this was not necessary; it seems better to play   16...b6  preventing the knight from landing on c5. }
17. Bf1
{ A slightly odd move; instead White could play   17.Qd2  maintaining the advantage. }
17... Rad8 18. Nc5 Nf6
{ At this point I am in some doubt, because in some sources I have seen that Bronstein is supposed to have played   18...Bf5 ?  here, which loses a pawn after  19.g4  in which case Keres declined it !  Here   18...e5  would fail to  19.Nxd7  Qxd7  20.g4  Nf6   20...e4  21.gxh5  exf3  22.Qf4  ±  21.Nxe5  Nxe5  22.Rxe5  with a clear advantage to White. }
19. b4
{ Gaining space on the queenside. As we can see, it is necessary to play on both wings to try to create weaknesses over the whole board.  Instead,   19.Bf4  Qc8  20.b4  also looks good. }
19... Bf5 20. Nh4
{ Keres decides to dislodge the black bishop immediately. Again  20.Bf4  was good. }
20... Bd7 { Black has no plan and awaits events. } 21. Bf4
{ Now Keres finally decides to return with the bishop and dislodge Blacks queen.  21.Nf3  was not bad either. }
21... Qc8 22. g4
{ Keres goes over to the attack on the kingside, relying on his clear advantage in space, although it seems that the quiet continuations  22.Nf3  and  22.Bh2  were better. }
22... h5 23. f3 hxg4 24. hxg4 Nh7
{ Another great defensive move by Bronstein. Now the knight can go to f8 and e6. It also controls g5 and allows a timely f7-f6, to deny the e5-square to the white pieces. The position is now equal. }
25. Nd3 Bf6
{ Here   25...a5  was good for Black:  26.a3  rather than   26.b5  Nxd4 !  27.cxd4  Bxd4+  28.Be3  Bxa1  29.Qxa1  Bxb5  which seems slightly better for Black  26...b6  or 25... Nf8 immediately. }
26. Ng2 Nb8 { Again   26...b6  was better, with equality. } 27. a4
{ Playing on both wings to create weaknesses is an important concept, because in that case the opponents pieces can end up awkwardly placed after going to the defence of one wing or the other, or they can simply be unable to arrive in time to defend.  Here   27.g5  Bg7  28.Ne3  +=  was also good. }
27... Na6 28. Ne3 Nc7 29. Bg2 { 29.Be2  +=  seems slightly better. } 29... Bh4
30. Re2 b5
{ A radical move to restrain White's queenside pawns; this move is approved by the Houdini engine, which considers this to be the best move. White was threatening to advance his pawns with a4-a5 or b4-b5. }
31. a5
{ It is bad to play   31.axb5  Bxb5  Or   31...Ne6  The critical move was   31.Bxc7  Qxc7  32.Nxd5  Qd6  33.Ne3  Bg5   33...bxa4  34.Nc4  ±  34.Qe1  a6  and Black has to prove that he has sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
31... Ne6 32. Bh2 Bc6
{ The bishop was fine on d7, where it controlled the h3-c8 diagonal.  It was better to play   32...Nf6  33.Qc2  += }
33. Qc2
{ Now or within the next few moves it would have been good to play the thematic advance   33.f4 !  Bf6  34.Qc2  ± }
33... Bf6 34. Ne5 Bb7 35. Rf1 Nef8
{ It seems better to play   35...Nhg5 !  and Black is holding. } 36. Qd3
{ Once again   36.f4 !  is good. } 36... Ng5 37. f4 Ne4
{ This jump is badly timed. The only way was  37...Bxe5  38.dxe5  Ne4  39.f5  Not   39.Nxd5  Bxd5  40.Bxe4  Bc4  and Black wins  e6  40.fxg6  Nxg6  and although the position is complicated, Black can resist. }
38. Nxd5 Nd6
{ This loses, but after   38...Bxd5  39.Bxe4  White remains with a healthy extra pawn.  The best try was   38...Bxe5  39.Rxe4  Bxd5  40.Rxe5  Bxg2  41.Kxg2  Qxg4+  42.Bg3  and although White retains the advantage, this is not yet decisive. }
39. Ne3
{ 39.f5  was much more direct and decisive: if  g5   39...gxf5  40.gxf5  opening the position even more, seems even worse  then  40.Rfe1  with a winning advantage. }
39... Bxg2 40. Rxg2 Bg7 41. g5 { 41.f5  was again better. } 41... Qb7
{ Black had to play   41...e6  since it was essential to prevent f4-f5. } 42.
f5 { White's advantage is almost decisive. } 42... Qe4 43. Qxe4 Nxe4
{ The exchange of queens fails to solve Black's problems. } 44. Rg4
{ It was slightly better to play   44.Nc6  Rd7  45.Ng4  Nxg5   45...gxf5  46.Rxf5  +-  46.Nge5  +- }
44... Nxc3 45. f6 Bh8
{ Or   45...exf6  46.gxf6  Bh8   46...Bh6  47.Nf5  47.Rh4  transposing to the game. }
46. Rh4
{ This move decides the game, setting up threats of N3g4 and Nh6+, or Rxh8+ and Nxf7+. We can see that the white attack remains very strong even without the queens. The passivity of the h8-bishop, the f8-knight and the e8-rook is noteworthy. }
46... exf6 47. gxf6 Rxd4 48. N3g4
{ There is no satisfactory answer to the threat of 49. Nh6+.  Instead   48.Rxd4 ?  was bad because of  Ne2+ }
48... g5 49. Rh5
{ A little more precise was   49.Rh3  Ne2+  50.Kh1  Nd7  51.Nh6+  Kf8  52.Nxd7+  Rxd7  53.Ng4  Kg8  54.Rf5  and wins. }
49... Rxe5 { 49...Ng6  50.Rxg5 } 50. Nh6+ Kh7 51. Nf5+ Kg8
{ 51...Kg6  52.Rh6# } 52. Ne7+ Rxe7 53. Rxh8+ Kxh8 54. fxe7
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we have seen another defensive system for Black based on exchanging pawns on d4 and with the idea of Nh5 and Nf4, to fight against White's queen's bishop.  It is a solid system, although White maintains good options of playing on both wings. It is notable that both players were amongst the best in the world in 1959, which adds to the importance of the game.  I liked Keres's treatment, based on attacking on both wings. He was able to decide the game with an attack on the king, even without the queens. Bronstein was on the defensive, without a clear plan. At various points he made good defensive moves, such as 22. h5, 24. Nh7 and 30. b5, although after that he went astray.  In the variation with 10. Qd6 it is worth noting White's plan of c3-c4, opening the position despite leaving the d-pawn isolated.  It is always advisable to check the analysis, even of great players, since it can contain errors or omissions. }
*

