{ Black's idea is to gain control of the f4-square and neutralise the strong white bishop. It is less common for Black to play for e7-e5, because this leaves the d-pawn weak after the exchange on e5  (one cannot have everything)  . }
10. Be3
{ White takes advantage of the exchange of pawns on d4 to use the e3-square, which is usually occupied. The disadvantage is that White has to abandon the h2-b8 diagonal, which is key in the London System for White's dark-squared bishop. }
10... Qc7 11. Re1 Bg4
{ Here it was good to put the question to the bishop with } 12. h3
{ to sound out Black's intentions, because it seems that if he takes on f3 White stands better: }
12... Bxf3 13. Nxf3 Rac8 14. Qd2 { and White is better. } *

