[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Grünfeld"]
[Black "Game 11 - Keres vs. Bronstein"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. Nbd2 d5 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 c5
{ Nowadays it is more common to play } 7. c3 { first. } 7... cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6
9. O-O Nh5
{ Black's idea is to gain control of the f4-square and neutralise the strong white bishop. It is less common for Black to play for e7-e5, because this leaves the d-pawn weak after the exchange on e5  (one cannot have everything)  . }
10. Be3
{ White takes advantage of the exchange of pawns on d4 to use the e3-square, which is usually occupied. The disadvantage is that White has to abandon the h2-b8 diagonal, which is key in the London System for White's dark-squared bishop. }
10... Qc7 11. Re1 Bg4
{ Here it was good to put the question to the bishop with } 12. h3
{ to sound out Black's intentions, because it seems that if he takes on f3 White stands better: }
12... Bd7
{ perhaps Bronstein was intending to play this, since h3 can be a weakness, and then fight for the f4-square; but after }
13. Nf1 Nf4 14. Qd2 Nxe2+ 15. Rxe2 Rfe8 16. Bf4 Qb6 17. Ne3 e6 18. Ng4
{ White has a strong initiative on the kingside; } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Grünfeld"]
[Black "Game 12 - Bauer vs. Edouard"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Nbd2
{ Another possible move order is   5.Be2  O-O  6.h3  c5  7.c3  b6  8.O-O  Bb7  9.b4 !?   9.Nbd2  is normal.  9...cxb4 ?!  9... Ne4 and 9... c4 are better.  10.cxb4  Nc6  11.Qb3  with a slight advantage to White in Burmakin-Nabaty, Schwäbisch Gmünd 2014. }
5... O-O 6. h3
{ Another move order would be   6.Be2  c5  7.c3  Nc6   7...b6  8.O-O  Bb7  8.O-O  b6  We could use the move order seen in the first game, without h2-h3, but for most club players I recommend playing h2-h3 to avoid having to study the lines with Nh5. }
6... c5 7. c3 b6 { A flexible move, retaining the option of Nbd7. } 8. Be2
{ In this move order, 8. Bd3 is playable. This has the advantage of controlling e4, although as a rule of thumb in the London System the bishop goes to d3 only in the lines without g7-g6 by Black, since it is stronger on d3 when the b1-h7 diagonal is open. Against the King's Indian it is not usually advisable to develop the bishop on d3, because after Black advances with e7-e5, he threatens e5-e4, and if White exchanges pawns on e5 Black recaptures with the pawn  (the d6-pawn)  , renewing the threat. Here, though, 8. Bd3 is playable, since although Black will be able to execute the e7-e5 advance he will not be able to recapture on e5 with a pawn. }
8... Bb7
{ It is quite normal to develop the knight to d7, although there are more games with the bishop on d3 rather than e2, which we shall see later in another game. After   8...Nbd7  9.O-O  Bb7  better than   9...Ne4  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Nd2  Bb7  12.Qc2  with advantage to White  The most popular move here is  10.Ne5  although after   10.Qb3  has not been played much, but it is interesting and thematic in many variations. Also, since Black has already played b7-b6, the white knight has no future on b3, so the queen can go there.  Rc8  11.a4  a6  remember that if Black closes the centre with   11...c4  White should play  12.Qa3 !  planning the thematic b2-b3, with advantage to White.  12.Rfd1  e6  13.Rac1  and White is a bit better, although the black position is solid.  The best move is considered to be   10.a4 !  which is thematic, gaining space on the queenside and with the idea of a4-a5.  a6  is the best response; Black is preparing to close the queenside by answering a4-a5 with b6-b5. Now there is a wide range of possibilities for White.  Again it is dubious to play   10...Ne4 ?!  because of  11.a5 !  Nd6  12.Ne5  +=  11.Ne5  The move   11.b4  was introduced by Atanas Kolev, but it is too direct and Black can equalise easily with  Ne4 !  In the game Kolev's opponent played   11...cxb4  12.cxb4  Ne4  13.Rc1  Rc8  14.Qb3  Nxd2  15.Nxd2  e5 !  but Kolev managed to win in Kolev-Ivanova, Plovdiv 2011;  12.Qc2   12.Rc1  c4  12...cxb4  13.cxb4  Rc8  14.Qb2  e6   11.Qb3 !  is again good and is my recommendation, as in the note to move 10 above. If  Rc8  we have a transposition.  It is also possible to play   11.Rc1  Rc8  12.Qb3   11.Qb1  is interesting and has the advantage over 11. Qb3 that White can play a quick b2-b4, although the downside is that the rooks are not connected:  Rc8  12.Rd1   12.Re1  12...e6  13.Ne5   13.b4  13...Qe7  14.Bf3   14.Nxd7  Nxd7  15.Nf3  14...Nxe5  15.Bxe5  Rfd8  Certic-Cabrilo, Belgrade 2011.  11...Nxe5  12.Bxe5  Nd7  13.Bxg7  Kxg7  leads to an equal position; there are a few interesting practical examples, but White gains no advantage:  14.a5   14.f4 !?  e6  15.Qe1  Qe7  16.Qg3  Nf6  17.h4  h5  18.Qg5  Rae8  and again Black has no problems, Kekelidze-Mulyar, Wheeling 2013.  14...b5  15.dxc5  Nxc5  16.Nb3  Na4   16...Nxb3  17.Qxb3  Qc7  18.Qb4  Rac8  19.Rad1  e6  20.h4  h5  21.Rd2  Qc5  Sedlak-Andrijevic, Valjevo 2012  17.Nc5   17.Qd2  17...Nxc5  18.Qd4+  e5  19.Qxc5  Rc8  and Black drew without any problems in Meins - Perez Candelario, Kallithea 2008;  10...Nxe5  11.Bxe5  Ne8  Or   11...Nd7  Black has easy equality, which is why I do not recommend this;  The move   8...Ba6 !?  is interesting.It is a very typical idea in several openings to exchange Black's theoretically bad queen's bishop for the good white bishop. It is playable here as well, but White remains slightly better:  9.Bxa6   9.O-O  Qc8   9...Bxe2  10.Qxe2  Nc6  11.b4 !  +=  cxb4  12.cxb4  Nxb4 ?  13.Qb5  ±  Nc2  14.Rac1  Na3  15.Qa6  Nc4  16.Nxc4  dxc4  17.Rxc4  ±  10.Re1   10.Rc1  +=   10.b4  +=  10...Nc6  11.Ne5   11.Rc1  +=  11...Bxe2  12.Qxe2  Qb7  Nguyen Anh-Lalic, Elista ol 1998.  9...Nxa6  10.O-O  Qc8   10...Nc7  11.Qe2   11.a4  +=   11.Qb3  +=  11...Qb7  12.a4  Rac8  13.Rfe1  Rfd8  Vafiadis-Ipatov, Rethymnon 2011; }
9. O-O Nc6
{ We have already examined variations with the move 9. Nbd7 in the note at move 8.   9...Nfd7  has been tried by Bologan:  10.b4 !   10.Re1  Nc6  11.Qb3  h6   11...e5 !?   11...c4  12.Qc2  e5   11...Qc8  12.Rad1  Rd8  13.Bg3  e6  14.Rc1  Ba6  15.Qd1  Bxe2  16.Qxe2  Qb7  17.e4  Rac8  18.exd5  exd5  19.Nb3  - Ribli-Adorjan, Hungary tt 1995/96  12.a4  a6 ?  13.Qxd5 !  and despite White's clear advantage here the game ended in a draw, Mouroutis-Bologan, Eretria tt 2011.  10...c4  11.a4  a6  12.Qc2  is good, with the idea of e3-e4, which is thematic when Black plays c5-c4  worse is the immediate   12.e4  dxe4  13.Ng5  Nf6  14.Bxc4  Nd5  with equality.  12...Nf6  13.b5  a5  14.Ne5  with advantage to White; }
10. Qb3
{ Many moves have been tried here, although this seems the best. The queen on b3 is natural for White, who threatens to take on c5 and also puts pressure on d5 to prevent Nd7. White also seeks to provoke c5-c4 or weaken Black on the queenside.  Grandmaster Danielsen recommends   10.Ne5  here, but I think that Black can equalise with  Nxe5 !  The continuation given by Danielsen is   10...Nd7  11.Nxc6  Bxc6  12.Nf3  e6   12...Qc8  13.Bg3  a5  14.a3  a4  15.Re1  Qb7  16.h4  Rfe8  17.h5  e5  Pakleza-Bartel, Warsaw ch-POL 2010   12...Re8  is better  13.a4  a6 ?!  14.b4  and Danielsen evaluates this as advantageous to White, which I do not see after 14c4 or 14Qe7.  11.Bxe5   11.dxe5 ?!  Nd7  =+  11...Ne8  and this well-known idea levels the position  Another idea is   10.a4  Nd7   10...Ne4  11.Qb3  e6 ?!   11...e5 !?   11...c4  12.Qa3  e5  12.Rad1   12.Bd6  c4  13.Qa3  Re8  14.b3  +=  12...Rc8  Bodiroga-Balogh, Rijeka Ech 2010.   10.Rc1  has also been played, for instance  a6  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.Qb3  Qc8  13.Rfd1  +=  Tu Hoang-Hossain, Calvia ol 2004. }
10... Qc8
{ Defending against Whites threat to capture on c5, Black guards the b7-bishop and now also has the idea of Ba6 available, exchanging his bad bishop. Instead, 10Nd7 transposes to the games by Bologan and Adorjan  (above)  . }
11. Rfd1 Ba6
{ Here   11...Nd7  is playable, with the idea of e7-e5, since now White cannot capture the d5-pawn, as the bishop on b7 is defended  12.h4 !?  is a typical plan for White:   12.a4 !  is better and now if  e5  then  13.dxe5  Ndxe5   13...c4  14.Qa2  Ncxe5  15.Nxe5  Nxe5  16.a5  +=  14.Nxe5  Bxe5   14...Nxe5  15.a5  +=  15.Qxd5  Bxf4  16.exf4  Nd4  17.Qc4  Bd5  18.Qd3  Nxe2+  19.Qxe2  Re8  20.Qg4  and White is better with his extra pawn.  12...e5  13.dxe5  Ndxe5  14.h5 !   14.Nxe5  Nxe5  15.a4   15.h5  Qf5  15...Re8  16.a5  d4  14...Qe6   14...Qf5  15.Nh4  15.Nxe5  Nxe5  16.Nf3  += }
12. Bxa6 Qxa6 13. a4
{ We can say that White has emerged slightly better from the opening, despite the exchange of bishops. As is usually the case, the bishop on f4 is better than its counterpart on g7, which is normally condemned to play a passive role. White controls the square e5 and can make progress on the queenside, where he now threatens 14. Qb5 }
13... Qc8
{ To avoid the unpleasant 14. Qb5 by White. Black has managed to exchange the bishops but has lost a few tempi with his queen. }
14. Rac1
{ In spite of everything it was still good to play   14.Qb5 !  Nd7  if   14...c4  15.b3 !  a thematic break which should be familiar to us by now  cxb3  16.Nxb3  +=  15.e4 !  dxe4  16.Nxe4  cxd4  17.cxd4  and White is better here, with the threat of 18. Rc1, and after  Qb7  18.d5  Nce5  19.Nxe5   19.Nd4  is also good, with a future Nc6 in the air  19...Nxe5  20.Rac1  and now the natural idea of  Rac8  is answered with  21.Nc5 !  Qa8  22.Na6  when White threatens 23. Nb4 and 24. Nc6. }
14... c4 15. Qa3
{ Now   15.Qb5  does not work, unlike in the previous variations, since Black can play  Qb7  with the threat of 16a6.  If   15.Qc2  instead, then  Na5  and now  16.e4 ?!  fails to  Nxe4  17.Nxe4  Qf5 !  with the better game for Black. }
15... a6
{ Rather than weakening b6 like this, it was better to play   15...Qb7  16.b3  cxb3  17.Qxb3  Rac8  with the idea of Nc6-a5-c4. }
16. b3 { Correct ! The thematic break that we need to remember. } 16... b5
{ After this, cxb3 will be bad, since after Qxb3 White is left with a clear advantage, in view of the weakness of the b5-pawn. How the position can be changed by a pawn move ! Before advancing a pawn and changing the structure, we should always remind ourselves that pawns cannot move backwards. }
17. axb5
{ A small inaccuracy by Bauer. It was simpler to play   17.bxc4  bxc4  18.Rb1 !  with a clear advantage to White. The position would then be similar to the one in Game 3 between Grachev and Rakhmanov, where we saw that White was better, owing to of his control of the b-file: the bishop on f4 prevents the black rooks from going to b8 and contesting the b-file. Unfortunately for Black, here he has no light-squared bishop to hinder White from playing his rook to b1. The other rook can go to e1 and then White can play e3-e4, which will leave the c4-pawn weak. }
17... axb5 18. Qc5 Qa6
{ It was better  (although difficult to see)  to play   18...Rd8 !  since after  19.Qxb5  Ra5  20.Qb6  Ra6  21.Qc7  Qa8  Black is going to incarcerate the queen, although White obtains compensation after  22.Bg3  e5  23.Nxe5  Nxe5  24.dxe5  Rc8  25.Qe7  Bf8  26.Qxf6  Rxf6  27.exf6  cxb3  28.Nxb3  Qa4  with a position that is difficult to assess. It is clear that White has compensation but there is no reason why Black should lose. }
19. Ra1
{ A good move: at first glance it looks as though it would be good for Black to give up his queen for two rooks, but this is not the case. It was also possible to play 19. Ne5, with advantage to White. }
19... Qb7
{ Edouard realises that it is not good to take on a1, and he retreats. If   19...Qxa1  20.Rxa1  Rxa1+  21.Kh2  Na5  and now:  22.bxc4 !  this is the right way   22.Qxb5 ?!  Nxb3  23.Nxb3  cxb3   23...Rb1  24.Nfd2  Rb2  25.Nxc4  dxc4  26.Qxc4  +=  24.Qxb3  Rfa8  22...Nxc4  23.Nxc4  bxc4  24.Qxe7  and White has a clear advantage, because the d5-pawn  (and subsequently the c4-pawn)  is weak and will fall after Qd6 and Be5. }
20. bxc4 Rxa1
{ 20...bxc4  21.Rab1  Qc8  22.Rb6  Ra6  23.Qb5  Rxb6  24.Qxb6  with advantage to White, owing to his control of the b-file, his more active pieces and the eventual break on e4. }
21. Rxa1 bxc4 22. Rb1 Qd7 23. Rb6 Rc8 24. Qb5
{ These last few moves are natural and almost forced. White has improved all his pieces and Black is defending as best he can. With his last move White threatens 25. Rb7 and also pins the knight, leaving a possible Ne5 in the air. }
24... e6
{ Black defends the d5-pawn, which in some lines would be left unguarded after the piece exchanges resulting from White's Ne5. }
25. Rb7
{ On this and the following move Bauer lets his advantage slip. Here   25.g4  was good, gaining space on the kingside and maintaining the advantage. Remember the importance of playing on both wings to create weaknesses in the opponents camp. If  Qe8  then  26.g5  Nh5  27.Bh2  += }
25... Qe8 26. Ng5
{ It was better to play   26.Rb6  but now Black is not worse. } 26... Nd8
{ A good defensive move, since after the forced exchange of queens Black equalises. }
27. Qxe8+ Nxe8 28. Ra7 h6 29. Ngf3 Nc6 30. Ra6 Nf6 31. g4 Nd7
{ Whites advantage is merely optical. Black has no weaknesses and his position is solid. }
32. Kg2 f5 { Safer was   32...g5 } 33. Kg3 Kf7 34. Ng1
{ It is important to remember that we should not relax, simply because the position appears to be dead and risk-free. Similarly, it is dangerous to keep playing all-out for a win, just because we previously held the advantage. This move is bad and it could have turned the game on its head. Correct was   34.g5  h5  with equality. }
34... Nf6
{ Black wastes his opportunity to punish the opponents error with   34...e5 !  which would give him the advantage after  35.dxe5   35.Bxe5  Ndxe5  36.dxe5  Bxe5+  37.Kg2  Bxc3  ∓  35...g5 !  when Black wins a piece for two pawns and has winning chances, e.g.  36.Kg2   36.e6+  Kxe6  37.gxf5+  Ke7  -+  36...gxf4  37.exf4  fxg4  38.hxg4  Nc5  and although the win is not easy with so little material left, and Whites connected passed pawns are dangerous, still the black position is preferable. }
35. f3 Ng8 36. Ne2 Nge7 37. Bd6 Rd8 38. Bxe7 Nxe7 39. Nf4 Rb8
{ The simple   39...e5  40.Ne6  Rb8  was good, with equality. } 40. Kf2
{ If White takes the pawn with   40.Nxe6  then after  Rb2  41.Nf1  Bf6  Black has compensation in the activity of his rook and the bad position of the knight. }
40... Rb2 41. Ke2 e5 42. Ne6 exd4
{ Here   42...f4 !?  would have been more unpleasant for White, e.g.  43.Nxg7  fxe3  44.Kxe3  exd4+  45.cxd4   45.Kxd4  Rxd2+  -+  45...c3  46.Ne6  c2 !  47.Nb3  Rxb3+  48.Kd2  Rxf3  49.Kxc2  g5  and White still has to solve a few problems.  worse is   49...Rxh3  50.Nf4  Rh2+  51.Kc3  h5  52.g5  and White is holding, thanks to the plan of Nf4-d3-e5+. }
43. exd4 Rc2 44. Nxg7 Kxg7 45. Ra3 Rc1 46. f4 Rh1 47. Ra7 Kf8 48. Ra8+ Kg7 49.
Ra7 Kf8
{ Black cannot avoid the draw. If   49...Kf7  then  50.Nf3  Rxh3  51.Ne5+  Kf8   51...Ke8 ?  52.Ra8+  +-   51...Ke6 ?  52.Ra6+  +-  52.Nd7+  Kf7  53.Ne5+ = }
50. Ra8+ Kg7 51. Ra7
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In the variation with b7-b6 Black has two options: to develop the knight to c6 or d7. The typical plan for Black of exchanging his light-squared bishop on a6 does not guarantee him equality.  The best plan for White is to play Qb3 and a2-a4, trying to create weaknesses on Blacks queenside. Remember the typical break with b2-b3 after c5-c4 by Black.  An advantageous plan is to exchange pawns on c4 and then occupy the b-file with the queens rook; Black cannot contest the b-file, because the bishop on f4 prevents Rb8; the other white rook can go to the e-file and the plan with e3-e4 is then always in the air.  We advise you never to relax, even though the position appears completely safe; White could have been made to suffer for his careless 34. Ng1.  As we saw, there were resources even in a very equal position, where it seemed that neither player could lose. }
*

