1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. h3 c5 7. c3 b6
{ A flexible move, retaining the option of Nbd7. } 8. Be2
{ In this move order, 8. Bd3 is playable. This has the advantage of controlling e4, although as a rule of thumb in the London System the bishop goes to d3 only in the lines without g7-g6 by Black, since it is stronger on d3 when the b1-h7 diagonal is open. Against the King's Indian it is not usually advisable to develop the bishop on d3, because after Black advances with e7-e5, he threatens e5-e4, and if White exchanges pawns on e5 Black recaptures with the pawn  (the d6-pawn)  , renewing the threat. Here, though, 8. Bd3 is playable, since although Black will be able to execute the e7-e5 advance he will not be able to recapture on e5 with a pawn.   It is quite normal to develop the knight to d7, although there are more games with the bishop on d3 rather than e2, which we shall see later in another game. After }
8... Nbd7 9. O-O Ne4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. Qc2
{ with advantage to White } *

