1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. h3 c5 7. c3 b6
{ A flexible move, retaining the option of Nbd7. } 8. Be2
{ In this move order, 8. Bd3 is playable. This has the advantage of controlling e4, although as a rule of thumb in the London System the bishop goes to d3 only in the lines without g7-g6 by Black, since it is stronger on d3 when the b1-h7 diagonal is open. Against the Kings Indian it is not usually advisable to develop the bishop on d3, because after Black advances with e7-e5, he threatens e5-e4, and if White exchanges pawns on e5 Black recaptures with the pawn  (the d6-pawn)  , renewing the threat. Here, though, 8. Bd3 is playable, since although Black will be able to execute the e7-e5 advance he will not be able to recapture on e5 with a pawn. }
8... Bb7 9. O-O
{ We have already examined variations with the move 9Nbd7 in the note at move 8. }
9... Nfd7 { has been tried by Bologan: } 10. b4 c4 11. a4 a6 12. Qc2
{ is good, with the idea of e3-e4, which is thematic when Black plays c5-c4 }
12... Nf6 13. b5 a5 14. Ne5 { with advantage to White; } *

