1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. h3 c5 7. c3 b6
{ A flexible move, retaining the option of Nbd7. } 8. Be2
{ In this move order, 8. Bd3 is playable. This has the advantage of controlling e4, although as a rule of thumb in the London System the bishop goes to d3 only in the lines without g7-g6 by Black, since it is stronger on d3 when the b1-h7 diagonal is open. Against the Kings Indian it is not usually advisable to develop the bishop on d3, because after Black advances with e7-e5, he threatens e5-e4, and if White exchanges pawns on e5 Black recaptures with the pawn  (the d6-pawn)  , renewing the threat. Here, though, 8. Bd3 is playable, since although Black will be able to execute the e7-e5 advance he will not be able to recapture on e5 with a pawn. }
8... Bb7 9. O-O Nc6 10. Qb3
{ Many moves have been tried here, although this seems the best. The queen on b3 is natural for White, who threatens to take on c5 and also puts pressure on d5 to prevent Nd7. White also seeks to provoke c5-c4 or weaken Black on the queenside. }
10... Qc8
{ Defending against Whites threat to capture on c5, Black guards the b7-bishop and now also has the idea of Ba6 available, exchanging his bad bishop. Instead, 10Nd7 transposes to the games by Bologan and Adorjan  (above)  . }
11. Rfd1 Ba6 12. Bxa6 Qxa6 13. a4
{ We can say that White has emerged slightly better from the opening, despite the exchange of bishops. As is usually the case, the bishop on f4 is better than its counterpart on g7, which is normally condemned to play a passive role. White controls the square e5 and can make progress on the queenside, where he now threatens 14. Qb5 }
