1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most popular move order for White to play the so-called Barry Attack, a system that was very popular in the 1980s, thanks to several English players, including GM Mark Hebden. Nowadays it remains quite popular. Any deep study of it would require another book, so we shall limit ourselves here to studying a few theoretical examples and one example game to provide us with an idea of the system. It is mainly used against the King's Indian, since by playing 3. Nc3 White forces Black to play 3. d5, as otherwise White can play e2-e4, channelling the game into the Pirc. The typical plan with Nf3, Bf4, e2-e3 and Nc3 is the most popular, although nowadays White also plays Qd2  (instead of e2-e3)  in a more modern version of the system.  White can also use the move orders   3.Bf4  Bg7  4.Nc3   4.e3  O-O  5.Be2  d5  6.Nc3  4...d5  5.e3 }
3... d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3
{ 5.Qd2  is a more modern alternative, used by GM Hebden, one of the greatest experts in the Barry Attack. Although it does not seem to give White any real advantage, since it can produce quite symmetrical positions, it is a good choice to play for a draw. Black usually plays 5. O-O or 5. Ne4:  O-O  The immediate leap   5...Ne4  is also good:  6.Nxe4  dxe4  7.Ne5  Nd7   7...Be6  8.e3  Nd7  9.Nc4  Hebden's move 9. Nxd7 is better  O-O  10.Be2  Bxc4  11.Bxc4  e5 =  Jussupow-Kasparov, Belfort 1988  8.Nxd7  Qxd7  9.e3  O-O   9...c5  10.c3  O-O  11.Be2  Rd8 =  10.Qb4  b6  11.Rd1  c6   11...Bb7 =  12.Be2  +=  Hebden-Valeanu, Dublin 2012  6.O-O-O !?   6.e3  c5  7.dxc5   7.Be2   7.O-O-O  7...Nbd7  8.O-O-O  Nxc5  9.Be5  Nce4  10.Qe1  Nxc3  11.Bxc3  Bf5  =+  Hebden-T. Andersson, London 2013   6.Bh6  Ne4   6...Nc6 !?  7.Bxg7  Kxg7  8.Ne5  Bf5  9.e3  Qd6 =  Kogan-Anand,Venaco rapid 2005;   6...Bxh6  7.Qxh6  c5  8.dxc5  d4  9.O-O-O  Ng4  10.Qf4  e5 =  Hebden-D.Fernandez, Coventry 2013  7.Nxe4   7.Qe3  Qd6   7...Nxc3  8.Bxg7  Kxg7  9.Qxc3  Qd6 =  Hebden-E.Berg, Oslo 2012  8.Bxg7  Kxg7  9.Nxe4   9.O-O-O  Nxc3  10.Qxc3  Nd7 =  Hebden-Gordon, Torquay 2013  9...dxe4  10.Nd2   10.Qxe4  Qb4+  =+  10...Nc6  11.Nxe4  Qxd4 =  7...dxe4  8.Bxg7  Kxg7  and now Black has two options:  9.Ng5   9.Ne5 ?!  b5 !  Stefanova-Dominguez Perez, San Sebastian 2011  9...e5  10.O-O-O  Qxd4  11.Qxd4  exd4  12.Rxd4  e3  13.fxe3  h6  14.Nf3 =  Stefanova-Lagno, Rostov-on-Don 2012  6...Ne4  7.Nxe4  dxe4  8.Ne5  Qd5  9.b3  Nc6  10.Nxc6  Qxc6  11.e3 =  Hebden-Shyam, Hastings 2010/11; }
5... O-O
{ I do not like to give up the bishop pair so soon with   5...Bg4  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  c6  8.O-O-O  O-O  9.g4  +=  I think that in this line White has the advantage, with attacking possibilities on the kingside, and in Santos-Berbatov, Fermo 2009, White won a good game;   5...c6  is more solid, and then:  6.h4 !?  White decides to sharpen the play and castle on the queenside. In this system this option is always available.   6.Be2  and now  O-O   6...Bg4  7.Ne5   7.h3  Bxf3  8.Bxf3  Nbd7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Qd2   10.a4  Re8  11.a5  e5 =  Giorgadze-De la Villa, Sanxenxo 2007  10...Re8 =  Hoang Thanh Trang-Ghaem, Jakarta 2013  7...Bxe2  8.Qxe2  Nh5   8...Nbd7 =  9.O-O-O  Nxf4  10.exf4  +=  Bellon-Romero, Mislata 2003  7.Ne5  Nfd7   7...Qb6  8.Rb1  c5  9.O-O  cxd4  10.exd4  Bf5  11.Bf3  Nc6 =  Praveen Kumar-Adhiban, Mumbai 2012  8.Qd2  b5   8...Nxe5  9.Bxe5 =  9.a3   9.Nd3  +=  9...Nb6  10.O-O  +=  Moldovan-A.Fedorov, Brasov 2011   6.h3  O-O  7.Be2   7.Bd3  c5   7...Nbd7  8.O-O  Nh5  9.Bh2  f5 ?!  10.Ne2  ±  Matnadze-Strikovic, Elgoibar 2012  8.O-O   8.dxc5  Nbd7  8...Nc6  9.dxc5  Qa5  10.Nb5  +=  7...Nbd7   7...c5 =  8.O-O   8.g4  Qa5  9.Qd2  b5   9...Nb6 =  10.Ne4  Qb6 =  Blatny-Krasenkow, Nimes 1991  8...b5  9.a3  a5  10.Bd3  Nb6  11.Ne5  +=  Nigalidze-Kantans,Kazan 2013;  6...h5  after   6...O-O  7. h5 might be premature but  7.Ne5  Nbd7  8.h5  comes into consideration, since on  Nxh5  white has  9.Rxh5  with an attack.  7.Ne5  Nbd7  8.Qd2  O-O  9.O-O-O  Ne4  after   9...Nxe5  10.Bxe5  Ne4  11.Nxe4  dxe4  White has several options to maintain a small advantage, such as  12.Bxg7   12.Be2  or else the simple   12.Qc3  12...Kxg7  13.Bc4  Bg4  14.Rdf1  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Bc4  Nxe5  12.dxe5 !  a good capture; the bishop on g7 will take a long time to come into play  Bg4  Here the exchange sacrifice  13.Qb4 !?   13.Qxd8  Rfxd8  14.Rd4 !  White's advantage is based on his strong e5-pawn, which hinders Black's communications, and on his control of the d-file, which is very important  b5  15.Bb3  c5  16.Rxd8+  Rxd8  17.c4  fixing the black pawn on c5  a6  18.Bc2  White is better here because of the weakness of the e4-pawn  Bf5   18...Be6  19.cxb5  axb5  20.a3  b4 ?  Black seeks activity, but this is ephemeral; it was more logical to play   20...Bf5  21.Rd1  Rxd1+  22.Kxd1  and the white king will try to penetrate via the queenside;  Kf8  23.Kd2  Ke8  24.a4   24.Bb3 !?  is possible, to hold up the progress of the black king and try to force the response  e6  which reduces the scope of the f5-bishop  24...bxa4  25.Bxa4+   25.Kc3 !?  to attack the c5-pawn  25...Bd7  26.b3  with advantage  21.Bxe4  Bb3  22.Bc2 !  Be6  23.Rd1  Ra8  24.Be4  Ra7  25.Rd8+  Kh7  26.Ra8  Rd7  27.Ra5  Rc7  28.Kc2  b3+  29.Kc3  f6  30.Ra6  with a decisive advantage  fxe5  31.Rxe6  exf4+  32.Kxb3  c4+  33.Kc2  and wins,Romero-Crnkovic, Pula 2012  19.Rd1  Rxd1+  20.Kxd1  and White has the advantage, owing to the weakness of the pawn on c5 and the limited activity of the black bishop on g7; let us see some examples:  f6   20...bxc4  21.Kd2  f6  22.Kc3 !  with a quick invasion by the white king.  21.Kd2  fxe5  22.Bg5  Bf6  23.Kc3  Bxg5  24.hxg5  and the white king penetrates on the queenside;  13...Bxd1  14.Rxd1  was very interesting:  Qc7   14...Qc8  15.Qxe7  ±   14...Qe8  15.e6  ±  15.e6  Qb6  16.exf7+  Kh7  17.Qxb6  axb6  18.Rd7  with advantage to White; }
6. Be2
{ This was the original scheme of the Barry Attack. The idea is to play Ne5 and a quick h2-h4-h5, with a strong attack. At first this gave very good results and White gained many victories, while Black could not find adequate counterplay. }
6... c6
{ 6...c5 !  is the most frequent response and definitely Black's best:  7.Ne5  is the move that has been played the most, e.g.   7.Nb5 !?  cxd4 !   7...Nc6  8.Nc7  Rb8  9.Nb5  Ra8  10.Nc7 =   7...Na6  8.h3 =  8.exd4   8.Nc7  dxe3  9.fxe3   9.Nxa8  exf2+  10.Kf1  Ng4  11.h3  e5  and Black has compensation  9...Nh5  10.Nxa8  Nxf4  11.exf4  Bxb2  when Black has very good compensation;  8...Nc6  9.O-O =   9.Nc7  Nh5  -+   7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  Nc6  transposes to the main line;   7.dxc5 !?  transposes to a favourable version of the Catalan, with reversed colours. The idea is to avoid the lines with the exchange on d4 and Qb6, which are awkward for White. It is similar to the 8. dxc5 that we saw against the Grnfeld, except that here Black can recover the pawn and equalise the game:  Qa5   7...Nbd7  8.O-O  Nxc5  9.Be5  Ncd7   9...Bg4  10.h3  Bxf3  11.Bxf3  e6  12.Qe2  Rc8  13.Rfd1  Qb6  14.Rab1 =  Megaranto-Rodshtein, Biel 2011;   9...Nce4  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Nd2   11.Qxd8  Rxd8  12.Nd4  Rd5 =  Megaranto-Morovic, Istanbul ol 2012  11...b6   11...Qd5 =  12.c4  Bb7 =  Magem-Fernandez, Barcelona 1990;  10.Bd4  b6   10...Qc7  11.Nxd5  Nxd5  12.Bxg7  Nxe3 =  11.Nxd5  Nxd5  12.Bxg7  Nxe3  13.fxe3   13.Qd2  Kxg7  14.Qxe3 =  13...Kxg7  14.Qd5  Qc7  15.Qxa8   15.Nd4  Bb7 =  Hebden-Pigott, Plymouth ch-GBR 1989  15...Bb7  16.Qxa7  Ra8  17.Ng5  Rxa7  18.Rxf7+  Kg8  19.Rg7+  Kh8  20.Rxh7+  Kg8  21.Rg7+ =  8.Nd2  Qxc5  9.Nb3  Qb6  10.Nb5  Na6  11.Be5  Qe6   11...Bg4  12.Bxg4   12.f3  Bd7  13.Bd4  Qd8 =  12...Qxb5  13.Be2  Qc6  14.Nd4   14.O-O  Rfd8  15.a4 =  Stefanova-Peptan, Belgrade 1995  14...Qb6 =  12.Bd4   12.f4  Ne8 =  12...b6  13.O-O  Bb7  14.a4  Rfc8 =  Richtrova-Baginskaite, Germany Frauenbundesliga 1993/94  7...Nc6  8.O-O  cxd4  9.exd4  Qb6  10.Nxc6  bxc6   10...Qxc6  11.Bb5  Qb6  12.a4  Qa5  13.Qd2  a6  14.Be2 =  Pri-Torrecillas,Catalua 2013  11.Na4  Qa5  12.c3  Nd7  Hebden-Nunn, Hastings 1996/97;  Another option is to play immediately   6...Bg4  7.Ne5 !?  the usual response is   7.h3  Bxf3  8.Bxf3  c6  9.O-O   9.Qd2  Nbd7  10.O-O-O  a5  11.h4  with complex play in De Prado-Gomez, Spain tt 2014  9...Nbd7  10.Re1  Re8  11.e4  dxe4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Bxe4   13.Rxe4 ! =  13...e5  14.dxe5  Nxe5   14...Bxe5 ! =  15.c3  Qb6  16.Qb3  +=  De Prado-Casares,Bembibre 2014  7...Bxe2  8.Qxe2  Nh5 ?!  it is more normal to play   8...c5  9.O-O-O   9.h4  h5  10.O-O-O  Qa5  11.g4  +=  Hebden-Burgess, London 1990  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Nc6  11.h4  with a complicated position in Chatalbashev-Lalev, Plovdiv 2003  9.Qb5 !  Nxf4  10.exf4  Nc6  11.Nxc6   11.O-O-O !  +=  11...bxc6  12.Qxc6  Bxd4  13.Nxd5  Bxb2  14.Rd1  Qe8  with a slight advantage to White in De Prado-Casares, Ferrol 2014   14...Qd6 = }
7. h4
{ A thematic idea in the Barry Attack, although usually White plays Ne5 first   7.h3  would transpose to the variations that we saw at move 6  ; after   7.Ne5  Nfd7   7...Nbd7  8.h4  Ne4   8...h5  9.Qd2  Nxe5  10.Bxe5  b5  11.f3  Ne8   11...Bh6  12.Bd3  Nd7  13.Bf4  Bg7  14.Bg5  b4  15.Ne2  c5 =  Stripunsky-Naroditsky, St Louis ch-USA 2011  12.Bxg7  Kxg7  13.e4  dxe4  14.Nxe4  Nf6  15.Ng5   15.a4  +=  15...Qc7 =  Vera-J. Cori, Panama 2013  9.Nxe4  dxe4   9...Nxe5 =  10.Nc4   10.Nxd7  Qxd7  11.h5  with an interesting position, although White has the advantage  10...h6  11.c3  +=  Stefanova-Diaz Castro, Mancha Real 2000  8.Nd3   8.h4  Nxe5  9.Bxe5  Bxe5  10.dxe5  Qb6 =  8...f6  9.Qd2  e5  10.Bg3  Qe7  11.O-O-O   11.h4  11...Nb6 =  Winants-Glek, Amsterdam 2000; }
7... Bg4
{ 7...Bf5  8.Ne5  Nfd7 ?!   8...h5 =   8...Nbd7 =  9.g4  Be6  10.Nxd7  Nxd7  11.Qd2   11.h5  +=  11...f5  12.gxf5  Bxf5  13.h5  +=  Hungaski-E. Hansen, Mar del Plata 2012;   7...Qb6  8.Rb1   8.Na4  Qa5+  9.c3  Nbd7 =  Izeta-Granero, Linares 1998  8...Nbd7   8...Bf5  9.Ne5  c5 =  Arencibia-Gareev, Calvia ol 2004  9.Ne5  Ne4  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Nc4  Qd8  12.h5  +=  Ju.Salgado-Manolache, Mondariz 2014. }
8. Ne5 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Nbd7
{ 9...b5  10.f3   10.a4  +=  b4  11.Na2  a5  12.Nc1  +=  10...Qa5  11.Qd2  Rc8  12.a3  - Miles-Nijboer, Escaldes zt 1998 }
10. O-O-O
{ Here we have one of the key positions in the Barry Attack. White is a bit better and above all his game is easier and his plans clearer. He has attacking chances on the kingside with the h4-h5 break  (with g2-g4 if necessary)  , he can bring the queen's rook to the g-file and he already has a strong knight on e5. Black is a long way behind in his preparations to mount a counterattack against the white king on the queenside. }
10... Qc8
{ 10...Nxe5  11.Bxe5  taking with the pawn is usually bad because after   11.dxe5  Nd7  the pawn is weak  12.e4  e6 =  11...b5  12.Kb1  Qa5   12...h5  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.g4  ±  13.Qe1   13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.Qf3  b4  15.Ne2  +=   13.Qf3  b4  14.Ne2  Ne4 =  13...b4  14.Ne2  c5  15.f3   15.Nf4 !  +=  15...Rac8  16.g4  +=  Izeta-Kazhgaleev, Cannes 1999;   10...h5  11.f3   11.Kb1  +=  11...Nxe5  12.Bxe5  Nd7  13.Bxg7  Kxg7  14.g4   14.e4  14...Rh8  15.e4  e6 =  Barva-Molnar, Hungary tt-2 1999/00   10...Ne4  11.Nxe4  dxe4  12.h5 !?   12.Nxd7  Qxd7  13.h5  Qe6  14.Kb1  +=   12.Kb1  +=  12...Nxe5  13.dxe5   13.Bxe5  Bxe5  14.dxe5  Qa5  15.hxg6  hxg6  16.Qg4  Qxe5  17.Rd4  Kg7  18.Rxe4  Qf6 =  13...Qa5 = }
11. f3 h6
{ As we have seen in several variations, it is better to play h7-h5; I dislike the advance of the pawn to h6, because it facilitates a pawn break on g5, or it can be attacked, as happens in the game. Other options for Black:   11...Nxe5  12.Bxe5  Qe6  13.g4  Ne8  14.Bxg7  Nxg7  15.e4   15.h5  +=  15...dxe4   15...h5  +=  16.fxe4  ±  Ansell-Blasko, Winterthur 2009   11...b5  12.g4  h5   12...b4  13.Na4  +=  13.Kb1  hxg4  14.Nxg4   14.fxg4  Nxe5  15.dxe5  Nxg4 =  14...Nh5  15.Rhg1  += }
12. g4 Ne8
{ Anticipating g4-g5 or h4-h5. It was again interesting to play   12...h5 !?  But if   12...b5  White can play  13.h5  g5  14.Bxg5  ±  hxg5 ?  15.h6  Bh8  16.h7+  Nxh7   16...Kg7  17.Qh2  mate in three  17.Nxd7  Qxd7  18.Qh2  mating }
13. e4
{ As we can see, White is combining his attack on the kingside with the opening of the centre, a logical plan in view of White's greater activity, whereas the black pieces are passive. Again the quiet 13. Kb1 was also good. }
13... Nb6 14. Qd2 Kh7 { Training question: What should White play here ? } 15.
Bxh6
{ An excellent winning move, and a difficult one even for an engine, which takes a while before it evaluates it as decisive. There were alternatives which retained White's advantage, such as 15. h5 or 15. Kb1, but the move played is very direct and decisive. }
15... Bxh6 16. g5 Nf6
{ This move loses, but the other options are not much better, as we can see in the following variations; Whites attack is very strong: if   16...Bg7  17.h5 !  Bxe5  18.hxg6+  Kg8   18...Kxg6  19.dxe5  +-  19.gxf7+  Rxf7  20.g6 !  Rg7  21.Qh6  with a decisive advantage for White   16...f6  17.Ng4 !  Nc4   17...Bg7  18.h5  Nc4  19.Qe2  and the position is winning for White.  18.Qe2  Bg7  19.h5  fxg5  20.exd5  Ncd6   20...b5  21.hxg6+  Kxg6  22.b3  +-  21.Qxe7  Qf5  22.hxg6+  Kxg6  23.Ne5+  Bxe5  24.Qh7+  Kf6  25.Rh6+  +- }
17. gxh6 Nh5 18. Rhg1 Qe6 19. Rde1
{ It was slightly better to play   19.b3 !  to prevent the black knight from jumping to c4. }
19... Qf6 20. Ng4 Qd6
{ 20...Qxh4  21.exd5  cxd5  22.Rh1  Qg3  23.Rxe7  with a decisive advantage. }
21. e5 Qe6 22. Ne3 Rac8 23. Ne2 c5 24. Rg5 Qh3 25. Reg1
{ Rather dubious. It was more precise to play   25.dxc5  +- } 25... Rg8
{ More tenacious was   25...Qxf3  26.R5g4  f5  27.exf6  Rxf6  28.dxc5  Nc4  29.Nxc4  Qxg4  30.Rxg4  Rf1+  31.Qd1  Rxd1+  32.Kxd1  dxc4  33.Rxc4  although White maintains a clear advantage. }
26. dxc5 Rxc5 27. Nd4
{ 27.Qd3  was also winning, with the idea of 28. Rxh5, and if  Qxf3  28.Rf1  +- }
27... Nc4 28. Nxc4 Rxc4 29. b3 Rc7
{ This loses immediately; comparatively best was   29...Rxd4  30.Qxd4  Qxf3  but after  31.Kb1  White should win. }
30. Rxh5
{ The finishing stroke to White's attack; the rook is immune from capture. }
30... f6 { 30...gxh5  31.Rxg8  Kxg8  32.Qg5+  Kf8  33.h7 } 31. exf6 exf6 32.
Rxd5
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@We have examined the Barry Attack, with Nc3, which can be played against both the Grünfeld and the King's Indian. The idea is to play Ne5, Be2, h2-h4-h5 and castle queenside, with a strong attack on the kingside.  It is a good weapon to have available and it is quite solid, although in my opinion Black can equalise more easily than against the London System. I think that the best defence for Black is with c7-c5.  The systems with c7-c6, or Bg4, as in this game, are inferior, because they grant White more freedom to attack the black king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Grünfeld"]
[Black "Game 13 - Le Roux vs. Benitah"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most popular move order for White to play the so-called Barry Attack, a system that was very popular in the 1980s, thanks to several English players, including GM Mark Hebden. Nowadays it remains quite popular. Any deep study of it would require another book, so we shall limit ourselves here to studying a few theoretical examples and one example game to provide us with an idea of the system. It is mainly used against the King's Indian, since by playing 3. Nc3 White forces Black to play 3... d5, as otherwise White can play e2-e4, channelling the game into the Pirc. The typical plan with Nf3, Bf4, e2-e3 and Nc3 is the most popular, although nowadays White also plays Qd2  (instead of e2-e3)  in a more modern version of the system. }
3... d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3
{ I do not like to give up the bishop pair so soon with } 5... Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3
7. Qxf3 c6 8. O-O-O O-O 9. g4
{ I think that in this line White has the advantage, with attacking possibilities on the kingside, and in Santos-Berbatov, Fermo 2009, White won a good game; }
*

