1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most popular move order for White to play the so-called Barry Attack, a system that was very popular in the 1980s, thanks to several English players, including GM Mark Hebden. Nowadays it remains quite popular. Any deep study of it would require another book, so we shall limit ourselves here to studying a few theoretical examples and one example game to provide us with an idea of the system. It is mainly used against the Kings Indian, since by playing 3. Nc3 White forces Black to play 3d5, as otherwise White can play e2-e4, channelling the game into the Pirc. The typical plan with Nf3, Bf4, e2-e3 and Nc3 is the most popular, although nowadays White also plays Qd2  (instead of e2-e3)  in a more modern version of the system. }
3... d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2
{ This was the original scheme of the Barry Attack. The idea is to play Ne5 and a quick h2-h4-h5, with a strong attack. At first this gave very good results and White gained many victories, while Black could not find adequate counterplay. }
6... c5 { is the most frequent response and definitely Blacks best: } 7. dxc5
{ transposes to a favourable version of the Catalan, with reversed colours. The idea is to avoid the lines with the exchange on d4 and Qb6, which are awkward for White. It is similar to the 8. dxc5 that we saw against the Grünfeld, except that here Black can recover the pawn and equalise the game: }
7... Nbd7 8. O-O Nxc5 9. Be5 Ncd7 10. Bd4 b6 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxg7 Nxe3 13.
Qd2 Kxg7 14. Qxe3 *

