1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 d6
{ The King's Indian against the London. } 5. Be2
{ 5.h3  is another option; we shall see that is possible to play with or without h2-h3. This move has advantages and disadvantages but according to the present state of theory it seems preferable to play without an early h2-h3. }
5... O-O
{ 5...Nh5  6.Bg5  h6   6...f5 ?!  7.c3  O-O  8.O-O  h6  9.Bh4  +=  De Prado-Merayo, A Corua 2013  7.Bh4  g5  8.Nfd2  gxh4   8...Nf6  9.Bg3  Nc6  10.c4  +=  Bocharov-Nepomniachtchi, Apatity 2011   8...Nf4  9.exf4  gxh4  10.c3  c5   10...Nd7  11.O-O  c5  12.d5  Nf6 =  Rivas-Romero, León 1995;  11.dxc5 !   11.Bb5+ !?  Kf8 ?!   11...Bd7 =  12.dxc5  dxc5  13.Qh5  +=  Banawa-Yermolinsky, Saint Louis 2013  11...dxc5  12.Na3  Nc6  +=  Prié-Iwanesko, Condom 2012  9.Bxh5  e5  10.dxe5   10.d5  +=  10...dxe5 ?!   10...Bxe5 =  11.Nc3  +=  Romanov-Drenchev, Skopje 2013 }
6. h3
{ We shall see further on that it is preferable to play   6.O-O  Nbd7  7.h3  which transposes to the game, since this move order cuts out certain lines for Black, especially involving the move c7-c5. }
6... Nbd7 7. O-O Qe8
{ We shall begin our analysis with this move. In the most classical King's Indian style, Black wants to play e7-e5. We shall see that Black has several options here. The lines with c7-c5 or b7-b6 are analysed in other games.  An interesting move here is   7...Ne4  with the idea of a quick e7-e5. This knight move is a resource that Black should always keep in mind, whether he has already played e7-e5 or not.  8.Bd3   8.Nbd2  Nxd2  9.Qxd2  e5  10.Bg5  Qe8   10...f6  11.Bh4  e4  12.Ne1  +=  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Nd4  h6  13.Bh4  a6 =   8.Qd3  is interesting and has been employed by the French player Prié:  f5 ?!   8...Ndf6  9.Nbd2  Bf5  10.Nxe4  Bxe4   10...Nxe4  11.Qa3  +=  11.Qb3  a5  12.c4  a4  13.Qa3 =  9.Nc3   9.Rd1  e6  10.Nfd2  Nxd2  11.Nxd2  +=  9...Ndf6  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Rad1  +=  8...e5 !?  it seems that this move is possible   8...Ndf6  is inferior due to  9.Nbd2  Bf5  10.Re1  +=  9.Bxe4  exf4  10.exf4  Nf6  11.Re1  d5   11...Bh6  12.c4  Bxf4  13.Nc3 =  12.Bd3  Nh5  13.f5  gxf5   13...Nf4 !  14.fxg6  fxg6  15.Bf1  and Black has sufficient compensation.  14.c3  +=  Another idea for Black is   7...c6  8.c4 !  other possible options are 8. Bh2, 8. c3 and 8. Nbd2  a6   8...Nh5 ?!  9.Bh2  e5  10.Nc3  +=  Muhammad-Simutowe, New York 2001   8...e5 !?  9.Bh2   9.dxe5  dxe5  10.Nxe5  Nh5  11.Bxh5  Nxe5  12.Be2  Nd3 =  9...Ne4  10.Qc2  f5  11.Nc3  Nxc3  12.Qxc3  +=  9.a4   9.Qc2  Re8  10.Nc3  b5   10...e5  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Rad1  +=  11.a3   11.e4  +=  11...e5  12.dxe5   12.Bh2 !  +=  12...Nxe5  13.Rad1  Qe7  +=  De Prado-Meskovs, Arteixo 2013  9...a5  10.Nc3  Nb8   10...h6  11.Qc2  Qe8  12.Bh2  e5  13.Rad1  +=  Khalifman-Rodshtein, Dresden 2007  11.e4  Na6  12.Qd2  +=  Dreev-Berg, Dresden 2007   7...Re8 !?  has also been played, with the plan of e7-e5:  8.Nc3 !  is best, with a slight advantage to White after   8.Bh2  e5 ?!   8...b6  9.dxe5 !   9.c4 ?  e4   9...Ne4 =  10.Ne1   10.Nfd2  +=  10...Nf8  11.Nc3  +=  Fedorowicz-Shirov, Stockholm 1990  9...dxe5  10.Nxe5  Ne4  11.Nd3  +=   8.c4  e5 !?  9.dxe5  dxe5   9...Ne4  10.Qc2  dxe5  11.Bh2  f5  12.Rd1  +=  10.Nxe5  Nh5 !  11.Bxh5  Nxe5  12.Be2  Nd3 !  13.Qxd3   13.Bxd3  Bxb2  14.Nc3  Bxc3  15.Rb1 =  13...Qxd3  14.Bxd3  Bxb2  15.Na3  Bxa3  16.Bxc7  Be6  and Black has compensation.  8...b6  9.Bc4  Bb7  Sakhatova-Kim, Yerevan 1996  However, the immediate   7...e5 ?!  does not work, due to  8.dxe5  Ne4  9.Qd5  dxe5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Qxe4  += }
8. c4
{ This is one of the variations in which White should play c2-c4 instead of c2-c3, since it is important that the knight has the c3-square available, leaving the d2-square free for the f3-knight to retreat, in the event of e5-e4 by Black. White's plan is to play on the queenside. It is possible to play in solid fashion with c2-c3, but in that case White cannot aspire to any advantage. The immediate 8. Bh2 can be played here, usually transposing. }
8... e5 9. Bh2 e4
{ I dislike this advance for Black, since it gives White a free hand to play on the queenside and opens the diagonal of the bishop on h2. There are a couple of alternatives:   9...Qe7  10.Nc3  b6   10...Re8 ?  11.Nb5 !  e4  12.Nxc7  exf3  13.Bxf3  Nb6  14.Nxe8  Nxe8  15.Rc1  ±  Kallai-Guliev, Nancy 2004   10...c6  11.Rc1  there are other options, such as   11.Qc2 !  Ne8  12.b4  +=  Nikolic-Bulaji, Sarajevo 2013   11.c5 ?!  dxc5  12.Nxe5  Nxe5  13.Bxe5  Rd8 =  Grachev-Mamedyarov, Moscow 2010   11.Re1  Ne8  12.b4  e4  13.Nd2  +=  Prié-Macak, Birmingham 2006   11.b4  b6  12.c5  bxc5  13.bxc5  dxc5  14.Nxe5  +=  Bellón-Tal, Barcelona 1986  11...Ne8  12.b4  f5  13.c5  ±  De Prado-Fernandez, Lugo 2014  11.Nd2   11.Qa4  11...Bb7  12.Bf3  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  in both cases with advantage to White;   9...Ne4  again this leap has been played quite often:  10.Qc2   10.Bd3   10.Na3 !?  a6  11.Rc1  f5  12.c5  dxc5  13.dxc5  c6  14.Nc4  +=  De Prado-Leao, Famalicao 2014   10.Nbd2  is the most common reply and was even played by Kasparov in the late 1970s:  Nxd2  11.Qxd2  e4   11...Qe7  12.Rfd1  e4  13.Ne1  Nf6  14.Rac1  with advantage to White, Kasparov-Horiguti, Sao Paulo 2004.  12.Ne1  Qe7   12...f5  13.Nc2  +=  Kasparov-Negulescu, Cagnes Sur Mer 1977  13.Nc2  Nf6   13...Nb6  14.Qa5  +=  14.Rac1  +=  Jussupow-Fuller, Esbjerg 1980;  10...f5  11.Bd3   11.Nc3  Nxc3  12.Qxc3  b6  +=  Palchun-Tseitlin, St Petersburg 2013  11...Nxf2   11...Nef6  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.c5  +=  12.Qxf2  e4  13.Be2  exf3  14.Bxf3 }
10. Nfd2
{ This is one of the key ideas that it is essential to remember leave the d2-square free for this knight to retreat. }
10... Qe7 11. Nc3
{ White has a comfortable advantage in this position. The move Nb5 is in the air and there are ideas of playing on the queenside with Rc1, b2-b4 and c4-c5. In contrast, Black has no clear plan; he needs to defend his pawn on e4 and furthermore the g7-bishop is likely to remain out of play. }
11... c6
{ After   11...Re8  there are several moves that give White an advantage:  12.Qc2   12.Nb5  was played by Spassky as early as 1978:  Qd8  13.c5 !?  a6  14.cxd6 !  this was Spasskys idea, the sacrifice of a piece for three pawns, including one very strong one on c7  axb5  15.dxc7  Qe7  16.Bxb5  White is slightly better and eventually won in Spassky-Bukic,Bugojno 1978;   12.b4  Nf8  13.Qc2   13.c5 !  ±  13...c6  14.d5   14.c5  ±  14...h5  ±  Bagaturov-Olarasu, La Fre 2006.  12...Nf8 ?   12...b6  13.a4  a5  14.Nb5  +=  13.Rae1  +=  Zhang Zhong-Nolte, Beijing 2008;   13.Nd5 !  ± }
12. b4 Re8 13. c5
{ The typical break: it is worth noting how the bishop on h2 comes to life again with the opening of the h2-b8 diagonal. It is typical of the London System that in many variations it seems that the h2-bishop is hardly in the game, but then suddenly it is transformed into a key piece. }
13... d5
{ If   13...dxc5  then  14.bxc5  b6  15.Bd6  Qd8  16.Rb1  with a clear advantage to White. }
14. b5 Nf8 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Qa4
{ White has managed to create weaknesses on c6 and a7, and his pieces are better. In particular the h2-bishop compares favourably with one on g7, which is out of play, as often happens in many variations of the London System. }
16... Qd7 17. Rab1
{ Another recurrent theme is White's control of the b-file, which Black is unable to contest because the b8-square is denied to the black rooks. }
17... Ne6 18. Rb8
{ It was better to employ the plan of   18.Rb4  Nd8  19.Rfb1  with the idea of Nb3 and Na5, with a clear advantage. }
18... Rxb8 19. Bxb8 Ba6 { 19...a6  20.Rb1  ± } 20. Rb1
{ It is essential to defend the valuable bishop on b8. } 20... Bxe2 21. Nxe2
Re7 { The only way to defend the a7-pawn. } 22. Bd6 Re8 23. Qa6
{ White has a decisive advantage: his control of the position is total, with command of the b-file and the h2-b8 diagonal, as well as having the more active queen, added to which the pawn on a7 will soon fall. }
23... Ra8 24. Rb8+ { But not   24.Rb7 ?  Qc8  and Black is better. } 24... Rxb8
25. Bxb8
{ And the a-pawn is lost. The white bishop has done a great job, enabling White to exchange all the rooks and finally helping to win the pawn. }
25... Nh5 26. Qxa7 Qc8
{ After   26...Qxa7  27.Bxa7  White should win the ending. } 27. Ng3 f5 28.
Nxh5 gxh5 29. Bd6 f4 30. Qb8 Qxb8 31. Bxb8 fxe3 32. fxe3 Nxd4
{ Trying to complicate in a lost position. If   32...Bh6  33.Nf1 } 33. exd4
Bxd4+ 34. Kf1 Bxc5 35. Nb3 Ba3 36. Nd4 c5 37. Nc2 Bc1 38. Ba7 c4 39. Be3
{ White has managed to block the black pawns and has a won game. } 39... Bxe3
40. Nxe3 c3 41. Nc2 Kf7 42. Ke2 Ke6 43. Ke3
{ After  43...Ke5  44.a4  wins.   @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw Black's traditional plan of playing Nbd7 and e7-e5, normally with Qe8, although we also analysed some other options for Black.  It is important to keep in mind that for White to gain any advantage he should play c2-c4  (instead of c2-c3, which is normal in the London System)  and Nc3, since it is necessary to leave the d2-square free for the knight on f3, when Black plays e5-e4.  I wish to draw your attention to the black plan of playing an immediate e7-e5 followed by Ne4, or Ne4 first, which can give Black equality. In the game I dislike Black's advance e5-e4, since this leaves White with the advantage. White's plan is clear: play on the queenside with ideas such as Nb5, b2-b4 and c4-c5, opening the diagonal of the bishop on h2, and also b4-b5, opening the b-file.  In this game these were the keys to White's victory. }
*

