{ The King's Indian against the London. } 5. Be2 O-O
{ We shall see further on that it is preferable to play } 6. O-O
{ Chessable Note:  6.h3  was the move order used in the game but this was modified to suit the Chessable MoveTrainer. }
6... Nbd7 7. h3
{ which transposes to the game, since this move order cuts out certain lines for Black, especially involving the move c7-c5. }
7... Qe8
{ We shall begin our analysis with this move. In the most classical King's Indian style, Black wants to play e7-e5. We shall see that Black has several options here. The lines with c7-c5 or b7-b6 are analysed in other games. }
8. c4
{ This is one of the variations in which White should play c2-c4 instead of c2-c3, since it is important that the knight has the c3-square available, leaving the d2-square free for the f3-knight to retreat, in the event of e5-e4 by Black. White's plan is to play on the queenside. It is possible to play in solid fashion with c2-c3, but in that case White cannot aspire to any advantage. The immediate 8. Bh2 can be played here, usually transposing. }
8... e5 9. Bh2 e4
{ I dislike this advance for Black, since it gives White a free hand to play on the queenside and opens the diagonal of the bishop on h2. There are a couple of alternatives: }
10. Nfd2
{ This is one of the key ideas that it is essential to remember leave the d2-square free for this knight to retreat. }
10... Qe7 11. Nc3
{ White has a comfortable advantage in this position. The move Nb5 is in the air and there are ideas of playing on the queenside with Rc1, b2-b4 and c4-c5. In contrast, Black has no clear plan; he needs to defend his pawn on e4 and furthermore the g7-bishop is likely to remain out of play.  After }
11... Re8 { there are several moves that give White an advantage: } 12. Qc2 b6
13. a4 a5 14. Nb5 *

