1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. O-O Nbd7 7. h3
{ Here the move h2-h3 is necessary, because   7.c4 ?!  e5 !  8.dxe5  Ne4  gives Black good play. }
7... b6
{ Playing b7-b6 is a good defensive method for Black, with the idea of playing Bb7 and a quick Ne4, without c7-c5. The lines with c7-c5 transpose to the Réti Reversed, which we shall investigate later and which is Blacks most popular set-up. White has several plans to combat this idea. }
8. a4
{ This seems be Whites best plan to try for an advantage.  The main move would be   8.c4  but it seems that Black equalises after  Bb7  9.Nc3  Ne4 !  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  and now  11.Qa4 !?   11.Bh2  has been played by some strong players:  c5   11...e6  12.Qa4  Qe7  13.Nd2  Bb7  14.Bf3  Bxf3  15.Nxf3  e5  16.Qc6  Rac8  17.Rac1  a5 =  Nguyen Ngoc-Edouard, Cap d'Agde 2010   11...Bb7  is also good, with equality;   11...e5 !  12.Qd2  Qe7  13.Rfd1  Rfd8  14.Rac1  a5 =  Kamsky-Smirin, Khanty-Mansiysk 2005;  12.Rc1   12.Ng5  Bb7  13.Bf3  Qc7  14.Qd3 =  12...Rc8   12...a5  13.d5 ?!  Bxf3   13...Bxb2 !  14.Nd2  Bxc1  15.Qxc1  Nf6  16.g4  Qd7  =+  14.gxf3  =+  Vallejo-Mikhalevski, Heviz 2008  13.a3   13.Ng5  13...Qc7  14.b4 =  Kamsky-T.L.Petrosian, Mainz 2007   11.Nd2  Bb7  12.Bf3  Qc8 =  Prié-Vachier-Lagrave, Marseille 2010  11...c5   11...e5 =  is better  12.Rad1  Qc7  13.b4  a5  14.b5  cxd4  15.exd4  - Sokolov-Cheparinov, Reykjavik 2012;  Another plan is   8.Nbd2  Bb7  9.a4  Re8  10.Bh2   10.a5 !  10...e5  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.c3  Qe7  13.a5  a6  14.axb6  cxb6  15.Qb3  b5  16.Qa3  +=  De Prado-Ferreiro, Arteixo 2013  An interesting and so far untried idea is to play   8.Nc3  Bb7  9.Bh2  White dispenses with moving the c-pawn and speeds up his development; this line deserves trials.  Also playable is   8.c3  Bb7  and now several alternatives have been played, but the majority involve the plan of a2-a4, which will usually transpose to the game.   8...c5  transposes to the Réti Reversed  If }
8... a5
{ then  If   8...Bb7  then  9.a5  bxa5  10.Nbd2   10.Rxa5 !  c5  11.Ra3  +=  10...c5   10...Nd5  11.Bg5  11.Nb3  Qb6  12.Nxa5  +=  Tu Hoang Thong-Bu Xiangzhi, Ottawa 2007  Another common idea is   8...a6  which has been played by some strong grandmasters:  9.Bh2  has been played quite often and after   9.Nc3  is again an interesting idea which awaits trials;   9.c4  Bb7  and now:  10.a5   10.Nc3  Ne4  11.Bh2   11.Nxe4  Bxe4  12.a5  with the initiative.   11.a5  11...c5   11...a5 =  12.Qb1   12.Qc2  +=  12...Ndf6  13.d5  Nxc3  14.bxc3  e6 =  Bauer-Le Roux, Le Port Marly 2012  10...Ne4  11.Nbd2   11.axb6  cxb6  12.Ng5  +=  11...c5  12.d5  Nef6  13.axb6  +=  De Prado-Martinez, Arteixo 2013;  9...Bb7  the game can transpose to lines of the Rti Reversed if Black plays c7-c5, but sometimes Black avoids this and different positions arise:  10.c3  would be normal after c7-c5 by Black, but otherwise it is better to abstain from this move and play c2-c4 or Nc3. Black now has several alternatives:   10.c4  Re8  11.Nc3  e5  12.Re1   12.dxe5  +=  12...a5 =  Grachev-Radjabov, Moscow 2010;  10...Qe8   10...e6  was played recently by Dominguez and Nepomniachtchi;  11.Nbd2   11.Nfd2 !?  Qe7  12.Bf3 =  Grachev-Nepomniachtchi, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013  11...Qe7  12.a5  worse is   12.Nc4  Rfd8  13.Qb3  Rab8  14.Qa3 =  Gareev-Sasikiran, Visakhpatnam 2008  12...b5  13.c4  bxc4  14.Nxc4   14.Rc1 !  is better  14...Rfb8  15.Qa4  Again   15.Rc1 !  15...Nd5  16.Rfe1  N7f6  17.Nfd2 =  Naiditsch-Dominguez, Wijk aan Zee 2014  11.c4   11.a5  b5  12.c4  bxc4  13.Bxc4  Ne4  14.Nc3  Ndf6  15.Qe2  +=   11.Na3 ?!  e5  12.Nc4  Ne4 =  Ivanchuk-Caruana, Reggio Emilia 2012;  11...e5   11...a5  12.Nc3  Ne4  13.Nb5  Rc8  14.Qc2  e5  15.Rae1  Qe7  - Burmakin-Banikas, Vrachati 2011  12.Nc3   12.a5 !  +=  12...exd4   12...a5 =  13.exd4  +=  Grachev-Nepomniachtchi, Moscow 2010; }
9. Nc3
{ Here   9.c3  has also been played, but this seems unnecessary. The systems with c2-c3 are very solid, but I think that without c7-c5 by Black White achieves nothing with c2-c3:  Bb7  10.Nbd2  Ne4   10...e6  11.Bh2  Qe7  12.Nc4  Ne4  13.Nfd2  Nxd2  14.Nxd2  f5  15.Bf3  Bxf3  16.Qxf3 =  Cacho-Morozevich, Bilbao 2014  11.Nxe4  Bxe4  12.Qb3 =  Gurevich-Ftacnik, Turin ol 2006  The move   9.Na3  is interesting, for instance  Bb7  10.Bh2  e6  11.c3  Qe7  12.Nb5  Rac8  13.b4 =  Nguyen Thi-Nguyen Anh, Ho Chi Minh City 2011 }
9... Bb7 10. Qd3
{ Provocative and strange. Pri wants to prevent Ne4 by Black and perhaps in future play e3-e4 or Qc4. Instead, the more normal   10.Bb5  was good  Rc8  11.Qe2  Ne4   11...c6  12.Bc4  12.Nxe4  Bxe4  13.c3  +=   13.Rad1  += }
10... Re8
{ 10...Ba6  11.Qd2   11.Nb5  c6  11...Bxe2  12.Qxe2  +=   10...Rc8  is also playable, with an unclear position after  11.Rad1  or 11. Bh2, although I prefer White. }
11. Rad1 Qc8
{ Black evades the pressure of the d1-rook, in order to play e7-e5; instead   11...e5 ?  fails to  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Nxe5  Other ideas are   11...c5  12.d5  += }
12. Bg3
{ Prophylaxis against the threat of e7-e5, but I think that it is better to play   12.Bh2 !  to prevent Black from gaining a tempo later with Ne4 and to give the white queen more room if it goes to h4, e.g.  e5  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.Qc4  Ba6  15.Qh4  Bxe2  16.Nxe2  with a slight advantage to White. }
12... e5 13. dxe5 dxe5
{ The alternative was   13...Nc5  14.Qd4  Nfd7  15.e4  Nxe5  16.Nxe5  dxe5  17.Qe3  += }
14. Qc4 Ba6 15. Qa2
{ Now the line   15.Qh4  Bxe2  16.Nxe2  is not good, since after  e4  17.Nfd4  the white queen does not have the square g3.  h6 }
15... Bxe2 16. Nxe2 Ne4
{ Black has equalised, largely due to the inaccurate move 12. Bg3. } 17. Nd2
{ 17.Bh2  Ndc5 = } 17... Ndc5 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Qc4 Nxg3
{ Eliminating White's dark-squared bishop is normally good for Black, but here that is not the case. It was preferable to play   19...Nc5  with equality. }
20. fxg3
{ White is better after this recapture, since he controls the light squares and can apply pressure along the half-open f-file against the weak point f7; his queen is more active, he dominates the open d-file and his knight is better than Black's bishop. }
20... Re6 21. Nc3 e4 22. Nd5 Be5 23. Qxe4 Qe8 24. Qc4
{ It was better to play   24.Qh4 !  with a clear advantage to White.  It would be inferior to play   24.Qxe5 ?!  Rxe5  25.Nf6+  Kf8  26.Nxe8  Raxe8  27.Rd7  R8e7  28.Rxe7  Kxe7  29.Kf2  Rc5  which would give Black drawing chances. }
24... Rc8 25. Rf3 Rd8 26. Rdf1 Rd7 27. b3 Kg7 28. g4 Red6
{ It was necessary to play   28...Kg8  although White would still maintain a clear advantage. }
29. Nxc7 Qe7 30. Rxf7+
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@The move 7. b6, with the idea of a quick Ne4 and without c7-c5, is a good defensive method for Black. For White it seems that the best plan is to play a2-a4 and Nc3, instead of c2-c4, when Black can equalise as in the game Prié-Vachier-Lagrave.  In the game, White tested the move Qd3, although the natural Bb5 seems better. Later he should have retreated the bishop to h2 instead of g3, which allowed Black to equalise.  Remember that, with rare exceptions, it is almost always better to move the bishop to h2 rather than g3.  White gained the advantage after the exchange of the knight for the bishop on g3; normally this is good for Black, but this case was an exception and Black was left with the worse position. }
*

