[Result "*"]

{ Gata Kamsky 2741-Abdul Rahman Saleh Salem 2531, Khanty-Mansiysk Wch blitz, 2013  (17)  . }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be2 Nc6
{ This move is usually made after   6...Nfd7  7.O-O  The idea is a quick e7-e5. }
7. O-O
{ 7.Nc3 !  preventing e7-e5. More recently, Carlsen played   7.Bh2  and now:  e5 !?   7...Nd7  8.a4  e5  9.a5  exd4  10.exd4  a6  11.O-O  Re8  12.Nc3  Nf6  13.Re1  Carlsen-Aronian, Berlin Wch blitz 2015.  8.dxe5   8.c3  Qe7  9.O-O =  8...Ne4  9.Qd5  Ng5  10.Nbd2  Nxf3+  11.Nxf3  Be6  12.Qb5  Nxe5  13.Nxe5  dxe5  14.O-O   14.Bxe5  c6  15.Qc5  Qg5  ∓   14.Qxb7  Bd5  =+  14...Qd5 = }
7... Nd7
{ Here Black could already play   7...e5 !  8.dxe5  Ne4  9.Bh2  dxe5  10.c3  with equality. }
8. Bh2
{ Here   8.Nc3 !?  looks interesting, which incidentally is Houdini's recommendation. After Black's  e5  in one game I mistakenly exchanged on e5  9.dxe5  instead the correct way to play is  I think that   9.Bg5 !  gives White a slight advantage in all lines:  Bf6   9...Nf6  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.Bb5  +=   9...Qe8 ?  10.Nd5 !  f6  11.Nxc7  Qe7  12.Nxa8  fxg5  13.Nc7  +-   9...f6  is best  10.Bh4  g5   10...Nb6  11.Re1  +=  11.Bg3  f5   11...exd4  12.Bc4+  Kh8  13.Nxd4  Nb6  14.Bb3  +=  12.dxe5   12.d5 !  Ncb8  13.e4  f4  14.Bh2  +=  12...Ndxe5  13.Bxe5 ?!   13.Nxe5  +=  13...Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Bxe5 =  Burmakin-Jelen, Schwarzach 1998.  10.Bh6  Bg7   10...Re8  11.d5  +=  11.Bxg7  Kxg7  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Bb5  +=   9.Bg3  is inferior  exd4  10.exd4  Ne7  11.Re1  Nf6  12.Bf1  Bd7  13.Bh4  h6 =  Harikrishna-Thipsay, New Delhi 2001  9...Ndxe5  10.Qd2  Be6   10...Nxf3+  11.Bxf3  Re8 =   10...Re8 =  11.Nd4   11.Ng5  Bc4 =  11...Nxd4   11...Nc4  12.Bxc4  Bxc4  13.Rfe1 =  12.exd4  Nc4 =  De Prado-Nicolas, Linares 2013  Another option is   8.c4  e5  9.Bh2  exd4  10.exd4  Re8   10...Qf6 !  11.Nc3  Nxd4  12.Nxd4  Qxd4  13.Nd5  c6 !   13...Qxb2  14.Rb1  Qxa2  15.Nxc7  +=  Prié-Moussard, Caen 2011  14.Ne7+  Kh8  15.Bxd6  Qxb2   15...Re8  16.Bg4   16.Re1 =  16...Nb6  17.Qxd4  Bxd4  18.Rad1  (it is better to play)   18.Nxc8  Nxc8  19.Ba3 =  although the bishop pair might become a factor in the endgame   18...Bf6  19.Nxc8  - Andrianov-Gareev, Mesa 2010  16.Rb1  Qxa2  17.Re1  Nf6  18.Be5   18.Bf1  +=  is better  18...Qa3  19.Nxc8  Rfxc8  20.Rxb7 =  Prié-Bedouin, Liverpool 2009  11.Nc3  Nf6  12.Bd3  Nh5  13.Bc2  Nb4  14.Ba4   14.Bb3  +=  14...Bd7  15.a3  Bxa4  16.Qxa4  Nc6  17.Rad1  +=  Grachev-Aronian, Moscow 2010; }
8... e5 9. c3 f5
{ This is the most common move in the position, but it is not the best. Kings Indian players are used to advancing their kingside pawns, but against the London System this is generally not such a good idea. Even though at first sight it looks good, the pawn advances leave weaknesses and White can easily defend against the pawn storm.  Another option is   9...Nb6  10.a4  a5  11.Nbd2  exd4  12.exd4  Be6  13.Qc2  with a balanced position, although I prefer White.   9...Qe7  10.Na3   10.d5  Ncb8  11.Qc2 =  10...f5   10...Nb6 =  11.Nb5  Nf6  12.Qb3+  Kh8  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.Qa3  +=  Burmakin-Gochelashvili, Sochi 2012  After   9...Re8  10.Qc2  e4  11.Nfd2  Nf6  12.a4  a6  13.b4  White has the initiative on the queenside; in the London System this is a typical plan for White against the Kings Indian. }
10. a4
{ There are many options in this position.   10.Na3 !?  is interesting; the knight usually goes to a3 or c3, in order to leave the square d2 free for the other knight in case Black plays e3-e4. Now if  g5 ?!   10...Kh8  11.Re1  a6  12.Rc1  Qe7 =  Naiditsch-Nataf, Evry 2008  Black has also played   10...e4  11.Nd2  Nf6  12.f3 !?   12.Qb3+  Kh8  13.c4 =  12...Ne7   12...exf3  13.Qb3+  Kh8  14.Bxf3  Re8 =   12...Bh6 !? =  13.fxe4  fxe4  14.Qb3+  +=  Alterman-Avrukh, Tel Aviv 1999.  White plays  11.dxe5  dxe5   11...Ncxe5  12.Nd4  +=  12.Qd5+   12.Nc4 !  +=   12.e4 !?  +=  12...Kh8  13.Rad1   13.Nc4  +=  13...Qe7  14.Nc4  Nf6   14...Nb6 =  15.Qb5   15.Qd2  +=  15...a6  16.Qb3  Ne4  17.a4  +=  De Prado-Nataf, Orense 2007  Another option is   10.b4 !?  a6  11.a4  Kh8  12.Nbd2 ?!   12.Qb3  12...e4  - M.Gurevich-Svidler, Evry 2004.  Houdinis recommendation is interesting:   10.d5 !?  Ne7  11.c4  Nc5  12.Nc3  a5  ∞  Even   10.Qb3+ !?  Kh8  11.d5  Ne7  12.c4  Nc5  13.Qa3  with a complex position, can be considered. }
10... Kh8
{ Other options include:   10...Qe7  11.b4   11.a5  +=  11...e4  12.Nfd2  Nd8  13.a5  a6  14.c4  +=  Golod-Sutovsky, Netanya 2009  and   10...g5 ?!  when the best continuation is  11.dxe5   11.a5  a6  12.dxe5   12.d5  Ncb8  13.Qc2  ±  12...dxe5  13.Qd5+   13.Nbd2  +=  13...Kh8  14.Rd1  Qe7 =  was played in Hoffman-Strikovic, Seville 1994  11...Ndxe5   11...dxe5  12.Na3  +=  12.Nd4  +=  If   10...e4  11.Nfd2  Qe7  12.a5  a6  13.c4  with advantage to White. }
11. b4
{ Here   11.a5  was also good, with advantage to White. In this type of position White should play on the queenside, where he can gain the advantage: the plan is to keep advancing the pawns with b2-b4 and c3-c4, bring the queen to b3 and prepare the pawn breaks c4-c5 or b4-b5. The white knight can develop to a3 or c3. White must defend against the black attack on the kingside, but this is not usually dangerous, even though it might appear so at first sight. }
11... e4 12. Nfd2 d5
{ This move is dubious, because it opens the h2-b8 diagonal for the bishop on h2, which helps White. It was better to play   12...a6  13.a5  Qe7  14.Qb3  Bh6  15.c4  f4  16.d5  +=   12...Qe7  += }
13. b5 Ne7 14. c4 c6
{ It was better to play   14...dxc4  15.Nc3  Nb6  16.a5  Nbd5  17.Nxd5  Nxd5  18.Bxc4  although White retains the advantage. }
15. bxc6 { Kamsky overlooks the right move, which is   15.Nc3  ± } 15... bxc6
16. cxd5 { But this is more serious;   16.Nc3 !  was now essential. } 16...
cxd5
{ Wasting his opportunity; with   16...Nxd5 !  Black equalises, because he threatens 17c5, ridding himself of his weak pawn, and at the same time prevents the b1-knight from developing to c3. }
17. Nc3
{ Kamsky finally plays the right move and White has a clear advantage. Again, this type of position is familiar to us: White has pressure on d5 and commands the open b- and c-files, because the bishop on h2 denies Black the use of both b8 and c7; the black bishop on g7 is a mere spectator in such variations. }
17... Nf6
{ Blacks best course of action was to throw his pawns forward with   17...g5  18.Rc1  f4  even though after  19.Nb5  Qb6  20.h4  White has the edge, since if  h6 ?  then  21.a5  Qxa5  22.hxg5  hxg5  23.Nc7  Rb8  24.Ne6  Rf6  25.Nxg5  and White has a clear advantage. }
18. Nb5 a6
{ This creates a fresh weakness on b6 and the white knight will penetrate in any case. A better defence was   18...Ne8  although with  19.Rc1  White maintains a clear advantage. }
19. Nd6 Be6 20. Nb3
{ White already has a decisive advantage: the white knights range freely through Blacks camp and the h2-bishop is a monster, whereas the black pieces are mere spectators. }
20... g5 21. Nc5 Bg8 22. Be5 { By now many moves win, such as   22.Rb1 } 22...
f4 { 22...Ne8  23.Nxe8  Qxe8  24.Bxa6  +- } 23. exf4 gxf4 24. Bxf4 Ng6 25. Bg3
Qe7 { Again if   25...Ne8  then  26.Nxe8  Qxe8  27.Bxa6  +- } 26. Nf5 Qf7 27.
Rb1 Nd7 { 27...Ra7  28.Nxg7  Qxg7  29.a5  wins } 28. Nd6 Qe7 29. Rb7 Rad8 30.
Bg4
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@The plan with Nfd7, preparing to play e7-e5, can be implemented immediately or after Nc6, as in this game. I think that 8. Nc3, to answer 8. e5 with 9. Bg5 !, gives White the advantage.  The positions arising in the game after 9f5, followed by the advance of the black pawns on the kingside, present no problems to White, who can usually gain the advantage by playing on the queenside. It is essential for White to leave the d2-square free for the f3-knight and to follow the plan of a2-a4, b2-b4, c3-c4, Qb3 and either Na3 or Nc3.  In the game, we saw that after d7-d5 White's position is preferable and he won easily, thanks to his control of the open files and his bishop on h2, which was once more a decisive influence, commanding the h2-b8 diagonal. }
*

