[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. h3
{ Also playable is   6.O-O  Nfd7  7.Nc3 !?  again an interesting and little explored idea. Now:  Nc6   7...e5  8.Bg5  f6  9.Bh4  Nc6  10.h3  +=  8.Qd2   8.h3  +=  8...e5  9.Bg3  += }
6... Nfd7 7. O-O
{ 7.Bh2  e5  8.Nc3 !?  an interesting idea, which occurs in several lines; 8. c4 and 8.O-O are the normal moves  Nc6  9.O-O  Re8  10.Re1  a6 =  Carlsen-Radjabov, Berlin Wch rapid 2015. }
7... e5
{ Here we see the immediate e7-e5 advance. We saw the alternative 7. Nc6 in the previous game. }
8. Bg5
{ In all the other known games White retreated the bishop to h2. However the text move also seems good to me, and Houdini backs me up.  The first time I reached this position I responded with   8.dxe5  dxe5   8...Nxe5 =  9.Bg5   9.Bg3  +=  9...f6   9...Qe8  10.Nc3  +=  10.Bh4  Nc6   10...Qe7 =  11.Bc4+   11.Nc3  Ne7 ?!   11...Nb6 =  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.Rfd1  Be6 =  12.Bg3   12.e4 !  Nb6  13.Nb5  +=   12.Bc4+ !  Kh8  13.e4  +=  12...Nb6  13.Nb5   13.e4  Qe8 =  13...c6  14.Nd6  Nf5  15.Nxf5   15.Nxc8 =  15...Bxf5  16.c3   16.Nd2 =  16...Qxd1  17.Rfxd1  - De Prado-Senlle, Spain tt 2008.  11...Kh8  12.Nc3  Ne7 ?!   12...Nb6  13.Bb3  Qe7  14.Qe2  Be6 =  13.a4 ?!   13.e4 !  +=  13...Nf5 =  Le Phu-Nguyen Hoang, Dalat City 2004;  White's usual move here is   8.Bh2  with several possibilities:  Re8   8...f5 !?  advancing the kingside pawns is a very typical plan in the King's Indian  9.c4  also good is   9.dxe5 !  dxe5  10.Nc3 !   10.Na3  Qe7  11.c3  +=  Cueto-Socko, Bled 2002  10...Nc6  11.Bb5   11.Bc4+  Kh8  12.Bb3  +=  11...Kh8  12.Qd5  Qf6  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.Qa5  +=  Arencibia-Paneque, St Spiritus ch-CUB 1989   8...exd4  9.exd4  Nc6   9...Re8  +=  10.a4   10.Re1  +=  10...Kh8   10...Re8 =  11.Re1  +=  Kovacevic-Nurkic, Tuzla 1981;   8...Qe7  9.c4  Nc6  10.Nc3  Moldovan-Nevednichy, Targoviste ch-ROM 2001.  9.Re1  Nc6  10.d5  Ne7  11.e4  f5  12.Nc3  += }
8... f6
{ The alternative   8...Qe8  is not usually a good move, because the white knight can go from c3 to d5:  9.c4   9.Nc3 !  h6  10.Bh4   10.Nd5  hxg5  11.Nxc7  Qe7  12.Nxa8  e4  13.Nd2  Nf6  14.b4  b6  15.a4  Qb7  16.Nxb6  Qxb6  17.c4  +=  10...g5  11.Bg3  Nc6   11...c6  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Qd6  ±  12.Re1  +=  9...h6  10.Bh4  g5   10...exd4  11.exd4  g5  12.Bg3  f5  13.Nc3  f4  14.Bh2  +=  11.Bg3  f5  12.Nc3  += }
9. Bh4 g5
{ 9...Nc6  10.Nc3  Nb6  11.Re1  Re8  12.Bg3  e4  13.Nd2  f5  14.a4  += } 10.
Bg3 f5
{ As mentioned already, there is no need for White to fear the advance of the black pawns on the kingside, since White can defend without any problems. Furthermore he has the better game in the centre of the board and on the queenside.   10...e4  11.Nfd2  f5  12.c4  Nb6  13.Nc3 }
11. dxe5
{ 11.Nc3 !  is the best move, with the possible variations:  Nc6   11...f4 ?!  12.Bh2  ±   11...e4  12.Nd2  Nc6  13.Bc4+   13.a4  +=   13.Bh2  +=  13...Kh8  14.Qh5  +=   14.a4  +=  12.d5  Nb4   12...Ne7  13.Nxg5  ±  13.a3   13.e4  f4  14.Bh2  +=  13...Na6  14.b4  += }
11... dxe5
{ It is bad for Black to play   11...Nxe5 ?  12.Bxe5  Bxe5  13.Qd5+  Kg7  14.Nxe5  ± }
12. Qd5+
{ It was slightly better to play   12.Nc3  Nc6   12...f4  13.Bh2  ±  13.Bb5 !?   13.a3  e4  14.Bc4+  Kh8  15.Nd2  Nc5  16.Nb3  +=   13.Bc4+  Kh8  14.a3  +=  13...e4  14.Qd5+   14.Bxc6  bxc6  15.Nd4  Nb6  16.Nxc6  Qe8  17.Nd4  f4  again with compensation.  14...Kh8  15.Bxc6   15.Nd2  Nde5  16.Qxd8  Nxd8  17.Bh2  c6  18.Be2  Be6 =  15...exf3  16.Bxd7   16.Bxb7  Bxb7  17.Qxb7  f4  18.Bh2  fxe3  19.fxe3  Rb8 =  16...Bxd7  17.Qxf3  Bc6  18.Qh5  f4  19.exf4  gxf4  20.Bh4  Qe8  and Black has compensation for the missing pawn;   12.h4  g4  13.Bc4+  Kh8  14.Ng5  Qe7  15.Qd5  Nb6  16.Nf7+  Kg8  17.Nh6+  with perpetual check }
12... Kh8 13. Nc3 Qe7 14. Rad1
{ It was better to play   14.Qa5  retaining some advantage for White. } 14...
Nc6 15. Bb5 { 15.Rd2 =  was better. } 15... Nb6 16. Qd2 Bd7 17. a4 Rad8 18. Qe2
e4
{ Or   18...f4 !?  19.exf4  exf4  20.Qxe7  Nxe7  21.Bh2  h6 =  What should White play now ? }
19. Bxc7
{ Seeing that White would stand worse after the normal 19. Nd2, I decided on this sacrifice, which appeared interesting, although it was better to take on g5 first:   19.Nxg5 !  Qxg5   19...h6  20.Ngxe4  fxe4  21.Bxc7  ±  20.Bxc7  Be5  21.Bxd8  Rxd8  22.a5  Nxa5  23.Bxd7  Nxd7   23...Rxd7  24.Qb5  +-  24.f4  exf3  25.Rxf3  with a complex position. White has compensation and his rooks are a danger to Black along the open files. }
19... exf3 20. Qxf3 Ne5
{ If   20...g4  then  21.hxg4  fxg4  22.Qe2  Rde8  23.Bd6  Qe6  24.Bxf8  Rxf8  with a complex position;  Or   20...Be6  21.Bxd8  Nxd8  22.e4  reaching a position which is rather difficult to assess; I think that the sacrifice leaves possibilities for both sides, but White of course has compensation for the sacrificed material. }
21. Qxb7
{ 21.Qe2  Bxb5  22.Bxd8  Bxe2  23.Bxe7  Bxd1  24.Bxf8  Bxc2  25.Bxg7+  Kxg7  26.Rc1 = }
21... Bxb5 22. Nxb5
{ It was better to play   22.Rxd8 !  Bxf1   22...Rxd8  23.Nxb5  +=  23.Rxf8+  Qxf8  24.Kxf1  Qa8 =  and White has three pawns for the piece. }
22... Nxa4
{ From now on the play is full of mistakes, but we were very short of time by this point. It was better to play   22...Rxd1  23.Rxd1  Nxa4  24.b3  Nc5  25.Qxa7  Ne4  again reaching a complex position with White having three pawns for the piece. }
23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Qa6
{ There was a simpler win with   24.Qxa7  Nxb2  25.Bxd8  Qxd8  26.Nd4  +- }
24... Nxb2 25. Bxd8 Qxd8 26. Qxa7 f4 27. Nd4 h6
{ The best try was   27...Bf6  but after  28.exf4  gxf4  29.Ne6  Qe8  30.Nxf4  White has a decisive advantage. }
28. Ne6 { Missing the obvious   28.Qxg7+  Kxg7  29.Ne6+  +- } 28... Qg8 29.
Nxg7 Qxg7 30. Qb8+ Kh7 31. Rb1 { 31.Qxb2 ??  Nf3+  -+ } 31... Nec4
{ 31...Nbc4  32.exf4  gxf4  33.Rb7  Nf7  34.Qxf4  Ncd6  35.Rd7  and White wins. }
32. Ra1
{ The rook threatens to invade on a7 or a8 and attack the black king, taking advantage of the fact that the black knights are a long way from the kingside. }
32... Qe5 33. Qb7+
{ It was simpler to play   33.Ra7+ !  Kg6  34.Qg8+  Kh5   34...Kf5  35.Qh7+  Ke6  36.Qd7+  Kf6  37.Qf7#  35.Qf7+  Kh4  36.Re7 !!  Qc3  37.g3+  fxg3  38.Re4+  g4  39.Rxg4+  Kxh3  40.Qh5# }
33... Kg6 34. Ra6+ Nd6 35. Rxd6+
{ The comedy of errors continues; White could win a knight with   35.Qb4  Nbc4  36.Qxc4  +- }
35... Qxd6 36. Qxb2 fxe3 37. fxe3 Qd1+ 38. Kh2 Qd6+ 39. Kg1 Qd1+ 40. Kf2 Qd2+
41. Kf3 Qd5+ 42. e4
{ White cannot escape the perpetual check without sacrificing a pawn. } 42...
Qd1+ 43. Kg3 Qe1+ 44. Kh2 g4
{ Black threatens 45... g3 mate !  It was better to take the pawn with   44...Qxe4  and after  45.Qb6+  Kg7  46.Qc7+  Kf6  47.c4  although White retains an extra pawn, it is difficult to win this ending. }
45. Qb6+ { If   45.hxg4  Black has a draw by perpetual check } 45... Kg5 46.
Qc5+ Kh4 { 46...Kf6  47.Qf8+  Ke5  48.Qg7+  Ke6  49.Qxh6+  Kf7  50.Qf4+  +- }
47. Qe7+ Kh5 48. Qf7+ Kh4 49. Qf6+
{ After 49... Kh5, 50. Qf5+ Kh4 51. Qxg4 is mate.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the idea of the immediate Nfd7 and e7-e5, without Nc6. My recommendation is the move 8. Bg5  (instead of the usual Bh2)  , which I think gives White better prospects.  There is no need to fear the advance of the black pawns on the kingside; White should play in the centre and on the queenside. White's bishop, despite being temporarily hemmed in on h2 after f5-f4, forces Black to weaken his position with this advance, especially his e4-pawn, and in the long run White has the advantage.  In the game we were able to see an interesting sacrifice and I think that despite the errors it was an interesting struggle. }
