1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7
{ Let us examine some deviations:   3...d6  4.e3  Nh5  5.Bg5  h6  6.Bh4  g5  7.Nfd2  Ng7  8.Bg3  Nf5  9.Qh5   9.Nc3  h5  10.h3  Nxg3  11.fxg3  c6  12.Qf3   9.Bd3  h5  10.Qf3  Qd7  11.h3  g4   11...Nxg3  12.Qxg3  +=  12.Qe2   12.Qxf5  Qxf5  13.Bxf5  Bxf5  14.hxg4  Bxg4  15.f3  Be6  with an interesting position; Black has the weakness on h5 but the bishop pair in return.  12...Nxg3  13.fxg3  and the position is complex.  9...Bg7  10.Bd3 =  Hoang Thi-Harika, Ningbo 2009 }
4. e3
{ 4.h4 !?  is an aggressive idea to attack Black's castled position. A possible continuation is  d6  5.Nc3   5.e3   5.Nbd2  5...O-O  6.Qd2   6.e4  6...c5  7.e3  with a position similar to the Barry Attack.  Another idea is   4.c3  O-O  5.Qc1  this is White's idea, to play a quick Bh6  d6  6.Bh6  c5  7.h4   7.Bxg7  Kxg7  =+  7...Bxh6  8.Qxh6  Qb6  ∓  Schlindwein-Prusikin, Altenkirchen 2001.  Finally   4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  transposes to a Pirc.   5.Qd2 !?  is very interesting. }
4... O-O
{ Castling can also be deferred with   4...b6  5.Be2  Bb7  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  d6  8.Nc3  Nbd7  9.Qc2   9.h3  9...Nh5  10.Bg5  h6  11.Bh4  c5  12.d5  g5   12...Ndf6  13.Nd2  g5  14.Qd1  +=  13.Bxg5 !?  hxg5  14.Nxg5  Nhf6  15.f4  with compensation;  Or   4...d6  5.Be2  Nh5   5...c5  6.c3  we should not forget that other ideas are possible, such as   6.h3  Qb6  7.Nbd2 !  Qxb2  8.Rb1  Qc3   8...Qa3  9.Nc4  Qc3+  10.Nfd2  ±   8...Qxa2  9.Nc4  ±  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Rb3  Qa5  11.Nc4  Qd8  12.dxc5  dxc5  13.Rd3  with advantage to White.  6...Qb6  7.Qb3  This is one of the lines that some players with white tend to dislike, but Black can equalise only with accurate play.  Instead of 7. Qb3 it is also possible to play the very interesting   7.Nbd2 !?  Qxb2  8.Nc4  Qxc3+  9.Nfd2   9.Kf1  b5  10.Rc1  Qb4  11.Rb1  bxc4  12.Rxb4  cxb4  13.Qa4+   13.Bxc4  O-O  13...Bd7  14.Qxb4  Nc6  15.Qxc4  and I prefer White  9...Bd7  10.a3  cxd4  11.Rc1  d5  12.O-O   12.Rxc3  dxc3  13.Nb1  dxc4  14.Nxc3  Nc6  15.Bxc4  ∞  12...dxc4  13.Rxc3  dxc3  14.Nxc4  when Black has compensation, but I prefer White.  The exchange on b3 is better for White; after  7...Qxb3   7...Be6  8.Qxb6  axb6  9.a3  and now there are two ways for Black to play:  Nc6  the development of the knight on c6 is always a quite logical idea   9...O-O  10.h3  Bd7   10...Bd5 !?  11.O-O  Bc6  12.Nbd2  Nbd7  13.Rfe1 =  Morozevich-Grischuk, Russia tt 2014  11.O-O  Bc6   11...b5  12.dxc5  dxc5  13.Ne5 ?!   13.Nbd2 =  13...b4  14.cxb4  cxb4  15.Nd2  Nd5  16.axb4  Rxa1  17.Rxa1  Nxf4  18.exf4  Bxe5  19.fxe5  Nc6 =  Grachev-Navara, Budva 2009  12.Rd1  b5   12...Ne4 =  13.dxc5  dxc5  14.Ne5  b4  15.Bc4  e6  16.cxb4  cxb4  17.Nd2  bxa3 =  Grachev-Volokitin, Moscow 2008  10.h3  O-O  11.Nbd2  Na5  Blacks most common plan; the idea is to play Nb3 and exchange the knight  Black has also tried   11...Rfe8  12.O-O  Bf5  13.Bh2  Ne4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.Nd2  Bf5  16.Nc4  +=  Alterman-Xie Jun, Wijk aan Zee 1998  12.O-O  Rfc8  Also good is   12...Nb3  13.Nxb3  Bxb3  14.Nd2  Bd5  15.Nc4  Nd7 =  16.Rfc1   16.Bg5  Rfe8  17.Rfd1  Bc6  Pakleza-Helis, Ustron 2006;   16.a4 ! =  16...b5  17.Nd2  Bc6 =  Burmakin-Gormally, Cappellela-Grande 2000.  13.Rfe1   13.Rfc1  Bb3 !?  14.Bd3  Nd7  15.Bb5  Nf8  16.a4  Ne6 =  Dreev-I. Sokolov, Groningen 1991  13...Nb3  14.Nxb3  Bxb3  15.Nd2  Be6  16.Bf3   16.Bg5  h6  17.Bxf6  Bxf6  18.Bg4  Bxg4  19.hxg4  d5  20.f4  e6  21.g3  Bg7  22.Kf2  f5  23.gxf5  exf5  24.Nf3  +=  Megaranto-Cvitan, Biel 2013   16.Rad1  Rc7  17.Bf3  h6  - Pantev-Ermenkov, Sunny Beach 2012  16...Bd5 ?  this hands White the advantage, since it helps his plan of advancing his centre pawns; it was better to play   16...Rc7  17.Rad1  and although the position is equal, White has the slightly preferable game, because he can play e3-e4 and advance his centre pawns  17.e4 !  Bc6  18.d5  Bb5  19.e5 !  with advantage to White, E. Alvarez-Bazan, Infiesto 2008;  8.axb3  cxd4  9.exd4  O-O  10.Nbd2  Nc6  11.O-O  the idea is to play b3-b4 and Nb3, with pressure on the queenside; White generally has the better prospects in this type of position;  6.Bg5  h6  7.Bh4  g5   7...c5  8.c3  Qb6  9.Nbd2  Qxb2 ?  10.Nc4  Qxc3+  11.Kf1  ±  8.Nfd2  Nf4  9.exf4  gxh4  10.c3  += }
5. Be2 d6 6. O-O
{ The alternative is 6. h3, a move which has both advantages and disadvantages. At one time it was considered essential, but the present state of theory considers that White can manage without it. An example:   6.h3  c5  7.c3  and now if  Be6  we should remember this idea :  8.dxc5 !  dxc5  9.Nbd2  += }
6... c5
{ Or   6...Nh5  7.Bg5  h6  8.Bh4  g5   8...f5  9.c4  g5  10.Nfd2  Nf6  11.Bg3  +=  Gunina-Bodnaruk, Moscow 2009  9.Nfd2  gxh4   9...Nf6  10.Bg3  10.Bxh5  c5  11.c3  cxd4  12.cxd4  e5  13.d5  +=  Montani-Smith, Presolana 2011. }
7. c3
{ 7.h3  is again an interesting alternative for White. The idea against Qb6 is the same, except that White plays h2-h3 instead of c2-c3. The ideas are similar and White usually ends up playing c2-c3 in any case, transposing:  Qb6  and now  8.Nc3 !?  sacrifices a pawn; it does not seem to grant White any advantage after:   8.Na3  Bf5   8...Qxb2  9.Nc4  +=  9.Nc4  Qc7  10.c3 =   8.Nbd2 !  is the right move, just as in the main game:  Be6   8...Bf5  9.dxc5  Qxc5  10.Rc1 =  9.Ng5   9.dxc5 !?  Qxc5  10.e4  9...Bd7  10.Nc4  Qc7  11.a4   11.c3  11...b6  12.c3  Nc6  with complex play, Macieja-McShane, Drammen 2005  8...cxd4   8...Qxb2  9.Nb5  Nd5   9...Na6  10.a3  cxd4  11.exd4  Bf5  12.Bd3  Rfc8  13.Rb1  Qa2  14.Bxf5  gxf5  15.Nh4  Qxc2  16.Qxc2  Rxc2  17.Nxf5  ∞  10.Rb1  Qxa2  11.Ra1  Qb2  12.Rb1 =  9.exd4  Qxb2  10.Nb5  Nc6  11.Bd3  Bf5   11...a6  12.Rb1  Qxa2  13.Ra1  Qb2  14.Rb1 =  12.a3  Rfc8  13.Bxf5  gxf5  14.Qd3  but White has compensation; }
7... Qb6
{ One of the critical ideas against the London System is for Black to play Qb6, putting pressure on the b2-pawn, which is vulnerable following the development of the c1-bishop. We shall see that this plan is used at a very early stage in some other variations, but here too it is quite a common continuation. Sometimes Black prepares the move Qb6 with Be6, to prevent White from playing Qb3.  Once again it is possible to play   7...Nh5 !?  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  g5  10.Nfd2  Nf4   10...cxd4  11.cxd4  Nf4  12.exf4  gxh4  13.Nf3   13.Nb3  a5  14.a4  Nc6 =  Jovanic-Jovanovic, Zadar 2011.  13...h3  14.g3  I prefer White here, despite the position being close to equal;  11.exf4  gxh4  12.dxc5   12.d5 !  +=  12...dxc5  13.Nf3  +=  Nguyen Thi-Franklin, Budapest 2010  The most popular alternative to playing 7. Qb6 is   7...Be6  With this move Black wants to prevent White from defending the b2-pawn with Qb3, in response to Blacks Qb6. Now  8.dxc5 !  is White's best move, e.g.  dxc5  9.Nbd2  Nc6  10.h3  Bf5   10...a6  11.a4  Qb6  12.Ng5  Bd5  13.e4  and White is better, as in Prié-Llaneza, San Sebastian 2009   10...Qb6  11.Qc2  Rfd8  12.Ng5  ±  Pham Le-Van der Merwe, Mardin 2011  11.Re1  a6  12.a4  h6  13.Nc4  +=  Prié-Apicella, Liverpool 2009. }
8. Nbd2
{ This indirect defence of the pawn is possible because White has castled quickly on the sixth move, instead of playing h2-h3. This enables White to avoid the lines with Qb3 and the subsequent exchange of queens, which many players dislike, although Whites chances are not worse in that case. }
8... Bf5
{ A recommendation of Houdini.  Most games have continued with   8...Be6  instead.  9.e4 !?   9.dxc5  Qxc5   9...dxc5  10.Ng5  +=  Bd7  11.Nc4  10.e4  +=   9.Ng5  Bd7  10.Nc4  Qc7  This is the difference. Without the exchange on c5 Black has the c7-square for the queen:  11.a4   11.h3  b6   11...h6  12.Nf3  and again we have several examples from the elite:  Bf5   12...b6  13.dxc5   13.Bd3  Bc6  14.Ncd2  Ne4  15.Nxe4  Bxe4  16.Qe2 =  Jussupow-Topalov, Las Palmas 1993  13...Qxc5   13...bxc5  14.Nxd6 !  exd6  15.Bxd6  Qc8  16.Bxf8  Bxf8  17.Ne5  +=  14.Nxd6 !  exd6  15.Bxd6  Qc8  16.Bxf8  Bxf8  17.Ne5  +=  In general the idea of Nxd6 is good for White;   12...Be6  13.Rc1   13.Ncd2  cxd4  14.exd4  13...Nbd7  14.Bd3  Rac8 =  Khismatullin-Sutovsky, Moscow 2008  13.Bh2  Nbd7  14.a4  Rad8  15.a5 =  Karpov-Gelfand, Cap d'Agde 1994;  12.Re1   12.Bf3  Bc6  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.Nxd6  exd6  15.Bxd6  Qc8  16.Bxf8  Bxf8  17.Bxc6  Qxc6  18.Qf3  ∞  12...Bc6   12...h6  13.Nf3  Bc6 =  13.Bf1   13.dxc5  bxc5  14.Nxd6  exd6  15.Bxd6  +=  13...Nbd7 =  Prié-Favarel, Pau 2012;  11...h6  12.Nf3  Nh5  13.Bg3 ?!   13.d5 =  13...Nxg3  14.hxg3 =  Karpov-Gelfand, Cap d'Agde 1994;  9...Qxb2  10.d5  Bg4  11.Nc4  Qb5  12.a4   12.Nxd6  Qd7  12...Qd7  13.Qc2  with compensation for White. This is similar to the Vaganian Gambit in the Trompowsky,which we shall study later;   8...Qxb2 ?  9.Nc4 !  This shows why it is better to castle instead of playing h2-h3, since if the white king were still on e1 Black would take on c3 with check.  Qb5   9...Qxc3  10.Rc1  Qb4  11.Rb1  Qc3  12.Rb3  +-  10.Nxd6  ±   8...cxd4  has also been played, for instance  9.Nc4 !?   9.exd4  +=  9...Qd8  10.exd4  Nd5  11.Bd2   11.Bg3 !?  11...Nc6 =  De Prado-Hoffman, Lisbon 2014 }
9. Nc4 { Also playable is   9.Qb3  Nc6  10.h3 =  Or   9.dxc5  Qxc5  10.h3 = }
9... Qc7 10. h3
{ 10.dxc5  Qxc5  11.h3 =  now it is not so good to play   11.Nxd6  exd6  12.Bxd6  Qc8  13.Bxf8  Bxf8  when the situation is unclear. }
10... Nbd7 11. a4
{ Other options for White are:   11.Ncd2  e5  12.Bh2  Rfe8   12...e4  13.Ng5  +=  h6  14.g4 !  hxg5  15.gxf5  gxf5  16.Nc4 !  Ne8  17.Nxd6  Nxd6  18.dxc5  +=  13.Nc4  ∞   11.Bd3  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  b5  13.Ncd2  Rab8 =   11.Bh2  Rfc8  12.a4  Nb6   12...h6 =  13.Na3   13.Ncd2  +=  13...a6  14.a5  +=  Anton-Chirila, Richardson 2013. }
11... Rac8 12. Bh2 Be6 { It was better to play   12...Rfd8 = } 13. Ncd2 cxd4
{ How should White recapture on d4 ? } 14. exd4
{ Here it was better to take with the knight:   14.Nxd4 !  Nc5   14...Bd5  15.c4  Bc6  16.Nxc6  Qxc6  17.a5  +=  15.Nxe6  Nxe6  16.a5  with advantage to White. }
14... Qb6 15. Qb1
{ Now   15.c4 !  Qxb2   15...Rfe8  16.Re1  +=  16.Rb1  Qa2  17.Rxb7  +=  was good. }
15... Rfe8 { Or   15...Bf5  16.Qa2  Be6  17.a5  Qc6  18.c4  d5  19.b3  += } 16.
a5
{ White has achieved a slight advantage; he has more space on the queenside and Black has nothing on the kingside. }
16... Qc7 17. Re1
{ Here it was good to play   17.Ng5 !  Bd5  18.c4  h6   18...Bc6 ?  19.d5  +-  19.Ngf3  Bxf3  20.Nxf3  e5  21.dxe5  Nxe5  22.Nxe5  dxe5  23.b4  with advantage to White, thanks to his pawn majority and space advantage on the queenside. }
17... Bh6 18. Bd3
{ Also good for White were 18. c4 and 18. Bf1, maintaining the advantage. }
18... Bd5 19. Re2
{ This allows Black to equalise.  With   19.c4 !  Bxf3  20.Nxf3  e5  21.b4  exd4   21...e4  22.Bxe4  Nxe4  23.Rxe4  Qxc4  24.Bxd6  22.a6 !  White would have kept the advantage. }
19... e5 20. dxe5
{ Now if   20.c4  Black equilises with  Bxf3  21.Nxf3  Nh5 = } 20... dxe5 21.
Qe1 { Or   21.a6  b6  22.Bb5 = } 21... Qc6 { 21...Rcd8 =  was better. } 22. Ne4
{ This move hands the advantage over to Black. It was essential to take the risk of grabbing the pawn with   22.Nxe5  Nxe5  23.Bxe5  Bxg2  24.Bxf6  Bxh3  25.Ne4  Rxe4  26.Bxe4  Qxf6  27.Bg2  Qg5  28.Qf1  Be6  when Black has compensation but White should not lose. }
22... Nxe4 23. Bxe4 Bxe4 24. Rxe4 f6
{ Black is better; the h2-bishop has been shut out of play, while the one on h6 is active; furthermore Black has threats of Nd7-c5-d3 and he commands the open d-file. }
25. Nd4 Qd5 26. Nc2 Nc5 27. Re2 Nd3 28. Qb1 Rcd8
{ Blacks advantage is clear. Whites forces are passive and Black dominates the whole board. In this game, for once the bishop on h6 is better than the one on h2. }
29. Ne1
{ This loses.  It was necessary to play   29.Ne3  although Black would maintain a clear advantage. }
29... Nc1 30. Rc2 Nb3 31. c4
{ If   31.Ra3  then  Qc4  with the threat of 32... Nd2  32.Nf3  Bf8  33.Ra2  Qd3  -+   31.Ra4  Qd1  -+ }
31... Qe4 { There was a simpler win with   31...Qd4 !  -+ } 32. Rc3 Qxb1 33.
Rxb1 Nxa5 34. b4 Bd2 35. Ra3 Nxc4 36. Rxa7 Rd7
{ Black has retained his extra pawn with the better position and should win the game without any great problems. }
37. g4 Red8 38. Kg2 b6 39. Rxd7 Rxd7 40. Nf3 Kf7 41. b5 Ba5 42. Rc1 Rc7 43. Rd1
g5 44. h4 h5 { It was simpler to play   44...h6  ∓ } 45. hxg5
{ 45.gxh5 !  g4  46.Ng5+ !?   46.Ng1  Na3  ∓  46...fxg5  47.hxg5  would have provided White with some counterplay, although Black should still win. }
45... hxg4 46. Nh4 fxg5 47. Nf5 Kg6 48. Ng3 Nd2 49. Nf1 Nxf1 50. Bxe5
{ 50.Kxf1  Kf5  -+  the game is decided in Black's favour. } 50... Re7 51. Rd6+
Kf5 52. Bd4 Nd2 53. Rf6+ Ke4 54. Bxb6 Bxb6 55. Rxb6 Kf5 56. Rb8 Re1 57. Rf8+
Kg6 58. Rg8+ Kf6 59. Rh8 Rb1 60. b6 Nf3 61. Rh1 Nh4+ 62. Kh2 Rxb6 63. Kg3 Kf5
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw a variety of alternatives available to both White and Black at an early stage of the game.  The idea of c7-c5 followed by Qb6, or Be6 first, is a very popular way for Black to attack b2, Whites weak point after the bishop has moved to f4. White can repel the attack on b2 with the move Nbd2 as long as he has castled early, and in this way he can avoid the line with Qb3 followed by the exchange of queens, which is not to the taste of many players, even though it is favourable to White.  The present state of theory allows White to play an early O-O and manage without the move h2-h3, as long as he has a good knowledge of how to reply to Nh5 by Black. It is important to remember the idea of the Nxd6 sacrifice, after taking on c5, which leaves White with a rook and two pawns for two pieces and usually favours White.  In the game, Black used a new idea with Bf5, which is also recommended by Houdini. White reacted well at first and retained the advantage, but then he let it slip and after the erroneous 22. Ne4 he was worse, eventually losing. }
*

