1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 { Or } 4... d6 5. Be2 c5 6. c3 Qb6 7. Qb3
{ This is one of the lines that some players with white tend to dislike, but Black can equalise only with accurate play. The exchange on b3 is better for White; after }
7... Be6 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. a3 { and now there are two ways for Black to play: }
9... Nc6 { the development of the knight on c6 is always a quite logical idea }
10. h3 O-O 11. Nbd2 Na5
{ Blacks most common plan; the idea is to play Nb3 and exchange the knight }
12. O-O Rfc8 13. Rfe1 Nb3 14. Nxb3 Bxb3 15. Nd2 Be6 16. Bf3
{ this hands White the advantage, since it helps his plan of advancing his centre pawns; it was better to play }
16... Rc7 17. Rad1
{ and although the position is equal, White has the slightly preferable game, because he can play e3-e4 and advance his centre pawns }
