{ One of the critical ideas against the London System is for Black to play Qb6, putting pressure on the b2-pawn, which is vulnerable following the development of the c1-bishop. We shall see that this plan is used at a very early stage in some other variations, but here too it is quite a common continuation. Sometimes Black prepares the move Qb6 with Be6, to prevent White from playing Qb3. }
8. Nbd2
{ This indirect defence of the pawn is possible because White has castled quickly on the sixth move, instead of playing h2-h3. This enables White to avoid the lines with Qb3 and the subsequent exchange of queens, which many players dislike, although White's chances are not worse in that case. }
8... Bf5 { A recommendation of Houdini. } 9. Nc4 Qc7 10. h3 Nbd7 11. a4 Rac8
12. Bh2 Be6 13. Ncd2 cxd4
{ How should White recapture on d4 ? Here it was better to take with the knight: }
14. Nxd4 Nc5 15. Nxe6 Nxe6 16. a5 { with advantage to White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the King’s Indian"]
[Black "Game 19 - Romero Holmes vs. Kortchnoi"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 c5
{ A more common move order is   5...d6  6.O-O  c5  7.c3  cxd4 } 6. c3 cxd4
{ Here we shall look at another line for Black where he takes on d4 at an early stage and then plays Nc6 and Be6. At this point White can recapture with either pawn: taking with the c-pawn is good in this position because the b1-knight has not moved yet, so it can develop on c3, where it stands better than on d2, with the possibility of playing Nb5 at some point. Taking with the e-pawn allows White to manage without playing h2-h3, since there is no longer any danger that the bishop will be exchanged. If Nh5 we have the move Be3 available, while if Nd5 we can play Bg3. }
7. exd4
{ Let us examine the recapture with the other pawn:   7.cxd4  and now  Qb6   7...d6  8.Nc3  b6   8...Nbd7  9.O-O  Nb6  10.h3   10.e4  +=  10...Nfd5 =  11.Bh2   11.Nxd5  Nxd5  12.Bh2 =  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  Be6  13.a4  Qc7  14.Qd2 =  Rogers-Ftacnik, Prague 1999.  9.O-O  Bb7  10.h3   10.Rc1  +=  10...Nbd7  11.Rc1   11.Qb3  +=  11...Rc8  12.Bh2   12.Qb3  +=  12...Nd5  13.Nxd5  Bxd5  14.Qa4  Rc7  15.Nd2 =  Gelfand-Golubev, Odessa 2008;  8.Qb3 !?  this was the choice of GM Danielsen, a specialist in the London System; although he gained an advantage, this does not seem to be White's best continuation. It is better to play   8.Qd2  Nc6  9.Nc3  d5  10.O-O  Bf5 =  Or   8.Nbd2 !?  Qxb2  9.Rb1  Qc3  10.O-O  and White has compensation.  8...Qxb3  9.axb3  d6  10.Nc3  Nc6  11.O-O  Nh5  12.Bg3  Nxg3  13.hxg3  Bd7  14.Rfc1  Rfc8  15.Ne1  Kf8  16.Nd3  f5  17.b4  Nd8  18.Bf3  e6  19.b5  d5 ?!   19...e5 =  20.Ra2  b6 ?!  21.Rca1  ±  Danielsen-Kjartansson, Kopavogur 2012 }
7... d6 8. O-O
{ White can also include h2-h3, although this is not necessary:   8.h3  Nc6  9.O-O  Be6   9...Nh5  10.Bh2  e5  11.dxe5 ?!   11.Re1  +=  11...dxe5 =  Kovacevic-Zufic, Rabat 2004.  10.Na3   10.Nbd2  Qb6  11.Qb1  Rac8  12.a4 =  Jovanic-Kozul, Zagreb 2011  10...Rc8  11.c4 ?!   11.Re1 =  11...d5  12.c5  Nd7   12...Ne4  13.Bb5   13.Qd2  13...Ndb8  14.Qd2 =  Ruiz-Recuero, Linares 2013 }
8... Be6
{ In a recent game Black unsuccessfully tried   8...Nd5  9.Bg3  Nc6  10.Nbd2  Bf5  11.Qb3  Nb6  12.d5   12.a4  +=  12...Na5 ?   12...Ne5 =  13.Qb5  Nd7  14.b4  Bxc3  15.Rac1  and White wins a piece with a decisive advantage, Dreev-Zviagintsev, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013   8...Nc6  is the usual move.  9.Nbd2   9.Na3  is interesting  9...h6   9...Be6  transposes to the game,  but   9...Qc7   9...Bf5  are interesting;   9...Re8  10.Nc4  Nd5  11.Bg3  e5  12.dxe5   12.Re1 !  +=  12...dxe5  13.Qb3 ?!   13.Re1  13...Nf4  14.Bxf4  exf4  15.Rad1  Qc7 =  Nikolic-Negi, Amsterdam 2007.  10.Re1   10.h3  10...e5 !?   10...Bf5 =  11.dxe5  Nh5  12.Be3  dxe5 =  Nguyen Anh-Szabo, Budapest 1999; }
9. Nbd2
{ An interesting alternative against this move order by Black is   9.c4 !?  d5  10.c5  Ne4  11.Nc3  b6 = }
9... Nc6
{ This is Black's plan: hold the centre, control the d5-square and try in the future to play e7-e5.  If   9...Qb6  then  10.Ng5  Bf5  11.Nc4  Qc7  12.Ne3  += }
10. Re1
{ One of the other co-authors games continued   10.Nc4  Nd5  11.Bd2   11.Bg3  was better  11...Rc8  12.Ng5   12.Re1  was better.  12...Bf5  13.Bf3  Nb6 =  De Prado-Rodriguez, Spain tt 2012.  Houdini's recommendation is   10.Bc4  Bxc4   10...Bf5  11.Nxc4  Rc8  12.Qe2 =  with an equal game   10.Ng5  Bf5  11.Nc4  h6  12.Nf3  Nd5  13.Bg3  Rc8  gives White no advantage either. }
10... a6 { 10...Rc8 =  would be normal. } 11. Bd3
{ Here it would be better for White to play   11.Bc4  with equality, trying to exchange Black's bishop, which will be very strong on d5. }
11... b5
{ Advancing this pawn is dubious. Instead, the thematic idea   11...Qb6 =  was better. }
12. a3
{ Here it was good to play   12.a4 !   12.h3  or  12.Qe2  , which gives White some advantage after:  Qb6   12...b4  was the move that I feared, but after  13.c4  d5  14.c5  Nh5  15.Be3  White has the advantage with his passed pawn on c5.  13.Be3  Qb7  14.Qe2  Rfb8   14...bxa4  15.Rxa4  +=  Qxb2 ?  16.Rb1  Qxc3  17.Ne4  Nxe4  18.Bxe4  ±  15.axb5  axb5  16.Rxa8  Rxa8  17.Bxb5  += }
12... Bd5 13. Ne4
{ Again   13.a4  +=  was good. This move was necessary, to create weaknesses on the queenside and try to dislodge the black bishop from d5. }
13... Nh5 { 13...Nd7  14.h4  / h5-> } 14. Bg5
{ A little better was   14.Be3  f5  15.Neg5  h6   15...f4  16.Bd2  +=  16.Nh4 !  Qe8   16...hxg5  17.Nxg6  g4  18.Nxf8  Qxf8  19.a4  ∞  17.Nh3  with complex play. }
14... Qd7
{ Here   14...h6 !  15.Be3  f5  was good, e.g.  16.Ng3  Nxg3  17.hxg3  e5  18.dxe5  dxe5 = }
15. Ng3 Nf6 16. h4
{ White tries to create threats on the kingside. Another interesting idea was   16.Nf1  with the idea of Ne3 to eliminate the annoying bishop on d5. }
16... Rfe8 17. h5
{ Consistent with the previous move, trying to open the kingside, but curiously the open h-file will eventually benefit Black ! }
17... Qg4 18. hxg6 hxg6 19. Be2
{ It was much better to play   19.Bxf6 !  Bxf6   19...exf6 !?  20.a4 !  b4   20...Rab8  21.axb5  axb5  22.Be4  Bxe4  23.Nxe4  Bg7  24.b4  +=  21.Be4  Bxe4  22.Rxe4  Qd7  23.d5  Ne5  24.Rxb4  with a slight advantage. }
19... Na5 { 19...Ne4 !? } 20. b4
{ This move cannot be good, because it leaves the c3-pawn weak and grants Black the strong square c4. It was better to play   20.Bxf6  Bxf6   20...exf6  ∞  21.Nd2  Qf4  22.Bf3  with equality. }
20... Nc4 21. Bxf6 exf6
{ 21...Bxf6  22.Ne5  Qc8   22...Qg5  23.Nxc4  bxc4  24.Bf3  Kg7  is equal, although I prefer Black, since he can create threats along the h-file.  23.Nxc4  Bxc4  24.Bxc4  Qxc4  =+ }
22. Ne5
{ After   22.Nd2  Qd7  23.Nxc4  bxc4  24.Qd2  Qc6  Black is still better: he has the bishop pair and can mobilise his kingside pawns; he also commands the h1-a8 diagonal. }
22... Qf4 { 22...Qg5  =+ } 23. Nxc4 bxc4 24. Bf1
{ White's pieces are becoming very passive. White should play more actively with   24.Qa4 !  Qd2  25.Qa5  Bc6  26.Red1  Qxc3  27.Rac1  Qb3  28.Bxc4 = }
24... Rxe1 25. Qxe1 f5
{ 25...Bh6  26.Qe7  Kg7  27.Ne2  Qh4  28.Qxd6  Bd2 !  was also good, and now:  29.Qxd5 ??   29.Qg3  Qxg3  30.Nxg3   30.fxg3  Be3+  31.Kh2  Rh8#  30...Bxc3  =+   29.Qh2  Qe4  30.Qg3  Rh8  and Black has the advantage with his very active pieces and threats along the h-file, in return for a single pawn.  29...Rh8  -+ }
26. Ra2
{ 26.Qe7 !?  ⇆  was necessary, trying to activate the queen a little and harass the black pieces, but after  Bf8  27.Qc7  Qd2  28.Qa5  Be6  Black retains the advantage. }
26... Bf6 27. Re2 Kf8
{ Kortchnoi wants to avoid the exchange of rooks, but this was not necessary, because Black would have a won endgame after   27...Kg7 !  28.Re8  Rxe8  29.Qxe8  Qd2  30.Qe3  Bg5  31.Qxd2  Bxd2  32.Ne2  f4  33.f3  f5  34.a4  Bc6  35.a5  g5 !  with the plan of g5-g4 and f4-f3, dislodging the white knight, with a decisive advantage. }
28. a4
{ A little better was   28.Re3  Bh4  29.Qc1  Kg7  30.Re1  Bxg3  31.fxg3  Qxg3  32.Qe3  Qh4  ∓ }
28... Qh4
{ Black now has a decisive advantage. There are several plans: Kg7 and Rh8, or Bf6-g5-f4, followed by Kg7 }
29. b5
{ There was no salvation in   29.a5  Bg5  30.Nh1  Bf4  31.Ng3  Kg7  32.Re8  Rxe8  33.Qxe8  Bxg3  34.fxg3  Qxg3  -+ }
29... axb5 30. axb5 Rb8
{ The idea is to force White to move either his queen or his rook, so that White cannot respond to Kg7 with Re8; in that case Black's attack along the h-file will be impossible to parry. }
31. Qb1 Kg7 32. Qb4
{ White would fail to save the game with   32.Re3  Rh8  33.Nxf5+  gxf5  34.Rh3  Qe4  35.Qxe4  fxe4  -+ }
32... Rh8 33. f4 Qxg3 34. Qxd6 Qxc3 35. Qxd5 Qxd4+ 36. Qxd4 Bxd4+
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we have seen a line which is quite solid for Black but not very common, based on cxd4, followed by Nc6 and Be6, trying to command the centre and deploy the black bishop on d5.  It is essential for White to keep in mind the possibility of recapturing on d4 with the c-pawn, instead of the e-pawn, especially if White's queens knight has not yet moved and can go directly to c3, where it is better placed than on d2.  However, if White recaptures on d4 with the e-pawn he can manage without playing h2-h3, since his queens bishop is in no danger of being exchanged.  In the game, White should have played a2-a4 to weaken Black's queenside and especially to be able to exchange or dislodge the strong d5-bishop.  Black gained the advantage of the bishop pair and following the opening of the h-file he used it to attack and win the game. }
*

