[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. h3 c5 7. c3 b6
{ The line with c7-c5 and b7-b6 is the most common, by far, among King's Indian players when faced with the London System. In some books this is also called the Réti Reversed.  After   7...Nbd7  8.O-O  there are other options instead of the normal 8b6:  Rb8 !?   8...Ne4 !?  9.Bh2   9.Nbd2  +=  9...b6  10.Nbd2   10.Nfd2 !?  10...Nxd2  11.Qxd2  Re8   11...Bb7 =  12.e4  Bb7  13.Bd3   13.d5  13...cxd4  14.cxd4  e5 =  De Prado-Suarez, A Corua 2013.  9.a4   9.c4  +=  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Nd5  11.Bd2   11.Bh2  11...N7f6  12.c4  Nc7  13.Nc3  +=  De Prado-Perera, Linares 2013 }
8. O-O Bb7 9. Nbd2 Nc6
{ The move   9...Nbd7  which we shall see in the following games, is more common. It would seem that the knight is better on d7, since it leaves the diagonal open for the bishop on b7. }
10. Bh2
{ Nowadays this is the most common move. Sometimes White plays 10. a4 but ends up transposing. The main alternative is   10.Re1  and now:  Nd7   10...Re8  11.Bh2  Rc8  12.dxc5   12.Rc1   12.Qb3  12...bxc5 =  Gonzalez-Jerez, Burgos 2003   10...Qd7  11.Bh2  Rac8  12.a3  Rfd8  13.e4  cxd4  14.cxd4  d5 =  Pri-Lagarde, Belfort 2010.  11.Bh2  e5 ?   11...Rc8  12.Rc1  +=  12.dxe5 ?   12.Nc4 !  ±  12...Ncxe5  13.Nxe5  Nxe5  14.Nf3  Qe7 =  Vysochin-Kurnosov, Internet 2004; }
10... Rc8
{ 10...cxd4  11.exd4  Bh6  12.a4   12.Re1 !  is better and if Black follows the same plan with  Nd5  13.Bf1  Bf4  14.Bxf4  Nxf4  15.g3  White is left with the advantage; the f1-bishop will be redeployed on g2 and the absence of the black bishop from g7 can make itself felt  12...Nd5 !?   12...Qc7 =  13.Re1  Bf4  14.Ne4   14.Bc4  +=  14...Bxh2+  15.Kxh2  e6  16.Qd2  +=  Kamsky-Ftacnik, Manila 1990   10...Qd7  has also been played, e.g.  11.a4   11.Re1  11...Rfd8  12.Nc4   12.Bb5  12...Rac8  13.Qb3   13.a5  13...Ne4  14.Rfd1 ?!   14.d5  +=  14...d5 =  Grachev-Korobov, Pardubice 2007. }
11. a4 { The alternatives 11. Bb5 and 11. Re1 are also good. } 11... cxd4
{ Let us examine some alternatives:   11...Nd7 ?!  12.Re1   12.d5 !  Nce5  13.Nxe5  Nxe5  14.e4  +=  12...d5  13.Qb3  e6 =  E. Alvarez-Teske, Pardubice 2011   11...Qc7  12.Re1  Rfd8  13.Bc4  e6  14.Bf1 !?   14.Qe2  +=  14...Qe7 =  Stripunsky-G.Shahade, Philadelphia 2012;   11...Na5 ?!  12.Nb3   12.b4 !  +=  12...Nxb3  13.Qxb3 =  Pham Le-Cao, Jakarta 2012;   11...Rc7 ?  12.a5 !  cxd4   12...Nxa5  13.dxc5  +=  13.axb6  axb6  14.exd4  +=  Bellon-Calvo, Spain 1993. }
12. exd4 Na5
{ Once again we have further options for Black to consider:   12...Nd5  13.Bc4   13.Re1  Na5  14.Bf1   14.Bb5  14...a6  15.Ra3  +=  Bellon-Sion,Spain 1993  13...Nb8 ?   13...Na5  +=  14.Re1  Nd7  15.Qb3  N7f6  16.a5  ±  Kamsky-Kasimdzhanov, Moscow 2007;   12...Re8  13.Nc4   13.Bb5   13.Re1  13...Ba6   13...Qc7  14.Re1  d5  15.Nce5  +=  Burmakin-Cocchi, Ortisei 2013;   12...Qd7  13.Nc4   13.Bb5  +=   13.Re1  +=  13...Nd8  14.Ne3  Bh6 =  Hoang Thi-Gu Xiaobing, Subic Bay 2009; }
13. Re1 Bh6
{ This is an idea that Black should keep in mind, since from h6 the bishop tries to control the f4-square and after Nd5 he can play Bf4 or Nf4. }
14. b4
{ 14.h4  is interesting  (with the idea of Ng5)  , e.g.  Nd5  15.Ng5  e5  16.dxe5  dxe5  17.Bf1  += }
14... Nc6 15. Qb3
{ The white position is more pleasant, with the advantage on the queenside.  If   15.a5  then  bxa5  16.b5   16.bxa5  Nxa5 =  16...Nb8  17.Qb3  a6  18.c4  axb5  19.Qxb5  Bxf3  20.Nxf3  Nc6 = }
15... e5 { If   15...Qc7  then  16.Rad1  += } 16. dxe5
{ The alternative was   16.Nc4  Ne4 !  17.dxe5  Nxe5  and now:  18.Nfxe5 ?!   18.Bxe5  dxe5  19.Rad1   19.Nfxe5  Qh4  =+   19.Ncxe5  Rxc3  =+  19...Qf6  20.Ncxe5  Rxc3 =   18.Ncxe5  dxe5  19.Bxe5  Nd2 !  20.Nxd2  Bxd2  21.Red1  Qg5  22.Bf1  Qxe5  23.Rxd2  Rxc3  24.Qb2  Qc7  25.a5 =  18...dxe5  19.Bxe5  Qd5  =+ }
16... Nxe5 { If   16...dxe5  then  17.Nc4  ± } 17. Rad1
{ 17.c4  Nxf3+  18.Nxf3  Bg7  19.Rad1  Ne4 = } 17... Qc7 18. Nxe5
{ This exchange leads to equality; it seems better to wait, leaving the weak pawn on d6. For example:   18.c4  Rfe8  19.Bf1  with a complex position. }
18... dxe5
{ A risky decision, since White is allowing his kingside pawn structure to be damaged. Instead, }
19. Bf3 { 19.c4  is equal. } 19... Bxd2 20. Rxd2
{ 20.Bxe5  fails to  Qe7  21.Rxd2  Bxf3  22.gxf3  Ne4 !  23.Rd5   23.fxe4   23.Rxe4  23...Ng5  and Black recovers the pawn with a very good position. }
20... Bxf3 21. gxf3 Rfe8
{ There was nothing wrong with taking on c3:   21...Qxc3  22.Qxc3  Rxc3  23.Kg2 =   23.Bxe5  Rxf3  24.Kg2  Rf5  25.Rd6  Nh5  26.Rd7  Ra8  ∞ }
22. Re3 Re6 { A slip.   22...Re7  was good, with equality } 23. f4 exf4
{ This loses. It was necessary to play   23...Rd8  24.Rxd8+  Qxd8  25.fxe5  Nd5  26.Re1  Qg5+  27.Bg3  Ne7  28.Kh2  Nf5  29.Qd5  Kg7  and despite being a pawn down Black has good drawing chances, since his knight is so strong, the position is blocked and the white king is weak. }
24. Rxe6 fxe6 25. Qxe6+ Kg7 26. Rd6 Rf8 27. Bxf4 Qxc3
{ 27...Qf7  28.Be5  Qxe6  29.Rxe6  Black is in zugzwang and loses. } 28. Be5
Qf3 29. Qg4
{ Black resigned, in view of 29. Qxg4+ 30. hxg4 h6 31. f4 g5 32. f5 Rf7 33. Kg2. Black is in zugzwang and White wins by bringing his king to the queenside.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@We have looked at the line which is the most popular with King's Indian players and which is one of the most solid against the London System, where Black plays c7-c5 and b7-b6.  In this game Black played Nc6, which is unusual. It seems better to play Nd7 and leave the diagonal of the b7-bishop open. White played solidly with c2-c3, followed by a2-a4, b2-b4 and Qb3, with the initiative on the queenside.  Remember the ideas for White with Re1 or Bb5. In the game, after Bh6, which is an idea that Black should keep in mind, it would have been interesting for White to play h2-h4, with the idea of Ng5. After Blacks e7-e5, Nc4 would have been interesting for White.  Later, it would have been better for White not to exchange knights on e5, since this led to equality. Black slipped up by playing 22... Re6, not seeing White's response 23. f4, after which taking the pawn on f4 landed Black in a lost position. }
*

