1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. h3 c5 7. c3 b6
{ The line with c7-c5 and b7-b6 is the most common, by far, among King's Indian players when faced with the London System. In some books this is also called the Réti Reversed. }
8. O-O Bb7 9. Nbd2 Nc6 10. Bh2 Rc8 11. a4
{ The alternatives 11. Bb5 and 11. Re1 are also good. } 11... cxd4
{ Let us examine some alternatives: } 12. exd4 Na5
{ Once again we have further options for Black to consider: } 13. Re1 Bh6
{ This is an idea that Black should keep in mind, since from h6 the bishop tries to control the f4-square and after Nd5 he can play Bf4 or Nf4. }
14. b4 Nc6 15. Qb3
{ The white position is more pleasant, with the advantage on the queenside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the King’s Indian"]
[Black "Game 21 - Kamsky vs. Svidler"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4
{ We shall see that on move 10 White could play Bc4, but if White wants to place his bishop there it is usually better to do so in one move, rather than first playing Be2. Some examples:   3.h3  Bg7  4.Bf4  O-O  5.Nbd2  d6  6.e3  Nbd7  7.c3  c5  8.Bc4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  10.Qe2   10.Re1  a6  11.a4  Bc6  12.Qe2  +=  Dgebuadze-Antic, Charleroi 2005  10...Qc7   10...Rc8  11.a4  Re8  12.Bh2  h6  13.Bb5  cxd4  14.exd4  +=  Ljubojevic-Piket, Monaco 1997  11.Bh2  Rae8  12.e4  cxd4  13.cxd4  e5  14.Rac1  +=  and White gained a smooth victory in Capablanca-Réti, London 1922. }
3... Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. h3 b6 6. Nbd2 Bb7
{ I faced a similar plan after   6...c5  7.e3  d6  8.a4  Nbd7  9.Be2  cxd4  10.exd4  Nd5  11.Bg3   11.Bh2  11...Bh6  12.Bc4   12.O-O  Nf4  13.Re1  Nxe2+ ?  14.Qxe2  ±  12...Nf4  13.O-O  Bb7  14.Re1  e6  De Prado-Cuenca, Maspalomas 2012 }
7. e3 c5 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Nbd7
{ In the previous game we saw Nc6. The development of the knight to d7 is the more popular continuation, since it leaves the diagonal of the b7-bishop open. }
10. Re1
{ There are several possible move orders, such as with 10. Bh2 or 10. Bc4; however, if White wants to develop the king's bishop to c4 it is preferable to do so in one move, as indicated in the note to move 3. The most popular move here is 10. a4, which we shall look at in the next few games. }
10... a6
{ 10...Qc7  11.Bh2  Rfe8  12.a4  a6  13.Bc4  Qc6  14.e4  +=  Prié-Apicella, Belfort 2010. }
11. a4 cxd4
{ We shall view Black's options of 11... Qc7, 11... Ra7 or 11... Rc8 in the following games. }
12. exd4 Nd5
{ We have already come across the plan that Black carries out in this game. It is clearly to Svidler's liking, since he had already played it in an earlier game, which continued   12...Rc8  13.Bh2   13.Bc4  +=  13...Bh6  again we see this idea for Black, taking control of the h6-c1 diagonal and the f4-square, together with Nd5  14.Bd3   14.h4  with the idea of Ng5, is a good plan to counter Black's idea;  14...Re8  15.Ne4  Nxe4  16.Bxe4  Bxe4  17.Rxe4  Nf6 =  Apicella-Svidler, Paris 2004  Black has also played   12...Re8  13.Bf1   13.Qb3  +=  13...Qc7  14.Bh2  h6  15.Qb3  +=  Hertneck-Swinkels, Amsterdam 2013. }
13. Bh2 Bh6
{ A plan which is familiar to us by now. Black's idea is to seize the f4-square and the h6-c1 diagonal. On g7 the bishop usually has little to do, faced with Whites solid pawn chain b2-c3-d4. }
14. Bf1
{ I do not think this is the best move.   14.Ne4 !  seems good, e.g.  N7f6   14...Bf4  15.Bxf4  Nxf4  16.Bf1  +=   14...Nf4  15.Bf1  +=  15.Neg5  and I prefer White.  If   14.h4  then  Bf4 =  Also interesting is   14.Qb3  Nf4   14...Bf4  15.c4  Bxh2+  16.Nxh2  Nf4  17.Bf3  Bxf3  18.Ndxf3  +=   14...N7f6  15.c4  +=  15.Bf1  with a slight advantage to White. }
14... a5 15. Nc4
{ Now   15.h4 !?  was definitely good, e.g.  Bf4   15...N7f6  16.Ng5  Bg7  17.Qb3  +=   15...Nf4  16.Ng5  +=  16.Bxf4  Nxf4  17.Ne4  +=  Also playable is   15.Qe2  Ba6  16.c4  N7f6  17.Ne4  Re8  18.Rad1 = }
15... N7f6 16. Na3
{ Kamsky tries to exploit the square b5, weakened by Black's move a7-a5. }
16... Bf4
{ 16...Rc8  17.Nb5  Nc7  18.c4  Nxb5  19.axb5  with a balanced position. } 17.
Bxf4 Nxf4 18. g3 { Or   18.Nb5  Ne6  19.Nh2  +=  with the idea of Ng4. } 18...
N4d5 19. Bg2
{ Kamsky has recycled his bishop to g2, to oppose Black's bishop on b7. The position is equalised. }
19... e6 20. Qd2 Kg7 21. Nh2 Rb8 22. Ng4 Nxg4 23. hxg4 h6
{ White would like to use the h-file for attack, but Black prevents this. } 24.
Nb5 Nc7 25. c4 Bxg2 26. Kxg2 d5
{ An alternative was   26...Nxb5  27.cxb5   27.axb5  d5 =  27...Qg5  28.Qxg5  hxg5  29.d5  exd5   29...e5 ?  30.Rac1  Rbc8  31.Rc6  ±  30.Rad1  Rfc8  31.Rxd5  Rc4  32.b3  Rc3 = }
27. Qf4 Nxb5 28. cxb5 Qf6 29. Qe3 Rbc8 30. Rac1 Qg5 31. Qxg5 hxg5
{ The ending is equal, although not lacking in subtleties. White probed for a while }
32. Kf3
{ It would be bad to play   32.Rc6 ?  Rxc6  33.bxc6  Kf6  34.Rc1  Ke7  35.c7  Kd7  =+ }
32... Kf6 33. b3 Ke7 34. Ke3 Kd7 35. Kd2 Rxc1 36. Rxc1 Rc8 37. Rh1
{ Trying to enter via the open file. The pawn ending is drawn after   37.Rxc8  Kxc8  38.f4  gxf4  39.gxf4  Kc7  40.b4  f6  41.bxa5  bxa5  42.Kd3  Kd7  43.Kc2  Kc7  44.Kc3  since neither king can force an entry. }
37... Ke7 38. f4 gxf4 39. gxf4 Kf6 40. Rh7 Rf8 41. Kc3 Rc8+ 42. Kb2 Ke7
{ White's idea is to play Kb2-a3-b4 and then create a passed pawn, but this proves impractical, because in that case the black rook would become active along the c-file. }
43. Rh3
{ 43.g5  Rd8  44.Ka3  Ra8  45.b4  axb4+  46.Kxb4  Rc8 =  since if  47.a5 ?  Rc4+ }
43... Kd7 44. Rh2 Ke7 45. g5 Kd7 46. Rh7 Ke7 47. Rh3 Kd7 48. Ka3
{ Kamsky is trying all means possible to win, but Svidler defends well. } 48...
Kd6 49. Rh7 Ke7 50. Kb2 Rf8 51. b4
{ Finally ! This is the only possible plan, although it is not good enough to win. }
51... axb4 52. Rh2 Rc8 53. Rc2 Rc4 54. Kb3 Rxd4 55. a5
{ Kamsky finds this ingenious resource. The endgame was looking dead-drawn but has suddenly come to life. }
55... Rd3+
{ 55...bxa5 ?  56.b6  Rd3+  57.Kb2  b3  58.b7  bxc2  59.Kxc2  and White wins. }
56. Kb2 Kd7 57. a6 Ra3
{ Black has defended very well and the draw is very close } 58. Rc1 d4
{ After defending so well, Svidler blunders. This move is unnecessary. Instead,   58...Ra5  59.Kb3  Ra3+   59...Rxb5 ?  60.Ra1  +-  60.Kxb4  would give White some chances  the right move was   58...Rh3 !  59.Rc6  d4  60.Rxb6  Rh2+  61.Kb3  d3  62.Rb7+   62.a7 ??  d2  -+  62...Kc8  63.Rb6  Kd7  with a draw. }
59. Rc4 Kd6 { 59...d3  60.Rxb4  Ra5  61.Kc3  with advantage to White. } 60.
Rxb4 Ra5 61. Rb3
{ Kamsky acquiesces to the draw, but in fact he could have continued to press for a win with   61.Rxd4+ !  Kc5  62.Rd7  Rxb5+  63.Kc2  Ra5  64.a7  b5  65.Rxf7  and White retains an edge. }
61... Kc7 62. Rb4 Kd6 63. Rb3 Kc7 64. Rb4
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the main line of the system with c7-c5 and b7-b6, this time with Black playing Nbd7. Whites usual plan involves a2-a4, but in this game we saw the idea of Re1.  Black responded with cxd4 and the plan of Nd5 and Bh6, which we have already seen in other games and which is thematic. To counter this plan it is interesting to play h2-h4, with the idea of Ng5 or Ne4.  In the game, Kamsky came up with the interesting plan of bringing his knight to the b5-square, which Black had weakened by playing a7-a5. Whites Nh2, with the idea of Ng4, was also interesting.  Black equalised and in the rook ending, which seemed an easy draw, Kamsky managed to set some problems for Svidler after creating a passed pawn. }
*

