[Result "*"]

{ Oscar de Prado Rodriguez 2208-Jos Larrosa Vila 2265, Arteixo 2007  (7)  . }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c3 b6 4. Bf4 Bb7 5. e3 g6 6. h3 Bg7 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Be2
{ When Black uses this move order, with an early c7-c5 and b7-b6, we know that he is not going to play d7-d6 and e7-e5, so it is possible for us to develop the bishop to c4 or d3 immediately, which are squares to which the bishop usually moves anyway in the main line with Be2. On d3 the bishop supports e4; on c4 it controls d5 and after a later Qb3 it puts pressure on f7.  Let us examine   8.Bc4  and now:  d5   8...d6  9.O-O  Qd7  10.Re1  b5  11.Bf1  +=  Krumpacnik-Kveinys, Pula 2006  9.Bd3  Nc6  10.Qe2  Nd7  11.h4   11.O-O =  11...e5  12.dxe5  Ndxe5  13.h5  Re8  14.hxg6  hxg6  15.Nxe5  Nxe5  16.Bb5  Re6  17.Nf3   17.Bxe5  Bxe5  18.Nf3  Bg7 =  17...Nxf3+  18.Qxf3  a6  19.Bd3  g5 !?  20.Bg3  Qe7 ?!   20...Bc6 =  21.Qf5  d4 ??   21...Kf8  22.Rh7  +=  22.Rh8+  1-0 Olbrich-Voiska, Germany Frauenbundesliga 2000;  The other option is   8.Bd3  with the possible continuations:  d5   8...d6  9.O-O  Nbd7  10.Qe2   10.Bh2  Qc7  11.e4  e5  12.d5  Nh5  13.Re1  Bh6  14.Bf1   14.a4  +=  14...Ng7   14...Nf4 =  15.g4  +=  Ipatov-Vlashki, Sofia 2010  10...Re8   10...cxd4  11.exd4  e5 !  12.dxe5  dxe5 =  11.e4   11.Bh2  e5  12.dxe5  Nxe5  13.Nxe5  dxe5  14.Rfd1  +=  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  e5  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.Be3 =  Kamsky-Svidler, Moscow 2008;  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Qe2  Nd7  11.Ba6  Qc8  12.Bxb7  Qxb7  13.Rad1 =  Chubar-Dziuba, Warsaw 2013; }
8... d6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. a4 a6 11. Bh2
{ In this position there are other ideas, such as 11. Re1 or 11. Qb3. For example:   11.Qb3  and now:  Rb8 !?  a surprise.  I have also faced   11...Ra7  12.Rfe1   12.Bc4 !  +=  12...Qa8  13.Bf1   13.c4  Ne4  14.d5  13...h6  14.Bh2   14.Rac1  14...Ne4  15.Nxe4  Bxe4  16.Nd2  Bc6  17.Qa3  Re8  18.Nc4  Qb8  19.b4  cxb4   19...Rc8  20.Qxb4  +=  De Prado-Casares, Lugo 2010;   11...Rc8  12.Rfe1  Rc7  13.Qa3   13.Bc4 !  +=  is better, e.g.  Qa8  14.Ng5  Bd5  15.e4  Bxc4  16.Qxc4  h6  17.Ngf3  Rfc8  18.d5  +=  13...Qa8  14.b4   14.c4 !  Ne4  15.Nxe4  Bxe4  16.d5  Bxf3  17.Bxf3  +=  14...Re8  15.Bh2  Ne4 =  De Prado-P. Garcia, Padron 2013.  12.Rfe1   12.Rfd1  Nd5  13.Bg3  Nc7   13...cxd4  14.exd4  a5 =  14.Qc2  Hort-Nikolic, Vinkovci 1968   14.e4  +=  12...Qc7   12...b5 !?  was interesting:  13.axb5  axb5  14.Qc2   14.Bxb5  Bc6  15.c4  Bxb5  16.cxb5  Qb6 =   14.Ra7  Qb6  15.Rea1  c4  16.Qc2 =  14...Nd5  15.Bg3  Qb6  16.e4  Nc7  with equality  13.Bh2  Bd5   13...e5  14.Bc4  h6  15.Rad1   15.dxe5  Nxe5  16.Nxe5  dxe5  17.Red1  +=  15...g5  16.dxe5  Nxe5  17.Nxe5  dxe5  +=  Vujadinovic-Stamatovic, Belgrade 2011  14.Qa3  Whites best move seems to be   14.Qc2  cxd4   14...Bb7  15.Bc4  15.exd4  b5  16.axb5  axb5  17.Ra6  14...b5  15.axb5  White would have fewer problems after   15.b4 !  c4   15...cxb4  16.cxb4 =  16.Bd1  Ne4  17.Nxe4  Bxe4  18.Nd2  Bc6  19.e4 =  15...axb5  16.dxc5 ?!  this move is dubious. At first sight it seems to leave the b5-pawn weak, but in reality Black will play b5-b4 and retain the advantage.  Instead, White could have kept the balance with   16.Qa5  Qxa5   16...Qb7  17.Qa6  Qxa6   17...Qc7  18.Qa5 =  18.Rxa6  c4 =  17.Rxa5  c4   17...b4  18.Bb5  +=  18.Rea1  Rfc8  19.g4 =  16...Nxc5 !  If   16...Qxc5  then  17.Qxc5  Nxc5  18.Ra7  with a slight advantage to White  17.Qb4 ?!   17.Qa7  was slightly better, e.g.  Rb7  18.Qa5  Rb6  19.Nd4  Nfe4  20.Nxe4  Bxe4  21.Qb4  Qb7  =+  17...Bxf3 ?  De Prado-Starostits, Ferrol 2013  the right way was   17...Bc4 !  18.Qa5   18.Bxc4  bxc4  19.Qxc4  Rxb2  =+   18.Nxc4  bxc4  19.Qxc4  Rxb2  =+  18...Qxa5  19.Rxa5  Bxe2  20.Rxe2  Nd3  with a slight advantage to Black; }
11... Rc8
{ Black has also tried   11...Ra7  Or   11...Re8  12.b4   12.Bc4 !?   12.Rc1 =  12...cxd4  13.cxd4  Rc8  14.Qb3   14.Rc1 =  14...Bd5   14...e5  15.Qb2  +=  Kotov-Nikolaevsky, Kiev 1957. }
12. Rc1
{ Not the best move. Practice has also seen   12.Qb3  Qc7  13.Rfd1  Qb8  14.c4  cxd4  15.Nxd4 ?!   15.exd4 =  15...Qa8 =  Burmakin-Kulkarni, Sort 2009  The best move is   12.Re1  and now:  d5   12...Re8  13.Bc4  e5  14.dxe5  Nxe5   14...dxe5  15.Qe2  +=  15.Nxe5  dxe5  16.Qe2  +=   12...Qc7  13.Bd3  Qb8  14.Qe2  Qa8  Black has lost a tempo  15.e4  cxd4  16.cxd4  and White is better, with a space advantage and the push e4-e5-e6 in the air, Raicevic-Vuckovic, Belgrade 2006;   12...Rc7  13.Bd3  Qa8  This plan is often used by White in the Réti Opening, hence this system is often called the Réti Reversed. White's plan is to try to play e3-e4, or c3-c4 and d4-d5, to shut down the bishop on b7, and then play on the kingside, taking advantage of the absence of so many black pieces on the queenside.  14.e4   14.c4 !?  +=  14...cxd4  15.cxd4  and now:  Ne8 ?!   15...e5  16.dxe5  Nxe5  17.Nxe5  dxe5  18.Bxe5  Rd7  and Black has compensation, but no more than that, despite which he went on to win in Mertens-Golod, Trieste 2011  16.Qb3   16.Qe2  +=  16...Rc8  +=  Stewart-Kohlweyer, Germany 2011;  13.Ne5   13.b4  +=  13...Nxe5  14.Bxe5  Nd7  15.Bxg7  Kxg7 =  Kallai-Maze, Montpellier 2007; }
12... Rc7
{ 12...cxd4  13.exd4   13.cxd4  Rxc1  14.Qxc1  Qa8 =  13...Qc7  14.Re1  Bh6  15.Bf1  with equality. }
13. b4
{ Or   13.Ne1  Qa8  14.Bf3  Rfc8 =  Nguyen Thanh-Nguyen Thien, Vietnam 2005.  White has also tried   13.Qb3  Qa8  14.Rfd1  Bc6   14...Ne4 =  Alcaraz-Lara, Cullera 2012  15.Qa3   15.c4  +=  15...Rfc8  Vlzke-Pittelkow, Germany tt 1988.  But once again   13.Re1  with the idea of a future e3-e4 or c3-c4, is White's best idea. }
13... cxb4
{ 13...Qa8  14.bxc5  bxc5  15.c4  Ne4  16.d5  Nc3  17.Qe1  Na2  18.Rb1  Nb4  , with equality. }
14. cxb4 Nd5
{ This seemingly active move, which attacks the b4-pawn and threatens 15... Nc3, is the cause of problems for Black. It was better to play   14...Rxc1  15.Qxc1  Qa8  16.Qb2  Rc8  17.Rc1  with equality. This type of position is very solid. }
15. Qb3 Qc8
{ Black was relying on this, thinking that if he gained control of the c-file he would stand slightly better. He had no inkling of the danger hanging over him. It was not too late to play   15...a5  16.bxa5  bxa5  17.Qb5   17.Bc4  N7b6 =  this is the point of playing a7-a5, to free the b6-square  17...N7f6 = }
16. Rxc7 Qxc7 { If   16...Nxc7  then  17.Rc1  += } 17. Bc4 N5f6
{ This is bad, although at first sight it just looks normal. Black didn't want to weaken d6 by playing   17...e6  but this was the only possible move, when White would retain some advantage after  18.b5 !  and now:  a5   18...axb5  19.Bxb5  Rc8  20.Ne4  e5   20...Bf8  21.Bxd7  Qxd7  22.Qxd5  ±  21.Rd1  with a clear advantage to White; the threat is to take on e5.  19.Ne4 !  Nxe3  20.Qxe3  Bxe4  21.Qxe4  Qxc4  22.Bxd6  Rd8   22...Rc8  23.Qb7 !  ±  without b4-b5 this variation would not work for White due to Qc6  23.Qb7 !  +=  . What should White play now ? }
18. Ng5
{ An unexpected leap, which gives White a decisive advantage. Black is unable to parry White's threats to break in on f7 or to sacrifice on e6. }
18... e6
{ This loses. It was essential to accept the loss of the f7-pawn with   18...Qc8  19.Bxf7+  Kh8  20.Bc4  although White's advantage should be decisive.  Instead,   18...Rc8 !?  19.Nxf7  b5  20.axb5  axb5  21.Nxd6+  bxc4  22.N6xc4  Qd8  23.Nb6+  Kf8  24.Nxc8  Qxc8  25.b5  would also give White a winning advantage. }
19. Bxe6 Nb8
{ There was no salvation for Black with   19...fxe6  20.Nxe6  Qc8   20...Qc6  21.Nd8+  Qd5  22.Nxb7  +-  21.Nxf8+  Bd5  22.Nxg6  hxg6  23.Qd3  +- }
20. Bxf7+ Rxf7 { 20...Kh8  21.Be6  Qc6  22.d5  +- } 21. Bxd6 Bd5
{ 21...Qd7  22.Qxf7+  Qxf7  23.Nxf7  Kxf7  24.Bxb8  +-   21...Qxd6  22.Qxf7+  Kh8  23.Qxb7  +- }
22. Bxc7 Rxc7
{ Desperation, but   22...Bxb3  23.Nxf7  Bxf7  24.Bxb8  was also losing. } 23.
Qb2 h6 24. Ngf3 Nbd7 25. Rc1
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the line with Rc8, where Black tries to play like in the Réti with Rc7 and Qa8, to put pressure along the long diagonal.  White should try to block this diagonal with e3-e4, or c3-c4 and d4-d5, and then play on the kingside, taking advantage of the fact that so many of the black pieces are absent on the other wing. The best reply for White is 12. Re1.  Although in the game Black equalised, it is worth noting how normal-looking moves such as Nd5 and Rc8, which might even appear to give Black the advantage, are bad, since the plan of Qb3, followed by the counterattack with Bc4 and Ng5, leaves White with the advantage. One would not think that this position holds so many dangers for Black.  Once again we can see that, in the London System, attacks can suddenly appear when Black is least expecting them. }
*

