1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c3 b6 4. Bf4 Bb7 5. e3 g6 6. h3 Bg7 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Be2
{ When Black uses this move order, with an early c7-c5 and b7-b6, we know that he is not going to play d7-d6 and e7-e5, so it is possible for us to develop the bishop to c4 or d3 immediately, which are squares to which the bishop usually moves anyway in the main line with Be2. On d3 the bishop supports e4; on c4 it controls d5 and after a later Qb3 it puts pressure on f7. }
8... d6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. a4 a6 11. Bh2
{ In this position there are other ideas, such as 11. Re1 or 11. Qb3. For example: }
11... Rc8 { The best move is } 12. Re1 { and now: } 12... Rc7 13. Bd3 Qa8
{ This plan is often used by White in the Réti Opening, hence this system is often called the Réti Reversed. White's plan is to try to play e3-e4, or c3-c4 and d4-d5, to shut down the bishop on b7, and then play on the kingside, taking advantage of the absence of so many black pieces on the queenside. }
