1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 d6 4. h3 c5 5. e3 Bg7 6. c3 Nbd7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O
b6 9. a4 a6 10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. Bh2 Qc7
{ The most common move in this position. Previously we saw Rc8 and we shall examine Ra7 and Qb8 in the following games. }
12. Re1
{ A very popular alternative is   12.Qb3  with several options:  Rab8   12...Rfb8 ?!  13.e4 !  b5   13...Nxe4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.Ng5  +-   13...Bxe4  14.Bc4 !  ±  14.e5 ?!   14.axb5  axb5  15.Ng5  c4  16.Qxb5 !  Bxe4  17.Qxc4  +=  14...c4   14...Bd5 =  15.Qc2   15.Qa3  +=  15...Ne8  +=  Prié-Huerga, San Sebastian 2009   12...Rac8  13.Rfe1  and again Black has various options:  Bd5   13...cxd4  14.exd4  e5  15.Bf1  +=   13...Qb8  14.Qa3  The best continuation is   14.e4 !  cxd4  15.cxd4  Qa8   15...Nxe4  16.Nxe4  Bxe4  17.Bxa6  ±  16.Bd3  +=  14...Qa8  15.Rec1   15.Bf1  Rfe8  16.Rad1  h6  17.Qb3  Bc6  +=  Guerrero-Perez, Orense 2006  15...Ne4  16.Nxe4  Bxe4 =  De Prado-Ramo, Barcelona 2006;  14.c4  Bb7  15.a5   15.d5  +=  15...bxa5  16.Qa3   16.d5  16...Rb8  17.b3   17.d5  17...Rfc8  18.Qxa5 =  Pri-Sanchez, Cap d'Agde 2008   12...cxd4  13.exd4  h6   13...Bh6  14.Rfe1  Ne4  15.Rad1  +=  14.Rfe1  +=  Wahono-Kasmiran, Jakarta 2012;   12...Bc6  is the most popular move:  13.Bc4   13.Rfd1  Qb7  14.Ne1 !?  played by grandmaster Megaranto,  but   14.c4 !  +=  looks better to me  14...b5   14...Rfe8  15.Nc4  Bd5  16.Bf3  Bxf3  17.Nxf3 =  Megaranto-Kasyan, Tashkent 2012   13.Rfc1  Bd5   13...Rfb8  14.Bc4  ±   13...Rfc8 =  14.Qa3   14.c4 !  Bb7  15.d5  +=  14...Bb7   14...b5 =  15.a5  b5 =  Gelle-Horvath, Hungary tt 1995   13.c4  e6   13...cxd4  14.exd4  a5 =  15.Nb1 !?  14.Rfd1   14.a5 !  bxa5  15.Qa3  Ne4  16.Nxe4  Bxe4  17.Rfd1  +=  14...Rfd8   14...a5 =  15.Rac1   15.a5  +=  15...Rab8  16.Nb1  Ne4  17.d5  exd5  18.cxd5  Bb7  19.Nfd2 =  Bruzón-Radjabov, Tromsø 2013  13...Qb7 ! =  San Marco-Picard, Issy-les-Moulineaux 2006;  13.Rfc1   13.Rfe1  b5  14.Qc2  cxd4  15.exd4  +=  13...b5  14.axb5  axb5  15.Ra7   15.Qc2  +=  15...Qb6  - Kosic-Berkes, Bizovac 2007;  Another idea is   12.Bd3 !?  but I think that Black equalises easily with  e5  Let us see:   12...Rad8  13.e4   13.Qe2  +=  13...c4  14.Bc2   14.Nxc4  +=  14...e5  15.Re1  Rfe8 =  Kamsky-Nyzhnyk, Moscow 2013  13.e4 !?   13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.Nxe5   14.Be2  Rad8  15.Nc4  Nxc4  16.Bxc4  Qc8 =  Malakhatko-Rjanova, St.Petersburg 2011.  14...dxe5  15.Be2  Ne4 =  Andersson-Moberg, Sweden tt 1999  13...Nh5   13...b5 =  14.dxe5  dxe5  15.Bc4  Nf4 =  Grachev-Bernasek, Pardubice 2006; }
12... Ne4
{ One of the co-author's games continued   12...Rfe8  13.Qb3   13.Bc4  +=  is better  13...Rac8  14.Bc4  e6  15.Rac1   15.Qd1  Bh6  16.Qe2  +=  is better  15...Bh6  16.Qd1  Qc6  17.Qe2 !?   17.Bf1 =  17...cxd4  18.cxd4  b5 ?  it is better to play   18...d5  19.Bxa6  Qxc1  20.Rxc1  Rxc1+  21.Nf1  Bxa6  22.Qxa6 =  19.axb5  axb5  20.Bxb5  Qxc1  21.Rxc1 ?  White could have won with the neat zwischenzug   21.Nc4 !!  Qxe1+  forced, since the queen is trapped  22.Nxe1  Bc6  23.Nxd6  Bxb5  24.Nxb5  with a decisive advantage to White; the big difference from the game is that this way the black rooks are kept out and White wins a second pawn  21...Rxc1+  22.Nf1  and, despite the position now being equal, I ended up losing in the game De Prado-Barlov, Ferrol 2012. }
13. Nxe4
{ White has also tried the thematic   13.Qb3  Nxd2   13...Bh6  14.d5  Nxd2  15.Nxd2  Nf6  16.c4  Rfb8  17.Bf3  Bg7  18.e4  Nd7  19.Be2  +=  Anastasian-Mirumian, Yerevan 1994  14.Nxd2  Rac8   14...Qc6  15.Bf3  Qc7  - Dorfman-Macieja, Elista 1998  16.d5  15.Bf1   15.d5 !  +=  15...Qc6  16.Rad1 =  Bruzon-Lorenzo, Manresa 2008   13.Rc1  Ndf6  14.c4  Rab8  15.Nb1  Nd7  16.Bd3 =  Hoffman-Ubilava, Candas 1992. }
13... Bxe4 14. Bf1
{ A move designed to defend g2 against a possible Qb7, in preparation for moving the knight to d2.  The main alternative is   14.Nd2  immediately and now:  Bc6   14...Bb7  15.Rc1   15.Qb3  15...Nf6  16.b4  Rfc8  17.Nc4  Bd5  18.dxc5  bxc5  19.a5  Bxc4  20.Bxc4  Qb7  21.Rb1 =  Ding Liren-Gupta, Subic Bay 2009.  15.Bf3   15.Bf1  Rfc8  16.b4  cxb4  17.cxb4  b5 =  Mitkov-Jancovic, Montreal 2009  15...b5   15...Qb7  16.Bxc6  Qxc6  17.Qf3  Qxf3  18.Nxf3 =  Balashov-Mikhalchishin, Klaipeda 1988  16.axb5  axb5  17.Qe2  Qb7 =  Schorr-Lputian, Chicago 1994 }
14... e5 { A good alternative was   14...Qb7  with a balanced position. } 15.
dxe5 { It was perhaps preferable to maintain the tension with   15.Rc1  ∞ }
15... Nxe5 { 15...dxe5  then  16.Qb3  += } 16. Nxe5
{ Black can equalise after   16.Nd2  Bc6  17.Nc4   17.e4  b5 =  17...d5 } 16...
dxe5 17. Qb3
{ Objectively the position is equal. Each side has an active bishop, but White's space advantage on the queenside and the pressure on e5 mean that White's play is simpler and it is easier for Black to go wrong. }
17... Bc6 18. Red1 Qb7 19. Qc4
{ 19.Rd6 !?  looks promising, e.g.  b5  not   19...Rfd8 ?  20.Bxa6 !  ±  20.Qa3  bxa4  21.Rad1   21.Qxc5  Qxb2   21.Rb1  Rfd8  22.Qxc5  Rxd6  23.Qxd6 =  21...Rfc8  22.Bg3  Rab8 = }
19... Rfe8 20. a5
{ The game has reached a key moment, one where Black needs to make a decision. When players with black arrive at this type of position, which is equal, they relax, thinking that they are in no danger, and this leads them into making mistakes. Or else they take too big a risk trying to win. Equality does not mean a draw. In general White usually has the initiative and the more comfortable game, while Black needs to stay alert. }
20... bxa5
{ And Black immediately commits an error, spoiling his pawn structure.  Instead,   20...Bb5  was good, e.g.  21.Qb3  Bxf1  22.Kxf1  b5  23.Qd5  Qc8  24.c4  but although the position is equal, White has a slight initiative   20...b5 !?  21.Qxc5  Bf8  22.Qb6  Qc8  23.e4  Bxe4 =  was also playable. }
21. Rxa5
{ White now has the advantage, in view of the weaknesses on a6 and c5. } 21...
Bb5 22. Qb3 Qc7 23. Bxb5 Qxa5
{ 23...axb5  24.Rxa8  Rxa8  25.Qxb5  Rb8  26.Qa4  ± } 24. Bxe8 Rxe8 25. g4
{ White gives his king some air. His control of the open files gives him a clear advantage, even though Black has managed to maintain the material balance. }
25... Qc7 26. Qa4
{ Perhaps it was better to play   26.Qc4  Re6  27.Rd5  Bf8  28.e4   28.b4  Rc6  29.Bxe5  cxb4  30.Qd3  bxc3  31.Bxc7  c2  32.Bf4  c1=Q+  33.Kg2  28...Qe7  29.b3  with a comfortable advantage. }
26... Rd8
{ Here   26...Re6  was better, although after  27.Rd5  Bf8  28.b3  White retains the advantage. }
27. Rxd8+ Qxd8 28. Qc6
{ A strange move, which loses the advantage. It was good to take the pawn:   28.Qxa6  Qd1+  29.Qf1  ± }
28... h5 29. gxh5 Qg5+
{ Black returns the favour; he should have played   29...gxh5 !  30.Qxa6   30.Qxc5  Qg5+  31.Kf1  Qf5 =  30...Qg5+  31.Kf1  Qf5  32.Qa8+  Kh7  33.Kg2  Qg6+  34.Kh1   34.Bg3  h4  34...Qb1+  35.Bg1  Qxb2 = }
30. Bg3 Qxh5 { 30...gxh5  31.h4  ± } 31. Kg2 Qf5 32. e4 Qe6 33. Qxc5
{ Now White wins a pawn and is left with a decisive advantage. } 33... f5 34.
Qd5 Qxd5 35. exd5 Kf7 36. f3 Ke7 37. c4 Kd6 38. Bf2 Bh6 39. Kf1 Bd2 40. Be1
Bxe1
{ This loses easily. More tenacious was   40...Bc1  although after  41.Bb4+  Kd7  42.b3  Be3  43.Ke2  Bd4  44.Ba3  White should win by advancing his pawns. }
41. Kxe1 a5 42. b3 Kc5 43. Kf2 Kd6 44. Kg2 Kc5 45. Kg3 Kd6 46. Kh4 f4
{ 46...Kc5  47.Kg5  Kd6  48.h4  Kc5  49.h5  gxh5  50.Kxf5  +- } 47. Kg4 Kc5 48.
h4 Kd6 49. Kh3 Kc5 50. Kg2
{ White wins by bringing his king to e4.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw 11... Qc7, which is the most popular move in the position. White has two good options: Re1 and Qb3. In the game Black employed the thematic idea of Ne4, exchanging pieces and preventing e3-e4 by White. After e7-e5 the position was equal; both sides had an active bishop, but the one on h2 always had pressure against the e5-pawn.  White gained the advantage after Black's error in breaking up his own pawn chain, spoiling his pawn structure. What stands out most is the necessity of taking care, because equality does not mean that the game will be drawn, and players with black often relax, thinking that there is no danger. }
*

