1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be2 b6 7. c3 Bb7 8. O-O
Nbd7 9. a4 a6 10. Nbd2 Ra7
{ Another plan for Black is to play the rook immediately to a7, making room for the queen on a8. At the same time the rook can be useful on a7 if Black plays b6-b5, and it can also go to c7 if the bishop moves. Against this piece set-up, White should try to close the centre with d4-d5, to leave the black pieces passive on the queenside.  The normal move order would be   10...c5  for example:  11.Re1   11.Bh2  would be normal. Now:  Qb8 !?   11...Ra7  The same plan as in the game, and now:  12.b4   12.Qb3  Qa8  13.c4   13.Rfd1  Bc6   13...Ne4  14.Nxe4   14.Bf1  Nxd2  15.Nxd2  Rc8 =  Pham-Lorparizangeneh, Jakarta 2013  14...Bxe4  15.d5  Bxf3  16.gxf3 !  ∞  Burmakin-Gopal,Benasque 2014  14.Qa3   14.c4  cxd4  15.exd4  d5 ! =  Teijeiro-Pazos, Pontevedra 2015;   14.Ne1  Ne4   14...b5 !  15.Nxe4  Bxe4  16.Bf3   16.d5  +=  16...Bxf3  17.Nxf3 =  Pakleza-Kukula, Katowice 2015  14...Rc8  15.Bf1   15.Ne1  Rcc7  16.Bf3 =  Zurek-Nedela, Czechia tt 1997;   15.c4 !  +=  15...Bf8  16.Ne1  Qb7  17.Nd3 =  Kamsky-Becerra, USA tt 2014;  13...Ne4  14.d5  Nxd2  15.Nxd2  b5  16.axb5   16.e4  ∞  is better  16...axb5  17.Rxa7  Qxa7  18.Qxb5   18.cxb5  Nb6  19.e4  f5  and Black has compensation  18...Ba8  with equality;   12.Re1  Qa8  13.c4  Ne4  14.d5  Nxd2  15.Qxd2  b5  16.e4  +=   12.Bd3  Qa8  and here White has tried:  a recent game continued   12...cxd4  13.exd4  e5 !?   13...Qa8  14.Re1  +=  14.Re1  Qa8 ?!   14...Re8  +=  15.dxe5  dxe5  16.Bxe5 !?   16.Bf1 !  +=  16...Nxe5  17.Rxe5  Rd8   17...Nd7 !  with compensation  18.Qc2  +=  Anurag-Gupta, Cappelle-la-Grande 2016  13.Qb1   13.e4  cxd4  14.cxd4  Nxe4  15.Nxe4  Bxe4  16.Bxe4  Qxe4  17.Re1  Qd5  18.Rxe7 =  Sandipan-Cyborowski, Trier 2013   13.Qe2  Rc8 ?!   13...Ne4 =  14.e4 !  +=  Nguyen-Nandhidhaa, Sharjah 2013  13...e5  14.e4  cxd4  15.cxd4  exd4 ?   15...d5  16.Nxe5  dxe4  17.Nxd7  Nxd7  18.Bxe4  Bxd4 =  16.Bxd6  Re8  17.Re1  +=  Muranyi-Khairallah, Budapest 2007;  12...Qa8  13.Qb3  cxb4  14.cxb4  Bd5 =  Deepan-David, Coubertin 2009;  12.Qb3   12.Re1  Qa7  13.Bc4  +=  12...Qa7  13.Rfe1   13.Bc4 !  +=  is good  also interesting is   13.c4  Ne4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.d5  Bxf3  16.Bxf3  and I prefer White  13...Rac8  14.Bd3  to play e4, but   14.Rad1  +=  is better  14...d5  15.c4 !?   15.Bf1  +=  15...Rfd8  16.cxd5  Bxd5  17.Qa3 !?   17.Bc4 =  17...cxd4  18.e4 !?   18.exd4 =  18...Be6  - De Prado-Pazos, Arteixo 2013;  11...Ra7  12.Qb3   12.Bc4  Qa8  13.Qe2  +=   12.Bh2  12...Qa8  13.Rad1   13.c4  cxd4  14.exd4  e5 =   13.Bf1   13.Bc4  13...Bc6  14.Bc4  h6  15.Bh2  b5  16.axb5  axb5  17.Bxb5  Bxb5  18.Qxb5  Rb8  19.Qd3  Rxb2 =  De Prado-Garcia, Spain tt 2013; }
11. Re1 Qa8 12. Bf1
{ Another option was   12.Bh2  c5  13.b4  it is better to play   13.c4  Ne4  14.d5  Nxd2  15.Qxd2  b5  16.e4  +=  13...cxd4  and now  14.cxd4   14.exd4  is better  Rc8  15.Qb3  Ne4 ?!   15...Bh6  16.c4 =  16.Nxe4  Bxe4  17.Bc4 !  +=  14...Ne4  15.Bf1  Rc8 =  De Prado-Leira, Puentedeume 2012; }
12... c5
{ Finally Black opts for the normal c7-c5.  If   12...Ne4  then  13.Nxe4  Bxe4  14.Nd2  Bb7  15.e4  +=  Deepan-Gupta, Ho Chi Minh City 2012. }
13. Bh2 Ne4
{ Black has other possibilities:   13...Re8  14.Qb3   14.Qe2  14...h6   14...Ne4  15.Bc4  d5  16.Be2  Nxd2  17.Nxd2  e5  18.dxe5  +=  15.Bc4  +=  Bd5   15...Rf8  Toufighi-Ganguly, Guangzhou 2010  16.Nh4 !  +=  16.Bxd5  Nxd5  17.Nc4   17.e4 !  +=  17...N5f6 =  Manakova-Havlikova, Germany Frauenbundesliga 2013;   13...Rc8  14.Rc1  again it is better to play   14.c4  Ne4  15.d5  Nxd2  16.Qxd2  b5  17.e4  +=  14...Bc6  15.c4  d5  16.b3  +=  Ilic-Damljanovic, Struga 2005   13...Bc6 ?!  14.Qc2 ?!   14.c4 !  +=  14...Ne4 =  E.Alvarez-Busto, Gijon 2006 }
14. Nxe4
{ 14.Nc4  Bd5  15.Na3   15.a5  15...Bc6  16.Nc2  Nef6  17.Nd2  Rc8  18.f3  Rac7  19.Na3  - Chowdhury-Kunte, Calcutta 2003   14.Qb3  Nxd2  15.Nxd2  d5   15...Bc6 =  16.Nf3  Bc6  17.Qa3  +=  Thi Mai Nguyen-Havlikova, Istanbul 2012. }
14... Bxe4 15. Nd2 Bc6 16. Nc4 Re8
{ 16...d5  17.Nd2  e5  18.Nf3   18.dxe5  Nxe5  19.a5  b5  20.Nb3  c4  21.Nd4  +=  18...e4  19.Nd2  c4   19...Re8 =  20.b3  b5  21.Ra3  Qb7  22.Qa1  +=  Rivas-Moreno, Lorca 2005 }
17. b4
{ It is better to play   17.a5  b5  18.d5 !  Bb7   18...Bxd5  19.Nb6  Nxb6  20.axb6  Rd7  21.Bxb5  ±  19.Nb6  Qd8  20.Nxd7  Qxd7  21.e4  with a balanced position, but I prefer White. }
17... d5 { Here   17...cxb4  18.cxb4  Rc8  19.Rc1  was better, with equality. }
18. Ne5
{ The best move here is   18.Na3  c4   18...Rc8  19.b5  axb5  20.axb5  Bb7  21.Qb3  +=  19.e4  e6   19...b5 ?  20.axb5  axb5  21.exd5  +-  20.e5  +=   18.Nd2  c4  19.e4   19.Be2  e5  20.Qc2  b5  21.a5  exd4  22.exd4  Nf6  23.Bf3  Rae7 =  19...b5  20.Qc2  Nb6  21.a5  Nd7  22.e5  Pham Le Thao-Mohota, Ho Chi Minh City 2012 }
18... Nxe5 19. Bxe5 Bxe5 20. dxe5 Rd7
{ Once again an error in a theoretically simple position, apparently without any problems for Black.  Here   20...Qb8  was good, e.g.  21.f4  Rd8  22.Qd2  a5  23.b5  Bd7  24.Bd3  with equality, but I prefer White, who can try to play e3-e4 at an opportune moment, or play on the kingside with h3-h4-h5, to try to exploit the absence of the dark-squared bishop. }
21. b5 Bb7 { Of course not   21...axb5 ?  22.axb5  +- } 22. a5
{ A very good move, which gives White a clear advantage. Once again queenside play has proved fruitful for White. }
22... bxa5
{ Or   22...axb5  23.axb6  Qc8  24.Bxb5  Bc6  25.Qa4  with a decisive advantage to White. }
23. bxa6 Bxa6
{ It was better to play   23...Bc6  but after  24.Rxa5  White still has a clear advantage. }
24. Rxa5
{ Black was intent on not losing the pawn, but the pin is deadly. White now has a decisive advantage. }
24... Ra7 25. Qa1 c4 26. e4 e6 { 26...dxe4  then  27.Bxc4  wins. } 27. Rd1
{ It was better to play   27.Qa3  Rc8  28.Ra1  Rc6  29.exd5  exd5  30.Rxd5  with a decisive advantage. }
27... Rd8
{ Black had to try   27...Ree7 !  even though after  28.exd5  Bb5  29.Qa3  Rxa5  30.Qxe7  Ra7  31.Qf6  exd5  32.e6  White has a clear advantage. }
28. exd5
{ Again the plan of tripling on the a-file was winning:   28.Qa3  Qb7  29.Ra1  d4  30.cxd4  Qxe4  31.Rxa6  +- }
28... Rxd5 { 28...exd5  29.Qa3  +- } 29. Rdxd5 exd5 30. Be2
{ The bishop will take aim at the weak pawn on d5 and Black can do nothing about it. }
30... Qc8 31. Bg4 Qc6 32. Bf3 Qc8 33. Bxd5
{ The rest needs no commentary; the game is over. } 33... Kg7 34. Bf3 Qe6 35.
Qa3 Qb6 36. Qa1 Qe6 37. Qa2 Qc8 38. Qa3 Qe6 39. Qd6 h5 40. Bd5 Qc8 41. Qf6+
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw Black's plan of Ra7, with the idea of Qa8: from a7 the rook can play along the a-file if it becomes open or after playing b6-b5. It can also go to c7 if the bishop moves.  Once again the best plan for White is to try to close the centre with c3-c4, or e3-e4 and d4-d5, in order to leave some of Blacks forces cut off from the centre and the kingside. In the game White should have played 18. Na3, but after 18. Ne5, even though the position became level, Black made a mistake, in a position that seemed harmless.  After the precise advances b4-b5 and a4-a5, White gained a clear advantage, which became decisive following the pin on the a-file. }
