[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the King’s Indian"]
[Black "Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ The King's Indian is one of the most popular defences, both at master level and  (especially)  among club players.  In this chapter we have seen Black's possible responses when confronted with the London System. Black has various ways of preparing the traditional plan of e7-e5; he can play Nbd7 and Qe8, as in Game 14; Nbd7 and b7-b6, as in Game 15; Nc6 and Nfd7 as in Game 16, or Nfd7 and e7-e5 but without Nc6, as in game 17.  We also looked at Black's ideas based on playing c7-c5 and Qb6; in Game 18 we saw White trying to avoid playing Qb3; in the notes to this game we also examined the option of Qb3, offering the exchange of queens.  In Game 19 we saw a different plan for Black, based on playing c5xd4, followed by Nc6 and Be6, to control the centre.  In Game 20 we began our survey of what is sometimes called the Réti Reversed: the system with c7-c5 and b7-b6, which is Black's most popular; in this game we looked at the development of the black knight on c6, while in the remaining games  (21-24)  we saw the usual development of the black knight on d7 and we examined the various plans, both for White, with moves such as Re1, Qb3 or Bh2, and for Black, with Rc8, Qc7, Ra7 and even Qb8 and Rb8.  For White, to summarise, there are several plans available: against ideas based on a quick e7-e5, remember to play c3-c4 and Nc3 and leave the square d2 free for the f3-knight, in case Black plays e5-e4.  It is interesting to play on the queenside, which is where White can hope to gain the advantage. There is no need to fear the variations where Black advances his kingside pawns with accurate play in the centre and queenside, White can gain the advantage.  Against the plan with b7-b6 but without c7-c5, it is interesting to play a2-a4 instead of c3-c4. By castling quickly White can avoid the line involving the exchange of queens with Qb3; instead he can play Nbd2, indirectly defending the b2-pawn, then after Nc4 he can harass the black queen.  Against the Réti Reversed it is necessary to keep in mind the plan of trying to play d4-d5, after e3-e4 or c3-c4, to leave the black pieces  (the bishop and the queen or rook)  out of play and remote from the centre or the kingside.  White should also remember the idea of playing Bc4 and Qb3, to put pressure on f7  (with Ng5)  or to provoke d6-d5, in order to gain the use of the e5-square and close the diagonal of the bishop on b7. Against Blacks move order with an early c7-c5 and b7-b6, White has the option of playing the bishop to d3 or c4, instead of e2, and this is covered in Game 27.  Also remember that White has the option of playing the Barry Attack with Nc3, which we looked at in the previous chapter, which was devoted to playing against the Grünfeld set-up.  It can be said that the King's Indian is one of the most solid systems that White has to face when playing the London System. But this does not mean that White cannot gain the advantage against it, or reach positions which are equal but more pleasant and easier to play with white.  Of course, none of the lines involve any risk for White and any losses are not the fault of the opening but are caused by errors committed later.  One thing I want to particularly emphasise is that, as we saw in Games 22, 23 and 24, very often Black relaxes, thinking that the position is equal or without any danger, and then he commits errors.  Sudden attacks or tactical blows crop up in the London System where they are least expected. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Queen’s Indian"]
[Black "London V. Queen's Indian"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. Nf3 b6
{ 3...c5  4.e3  b6  5.Nc3   3...Be7  4.h3  b6  5.e3  Ne4 } 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3
{ 5.Nbd2   5.h3 } 5... Be7 6. h3 c5 7. c3 O-O { 7...cxd4  8.cxd4 } 8. Nbd2 cxd4
9. exd4 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 { 10...Nc6 } 11. Re1
{ The Queen's Indian Defence is characterised by the plan of Nf6, e7-e6, b7-b6, Bb7, c7-c5 and d7-d6, followed by the development of the queen's knight to d7 or c6 and exchanging pawns on d4.  It is usually the choice of Nimzo-Indian players. Black's idea is to build a solid position, with the a8-g2 diagonal open for his bishop. The pawns on e6 and d6 cover important squares and Black prepares to play e7-e5 in the future, with the plan of Re8 and Bf8.  White has several plans at his disposal: to play a2-a4, bring the bishop to h2, the rook to e1 and the queen to e2 or b3. White's queens knight can go via c4 to e3 and g4; the king's knight sometimes goes to g5 to provoke weaknesses on the kingside.  There is also the plan of playing on the queenside with c3-c4, b2-b4, Rc1 and c4-c5. If Black exchanges pawns on d4, White can recapture either way, with the e-pawn or the c-pawn.  As a matter of fact, GM Prié, one of the greatest specialists in the London System, recommends taking with the c-pawn, although there are some exceptions where it is better to take with the e-pawn.  We shall examine some selected games illustrating the main plans and options for both sides and we shall conclude this chapter with some little-known alternatives, such as the idea of the Czech GM Blatny, who castles queenside, and some ideas for Black involving Ne4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Queen’s Indian"]
[Black "Game 25 - Kamsky vs. Tiviakov"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Be7 5. c3
{ When Black plays Be7 White should play h2-h3, to prevent the exchange of the f4-bishop after Nh5. It was therefore better to play 5. h3. }
5... b6 { 5...Nh5  was good. } 6. h3 Bb7 7. Nbd2
{ Or   7.Be2 !?  O-O  8.O-O  d6   8...d5 ! =  exploiting the absence of the bishop from d3  9.a4  a6  10.Nbd2  cxd4  11.exd4  Nbd7  12.Re1  Re8  13.Bd3  reaching a theoretical position with a tempo less for White  Qc7  14.Bh2  Bf8  15.Nc4  Bd5   15...Bc6  16.Ne3  Qb7  17.Nd2  b5  18.Qb3 =  Burmakin-Zeller, Schwbisch Gmnd 2014  16.Ne3  Bc6  17.Nd2   17.Qe2  +=  17...g6  18.Qe2  - Spassky-Portisch, Geneva 1977 by transposition   7.Bd3  is normal }
7... cxd4 8. exd4
{ White can recapture with either pawn. Prié recommends   8.cxd4  as we shall see further on. }
8... d6 9. Bd3 Nbd7
{ The alternative is to develop the knight on c6, which we shall look at later:   9...O-O  10.O-O  Nc6 }
10. O-O
{ White has several plans and sometimes the move order is unimportant. The same can also be said for Black.   10.Qe2  O-O  11.O-O  Re8  12.Bc2   12.Bh2  a6  13.Nc4  Nf8  14.Nfd2  Qc7  15.Ne3  Ng6  16.Rfe1 =  Bauer-Graf, Schwbisch Gmnd 2012  12...a6  13.Rfe1  Bc6  14.a4  Nf8  15.Bd3   15.Bh2  +=  15...Qc8  16.Nc4  Nd5  17.Bg3  Qd7  +=  Radlovacki-Laketic, Kragujevac 2013. }
10... O-O 11. Re1 Re8
{ The alternative is   11...Qc7  then  12.a3   12.Bh2   12.Qe2  are all interesting. Practice has seen:   12.Bg3 !?  Rfe8  13.Nf1  the knight is heading for e3, although normally it travels via c4;   13.Qe2  +=   13.Rc1  +=  13...Bf8  14.Ne3  Bc6  15.c4  Qb7  16.Rc1   16.Nd2  +=  16...Rab8  17.Be2  d5  18.cxd5  Nxd5  19.Nc4 =  Pakleza-Piorun, Chorzow ch-POL 2013;   12.Nc4  Rfe8  13.Ng5  Bf8   13...h6 =  14.Qc2  h6 ??  A horrible blunder;   14...g6 =  was correct  15.Bh7+  1-0 Perez-Mejuto, Ferrol 2014   12.c4  Rfe8  13.Rc1   13.Qc2  Bf8  14.Qc3   14.Bh2  14...Rac8  15.Rac1  Qb8  16.Bg3   16.Bh2  16...Qa8  17.b4  g6 =  De Prado-Quesada, Ferrol 2010  13...Rac8  14.b4   14.Nb1 ?!  Bf8 ?!   14...e5 !  15.dxe5  dxe5  16.Nxe5  Bc5  =+  15.Bh2  Qb8   15...e5 =  16.Nc3  a6  +=  Karjakin-Leko, Beijing 2013  14...Bf8  15.a3  Qb8   15...e5 =  16.Bf1   16.Qb3  16...Qa8   16...e5 =  17.Qb3  +=   11...h6  has also been played:  12.a4  a6  13.Qe2  Re8  14.Bh2  Bf8  15.Ne4  Nxe4  16.Bxe4  Bxe4  17.Qxe4 =  Soos-Csom, Koszeg 2000. }
12. a4 { Again the alternatives were   12.a3   12.Qe2   12.Bh2 } 12... a6 13.
Bh2
{ Here one of the co-authors has employed another idea:   13.Ng5 !?  Qc7  14.Qe2   14.Bh2  transposes to the note at move  14...Bf8  15.Nge4  Nxe4  16.Bxe4  Bxe4  17.Nxe4  Qc6 =  De Prado-Sanchez, Cambre 2013  White has also tried   13.Nc4  Qc7  14.Bg3   14.Bf1  Bf8  15.Bg3  Bc6 =  Popchev-Kersten, Marianske Lazne 2006   14.Bh2  Bd5  15.Ne3  Bb7  16.Nc4  Bd5  - Knezevic-Rajkovic, Vrnjacka Banja 1987  14...Bc6  15.Qe2  +=  Berezjuk-Petrik, Slovakia tt 2016 }
13... Qc7
{ 13...Bf8  14.Nc4  Qc7  15.Qe2  g6  16.Ncd2   16.Ng5  +=  16...Bg7  17.Ne4   17.a5  +=  17...Nxe4  18.Bxe4  Bxe4  19.Qxe4  Nf6 =  Lenic-Dervishi, Bratto 2009. }
14. c4
{ One of the plans for White is to play c3-c4, b2-b4, Rc1 and c4-c5, to exploit the pin on the d6-pawn. Another idea is to play Qe2 and Ng5-e4. The following year Kamsky himself tried to improve with   14.Qb3  Bf8  15.Re2 !?  Bc6   15...h6  16.Rae1  Bc6  17.Qa3   17.c4 !?  17...b5  18.a5  Bd5 =  Cacho-Moreno, Linares 2015  16.c4  Qb7  17.Rae1 ?!   17.Qc2  +=  17...d5 =  Kamsky-Carlsen, Moscow 2008.  GM Kosic likes to play   14.Ng5 !?  h6  and now:  15.Ngf3   15.Nge4  Qc6   15...Nxe4 =  16.Qf3  Nxe4 ?!   16...Qc7 =  17.Bxe4  d5  18.Bc2  +=  Kosic-Drasko, Belgrade 1994.  15...Bf8  16.Qe2  Qc6  17.Nc4   17.Bc2  17...Rac8   17...Nd5 =  18.Ne3  +=  Kosic-Mihok, Budapest 2008 }
14... a5
{ 14...e5  Possibly this explains why Kamsky varied with 14. Qb3 against Carlsen, since it seems that Black equalises:  15.dxe5   15.a5 =  15...dxe5  16.Nxe5  Bd6  17.Nef3  Bxh2+  18.Nxh2  Rxe1+  19.Qxe1  Re8  20.Qb1  h6  21.Qc2  Nc5 =  and Black has very good compensation. }
15. Nb1
{ Kamsky recycles his knight towards the square b5, via a3 or c3. This is an idea to keep in mind, exploiting the squares that our opponent weakens. }
15... Qd8 16. Nc3
{ White is a bit better, with a space advantage, pressure on d6 and the square b5.   16.Na3  d5  17.b3  +=  was also good. }
16... d5 17. b3
{ Kamsky does not want to leave his queen's pawn isolated.  If   17.cxd5  then  Nxd5 =  or if   17.Nb5  then  dxc4  18.Bxc4  Rc8  19.Rc1  Bb4 =   17.Rc1  dxc4  18.Bxc4  Rc8  19.Qd3  +=  was also playable. }
17... Bb4 18. Rc1 Rc8 19. Re3
{ From here the rook can go to the queenside on c3 or the kingside on g3 and it also restrains Black's e6-e5 break. }
19... Nf8 20. Nb5 Ne4 21. Rc2 Re7 { 21...Ng6  +=  was a little better. } 22.
Qc1 Nd7 { It was better to play   22...f6  += } 23. Na7 Ra8 24. cxd5 exd5 25.
Nc6 Bxc6 26. Rxc6
{ White has a clear advantage: he commands the c-file, the h2-b8 diagonal and in particular the c7-square. He will soon invade with his rooks and bishops. The pawns on b6 and d5 are weak and will eventually fall. Once more it is worth noting that Black's bishop plays the role of a mere spectator, as in many other lines when it is placed on g7, in comparison with its opponent on h2. }
26... Qf8 27. Re2 Rae8 28. Rec2
{ It was better to play   28.Bb5  ±  and if  f6  then  29.Rc7 } 28... h6 29.
Bf4 { Once again   29.Bb5  was better, with a clear advantage to White. } 29...
g5 30. Bc7 Nef6 { Or   30...f6  31.Bxb6  ± } 31. Bf5
{ Whites advantage is decisive: the invasion of the eighth rank and the capture of the weak pawns will grant him victory in a few moves. }
31... Qg7 32. Bd6 Bxd6 33. Rxd6 Nf8 34. Rc8 Rxc8 35. Qxc8 Ne8 36. Rxb6 h5 37.
Qd8 Re2 38. Bd3
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the classic Queen's Indian set-up against the London with b7-b6, Bb7, c7-c5, e7-e6 and d7-d6 and the development of the black queen's knight to d7.  In another game we shall see the plan with Nc6. White recaptured on d4 with the e-pawn  (we shall cover the recapture with the c-pawn in another game)  and employed one of the traditional plans in such positions of playing a2-a4, Bh2, Re1 and then the idea of c3-c4, to play on the queenside with Rc1, b2-b4 and c4-c5.  Black prevented b2-b4 by playing a6-a5, but this left the square b5 weak, which Kamsky exploited in masterly fashion with the plan of Nd2-b1-c3-b5. Then he invaded along the c-file, which, combined with the power of the bishop on h2, gave him a decisive advantage.  Once again White wins by occupying a file on the queenside  (the b or the c-file)  with the help of the bishop on h2. }
*

