[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5
{ The immediate   3...b6  is playable, e.g.  4.e3  Bb7  5.Bd3  Be7  6.h3  c5  7.Nbd2  Nc6  8.c3  d6  9.Bh2  O-O  10.O-O  Rc8  11.a4  Re8  12.Nc4  Bf8 ?   12...d5  +=  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.Nxd6  Bxd6  15.Bxd6  ±  Sandipan-Diaz, Sabadell 2014. }
4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ Here   5.Nc3  is interesting. It has not been played often, but was tested in 2014 by Rapport and Vitiugov:  cxd4   5...Qa5  6.Nd2  +=  Van Dijk-Fedorchuk, Maastricht 2011  6.exd4  Bb4   6...Be7  7.a3  O-O  8.Bd3  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  10.Re1  Rc8  11.Qe2  Hort-Am. Rodriguez, Amsterdam 1987  7.Bd3  O-O   7...Nd5  8.Bd2  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Be7  10.h4 !?   10.c4 !   10.O-O  10...h6  11.O-O  d5  12.h5  O-O  Rapport-Naiditsch, Nagykanizsa 2014  8.O-O  Be7  9.Ne4   9.Nb5 !?  is interesting, e.g.  d5   9...d6  10.c4  +=  10.Bc7  Qd7  11.Ne5  Nxe5  12.Bxe5  a6  13.Nc3  9...Qb6 ?!   9...Nd5  10.Nxf6+  Bxf6  11.c3 !?   11.Bd6 !  +=  11...Qxb2  ∞  Vitiugov-Lysyj, Kazan 2014 }
5... b6 6. c3 cxd4 7. exd4 Be7 8. h3 Bb7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O d6
{ By a roundabout route we have reached the main position. In the previous game we saw Nbd7. }
11. Qe2
{ The alternative is   11.Re1  Re8  12.Nc4  This is another typical plan for White: from c4 the knight puts pressure on d6, supports a4-a5 and can go to the kingside via e3 and g4   12.Rc1  ;  12.Bh2  . Let us see what Black can do:  12...Bf8  If   12...h6  then  13.a4  +=  Or   12...b5  13.Ne3  a6  14.a4  +=   12...Nd5 !?  13.Bg3   13.Bh2  13...g6 !?   13...Qd7  +=  14.a4  a6  15.h4  a typical plan against g7-g6;   15.Qe2  +=  15...Na5 !?  16.Ncd2   16.Nxa5  bxa5  and although White is better Black has counterplay on the b-file.  16...Nf6  17.b4 !  Nc6  18.Ng5  Nh5  19.Bh2  e5   19...Bxg5  20.hxg5  Qxg5  21.Ne4  20.d5   20.b5  axb5  21.Bxb5  +=  20...Nb8  21.Qf3  Rf8  22.Nxh7  Kxh7  23.Qxh5+  Kg7  +=  Christiansen-Peter, Bad Mergentheim 1988.  13.Qe2   13.a4  +=  13...h6   13...e5 ?  14.dxe5  b5  15.Nxd6  Bxd6  16.Rad1  ±  14.a4  +=   11.Bh2 }
11... Re8
{ 11...Qc7  12.Rfe1  Rfe8  13.Bh2   13.a3  +=   13.Rad1  +=  13...Bf8  14.a4   14.Ne4 !?  +=   14.Ng5 !?  +=   14.Nc4 !?  +=  14...Ne7  15.a5  +=  Gholami-Sanal, Doha 2015;   11...Qd7  12.Rfe1   12.Ne4  +=  12...Rfe8  13.Rad1  +=  Kosic-Draskovic, Podgorica 2014 }
12. Rfe1 Bf8 13. Ne4
{ 13.Bg5 !?  has been tried here:  Be7   13...h6  14.Bh4  Be7  15.Rad1   15.Bg3  +=  15...a6  16.Bb1  Nh5 ?!  17.d5 !   17.Bxe7  Nxe7  Hu-Li Ruofan, Canberra 2008  17...exd5  18.Qd3  g6   18...Bxh4  19.Qh7+  Kf8  20.Qh8#  19.Qxd5  Na5   19...Bxh4  20.Rxe8+  Qxe8  21.Nxh4  +=  20.Qd4  +=  14.Bf4   14.Bh4  +=  14...Bf8  15.Bg5  Be7  16.Bf4  - Danielsen-Thorhallson, Kopagovur 2012; }
13... Nxe4 14. Qxe4
{ It was better to recapture with the bishop, maintaining a comfortable white advantage, but it seems that the capture with the queen weakens Black's castled position more quickly.   14.Bxe4  h6   14...g6  invites White to carry out the attractive plan of h3-h4-h5:  15.h4  +=  15.Rad1  += }
14... g6 15. Bg5
{ 15.Bh2  is better, e.g.  Bg7   15...Na5  16.Qe2  +=   15...Nb4  16.Qxb7  Nxd3  17.Re2  ±  16.Rad1  Rc8  17.Qg4  with a slight advantage to White.  Instead,   15.h4  can now be answered with  Ne5  which is why it was better to recapture on e4 with the bishop. }
15... Qc7 16. Qh4 Ne7
{ The knight is heading for f5, where it will strengthen Black's defences on the kingside and also harass the white queen. Black has now equalised. }
17. Nd2 Nf5 18. Qf4
{ It was better to play   18.Qg4  Bg7  19.Rad1   19.Ne4  Nxd4  20.cxd4  f5  21.Qh4  fxe4  22.Bxe4  Bxe4  23.Qxe4  19...h6  20.Bf4  Rad8 }
18... Bg7
{ A dubious move, to say the least. White wants to dislodge the knight from its good square on f5, but in doing so he gives up his dark-squared bishop and exposes his king by opening the h1-a8 diagonal. It was better to play }
19. g4
{ A dubious move, to say the least. White wants to dislodge the knight from its good square on f5, but in doing so he gives up his dark-squared bishop and exposes his king by opening the h1-a8 diagonal. It was better to play   19.Ne4  e5  20.dxe5  dxe5  21.Qg4  h6  22.Bf6  Bxe4  23.Bxe4  Bxf6  24.Bxf5  h5  25.Qg3  Rad8 }
19... h6 20. gxf5 hxg5 21. Qxg5 exf5 22. Kh2
{ This further error gives Black a clear advantage. It was necessary to play   22.Bb5  Rxe1+   22...Bc6  23.Rxe1  Bf8  24.h4  Qd8  with a balanced position. Black has the bishop pair and a weakness on d6, whereas White has a weakness on h4. }
22... Be4 { Here   22...Kh7 !  was good  23.Kg3  Bh6  24.Nf3  Qc6  25.Nh4  ∓ }
23. Bb5
{ If   23.Bxe4  then  d5+  24.Qg3  Qxg3+  25.Kxg3  fxe4  26.Nf1  f5  27.Ne3  Rad8  28.a4  Bf8  =+  It was better to play   23.Nxe4  fxe4   23...d5+ ?  24.Ng3  24.Bb5   24.Bxe4  d5+  24...d5+  25.Kg2  Red8  26.h4  Rd6  27.Rh1  with a balanced position. }
23... Re6
{ If   23...Bc6  then  24.Bxc6  Qxc6  25.h4  Rxe1  26.Rxe1  Re8  27.Rxe8+  Qxe8  with equality;  it was better to play   23...d5+  24.Kg1  Red8  when Black maintains a slight advantage }
24. Nxe4 fxe4 25. Qd5 Rf8 26. Kg2 Qe7 27. Re2 Qf6 28. Re3
{ Here   28.Rae1 !  Qf3+  29.Kg1  Qxh3   29...Rf6  30.Qxe4  30.Rxe4  was better, with equality. }
28... Qf4 { 28...Bh6  29.Rg3  was better. } 29. Rae1
{ Overlooking   29.Bc6 !  Rf6  30.Rf1  Bh6  31.Qxe4  Qg5+  32.Rg3  Qd2  33.Qb1  and White has the advantage, since he has an extra pawn and can repel Black's attack. }
29... Rf6 30. R1e2 Rf5 31. Qc6
{ The white queen will be cut off from the kingside. It was necessary to play   31.Qb3  d5  32.Qd1  ∓ }
31... d5
{ Now the white king is left unprotected and Black has a winning attack. } 32.
Rg3 Bf6 33. Rg4 Qf3+ 34. Kh2 Bg5 35. Rg2 Bf4+ 36. Kg1 Qxh3 37. Qd7 e3
{ It would have been more direct to choose the plan of Kg7 and Rh8, either now or on the following move. }
38. f3 Bg3 39. Rxe3 a6
{ Black will be able to win White's queen if the bishop ceases to protect it. But it was stronger to play   39...Qh6  40.Re1  Qh4  41.Re3  Bf2+  42.Rxf2  Qg5+  and wins. }
40. Bd3 { 40.Bc6  Qh6  -+  with the same plan as in the previous note. } 40...
Bh2+ 41. Kf2 Rxf3+ 42. Rxf3 Qxd7 43. Rxh2 Kg7 44. Rfh3 Qg4 45. Rh7+ Kf6 46.
R2h3 Ke7 47. Re3+ Kd6 48. Rf3 Qg5 49. Rh2
{ 49.Rhxf7  Rxf7  50.Rxf7  Qd2+  51.Be2  Qxb2  52.Rf6+  Ke7  53.Rxg6  Qxc3  54.Rg4  b5  -+ }
49... Re8 50. Rg2 Qd2+ 51. Kg1 { 51.Kg3  Qe1+  52.Rgf2  f5  -+ } 51... Qd1+
{ 0-1 .  SUMMARY:  In this game we saw the same set-up for Black as in the previous game, but with the knight developed to c6. I think that it is not as well placed there as on d7, because the b7-bishop is blocked.  White chose the plan with Qe2 and Ne4. Other ideas include Nc4 and a2-a4 or Bg5, as we saw in the analysis. In the game White should have recaptured on e4 with the bishop rather than the queen, thus maintaining a slight advantage.  Black equalised with the plan of Ne7-f5 and after Whites erroneous g2-g4 and Kh2 Black gained the advantage, but he continued inaccurately, after which anything could have happened. }
*

