[Black "Game 27 - PriÃ© vs. Garza Marco"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 c5 6. c3 Be7 7. h3 O-O 8. Nbd2
cxd4 9. cxd4
{ White is one of the top specialists in this system, and he prefers to recapture with the c-pawn rather than the e-pawn, since now White can play on the c-file. White can also play in the centre by advancing with e3-e4 and even attack the black king after e4-e5. Black usually exchanges on d4, but even if Black delays this, White eventually plays e3-e4, after which Black then exchanges on d4, reaching similar positions. A further advantage for White is that if Black exchanges on d4 very early in the game, White can take advantage of this to develop the queen's knight to c3 instead of d2. }
9... Nc6
{ This is the most popular move, but let us examine some alternatives:   9...Ba6 !?  is interesting. The idea of exchanging the bishop on a6 is very typical of the Queen's Indian, but it is perhaps better to do so directly, without losing a tempo. There are two options now:  10.Bxa6   10.Qe2  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  Qc8  12.a3  Qa6   12...Qb7  13.O-O  Nc6  14.Rac1  Rac8  15.Bg5  +=  13.Qxa6  Nxa6  14.Rc1  Rac8  15.Ke2  +=  10...Nxa6  11.O-O   11.a3  Qc8  12.O-O  Qb7   11.Qe2  Qc8  12.O-O  Qb7  13.Rac1  11...Qc8   11...Nb4  12.Qe2  Nc6  13.Rac1  Rc8  14.Qb5  +=  12.Qe2  Qb7  13.a3  Rac8   9...d6  10.O-O  Nbd7  is also possible and now  11.Nc4 !  +=  is good, although other ideas have also been seen, such as:   11.Qe2  Nd5  12.Bh2  Nb4  13.Bc4   13.Bb5  a6  14.Ba4  b5  15.Bb3  Vafiadis-Charkhalashvili, Kavala 2011  13...a6   13...d5  14.Bb5  a6  15.Ba4  b5  16.Bd1  +=  14.a3  d5  15.Bb3  Nc6  16.Rfc1  +=  Bagheri-Lputian, Warsaw 2005   11.Bh2  Re8  12.Qe2   12.Nc4  +=  12...Bf8  13.Rfd1  e5  14.dxe5  dxe5  15.e4  +=  - Rudolf-Nagy, Szombathely 2010;   11.a3  Re8  12.Qe2   12.Bh2  +=  12...a6  13.e4   13.Bh2  +=  13...Nf8  14.Bh2  Ng6  15.Rac1  Nh5  16.Qe3  e5  17.dxe5   17.Bb1 !  +=  17...dxe5  18.b4   18.Bc4  +=  18...Nhf4  19.Bc4  b5  20.Ba2  Bg5  De Prado-Paramos, Spain tt 2009 }
10. O-O
{ It is more precise to play   10.a3 !   to prevent  10...Nb4  a6  11.O-O  with the following examples:  b5   11...d6  12.Qe2  b5  13.Rfc1   13.Rac1  +=  13...Re8  14.Rc2  +=  Bharat-Karlsson, Reykjavik 2012;  Against   11...d5  Kamsky gained a good victory after  12.Rc1  h6  13.Ne5  Nxe5  14.dxe5  Ne4  15.Nf3   15.Qg4 !  +=  15...b5  16.Nd4  Qb6  17.Qg4  Kh8  18.f3  Nc5  19.Bb1   19.Rxc5 !  Qxc5  20.Nxe6  fxe6  21.Qg6  Rf5  22.g4  19...Nd7  20.Qh5  Kg8  21.Bxh6 !  gxh6  22.Qxh6  f5  23.Nxe6  Kf7  24.Bxf5  1-0 Kamsky-Gundavaa, Khanty-Mansiysk Wch blitz 2013.  12.e4   12.Qe2  +=  12...d6  13.Qe2  +=  Alcaraz-Kovacevic, Mislata 2011 }
10... Rc8
{ It was better to play   10...Nb4  11.Be2  a6  12.a3  Nbd5  13.Bg3  b5 } 11.
a3 d6
{ It is unusual for Black to play the Queen's Indian and then follow up with d7-d5, but it needs to be considered and later we shall also see it with the white knight on c3.   11...d5  and now  12.b4   12.Qe2  Bd6  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.Rfc1  Rc7  15.Rc3  Rfc8  16.Rac1  h6  - Spiridonov-Georgiev, Pernik 1983;   12.Rc1 !  Bd6  13.Ne5  Ne7   13...Qe7  14.Qf3  +=  14.Rxc8   14.Qa4  +=  14...Bxc8  15.Qc2  +=  Hoang Thanh Trang-Bokros, Hungary tt 2011/12.  12...Bd6  13.Ne5   13.Bxd6  Qxd6  13...Ne7  14.Qa4  a6  15.Rac1  Kamsky-Leko, Beijing 2012; }
12. Qe2
{ White has a slight advantage after the opening; he can play on the queenside with b2-b4 and Ba6, and on the kingside with e3-e4 and e4-e5.   12.Rc1  has also been played, for instance:  a6  13.b4  e5  14.Bh2  Nxb4  15.axb4  e4  16.Be2   16.Nxe4  Nxe4  17.Qb3  +=  16...exf3  17.Bxf3  Bxf3  18.Qxf3  d5  Theofilopoulos-Maier, Rio Achaia 2013 }
12... Qc7
{ 12...Nd7  13.Nc4   13.Rac1  +=  13...Nf6  14.Rfc1  d5   14...Qd7  +=  15.Nce5  Nxe5  16.Nxe5  +=  Meins-Babula, Bremen 2013  The continuation   12...Qd7  seems to be the best, but White maintains a slight advantage:  13.e4  better is   13.Rfe1  +=  or   13.Rad1  +=  13...Rfd8  14.Be3   14.Bb5  14...Qe8  15.Rfe1  Na5  16.b4  Nc6  17.Ba6   17.Rac1  +=  17...Bxa6  18.Qxa6  Qd7  Ponomariov-Carlsen, Moscow 2010.  Or   12...Rc7 !?  13.Rac1   13.Rad1 !?  +=   13.Rfe1  +=  13...Qd7  14.Bh2  Rfc8  15.Rc2   15.Rcd1  +=  15...Nb8  16.Rfc1  Rxc2  17.Rxc2  Rxc2  18.Bxc2  Qc6  Assmann-Larsen, Lugano 1989. }
13. Rac1 Qb8
{ The queen is not well placed on b8. It was better to unpin with   13...Qd7  14.e4  += }
14. Bh2 Qa8
{ We saw the same plan in the Réti Reversed, in the chapter on the King's Indian, but here it does not seem very appropriate, especially once Black has played d6-d5. }
15. e4 d5
{ This is a clear strategic error, closing the long diagonal and giving White a free hand to attack the black king. It was better to play   15...Rfd8  += }
16. e5 Nd7 17. h4
{ White takes advantage of the absence of black pieces from the kingside to launch an attack on the black king. The idea is support Ng5 and create weaknesses. Here   17.Bf4  was also good. }
17... Rce8
{ It was better to play   17...Na5 !?  18.b4 !   18.Bb1  Rxc1  19.Rxc1  Rc8  18...Nc4   18...Nc6  19.Bb1  ±  19.Nxc4  dxc4  20.Bxc4  still with advantage to White though. }
18. Bb1 a5 19. Qd3
{ The threat is simply to mate on h7 ! The idea is to provoke g7-g6 and then follow up with h4-h5 and open up Blacks castled position. }
19... g6
{ 19...f5  is worse, e.g.  20.exf6  Nxf6  21.Rfe1  Ba6  22.Qc3  Rc8  23.Qe3   23.Ng5  Nd8  24.Qh3  23...Nd8  24.Bc7 }
20. Qe3 f5
{ Black tries to close the b1-h7 diagonal but weakens his position; however, after   20...Ba6  21.Rfe1  Rc8  22.Qh6  White would retain a clear advantage, with a dangerous attack. }
21. Bf4
{ It was better to capture on f6 and open the position:   21.exf6  Bxf6  22.h5  gxh5  23.Ng5  Bxd4  24.Bxh7+  Kh8  25.Qh3  with a decisive advantage. }
21... a4 22. g3
{ Prié wants to play Kg2, Rh1 and h4-h5. There were several good alternatives for White, such as the immediate   22.h5  which was good either now or in the next few moves or   22.Bh6   22.Ng5 }
22... b5 23. Bh6
{ It seems stronger to play the immediate   23.h5  e.g.  Na5  24.hxg6  hxg6  25.Bh6  Nc4  26.Qf4  Rf7  27.Ng5  Bxg5  28.Qxg5  Nf8   28...Kh7  29.Kg2  29.Nf3  and wins. }
23... Rf7 24. Ng5 { Again   24.h5  was better. } 24... Bxg5 25. Bxg5 Nb6
{ It was better to play   25...Na5  26.Nf3  Ba6  27.Bh6  b4   27...Nc4  28.Qg5  +=  28.Rfe1  bxa3  29.bxa3  Nb3  += }
26. Nf3 Nc4 27. Qf4 Nxb2 28. h5
{ Finally White decides to make this move, which opens up the position of Blacks king and decides the game. The loss of the b2-pawn is not important, since White has a winning attack. }
28... Nc4
{ if   28...gxh5  then  29.Kg2   29.Bf6  29...Ne7  30.Bf6  Ng6  31.Qg5 } 29.
hxg6 hxg6 30. Kg2 Qb8
{ If   30...Rh7  then  31.Rh1  Rxh1   31...Ree7  32.Bxe7  Rxe7  33.Qh4  Kf7  34.Qf6+  Ke8  35.Rh8+  32.Rxh1  Rf8  33.Bf6  Kf7  34.Rh7+  Ke8  35.Qh6  with mate in a few moves. }
31. Rh1
{ In the end the absence of the bishop from g7 and the open h-file prove decisive. Black has no defence against the coming invasion by Whites queen and rooks along the hfile. }
31... Qc7 32. Bf6 Rg7
{ 32...Rxf6  33.Qh4  Ref8  34.exf6   32...Rh7  33.Rxh7  Qxh7  34.Rh1  is equally futile. }
33. Qh6 Kf8
{ And Black resigned, rather than allow the mate after 34. Qh8+ Rg8 35. Qxg8+ Kxg8 36. Rh8+ Kf7 37. Ng5 mate.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw White recapturing on d4 with 9. cxd4, instead of 9. exd4, as in the previous game, which is recommended by GM Prié.  The cxd4 recapture is even better for White if he is able to play Nc3, as we shall see in the next game. White's idea is to play e3-e4 and e4-e5 and then attack the black king. He can also play on the queenside, on the c-file or with Ba6. Black played Nc6, which is the main line, although we also analysed some alternatives such as Ba6, or d7-d6 and Nbd7, or d7-d5.  In the game, Black ended up in a bad position with the plan of Qa8, as in the Réti Reversed. However, White should have opened the game with 21. exf6. It is worth noting the plan of g2-g3, Kg2 and Rh1 to open the h-file, which, since Black lacked a bishop on g7, proved decisive. }
*

