[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Queen’s Indian"]
[Black "Game 28 - PriÃ© vs. Karpov"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
{ With the   2.Bf4  move order recommended here, Black has some interesting alternatives after  b6  3.e3  Bb7  4.Nf3   4.Nd2   4.h3  4...g6   4...Nh5  5.Bg5   5.Nc3 !?   5.Bg3 !?  5...h6  6.Bh4  g5  7.Nfd2  Ng7   7...Nf4  8.exf4  gxh4  9.Nf3  e6  ∞  8.Bg3  +=  d6   8...Nf5  9.Be5  +=  9.h4   9.e4  +=  9...Nf5  10.hxg5  Nxg3  11.fxg3  ∞  Prié-Weill, Montpellier 2015;   4...h6 !?  5.h3   5.Bd3 !?  5...e6  6.Bd3  Bd6  7.Bxd6   7.Nc3 !?  Bxf4  8.exf4  c5  9.Qe2  ∞  De Prado-Fernandez, Arteixo 2016  7...cxd6  8.c4  O-O  9.Nc3  d5  Grischuk-Anton,Berlin Wch rapid 2015  5.Nbd2   5.c4 !?  Bg7  6.Nc3  d6  7.d5  Grischuk-Vachier-Lagrave, Berlin Wch blitz 2015  5...Bg7  6.Bc4  O-O  7.O-O  c5  8.c3  Sergeev-Kovalenko, Lutsk 2015 }
2... e6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 { If   4.h3 !?  then  Ba6  or   4...Bd6 } 4... Bb7
{ In a game by one of the co-authors, White was able to take advantage of the premature exchange on d4. After   4...c5  5.Nbd2  cxd4  6.exd4  Bb7  7.Bd3  Be7  8.h3  O-O  9.a3  d6  10.O-O  Nbd7  11.c4  Better were   11.Bh2   11.Re1  or   11.Qe2  11...Re8  12.Re1  +=  White had reached a theoretical position with an extra tempo, having played c2-c4 in one move, in De Prado-Sanchez, Spain tt 2011. }
5. h3
{ This is an inaccuracy. Playing h2-h3 prematurely is one of the greatest mistakes made by players on the white side of the London System. In this line the right moment to play h2-h3 is when Black has played Be7 and threatens to play Nh5. The right move order is therefore   5.Bd3  Be7  and now after   5...Bd6 !?  is playable, e.g.  6.Bg3  I think that it is better to respond with   6.Bxd6  cxd6  7.Nbd2   7.c4  7...d5  8.O-O  O-O  Maisuradze-Bollengier, Caen 2011  6...Bxg3  7.hxg3  c5  8.Nbd2  Nc6  9.c3  Qc7  10.dxc5  bxc5  11.Qa4  Appel-LAmi, Germany Bundesliga 2013/14  6.h3  playing  Bd6  at the cost of a tempo is not so effective for Black, for instance:  7.Bxd6   7.Be5  Bxe5  8.dxe5  Ne4  9.Bxe4  Bxe4  10.Nc3  Bb7  11.Qe2  O-O  12.O-O-O  with a complex position.  7...cxd6  8.Nbd2   8.O-O  O-O  9.c4  d5  10.Nc3  dxc4  11.Bxc4  Nc6  12.Qe2  +=  8...d5  9.O-O  O-O  and now  10.c4   10.Rc1  Nc6  11.c4  Nb4  12.Bb1  dxc4  13.Nxc4  Qe7  14.a3  Nc6  +=  Hoang Thanh Trang-Vazquez, Jakarta 2013.  10...Nc6  11.Re1  Nb4  12.Bf1  dxc4  Balogh-Kaunas, Budapest 1993; }
5... c5
{ Black has also tried   5...d6  6.Nbd2  Nbd7  7.Bd3  g6 !?  a mixture of the Queens Indian and the King's Indian  8.Qe2  Bg7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Rfd1   10.c3  Qe7  11.e4  e5  Vager-Medvedkov, St Petersburg 1997   10.Ba6  +=   10.Rad1  +=  10...a6  11.a4  Qe7  +=  Pri-Delchev, Noyon 2008. }
6. c3 cxd4
{ Other options are:   6...Be7  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Nbd2  Ba6  9.Bxa6  Nxa6  10.Qe2  Nb8  11.O-O  Nc6  12.Rfd1  +=   6...d5  7.Bxb8  Rxb8  8.Bb5+  +=   6...Nc6  7.Nbd2  d5  8.Ne5  Nxe5  9.dxe5   9.Bxe5  +=  9...Nd7  10.h4  h5  11.Qf3  Qc7  12.Qg3  O-O-O  +=  Kamsky-Karjakin, Beijing 2013   12...g6 }
7. cxd4
{ Recapturing with the c-pawn is even better here, because White's queens knight now has the option of going to c3 immediately or to d2, depending on what Black does. }
7... Nc6
{ Now   7...Ba6  is inferior:  8.Bxa6  Nxa6  9.O-O  Be7  10.a3  O-O  11.Qd3  += }
8. a3
{ To prevent the unpleasant idea of ...Nb4 if we play the bishop to d3. Also playable is   8.Nbd2  Be7  9.a3  O-O  10.Bd3  += }
8... Be7 9. Nc3 d5
{ This move seems dubious to me: I think that it is bad to block in the b7-bishop. It seems to me to be better to leave the pawn on d7 and then play d7-d6 or d7-d5 later, as and when appropriate. The position now resembles a line of the Exchange Variation of the Slav Defence where Black has not equalised, due to placing his bishop on b7. It was better to play   9...O-O  10.Bd3  Rc8  11.Qe2  += }
10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O Rc8 12. Qe2 Na5
{ Black seeks counterplay against c4 and b3. If   12...Bd6  then  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.Rfc1   14.Rac1  +=  14...Qe7  15.Rc2  Ne8  +=  Camara-Dos Santos, Sao Paulo 1997 }
13. Ne5
{ A dubious move that allows Black to equalise. Ulf Andersson played better with   13.Nd2  Bd6  14.Bxd6  Qxd6  15.Rac1  Qe7  16.Rc2  Ne8  17.b4  Nc6  18.Rfc1  with a comfortable advantage, which White steered to a win in Andersson-Ansell, Birmingham 2006.   13.Rac1  += }
13... Nd7
{ It was better to play   13...Ne4 !  which would equalise for Black. } 14.
Rfe1 { White should acknowledge his error and retreat with   14.Nf3  += } 14...
Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Nc4 16. Bg3 Nd6
{ Black would equalise more easily by bolstering the knight on c4 with a7-a6 and b7-b5:   16...a6  17.Rec1  b5 }
17. Rac1 Qd7 18. Rc2 Nc4 19. Rec1 a6
{ It would be bad to play   19...Nxb2  20.Rxb2  Bxa3  21.Qd2  Bxb2  22.Qxb2  h6  23.Ra1  ±  Instead, it was more logical to support the knight with   19...b5  with equality. }
20. Nb1
{ White wants to play b2-b3 and evict the annoying knight from c4.  Instead,   20.a4  b5  21.axb5  axb5  22.Nb1  was playable, with the same idea. }
20... b5 21. b3 Nd6
{ 21...Nxa3  fails to  22.Rc7 !  Qd8  23.Qa2  b4  24.Nxa3  bxa3  25.Qb1  Rxc7   25...h6  26.Rxb7  26.Bxh7+  Kh8  27.Rxc7  Ba8  28.Bd3  with a clear advantage to White. }
22. Rc5 Rc6
{ A bad move that allows White to make a combination.  It was better to play   22...Ne4  23.Bxe4  Bxc5  24.Bxh7+  Kxh7  25.dxc5  and, although White has compensation, Black is not worse. }
23. Rxc6 Bxc6 { How should White continue now ? } 24. Bxh7+
{ Correct. White wins a pawn. A most surprising error on Karpov's part, although it should be said that this was a rapidplay game with only 25 minutes per player. }
24... Kxh7 25. Qc2+
{ It was more precise to eliminate the knight first with   25.Bxd6  Qxd6  26.Qc2+  Kg8  27.Qxc6  and White's advantage is clear. }
25... Ne4 26. Qxc6 Qxc6 27. Rxc6 Nxg3 28. fxg3 a5 29. Kf2 Kg6 30. Kf3
{ White misses the opportunity to activate his knight with   30.Nc3  Bxa3  31.Nxd5  again maintaining a clear advantage. }
30... Rb8 31. Rc7 Bd6 32. Rc6 Be7 33. Rc7
{ Prié decided to repeat moves; perhaps he was very short of time. White could retain the advantage with   33.g4  Rb7  34.Ke2  Rb8  35.g3  Rb7  36.h4  Rb8  37.Ra6  b4   37...a4  38.b4  38.a4  ±  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the premature exchange  6...cxd4  , which allows White to recapture with his c-pawn and have the option of developing his queen's knight to  c3.  Also remember the correct moment to play h2-h3, which is after Black has played  Be7.   In the game Black could have equalised with  Bd6.  For White the move a2-a3 is quite thematic, to prevent the black knight leaping to  b4  to harass the bishop on  d3.  I think that the black scheme with  Bb7  followed by d7-d5 is dubious, because the black bishop on  b7  remains passive.  White can gain the advantage by doubling his rooks on the c-file, as in the Andersson game that we saw. Prié allowed Karpov to equalise after  Ne5  , which in that position was not correct. Then Karpov allowed the shot  Bxh7+  and was almost lost. }
*

