[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Queen’s Indian"]
[Black "Game 29 - Blatny vs. Jurek"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 Be7 6. Bd3
{ The Czech GM Pavel Blatny likes to play attacking positions and is one of the few players who do not play h2-h3. He has his own ideas, based on rapid queenside castling and an attack on the enemy king. }
6... Nh5
{ This is the only way to try to punish White for not playing h2-h3.  Black has also played   6...c5  7.c3  and now:  Nh5   7...d6  8.Qe2  O-O  9.h4 !?  Nc6  10.O-O-O  Rc8  11.Kb1  cxd4  12.exd4  Re8  13.Ne4  +=  Blatny-Pioch, Triberg 1991   7...cxd4  8.exd4  O-O  9.h4  Ba6  10.Qe2  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  Qc8  12.Ng5  Qc6  13.O-O-O  d6  with unclear play, Blatny-D. Gurevich, Biel 1991.  8.Bg3  d6   8...Nxg3  9.hxg3  h6  10.Qe2  Nc6  11.g4  d6  12.O-O-O  Qc7  13.g5  +=  Blatny-De Francesco, Graz 2013  9.Qe2  Nd7   9...a6  10.O-O-O   10.e4  cxd4  11.cxd4  Nc6  12.a3  d5  13.e5  O-O  14.O-O =  Kamsky-Almasi, Beijing 2011  10...Nd7  11.Ne4   11.Kb1  ∞  11...Nxg3  12.hxg3  c4  13.Bc2  b5  14.g4  b4   14...d5  =+  15.cxb4 =  Blatny-Forintos, Germany Bundesliga B 1991  10.O-O-O  h6  11.Kb1  Qc7  12.Bc2   12.e4  a6  13.d5  e5  14.c4  g6  15.Ne1  Bg5  16.Nc2 =  Chernyshov-Krejci, Olomouc 2010  12...Nxg3  13.hxg3  O-O-O  14.g4  Kb8  15.e4 =  Blatny-Chachere, Gausdal 1992; }
7. Qe2
{ This is Blatny's idea: he spends no time on retreating the bishop and quickly castles queenside.  The main move here is   7.Bg3  but Black has no problems in this line and equalises easily, for example after  d6   7...h6   7...Nxg3  8.hxg3  h6  8.c3  Nd7  9.Qe2   9.Qc2  g6  10.a4  a6  11.O-O  O-O =  J.Polgar-Topalov, Linares 1994  9...c5  10.a3  h6  11.e4  cxd4  12.Nxd4  Nxg3  13.hxg3  a6  14.f4  Nc5  15.Bc2  Qc7  16.O-O-O =  Kamsky-Rozentalis, Manila 1992. }
7... d6
{ 7...Nxf4  8.exf4  c5  9.dxc5   9.c3  9...bxc5  10.O-O  O-O =  Cinar-Maric, Varna 1994. }
8. h4
{ White has no intention of castling on the kingside. 8. Bg3 would take us back into known theory. Instead,   8.O-O-O  Nd7  9.Ne4  O-O  10.h4  Nxf4  11.exf4  Re8  was unclear in Orlov-Renet, Pancevo 1985 }
8... Nxf4
{ Black eliminates the bishop before White can retreat it to h2. However,   8...Nd7  9.Bh2  Nhf6  10.O-O-O  c5  11.c3  Qc7  12.Kb1  a6  13.e4  was about equal in Ortega-Dizdarevic, Formia 1995. }
9. exf4 Nd7 10. f5
{ It was better to play   10.O-O-O  O-O  11.Rde1  and now if Black makes a natural move, such as  Re8  intending to play to play Bf8 or Nf8, he lands in a mess after the sacrifice  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Ng5+  Kg8   13...Bxg5  14.hxg5+  Kg8  15.Qh5  ±  14.Qh5  ± }
10... exf5 11. Bxf5 g6
{ It was better to play   11...O-O  12.O-O-O  Re8  13.Be4   13.Bxh7+  Kxh7  14.Ng5+  Kg8  15.Qh5  Nf8  16.Qxf7+  Kh8  17.Qh5+  Kg8  13...Bxe4  14.Qxe4  c5  with equality. }
12. Be4
{ Here it is better to play   12.Bd3  O-O  13.h5   13.Ba6  Bxa6  14.Qxa6  c5  15.O-O-O  ∞  13...Re8  14.hxg6  hxg6   14...Bf6  15.gxf7+  Kxf7  16.Ne4  Kf8  17.O-O-O  ±  15.O-O-O  Bf6  16.Qf1  c5  with complex play. }
12... c6
{ It was better to play   12...d5 !  13.Bd3  c5  14.c3  O-O  15.O-O-O  Re8  =+ }
13. h5
{ A thematic move to gain space and open the h-file, despite the fact that Black has not yet castled. White seizes the initiative and poses Black problems, because he threatens to take on g6. What should Black do ? }
13... Rg8
{ This is an error. It was essential to take the risk of castling, e.g.   13...O-O  14.O-O-O  Bf6  15.hxg6  hxg6  16.Qd3  Bg7  17.Bxg6  fxg6  18.Qxg6  Rf4   18...Rf6  19.Qh7+  Kf8  20.Ne4  +=  19.Qxd6  Rf6  20.Qg3  Nf8  when White has three pawns for the piece and the attack. }
14. O-O-O Nf6 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Rde1
{ White has a clear advantage: the black king is still in the centre and the bishop on b7 is passive. }
16... Kd7
{ The best move: the king flees but will find no safe haven. Black would be lost after   16...Nxe4  17.Qxe4  Kf8   17...Qd7  18.Ng5  18.Rh7  Bg5  19.Nxg5  Qxg5  20.Qf3  Rg7  21.Rh8+  Rg8  22.Qh3 }
17. Ng5 Qf8 18. d5
{ Trying to expose the black king, which is still in the centre of the board. }
18... cxd5
{ 18...Nxd5  fails to  19.Bxd5  cxd5   19...Bxg5  20.Qg4+  Kc7  21.Qxg5  cxd5  22.Re7+  20.Nh7  Qd8  21.Qf3  f5  22.Qe3  ± }
19. Bd3 Rc8
{ It was necessary to prevent the check on b5 with   19...a6  20.Ndf3  Bd8  21.Kb1  Kc8  22.Qd2  Kb8  23.Qb4  Ka7  24.Qa4  White retains the advantage, but Black is still in the game. }
20. Bb5+ Kd8
{ It was slightly more tenacious to play   20...Bc6  but after, for instance,  21.Ndf3  Bxb5  22.Qxb5+  Kc7  23.Nd4  Qe8  24.Qa6  Kb8  25.Nb5  Qd7  26.Nxa7  Qxa7  27.Qxa7+  Kxa7  28.Rxe7+  White would have a decisive advantage. How should White continue now ? }
21. Qe6
{ Very pretty, but less effective than the spectacular   21.Rh7 !!  with the unstoppable threat of 22. Rxf7, while after  Nxh7  22.Nxh7  wins; the black queen cannot move away because of the mate on e7. }
21... Rxc2+ { 21...Rg7  then  22.Rh8 !   21...fxe6  22.Nxe6# ! } 22. Kxc2 fxe6
23. Nxe6+ Kc8 24. Nxf8 Bxf8
{ White is the exchange up, the b7-bishop is passive and Black's pawns are doubled, but the game still carried on for a good while. }
25. Nb3 a6 26. Bd3 Kd7 27. Nd4 Ne4 28. f3 Bg7 29. fxe4
{ It was better to play   29.Rh7 !  Nf6  30.Bxg6  Nxh7  31.Bxh7  Rc8+  32.Kd3  Re8  33.Bf5+  Kd8  34.Ne6+  with a decisive advantage. }
29... Bxd4 30. Rh7+ Rg7 31. Rxg7+ Bxg7 32. exd5 Bxd5 33. Bxg6 Be5
{ 33...Bxg2  fails to  34.Bf5+  Kc6  35.Rg1   33...Bxa2  34.b3  Be5  35.g4  a5  36.Bd3  Kc6  37.Re4  wins. }
34. g4 Ke6 35. Rf1 Ke7 36. Bd3 b5 37. g5 Be6 38. b3 Bd7 39. b4 Be6 40. a3 Bd5
41. g6 Bg7 42. Re1+ Be5 43. Be4
{ White either exchanges bishops or invades b7. } 43... Be6
{ 43...Bxe4+  44.Rxe4  Kf6  45.Rg4 } 44. Rf1 Bc4 45. Rf3 Bf6 46. Bb7 d5 47. Rf5
Ke6 48. Bc8+ Ke7 49. Bxa6 Ke6 50. Bc8+ Ke7 51. Rf3 d4 52. Bf5 Bd5 53. Rf1
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw GM Blatny's idea of playing without h2-h3, thus allowing the London bishop to be exchanged. His plan is to play Qe2, O-O-O and h2-h4, to attack on the kingside.   It is an interesting option and worth considering if we want a complicated game, or we need to take risks in pursuit of a win. If Black is not well prepared he can come unstuck.   In the game Black did not dare to castle on the kingside, but his king remained in the centre and came under a strong attack just the same. }
*

