1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 Be7
{ An interesting idea is the move order   3...c5  4.e3  and now :  cxd4   4...b6  5.Nc3 !  This move gives White the advantage. Let us view a few examples:  cxd4   5...d5  6.Nb5 !  +=  Na6  7.Ne5   7.h3  +=   7.Be2  +=  7...Bb7  8.c3  Be7  9.a4 ?!   9.Ng4  +=  9...O-O  10.Bd3  Nb8 =  Kosic-Belezky, Munich 2013;   5...a6  6.d5 !  +=  d6  7.dxe6   7.a4  +=  Nilsen-Djurhuus, Oslo 2015  7...Bxe6  8.Ng5  d5  9.Nxe6  fxe6  10.g4  ±  Karjakin-Ni, Doha 2015  6.Nb5 !  with the threat of 7. Nc7;   6.Nxd4  Bb4  7.Qf3   7.Ndb5  +=  7...d5  8.Ndb5   8.Bd3  +=  8...Na6  9.a3  Bxc3+  10.Nxc3  O-O  11.Bg5  +=  Sammour Hasbun-Akobian, Saint Louis 2013   6.exd4  Bb7  7.Bd3  Be7  8.O-O  Kf8  9.h3  a6  10.Re1 =  Nguyen Thi May-Batchimeg, Tagaytay City 2013  6...d6   6...Nd5  7.Qxd4 !  worse is   7.Nd6+ ?  Bxd6  8.Bxd6  dxe3  =+  Bozic-Cabrilo, Vrnjacka Banja 2007  but   7.Bd6  is playable e.g.  a6   7...dxe3 ?  8.Bc4  8.Bxf8  Kxf8  9.Nbxd4  +=  7...Nc6   7...Nxf4  8.Qxf4  Na6  9.O-O-O  +=  Ortega-Marinelli, Catania 1993.   7...a6  8.Nd6+  Bxd6  9.Bxd6  ±  8.Qa4   8.Nd6+ ?!  Bxd6  9.Qxg7  Bb4+  10.c3  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Qf6 =  Echeverria-Gongora, Mislata 2008  8...a6  9.Nd6+  Bxd6  10.Bxd6  Bb7  11.O-O-O  ±  Peter Horvath-Pal Petran, Hungary tt 2001;  7.Qxd4  ±  Nd5 ?   7...Nc6  8.Nxd6+  Bxd6  9.Qxd6  ±   7...e5 ?  8.Nxe5  dxe5  9.Qxe5+  Be7  10.Nc7+  8.Nxd6+  Bxd6  9.Qxg7  Kd7   9...Rf8  10.Bb5+  10.Bxd6  Kxd6  11.e4  +-  Ortega-Farago, Montecatini Terme 2000;  5.exd4  b6  6.Nbd2  it is better to use the move order   6.Bd3  Be7  7.O-O  Ba6  8.c4  Nc6  9.Nc3  +=  d5  10.Qa4  ±  6...Be7  7.h3  O-O  8.Bd3  Ba6  this idea works better without losing a tempo with Bb7  9.Bxa6   9.c4  Nc6  10.a3  d5  9...Nxa6  10.O-O  b5  11.c3  Nc7  12.a4 =  Kamsky-Topalov, Sofia 2007  Another alternative for Black is   3...Nh5 !?  4.Bg5  Be7  5.Bxe7  Qxe7  6.e3   6.e4 !?  6...O-O   6...Qb4+  7.Nc3  Qxb2 ?  8.Nb5  ±  7.c4  Nf6   7...Qb4+  8.Qd2  +=  8.Nc3  += }
4. h3 { We need to remember that if   4.e3  then  Nh5 } 4... b6 5. e3 Ne4
{ This was a surprise, since Black does not usually play this move so early. Black wants to seize control of the e4-square with Bb7 and then f7-f5. The normal moves are   5...Bb7   5...O-O }
6. Bd3 { 6.Nbd2   6.Nfd2  were also playable. } 6... Bb7 7. Nbd2
{ The natural move would be to castle, but I preferred this move, since if Black plays f7-f5 then White has other options.  After   7.O-O  O-O  there are several examples:  8.Bxe4   8.Nfd2 !?  d5  and now  9.Nxe4   9.a4  a5   9...f5  10.Nxe4   10.Bxe4  dxe4  11.Nc3  f5  12.Nb5  +=  10...dxe4  11.Bc4  Bd6 =  Bauer-Miezis, Grchen 2013  9...dxe4  10.Be2  Nd7  11.c4  Bf6   11...f5  12.Nc3  +=  Vila-Fernandez, Valencia 2006;   8.a4  f5  9.a5  Kh8  10.a6  Bc6  11.c4  +=  Renner-Traunwieser, Grieskirchen 2013;   8.Nbd2  f5  9.c3  d6   9...Qe8  10.Qc2  Nxd2  11.Nxd2  Nc6   11...Nd7 =  Noiroux-M.Erwich, Belgium tt 2010/11  12.a3  Bf6  13.d5  +=  De Prado-Baltar, Spain tt 2014  8...Bxe4  9.c4  d6  10.Nc3  Bb7  11.e4  Nd7 =  Appel-Gordon, Trier 2013; }
7... d5
{ Another option is   7...Nxd2  8.Qxd2   8.Nxd2  8...O-O  9.e4  +=   9.O-O-O !?   9.c3 }
8. O-O
{ Or   8.c3  Nd7  and now :  9.Qe2   9.O-O  O-O  10.a4  c5  11.Qe2   11.a5  +=  11...Nxd2   11...a5  12.Qxd2  Bf6   12...c4  13.b4  Qe7   13...c4  +=  14.bxc5  bxc5  15.Rfb1  +=  Bogosavljevic-Miljkovic, Kragujevac 2013;   9.Qc2  and Black has the following options:  Ndf6   9...f5  10.g4  g6  11.gxf5  exf5  12.h4  +=  Lomineishvili-Makropoulou, Belgrade 2013.  10.Ne5   10.a4  10...O-O  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.f3   12.O-O  12...Bh4+   12...Nf6  13.Ke2  g5  14.Bh2  Ng3+  15.Bxg3  Bxg3  16.Bxh7+  Kg7  17.Bd3  c5  and Black has compensation, Toufighi-Khalesi, Tabriz 2012;  9...a6  10.O-O  it is better to play   10.O-O-O  10...g5 !   10...O-O  11.Bh2  h5  12.Ne5  Nxe5  13.Bxe5  f6  14.Bh2  Nxd2  15.Qxd2  f5 =  Macek-Pokorna, Pula 2002;   8.c4 !  and   8.a4  are also playable. }
8... Nd7
{ Another option was   8...g5  9.Be5   9.Bh2  h5  10.Ne5  ±  9...Rg8  10.Nh2 ?!   10.c4  ±  10...Nxd2  11.Qxd2  f6  12.Bg3  h5  +=  Dobos-Lakat, Budapest 2005. }
9. c4
{ This seems to be the best plan for White: attack d5 and e4, and open the c-file to put pressure on c7, with the aid of the rook on c1 and the bishop on f4. White could also employ the move order   9.Rc1  O-O  10.c4 }
9... Nxd2
{ Now   9...g5 ?  is not a good idea:  10.Bh2  f5  or   10...h5  11.cxd5  exd5  12.Qc2  Nxd2  13.Nxd2  c5  14.Bf5  ±  11.cxd5  Bxd5   11...exd5  12.Rc1  ±  12.Rc1  ±  White retains some advantage after   9...c5  10.cxd5   10.Rc1  O-O  11.cxd5  exd5  12.Bb5  +=  10...exd5  11.Qc2  f5   11...Nxd2  12.Nxd2  +=   11...Ndf6  12.Bb5+  ±  12.dxc5  bxc5  13.Bb5  += }
10. Nxd2
{ If   10.Qxd2  then  dxc4  11.Bxc4  O-O   11...Bxf3 !?  12.gxf3  O-O  ∞  12.Qe2  Bd6 }
10... dxc4
{ This appears to be the best move.  If   10...Nf6  then  11.Qa4+  c6   11...Qd7  12.Qxd7+  Kxd7  13.Rac1  +=  12.Rfd1  +=  Once again   10...O-O ?  is bad due to  11.cxd5  Bxd5   11...exd5  12.Qc2  ±  12.Qc2  ±  If   10...c5  then  11.cxd5  Bxd5   11...exd5  12.Qc2  h6  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.Rad1  +=  12.Qg4  += }
11. Nxc4 O-O 12. Qc2
{ Trying to put pressure on h7 and c7.  Other options were   12.Rc1  +=  or   12.Qe2  += }
12... h6 { 12...g6  13.Rac1  +=   12...Nf6  13.Rfd1  += } 13. Rfd1
{ White had the interesting alternatives   13.Bh7+  Kh8  14.Be4  Bxe4  15.Qxe4  Nf6   15...c5  16.Rad1  +=  16.Qc6  Nd5  17.Bg3  Rc8  18.Rfc1  +=   13.Rac1  += }
13... Nf6 14. a3
{ This move was directed against 14... Nd5, which would threaten 15... Nb4 as well as 15... Nxf4, although it was also possible to ignore this with   14.Rac1  Nd5   14...Qd5  15.f3  c5  16.Ne5  +=  15.a3   15.Ne5  Nxf4  16.exf4  +=  15...Nxf4  16.exf4  Bd5   16...Qd5  17.Ne3  +=   16...f5  17.Qe2  +=  17.Ne3  += }
14... Qd5
{ Or   14...Nd5  15.Bg3  Rc8  16.Rac1  c5  17.dxc5  Bxc5  18.Qd2  += } 15. f3
{ It was better to play   15.Bf1  c5  16.Rac1  Rfd8  17.Ne5  += } 15... c5 16.
dxc5 Qxc5 17. b4 Qh5
{ The black queen will remain exposed in the future. It was better to play   17...Qc6  18.Rac1  Rfd8  19.Qb2   19.Qb1  Qe8  20.Bc7  Rdc8  21.Be5  +=  19...Qa4  20.Bc2  Qc6  21.Bb3  += }
18. e4
{ This move was designed to avoid possible sacrifices on f3 and to leave the b7-bishop out of play. White could also have opted for   18.Nd6  or   18.Bd6  retaining a slight advantage. }
18... Qh4 { it seems best to play   18...Rac8  19.Qf2  Rfd8  20.Be2  += } 19.
g3
{ White wants to hunt down the black queen and so sacrifices a pawn.  A quieter continuation was   19.Bd6 !  Rfe8   19...Nh5  20.Qf2  +=  20.Qf2  Qxf2+  21.Kxf2  Ba6  22.Bxe7  Rxe7  23.Rac1  +=  but during the game I considered that the move 19. g3 presented Black with more difficulties. }
19... Qxh3
{ Black must accept the challenge or lose time; if   19...Qh5  then  20.Kg2   20.Qf2  20...Rac8  21.Qe2  ± }
20. Rd2 { Threatening 21. Rh2, winning the queen. } 20... e5
{ Black had to play   20...Qh5  and although after  21.Ne5  he has to sacrifice his queen, in return he gains some counterplay:  Bd6   21...Rfc8  22.Bc4   22.Qa2  Bd6  23.g4  Bxe5  24.gxh5  Bxf4  ±  22...Ba6  23.Rh2  Bxc4  24.Rxh5  Nxh5  25.Bxh6  Bf6  26.Bf4  +=  22.g4  Bxe5   22...Qh4  23.Rh2  Bxe5  24.Rxh4  Bxa1  25.Bxh6  ±  23.gxh5  Bxf4   23...Bxa1  24.Qc7  Rab8  25.Bb5  24.Rdd1  and White is clearly better; }
21. Nxe5 g5
{ Black was relying on this resource, but he is lost.  if   21...Rac8  then  22.Qb3  and now :  g5 ?   22...Nh5  is slightly better, but fails to save Black after  23.Bf1  Qe6  24.Qxe6  fxe6  25.Rd7  Bf6  26.Rxb7  g5  27.Rd1  gxf4  28.Nd7  Rf7  29.g4  Ng3  30.Nxf6+  Rxf6  31.Rdd7  23.Ng6  Rfe8   23...gxf4  24.Nxe7+  24.Bb5  Qh5   24...gxf4  25.Nxf4  Qxg3+  26.Rg2   24...Bc6  25.Ne5  25.Ne5  gxf4  and White has a decisive advantage with multiple threats, such as  26.Rh2  or   26.Bxe8  Other defensive possibilities were   21...Qc8  22.Bc4  threatening 23. Ng6 and 23. Qb3   21...Nh5  22.Rh2 }
22. Qc7 Rae8
{ Other tries were   22...Rfe8  23.Qxb7  gxf4  24.Bc4  or   22...gxf4  23.Qxe7  Qe6  24.Qxe6  fxe6  25.gxf4 }
23. Qxb7 gxf4 24. Rh2 Qc8 { if   24...Qe6  then  25.gxf4 } 25. Qxc8 Rxc8 26.
gxf4
{ White has a decisive advantage: he is a pawn up, the black pawns on h6 and f7 are weak and there are attacking chances against the black king. }
26... h5 { 26...Kh7  27.Rd1  Rc3  28.Bc4  Rxa3  29.Nxf7 } 27. Rg2+ Kh7 28. Bc4
Rg8 29. Ra2 { Here   29.Rxg8  Rxg8+  30.Kh1  h4  31.Bxf7  was strong. } 29...
Rxg2+ 30. Rxg2 Rg8
{ if   30...Nd7  White wins with  31.Bxf7  Nxe5  32.fxe5  Rc3  33.f4  Rxa3  34.f5 }
31. Rxg8 Kxg8 32. Nxf7 { White wins a second pawn and the game. } 32... Kg7 33.
e5 Nd7 34. f5 Bh4 35. Kg2 a5 36. bxa5 bxa5 37. Kh3 Bf2 38. f4 Bc5 39. a4 Nb6
40. Bb3 Be3 41. Ng5 Nd7 42. f6+ Kf8 43. Ne6+ Ke8 44. Ng7+ Kf8 45. Nxh5
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@We saw in this game some alternatives to the main lines. Remember that an early c7-c5 and b7-b6 is well answered with 5. Nc3 !, which gives White the advantage.  In the game we saw Black's plan of ... Ne4 to gain a grip on the centre. Black can follow this up with f7-f5 or d7-d5. I think that it is better for White to delay castling, in case Black plays f7-f5, since in that case the plan of queenside castling, Rg1 and g2-g4 is good.  If Black plays d7-d5, the best plan for White is to advance with c2-c4, put pressure on d5 and e4, open the c-file and with the help of the f4-bishop put pressure on c7.  In the game Black had to make some concessions to enable him to castle and White emerged from the opening with advantage. Blacks plan of Qh5 was dubious, since he had problems with his queen on the kingside.  White sacrificed a pawn and gained a clear advantage, while Black, in order not to lose his queen, had to sacrifice material and was unable to save the game. }
*

