[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Queen’s Indian"]
[Black "Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ We have been studying the Queen's Indian set-up against the London System. In Game 25 we saw Blacks traditional line, based on exchanging pawns on d4: White recaptured with the e-pawn and Black continued with the plan of d7-d6 and Nbd7.  In Game 26 we saw Black's other option of developing his queen's knight to c6. White used one of the standard plans with a2-a4 and Re1, followed by the advance of the queenside pawns with c2-c4. Another option is to play Qe2 and operate on the kingside with Ng5, or Nc4 followed by Ne3-g4.  In Game 27 we saw the recommendation of GM Prié, which is to recapture on d4 with the c-pawn. Whites idea is to play on the open c-file, advance with e4-e5 and attack on the kingside.  In Game 28 we saw that if Black exchanges pawns on d4 at an early stage, recapturing with the c-pawn allows White to develop the queens knight directly to c3.  In Game 29 we saw GM Blatny's idea to dispense with h2-h3 and allow the exchange of the f4-bishop for Black's knight. White's plan then is to play Qe2, O-O-O and h2-h4 to attack the black king and this is an interesting and complex line, suitable for players who like to attack, or for when you need to go all out for a win.  It is good to have this plan in your arsenal, because if the opponent is not familiar with its nuances he can easily get into difficulties.  Finally in Game 30 we saw various ideas: if Black plays an early b7-b6 and c7-c5, White has the option of 5. Nc3, which gives him the advantage.  We also analysed Black's idea of Ne4, which can transpose to positions from the Dutch Defence if Black follows up with f7-f5. Whites idea is to undermine the strong centralised knight with c2-c4 and open the c-file.  Remember that if Black plays an early c7-c5 and exchanges on d4 we have some extra options. Also keep in mind that the move h2-h3 is only necessary when Black plays Be7 and threatens Nh5. If White plays h2-h3 before Black plays Be7 Black can equalise by playing Bd6 directly. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Benoni"]
[Black "Chapter 5 vs. London Versus the Benoni"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 { 1...c5  2.c3  cxd4  3.cxd4  d5 } 2. Bf4 c5 { 2...e6 } 3. e3
{ 3.d5   3.dxc5   3.c3 } 3... e6 { 3...Qb6   3...cxd4   3...Nd5 } 4. Nf3 Qb6
{ 4...d5 } 5. Nc3 { 5.Na3 } 5... d5 { 5...Qxb2   5...a6 } 6. Nb5 { 6.a3 } 6...
Na6 7. a4
{ The Benoni Defence is characterised by the move c7-c5 by Black. Against the London System Black cannot achieve a normal Benoni position because White usually abstains from advancing with d4-d5, instead playing c2-c3 or e2-e3.  Black then has the option of playing Qb6, putting pressure on b2. The majority of the lines follow this route. White has several options to defend against this threat: one option is to play c2-c3 and Qb3; another interesting idea is to respond to Qb6 by developing the queen's knight to c3, d2 or a3, since normally Black cannot then take the b2-pawn.  If White plays d4-d5, we usually transpose to the Vaganian Gambit, which normally arises from the Trompowsky Opening. Another option for Black is to exchange pawns on d4 and after d7-d5 transpose to the Exchange Variation of the Slav Defence, which we shall cover in Chapter 7.  In answer to c7-c5, if your opponent is normally a Benoni player, then responding with c2-c3 is a good idea. If he does not normally play the Benoni, then advancing with d4-d5 is an option worth considering. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Benoni"]
[Black "Game 31 - de Prado Rodriguez vs. Patino"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Qb6
{ One of Black's typical ideas is to move the queen to b6 to attack the weak point b2, but here this gives White the advantage, since he can just ignore the attack. In addition, capturing on b2 often allows White to repeat the position with a perpetual attack on the black queen, which will not suit Black if he is the stronger player. }
5. Nc3
{ This is the most common response but it is not the best.  Instead   5.Na3 !  +=  is the best move, because it allows White to play Nc4 as well as Nb5. Let us consider some examples:  d5   5...cxd4  6.Nb5  +=  Na6  7.exd4  d6  8.a4   8.c4  +=  8...Be7  9.Be2   9.Nd2 !  +=  is better, with the idea of playing Nc4, e.g.  d5   9...O-O  10.Nc4  and the d6-pawn falls  10.Bd3  Bd7  11.c3  O-O  12.O-O  ±  9...O-O  10.O-O  +=  Mitkov-Tiviakov, Morella 2007;  Taking the pawn is bad:   5...Qxb2 ?  6.Nb5  Nd5  7.Rb1  Qxa2  8.Ra1  Qb2  9.Bc4  Qb4+  10.Nd2  Na6  11.Rb1  Qa4  12.Bxd5   12.O-O  Be7  13.Bd6  12...exd5  13.Qh5  but if Black really cannot take the pawn, then the move Qb6 is not a good one, because the queen becomes exposed to attack.  6.Nb5 !  Na6  7.a4  +=   7.c3  +=  7...c4   7...cxd4  8.exd4  Be7  9.c3  O-O  10.Bd3  ±  Kosic-Rindlisbacher, Gabicce Mare 2014  8.c3  and now :  Bd7  Or   8...Be7  9.b3  cxb3  10.Qxb3  O-O  and now  11.Be2  or   11.Bd3  ±  Mary-Yepez, cr 2002  or   11.h3  Ne4  12.Bd3  Bd7  13.Bxe4  dxe4  14.Ne5  ±  Kosic-Kovacevic, Herceg Novi 2001.  11...Nh5 ?!   11...Ne4  12.h3  Bd7  13.O-O  Rfc8  14.Rfc1  ±  12.Bc7 !  Nxc7  13.a5  Qc6  14.Ne5  Nxb5  15.Nxc6  bxc6  16.Bxh5  +-  De Prado-Melgar, Spain tt 2014  9.b3 !  Bxb5  10.axb5  Qxb5  11.bxc4  dxc4  12.Ne5 ?!   12.Rb1 !  Qa5  13.Bxc4  Qxc3+  14.Nd2  12...Rc8  13.Bxc4  Rxc4  14.Qe2  ±  Torre-Sinurat, Jakarta 2013  A few strong GMs have played 5. Qc1, but this is passive, as is 5. b3, and in both cases Black equalises. On c1 the queen is badly placed   5.Qc1  Nc6   5...Nh5 =  6.c3   6.dxc5  Bxc5  7.h3  d5  6...Nh5  7.Bg3  h6   7...Nxg3  8.hxg3  d5 =  Grachev-Moiseenko, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013  8.Nbd2  d5  9.Bd3  Be7  10.O-O  Nxg3 =  Kamsky-Giri, Beijing 2013. }
5... d5
{ However, the b2-pawn cannot be captured; after   5...Qxb2 ?  6.Nb5  Nd5   6...Na6 ?  7.a3  and the black queen cannot escape:  Nd5  8.Rb1  Qa2  9.Bd6  Bxd6  10.Bc4  Nc3  11.Nxd6+  Ke7  12.Bxa2  Nxd1  13.Nxc8+  Rhxc8  14.Kxd1  7.Rb1  Qxa2  8.Ra1  Qb2  9.Bc4 !  with the decisive threat of 10. Rb1  Nc3  10.Nc7+  Kd8  11.Qc1  Qb4  12.Bf1 !  ±  and the rook on a8 falls.  The best move is   5...a6 !  This should give Black equality:  6.dxc5   6.a3  Nh5  with a few examples:   6...cxd4  7.exd4  Be7  8.h3  O-O  9.Bd3  d5   9...d6 =  10.O-O  Bd7  Kovacevic-Narciso, La Pobla de Lillet 1997;   6...d5  7.dxc5   7.Be2  cxd4 =  7...Bxc5  8.Bd3   8.Be2  O-O  9.O-O =  8...Bd7  9.Rb1  Bd6 =  Kovacevic-Saric, Sibenik 2011.  7.Bg5 ?!   7.dxc5 !  Bxc5  8.Na4  Qa5+  9.c3  Nxf4  10.b4  Qc7  11.bxc5  ±  7...h6  8.Bh4  g5  9.Ne5  gxh4  10.Qxh5   10.dxc5 !  Bxc5  11.Qxh5  Qxb2  12.Kd2  10...Qxb2  11.Qxf7+  Kd8  12.Qf6+  Kc7  13.Kd2 ?!   13.Nd1  Qxa1  14.Qxh8  +=  13...cxd4 =  Zsu. Polgar-Browne, Dortmund 1990  6...Bxc5   6...Qxc5  7.Be2   7.e4 !?   7.Bd3  7...d5  8.O-O =  Pereyra-Engel, cr Argentina 1991  7.Be2  Qxb2  8.Na4  and now:  Qb4+ ?   8...Qa3 !  9.c4  d6   9...Bb4+  10.Kf1  +=  10.Nxc5  Qa5+  11.Qd2  Qxd2+  12.Nxd2  dxc5  13.Bd6  and White has compensation;  9.c3  Qa5  10.Nxc5  Qxc5   10...Qxc3+  11.Nd2  Qxc5  12.Rc1  11.Bd6  Qxc3+  12.Nd2  Nc6  13.Rc1  Qa5  14.Bf3  and White has the advantage; he has compensation for the two pawns, since Black is behind in development and his king is stuck in the centre; }
6. a3
{ The idea of a2-a3 is thematic in many variations of the London System, because it indirectly defends the b2-pawn, since after Na4 the black queen is trapped.  But here it was better to play the immediate   6.Nb5 !  transposing to the note to the move 5. Na3 ! above. }
6... Be7
{ 6...Qxb2 ??  then  7.Na4  wins;  however,   6...Bd7   6...a6  were both good moves. }
7. Nb5 Na6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 { 8...Qxc5  9.b4  Qb6  10.c4  is similar to the game. }
9. b4 Be7 10. c4 Qd8
{ It was better to play   10...dxc4  although White retains the advantage after  11.Nd6+  Also after   11.Bxc4  O-O   11...Bd7  12.Nd6+  Bxd6  13.Qxd6  Qxd6  14.Bxd6  +=  12.Be5  Bd7  13.Bd4  Qd8  14.O-O  +=  White would stand better.  11...Bxd6  12.Bxd6  Ne4   12...Nd5  13.Bg3  O-O  14.Bxc4  ±  13.Be5   13.Bf4  Nxb4  14.axb4  Qxb4+  15.Nd2  b5  +=  13...f6   13...Nxb4  14.axb4  Qxb4+  15.Nd2  14.Qc2  Nxf2  15.Qxf2  fxe5  16.Nxe5  ± }
11. c5
{ White has a clear advantage from the opening; his pieces are more active, the d6-square is weak, the c5-pawn is strong, Black's knight is passive on a6, and his c8-bishop and a8-rook have poor prospects. In contrast, Whites kings bishop can go to d3 and attack Blacks kingside. Blacks only possible counterplay is with f7-f6 and e6-e5. }
11... O-O 12. Bd3 Ne8
{ Black reinforces the d6-square and prepares to play f7-f6 and e6-e5, but the knight is passive on e8 and its absence from f6 weakens the defence of the black king. It was slightly better to play   12...Ne4  13.Nfd4  ± }
13. Qc2
{ Putting pressure on h7 and with the other eye on the c-file, where the advance of the c5-pawn is in the air. }
13... h6 14. O-O Bd7 15. Rac1
{ It was better to try to avoid piece exchanges and play   15.Nbd4  with an advantage which is already almost decisive, despite White not having won any material yet. Black cannot prevent b4-b5 or c5-c6 and White also threatens to capture on a6. }
15... Nb8
{ 15...Bxb5  16.Bxb5  Nb8  would provide Black with some relief but White would retain some advantage. }
16. Nbd4 a6 17. a4
{ Whites idea is to play b4-b5 and c5-c6, creating a strong passed pawn, and there is little that Black can do to prevent this. White can also attack on the kingside. }
17... f6
{ Black tries to create some counterplay with e5-e4, but he is not in time. The great thing about this position for White is that he can play on either or both wings, as he wishes, thanks to the passivity of the black pieces. How would you continue now for White ? }
18. Bxh6
{ Opening Blacks castled position. It was essential to calculate accurately what happens if Black does not capture the piece immediately. }
18... e5
{ The hardest thing for me to calculate was how to respond to the annoying   18...Kh8  White plays  19.Bf4 !!  e5  20.Qe2 !!  This is the hidden idea; the queen goes to h5. And now:  exf4   20...exd4  21.Ng5  g6  22.Bxg6  Ng7  23.Nf7+  Rxf7  24.Bxf7  White's advantage is decisive: he has a rook and two pawns  (with more to follow)  and an attack, for two passive pieces.  21.Ng5 !  g6  22.Nge6  Bxe6   22...Qc8  23.Bxg6  with mate in five moves.  23.Bxg6  Ng7  24.Nxe6  Qd7  25.Qg4  and Black has to give up a lot of material to prevent mate;  Taking the piece does not save Black:   18...gxh6  19.Bh7+  Kh8  20.Qg6  Bxc5  21.Qxh6  Qe7  22.Bb1+  Kg8  23.Rxc5  with a decisive advantage, since if  Bxa4 ?  24.Nxe6  wins. }
19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Qg6 Rf7
{ White's threat was 21. Bxg7+ and 22. Qh6, mating. If   20...gxh6  21.Bg8  and mate is unstoppable,  while if   20...Rg8  then  21.Bf4 !!  is winning again with the same idea as before, clearing the h-file for the queen. }
21. Bf4
{ The winning move once more. The idea is to clear the h-file for the white queen. }
21... exf4
{ 21...exd4  22.Nh4 !!  but not   22.Qh5 ?  Bg4 !  22...Bg4  23.Qxf7  Kxh7  24.Qg6+  Kg8  25.Qxg4 }
22. Qh5
{ This wins, but the pretty   22.Nh4 !!  was more direct, e.g.  f5   22...Bg4  23.Ndf5  23.Qh5  Bxh4  24.Bg6+  Kg8  25.exf4 !!  Nf6  26.Bxf7+  Kf8  27.Qh8+  Kxf7   27...Ke7  28.Rfe1+  with a decisive advantage; the idea of 25. exf4 is now clear.  28.Qxd8  and wins. }
22... Bg4 23. Qxf7 Kxh7 24. Nh4
{ White still has a decisive advantage; he has an attack on the weak black king, the black pieces are passive or out of play, whereas the white knights rampage freely. }
24... Nc6
{ There was no salvation in either   24...Bc8  25.Ng6  or   24...Qd7  25.h3 !  Bxc5  26.Qg6+  Kg8  27.bxc5 }
25. Qg6+ Kg8 26. Qxg4 f5 27. Nhxf5 Nxb4 28. Ne6 Qc8
{ In extreme time pressure Black loses his queen, but there is no defence; if   28...Qd7  29.Nfxg7  wins. }
29. Nxe7+
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the idea of Qb6, after e7-e6 and c7-c5. In this move order, Qb6 is dubious, because Black cannot really take the b2-pawn. If he does so, he will be worse or even lost. But if the queen cannot take on b2, then Qb6 is just a loss of time, since the queen is exposed on that square.  Furthermore, after Black captures on b2 White always has the option of forcing a draw, if that suits him. White's best response is Na3 !, rather than Nc3, because from a3 the knight can go to either b5 or c4. However, after Nc3 the idea of playing a2-a3 is thematic in some variations of the London System, because it defends the b2-pawn indirectly. Against a2-a3, Black needs to have played Bd7 or a7-a6, preventing the plan that starts with Nb5.  In the game the sequence was forced and gave White a clear advantage. The black pieces remained passive and hemmed in on the queenside, while White had a clear advantage in space, the possibility of attacking on both wings, a strong c5-pawn and the square d6 under his control.  When Black tried to create counterplay, he was hit with the sacrifice 18. Bxh6, with a decisive attack on the black king. The idea of 21. Bf4 to clear the h-file for the white queen was very attractive. White's attack was decisive. }
