1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5
{ If Black is going to play this move, it is best to do it now, without d7-d5 or e7-e6. }
3. e3
{ We shall examine the options with 3. d5 in the next game.  Here   3.c3 ?!  is bad in view of  Qb6  and now:  4.Qb3   4.Qc2  cxd4  5.cxd4  Nc6  6.e3   6.Nf3 ?!  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  Qxd4  8.e3  Qe4  9.Qd2  Qd5  =+  Boguszlavszkij-Rajlich, Budapest 2001  6...d6   6...d5  7.Nc3  Bf5  8.Qd2 =  Salac-Cech, Germany tt 1995  7.Nf3  g6 =   7...Nb4  +=  8.Nc3  Bg7  Steinle-Begna, Dortmund 2013  4...cxd4  5.Bxb8   5.Qxb6  axb6  6.cxd4  Nc6  7.e3  Nb4  =+  5...Rxb8   5...Qxb3  =+  6.Qxb6  axb6  7.cxd4  d6  8.Nc3  Bd7  9.e3  e6  10.Nf3  Be7 =  Jakubiec-Mista, Czechia tt 2005/06;  An interesting alternative is   3.dxc5 !?  preventing the complications of Qb6. This was the recent choice of grandmaster Rapport against Giri in the 2014 Tata Steel tournament. The game continued  Na6  The alternative is   3...Qa5+  4.Qd2   4.Nc3  Ne4 !   4...Qxc5  5.Nf3  +=  5.Qd3  Nxc5  6.Qb5   6.Qd2 =  6...Qxb5  7.Nxb5  Nba6 =  4...Qxc5   4...Qxd2+  5.Nxd2  Na6  6.Nb3  Ne4 =  is better.  5.Nc3  d6  6.e4  +=  Nabaty-Loncar, Zagreb 2014  4.Qd4  Qa5+  5.Nc3   5.c3  Qxc5  6.e3  5...Nxc5   5...Qxc5  6.e3 =   6.Qd2 !?  6...Qxd4  7.exd4  Nb4  8.O-O-O =  Boguszlavszkij-Galyas, Budapest 2002  6.Bd2  Ne6  7.Qh4 !?   7.Qd3 =  7...g5 !?  8.Qg3  d5  9.e4  d4  10.Bb5+  Bd7  11.Bxd7+  Nxd7  12.Nd5  Qc5  with a complex position in Rapport-Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2014;   3.Nf3 ?!  is dubious:  cxd4  4.Qxd4   4.Nxd4 ?  e5  5.Bxe5  Qa5+  winning a piece. Curiously there are some forty games where White fell for this trap;   4.Bxb8  Qa5+  5.Qd2  Qxd2+  6.Nbxd2  Rxb8  7.Nxd4  d5  =+  4...d6  and Black is slightly better. The queen is badly placed on d4. }
3... Qb6
{ An alternative is to exchange on d4 first:   3...cxd4  4.exd4  Qb6  and now :  5.Nc3  with the following possibilities:   5.Na3  Nd5 =   5...Qxb2 ?  6.Nb5  ±   5...d5  6.Nb5  +=  5...e6   5...d6  again with several examples:  6.Bb5+   6.Nf3  with two options:  e6   6...g6  7.Be2   7.Bc4  +=   7.Bb5+  +=  7...Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Re1   9.a3  +=  9...Re8   9...Qxb2 =  10.Rb1 =  Ruiz-Shen, Linares 2013.  7.a3   7.Be2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.a3  Bd7 =  Aguinaga-Corts, Pamplona 2007  7...Bd7  8.Rb1  a6  9.Bd3 =  Kovacevic-Arribas, Valencia 1998;   9.d5  +=   6.a3  and again we have several examples:  Bd7   6...g6  7.Nf3   7.Bc4  Bg7  8.Nge2  O-O  9.O-O  Ponomariov-Grischuk, Moscow 2010  7...Bg7  8.Be2  O-O  9.O-O  Muse-Zaragatski, Berlin 2009  7.Rb1  e5 !?  8.Bg5 !?   8.Be3 !   8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Bxe5  Bc5  10.Bg3  O-O  11.Be2  Rd8  and Black has compensation.  8...exd4  =+  Ponomariov-Aronian, Moscow 2010  6...Bd7  7.a4   7.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  8.Rb1  e6 =  Vujic-Hansen, Germany Bundesliga 2004/05  7...a6  8.Bc4 ?!   8.a5  Qc7  9.Ba4  +=  8...g6   8...Nc6 =  9.Bg5  Bg7  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Nd5  Qc6  12.Bb3  O-O  13.Ne2  Re8 ?   13...Bh4  14.g3  e6 =  14.O-O  b6 ?   14...a5  +=  15.Nec3  Bg7 ?   15...Ra7  16.Re1  ±  16.Nxe7+  1-0 Bauer-Bressac, Calvi 2011;  6.Nf3  and now:   6.a3   6.Rb1  6...Be7   6...a6  7.a3   7.Rb1  7...d5  8.Bd3  Nc6  9.O-O  Bd7  10.Re1  +=  Kovacevic-Tiviakov, Calvia 2004;   6...Qxb2  7.Nb5  +=  7.a3   7.Be2  7...O-O  8.Bd3  Nc6  9.O-O  d6   9...a6  10.Re1   10.Nb5  +=  10...Nd5 ?!   10...a6  11.Nxd5  exd5  ±  Rakic-Perunovic, Novi Sad 2000;  A few other ideas have also been played on move three:   3...Nd5 !?  4.Bg3   4.Bxb8  Rxb8  5.c4   5.e4  Nc7  6.dxc5  Ne6 =  5...Qa5+  6.Nd2  Nf6  4...Qb6  5.Nc3 !  Nxc3  6.bxc3  Nc6   6...Qb2  7.Ne2  +=   6...e6  7.d5 =  7.Bd3   7.d5  +=  7...d6   7...d5 =  8.Ne2   8.Nf3  +=  8...e6   8...g6 =  9.O-O  +=  De Prado-Zlotnik, Cambre rapid 2013;   3...d6 !?  4.Nc3   4.Nf3   4.dxc5 !?   4.c3  Qb6  5.Na3 ?!  Qxb2  with advantage to Black, Fontecha-Popov, Bilbao 2014  4...Nbd7  5.Nf3  g6  6.Qd2 !?  with complex play in De Prado-Santos, Famalicao 2014  It is safer to play   6.h3  Bg7  7.Be2 = }
4. Nc3
{ 4.Nf3 !?  is an interesting gambit which has hardly been tested yet:  Qxb2   4...cxd4  5.Qxd4  +=  Boguszlavszkij-Berczes, Budapest 2001  5.Nbd2  Qc3  6.Rb1  cxd4  7.Rb3  Qa5  8.exd4  with compensation for the pawn in view of the advantage in development, the halfopen b-file and the possibility of transferring the rook to the kingside via g3-h3, although Black definitely has a solid position here. The position requires further practical tests;  White can also play   4.Na3  and then if  Qxb2  we reach the same position as in the game. }
4... Qxb2
{ if   4...d6 !?  then  5.Bb5+  Bd7  6.a4  a6  7.a5  Qc7  and now  8.Ba4   8.Bxd7+  is stronger:  Nbxd7  9.Nf3   9.d5  +=  9...g6  10.O-O  Bg7  11.h3  O-O  12.Qd2  b5  13.axb6  Nxb6  +=  De Prado-Sanchez, Spain tt 2014  8...g6  9.Bg5   9.Nf3  9...Bg7  10.Qd2   10.Nf3  10...Bxa4 =  Pri-Georgiev, Aix-les-Bains 2011;   4...Na6 !?  5.a3  e6  6.Be2   6.Nf3  +=  6...Be7  7.dxc5  Nxc5 =  To-Szeberenyi, Budapest 2014.   4...cxd4  5.Qxd4  Qxd4  6.exd4  += }
5. Nb5 Nd5
{ This is the only sound defence.  if   5...Na6  then  6.a3  ±  or   5...cxd4  6.exd4  ± }
6. a3
{ This is the only move that allows White to play for a win.  However, if he wants, he can draw immediately with   6.Rb1  Qxa2  7.Ra1  Qb2  8.Rb1  Qa2  9.Ra1  Qb2  10.Rb1  - Kamsky-Ivanchuk, Gibraltar 2014. White can still force a draw later on, so he might as well try this idea first to put Blacks approach to the test. }
6... a6 { The continuation   6...Nc3  7.Nc7+  Kd8  8.Qc1  is good for White. }
7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Qc1
{ With this move White is playing to win. Black is going to lose the queen but for quite a lot of material, with a complex position. White can still repeat with   8.Ra1  Qb2  9.Rb1 = }
8... axb5 9. Ra1 Qxa1 10. Qxa1 Nc6
{ The key position, very difficult to assess; Black has rook, piece and pawn for the queen. }
11. Bxb5
{ Pri faced this variation twice in the same tournament. In the first game he played the weaker   11.dxc5  b4  12.a4  Nc3  13.Nf3 ?!   13.Ne2  Rxa4  14.Qc1  Nxe2  15.Bxe2  e5 =  13...Rxa4   13...f6  14.Qc1  when he was worse and ended up losing in Pri-Gonzalez, San Sebastian 2011. }
11... cxd4 12. Bxc6
{ The alternative is   12.Ne2  e5  13.Bxc6  Rxa3  14.Qb2   14.Qxa3  Bxa3  15.Bxd5  exf4  16.exf4 =  14...Bb4+  15.Kd1  dxc6  16.Bxe5  dxe3  17.Nf4  with a complicated position. }
12... bxc6 { 12...dxc6  13.Qxd4  Rxa3  was also playable, with complex play. }
13. Qxd4 f6
{ It seems better to play   13...Rxa3  14.Nf3  e6  15.O-O  with a balanced position and chances for both sides. }
14. c4 Nxf4
{ Pris idea was to sacrifice material to gain the advantage after   14...e5  15.Bxe5  fxe5  16.Qxe5+  Ne7  17.Nf3  Rxa3  18.O-O  +=  when White, who is better here in view of Blacks poor development, has various plans: Nf3-g5-e4-d6 or Rf1-b1-b8. }
15. exf4 e5
{ This move gives White the advantage. It was better first to play   15...Rxa3  16.Ne2  and only then  e5 !  since after  17.Qb2   17.fxe5  Bb4+  18.Kd1  O-O =  17...exf4  18.Nxf4  Kf7  19.O-O  the position is unclear. Black always has good compensation in this variation. }
16. fxe5 Bxa3 17. exf6 O-O 18. Ne2
{ This allows Black to equalise.  White needed to play the bold   18.fxg7 !  and now:  Bb4+   18...Rf7  19.Ne2  Bb4+  20.Kd1  d6  21.f3  ±  19.Kd1  Rf7   19...Rxf2  20.Qxf2  Ra1+  21.Ke2  Ra2+  22.Kf3  ±  20.c5 }
18... Bb4+ 19. Kd1 Rxf6 20. c5 Rb8 21. Ng3
{ It was better to play   21.Nf4  d6  22.Nh5  Rf7  23.cxd6  Rb5  24.Nf4  Bc5 = }
21... d5
{ It was possible to play   21...d6  22.Ne4  Rf5  23.Kc2  Rd5  24.Qc4  dxc5  with equality, but the black pieces are dangerously active and White needs to play well to avoid being worse. }
22. Qe5 Rf8 23. f3 { 23.Qxb8 ?  Bg4+ } 23... Rb7 24. Qd6 Rf6 25. Qd8+ Rf8 26.
Qd6 Rf6 27. Qd8+ Rf8 28. Qd6 Bd7
{ Black avoids the repetition with the right move. What follows now is strange and it might be that the moves have been input wrongly in the database, or perhaps both players were in extreme time trouble. }
29. Nh5 { 29.Kc2  with a slight advantage to Black. } 29... Bc8
{ Black could gain a decisive advantage with   29...Re8 } 30. Ng3
{ Now White repeats the position and allows a draw, when he could have won with 30. Qxc6. A strange end in a critical line, one of the most complex in the whole system.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@ We have examined the critical line with 3... Qb6, without d7-d5 or e7-e6, which is the only variation in which Black can capture on b2 without being worse. Black must be willing to accept the draw by repetition with Rb1-a1.  If White wants to play for a win, as in the game, the only way is to play the line with a2-a3 and Qc1, which reaches a position which is difficult to evaluate. Black gives up his queen for rook, knight and pawn, with good compensation. The game then offers possibilities for both sides.  It could be that many players dislike playing without their queen, and this might explain why this variation is rarely seen in practice.  If White wants to avoid the messy lines following 3... Qb6 he has the option of 3. dxc5, as played by Rapport against Giri in the 2014 Tata Steel tournament, which is no more than equal but quite playable for both sides. }
