1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. d5
{ This move is a departure from the spirit of the London System, but can lead to interesting positions, especially if Black accepts the Vaganian Gambit. }
3... Qb6
{ Once again the thematic move, attacking b2. There are other options:  For example, the interesting   3...b5 !?  and now:  4.f3 !?   4.a4  Bb7   4...Qa5+  5.Nd2  +=   4...b4 ! =  5.axb5   5.e4  +=  5...Nxd5  6.Bg3  g6   6...d6  7.e4  +=  7.e4  Nb6  8.Nd2  Bg7  9.c3 =  Kamsky-Kramnik, Baku 2010;   4.Nf3  and now:  e6   4...Bb7  5.c4  d6  6.Nbd2   6.h3  6...g6   6...Nh5 =  7.e4  Bg7  8.cxb5  +=  Smirin-Tzermiadianos, Katerini 1992.  5.dxe6  fxe6  6.Nbd2  d5  7.e4  +=  c4   7...Nxe4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  10.O-O-O+  +-   7...dxe4  8.Bxb5+  ±  8.e5  Nfd7  9.Nd4  +=   4.c4  bxc4  5.Nc3  d6  6.e4  Nbd7  7.Bxc4  Rb8 =  4...Nh5  5.Bc1  e5  6.Nh3  d6  7.Nf2  Nd7 =  Pri-Crut, Pau 2012;   3...d6  is also playable, e.g.  4.Nc3  e5   4...g6  5.e4  Bg7  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Be2  O-O  8.O-O =  Renner-Ptz, Austria undesliga B 2012/13  5.dxe6  Bxe6  6.e4  Nc6  7.Qd3  or   7.Qd2  Be7  8.O-O-O  O-O  with complex play.  7...d5   7...Be7  8.exd5  Nxd5  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Qxd5  Bxd5  11.O-O-O  O-O-O =  Milosavljevic-Kocic, Belgrade 2011. }
4. Nc3 Qxb2
{ The so-called Vaganian Gambit, named after the Armenian GM Rafael Vaganian, who was one of the first to play it and develop it. The most common move order to reach it is via the Trompowsky: 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 c5 3. d5 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Bd2. Theory considers it to be a sound gambit, for which White obtains very good compensation, even against Blacks best defences. It is playable for both sides. White needs to like playing a pawn down but with the initiative, while Black must be happy to defend a rather passive position but with an advantage in material. From the Trompowsky this position can also be reached via 2Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Nf6 ?!  (4Qa5+ !)  5. d5 Qb6 6. Nc3 Qxb2 7. Bd2. }
5. Bd2
{ White sacrifices a pawn: his compensation is based on the half-open b-file and better development. Whites plan is to advance his centre pawns with f2-f4 and e2-e4, followed by e4-e5 or f4-f5, to build up a strong attack against the black king. }
5... Qb6 6. e4 e5
{ One of the possible defences is immediately to obstruct Whites intended e4-e5 advance by playing e7-e5 himself, and nowadays this is regarded as Blacks strongest defence.  The alternative is   6...d6  7.f4  and now there are three options for Black:  g6  Blacks best response is   7...e6  and now:  8.Rb1   8.Nf3  exd5  9.e5   9.Rb1 =  9...dxe5  10.fxe5  Ne4  11.Nxd5  Qd8  12.c4  ∞  McShane-Ni Hua, Bled 2002;  8...Qc7   8...Qd8  9.Bb5+  Bd7  10.dxe6  fxe6  ∞  Hodgson-Glavina, Spain tt 1993  9.Nf3  a6  10.dxe6  fxe6  ∞  Moskalenko-Erdogdu, Ankara 2010;   7...Nbd7 ?!  is dubious, because this square might be needed by the f6-knight:  8.Nf3  g6 ?  an error which hands White a clear advantage; the best defence was   8...Qc7  instead   8...e5 ?  loses to  9.dxe6  fxe6  10.Ng5  Nb8  11.Bc4  +-  9.Qe2   9.e5 !  dxe5  any move of the knight is answered with 10. e6  10.fxe5  Ng4  11.Rb1  Qd8  if   11...Qc7  then  12.e6  and now Blacks best is to sacrifice the piece with  Bg7  13.exd7+  Bxd7  14.Bb5  O-O  but White should win, since Black has only two pawns for the piece  12.e6 !  +-  and Blacks development is a disaster, Caselas-Khamrakulov, Ortigueira 2004.  9...Ng4   9...a6  10.e5  +=  10.h3  Nh6  +=  although White maintains the advantage;  8.e5 !  Nfd7   8...dxe5  9.fxe5  Nfd7  10.Nf3  Bg7  11.Rb1  Qd8  12.e6 !  ±  Vaganian-Kupreichik, Leningrad 1974  9.Nf3  a6 !   9...Bg7 ?!  10.Rb1  Qd8  11.e6 !  fxe6  12.Ng5  Nf8  13.Bb5+  Bd7  14.dxe6  ±  Bxb5  15.Nxb5 !  Qc8  16.O-O  a6   16...Qc6 ?  17.f5  +-  Zubarev-Zinchenko, Rethymnon 2011  17.Bc3 ?   17.Nxd6+ !  exd6  18.Nf7  +-  17...axb5  18.Bxg7  Rg8  19.Bxf8  Rxf8  20.Nxh7  ±  Vaganian-Jansa, Kragujevac 1974  10.Rb1   10.Bc4  +=  10...Qc7  11.e6   11.Ng5  ∞  11...fxe6  12.Ng5  Nf6  13.dxe6  Bg7  with a slight advantage to Black in Vachev-Stanojoski, Albena 2011; }
7. f4 d6 8. f5
{ The idea of this move is to shut in the bishop on c8 and prepare a kingside pawn storm with g4-g5. White has many options in this position, as we shall see:   8.Nf3  (I think that it is better to exchange first on e5, to prevent exf4)  and now:  exf4 !  looks best to me; now we have:   8...Nbd7  is the most common reply, but White stands very well. Two famous games continued  9.fxe5  dxe5  10.Bc4  Be7   10...Qd8  11.Rb1  Bd6  12.O-O  O-O  13.Bg5  h6  14.Bh4  a6  15.a4  Qa5  16.Be1  ∞  Nakamura-Nijboer, Wijk aan Zee 2004  11.Rb1  Qd8  12.Bg5  h6  13.d6  hxg5  14.Nxg5  O-O  15.O-O  +=  Bruzon-Nijboer, Wijk aan Zee 2004  9.e5   9.Rb1  Qd8  10.Bxf4  Be7  11.Bd3   11.Bb5+ !?  11...O-O  12.O-O  Nbd7  13.h3  ∞  Nguyen Ngoc-Karatorossian, Budapest 2004.  9...dxe5  10.Nxe5  Be7  11.Rb1  Qd8  12.Bb5+  with compensation;  It is better for White to exchange on e5 right away:   8.fxe5  dxe5  9.Nf3  Bd6   9...Nbd7  transposes to the previous note  10.Bc4  a6  11.O-O  Bg4 ?!   11...O-O  12.a4  ∞  12.h3  Bh5  13.a4  +=  Liascovich-Julia, Villa Martelli 2008;  Another option is to insert   8.Rb1  Qd8  and now:  9.fxe5   9.Nf3  Nbd7  10.fxe5 !  Nxe5  11.Nxe5  dxe5  12.Bb5+  Nd7 ?   12...Bd7 =  13.O-O  ±  Christiansen-De Firmian, cr 2001.  9...dxe5  10.Nf3  Nbd7   10...Bd6  11.Bc4  a6  12.a4  O-O  ∞  Romcovici-Belosvetov, Illichevsk 2008.  11.Be2  g6 ?!   11...Bd6 =  12.O-O  Bg7  13.Bg5  +=  Kanep-Landa, Deizisau 2003;  Finally,   8.Bb5+  has also been played, and now:  Bd7   8...Nbd7  9.Nf3   9.fxe5  dxe5  10.Qe2  ∞  9...a6  10.Bxd7+  Nxd7  11.f5   11.O-O  ∞  11...Be7  =+  12.g4 ?  h6  13.Qe2  ∓  Moskalenko-Movsziszian, Sitges 2007.  9.Bxd7+   9.fxe5  dxe5  10.Bc4  ∞  9...Nbxd7  10.f5  h5  11.Nf3  a6  12.a4  Be7  13.O-O  c4+  14.Kh1  Qc7  15.Qe2  ∞  Kekelidze-Griggs, Wheeling 2013; }
8... Be7
{ There is also   8...g6  9.Qf3   9.g4  gxf5  10.gxf5  Rg8  11.Qf3  Nbd7  12.Nh3  a6  13.a4  Qc7  ∞  Karttunen-Anjuhin, Finland tt 2007  9...gxf5  10.Bb5+ ?!   10.exf5 =  10...Nbd7   10...Kd8  =+  11.exf5 ?!   11.Qxf5 =  11...a6  12.Be2   12.Bxd7+  12...Rg8  =+  Cheng-Moiseenko, Edmonton 2008. }
9. g4
{ An aggressive move, continuing the plan instigated with f4-f5.  White has also played   9.Qf3  Na6  10.g4  Nb4  11.Kd1  Bd7   11...Nd7 =  12.a3  +=  Mertanen-Vepkhvishvili, Tallinn 2014. }
9... h6
{ Another option is   9...Na6  10.Rb1   10.g5  10...Qd8  11.g5  Nd7  12.h4  Nc7  with complex play, Wojtaszek-Czakon, Sroda Wielkopolska 2004. }
10. h4 h5
{ Trying to restrain the advance of the white pawns and conquer the g4-square.  Black has also tried   10...Na6  11.Rb1  Qd8  12.Qf3  Nd7  ∞  Pri-Cossin, Caen 2011   10...Qd8  11.Qf3   11.Rh3 !  11...Nh7   11...Nfd7  12.Qg3  Rg8  13.Nf3  f6   13...g6 =  14.Bh3   14.Bc4  +=  14...Nd7  15.Kf2  Rb8  16.a4  +=  Lahiri-Tukhaev, Alushta 2005. }
11. Rb1 Qc7 12. g5 Ng4 13. Be2
{ It seems better to develop the knight before the bishop, for example   13.Nge2  Nd7  14.Ng3  g6  15.Be2  += }
13... a6
{ It was better to play   13...g6  14.Bxg4   14.f6  Bd8  =+  14...hxg4  15.f6   15.Qxg4  Qd7  =+  15...Bd8  16.Nge2  ∞ }
14. a4 { It was also possible to capture:   14.Bxg4  hxg4  15.Qxg4 = } 14... g6
15. Bxg4 hxg4 16. f6
{ White gains space and drives Blacks bishop into passivity on d8. It is difficult for Black to develop his pieces and his king has no safe haven. This position is very comfortable for White to play. Less clear is   16.Qxg4  Qd7  17.Nge2  gxf5  18.exf5  Qxf5  19.Qe4  ∞ }
16... Bd8 17. Nge2 c4 18. Ng3 Qc5 19. Ke2
{ A bold and excellent move by Pri: the king advances into the centre but, since the position is fairly closed, there is no risk involved. White wants to connect his rook and his queen and he is planning to play h4-h5. I think that in this position White already has a decisive advantage; the engines do not think so at first, but the longer they are left to analyse the clearer the advantage becomes. It is a very interesting position and Pri handles it in masterly fashion. }
19... Ba5
{ 19...Kd7  20.h5  gxh5  21.Rxh5  Rxh5   21...Rf8  22.Rh7  ±  22.Nxh5  Kc7  23.Be3  Qa3  24.g6  +- }
20. h5 gxh5 21. Nxh5 Rg8
{ After   21...Rf8  22.Ng7+  Kd8  23.Be3  Qc7  24.Rh7  +-  White wins with the threat of 25. Ne6 !;   21...Kd8  also loses:  22.Ng7  Rh3  23.Rxh3  gxh3  24.Ne6+ !  Bxe6   24...fxe6  25.g6  +-  25.dxe6  again with a decisive advantage for White. }
22. Ng7+ Kf8 { How to continue Whites attack ? } 23. Qf1
{ This move wins, but the best and most attractive finish was with   23.Ne6+ !!  after which Black has no satisfactory defence:  fxe6   23...Bxe6  24.dxe6  Nc6   24...fxe6  25.g6  +-  25.exf7  Kxf7  26.Rxb7+  Kf8  27.g6  and wins.  24.g6 !  Rxg6  25.Rh8+  Rg8   25...Kf7  26.Qh1  forces mate:  Kxf6  27.Qh4+  Kf7  28.Rf1+  Kg7  29.Qh7#  26.Qh1  with mate soon; }
23... Qd4
{ There was no salvation in   23...Bxc3  24.Bxc3  g3  25.Qf3  Nd7  26.Rh7  Qf2+  27.Qxf2  gxf2  28.Nf5  Rxg5  29.Nh6  Nxf6  30.Rxf7+  Ke8  31.Rxf6  +- }
24. Nf5 Qc5
{ 24...Bxf5  is no use, since after  25.Qxf5  threatening mate on c8,  Ke8  26.Qc8+  Bd8  27.g6  the engines announce that it is mate in eight moves; Whites attack is unstoppable. }
25. Rh7
{ There was a quicker win here with   25.g6  Rxg6   25...fxg6  26.Rh7  +-  26.Rh8+  Rg8  27.Bh6+  +- }
25... g3 26. Be3 { 26.g6 !  +- } 26... Qa3 27. Qh3
{ Once again 27. g6 was quicker, but Black resigned because mate is near. The threat is 28. Rxf7. A possible continuation after 27. Qh3 would be 27Ke8 28. Rh8 Rxh8 29. Qxh8+ Kd7 30. Ne7 Nc6 31. Nxc6 bxc6 32. dxc6+ Kc7 33. Nd5+ Kxc6 34. Qe8+ Bd7 35. Qxa8 mate.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we have looked at the variations following the move 3. d5, taking the game into a Benoni set-up. Black played 3... Qb6 once more and we reached the so-called Vaganian Gambit, a very interesting line, usually arising from the Trompowsky Opening 2. Bg5, where White gains very good compensation for a pawn in the shape of the halfopen b-file and a strong pawn centre.  In the game we saw Black's option of playing e7-e5, which is considered best; White has several plans available but in this game we saw the one of closing the centre with f4-f5, followed by advancing the kingside pawns with g4-g5. Black ended up very cramped after White played f5-f6.  It is hard to spot exactly where Black went wrong, but after the surprising 19. Ke2 !! White had a decisive advantage. White won with his kingside attack and Black's queenside pieces played no part in the game whatsoever. }
*

