[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nf3 { 2.Nc3  d5  3.Bf4 } 2... Nf6 3. Bf4 d6 { 3...e6   3...g6 } 4.
h3 { 4.e3 } 4... g6 5. e3 { 5.c3 } 5... Bg7 6. Bc4
{ 6.Be2   6.Nbd2   In this chapter we are going to see the Dutch Defence against the London System.  There are several options for White, but the traditional London scheme works quite well here, because it prevents e7-e5, which is Black's main idea. Depending on which variation Black chooses, Leningrad, Classical or Stonewall, White can choose between several plans.  Against the Leningrad it is interesting to play Bc4, making it difficult for Black to castle. There are some interesting variations for White involving queenside castling and g2-g4, but he can also simply play the normal London plan.  Playing the London System against the Dutch tends to produce positions which are quite complex and normally open, in contrast to the other variations of the London which tend to be quieter or more closed. It is essential for White to be willing to play actively and take risks. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Dutch"]
[Black "Game 34 - Aronian vs. Van Wely"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ Recently Aronian has been playing the London System against the Dutch. Further on we shall see the idea of playing Nc3, which usually leads, after ...d7-d5, to variations of the Stonewall. }
3... d6 4. e3 h6 5. h3 g5 6. Bh2 Bg7 7. Nbd2
{ It seems better to play Kovacevic's idea of   7.Be2  e6  8.c4 !?  Qe7  9.Nc3  O-O  10.O-O  b6  11.Rc1  Kovacevic-Avshalumov, Paris 1992.  Nbd7 }
7... O-O
{ An earlier game had continued   7...Nc6  8.Bc4  e6  9.Qe2  a6  10.c3  Scekic-Kontic, Mataruska Banja 1997. }
8. c3 Nc6 9. Bd3
{ White, for the present, is preventing Black's main plan, which is to advance with ...e7-e5. White is preparing to advance in the centre himself with e2-e4 at an opportune moment. If Black plays ...g5-g4, this would weaken his kingside. }
9... Rb8
{ A strange move; I think that the idea is not so much to play ...b7-b5, but rather to defend the b7-pawn, so as to be able to develop the c8-bishop without any problems, preventing the queen check on b3 followed by the capture of the b7-pawn. }
10. O-O Qe8 11. Re1
{ It was better to play   11.Qc2  immediately, attacking f5, e.g.  g4   11...e6  12.e4  +=  12.hxg4  Nxg4  13.Bg3  e5  14.dxe5  dxe5  15.e4  f4  16.Bh4  +=  The rook normally goes to d1, since on e1 it is not so well placed. This position is very similar to some arising from the King's Indian. }
11... Qh5
{ This square is the usual one for the black queen in the main line of the Leningrad. Normally White will have played g2-g3 and Bg2 and Black typically wants to play e7-e5, f5-f4 and Bh3, exchanging the bishops; but the situation here is different and the advance of the black pawns is not so dangerous. White defends well and plays in the centre and on the queenside, with advantage. Black should have played   11...e5  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Qc2  e4  14.Bc4+  Be6   14...Kh8  15.Nd4  +=  15.Qb3  Bxc4  16.Nxc4  Kh7  17.Nd4  += }
12. Qc2 g4 13. hxg4 Nxg4
{ 13...fxg4 ?  fails to  14.Bg6  Qa5  15.b4  Qb6  16.Nh4  ± } 14. Bb5
{ I have played this type of position several times, usually reaching it from the King's Indian. White should move his bishop to g3, not allowing it to be exchanged for the knight, because it is a good defender of the castled position. So White should play   14.Bg3  , and after  e5  15.Nh4 !?   15.dxe5  dxe5  16.e4  f4  17.Bc4+  Kh8  18.Bh4  Bf6  ⇆  15...e4  16.Bc4+  Kh8  17.Nxe4 !  d5 !?   17...fxe4  18.Qxe4  Bf5  19.Nxf5  Qxf5  20.Qxf5  Rxf5  21.Be6  Rg5  22.Bf4  ±  18.Bxd5  Ne7  19.Bb3  fxe4  20.Qxe4  Nf5  21.Nxf5   21.Bc2  Nf6  22.Qf4  Nd5  ∞  21...Bxf5  22.Qf4  += }
14... Kh8
{ It was better to eliminate the bishop with   14...Nxh2  15.Nxh2  +=  when White's advantage is minimal. }
15. Qb3
{ 15.Bg3 ?  f4  But not 15. Bg3 ? now, since 15... f4 would win a piece, owing to the attack on b5. }
15... Nd8 { Again it was better to play   15...Nxh2 } 16. Bg3
{ Aronian finally safeguards his bishop from exchange, with a clear advantage. }
16... e5 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Qb4
{ One of White's plans in such positions is to double the rooks quickly on the d-file, so it was better to play   18.Rad1  +=2 ↑↑ }
18... Ne6 { Here   18...a6  19.Be2  Nc6  +=  was good. } 19. Rad1
{ Now it was better to retreat the bishop with   19.Be2 !?  → } 19... c5
{ 19...e4 !?  was possible, e.g.  20.Nh2 } 20. Qb3 Nc7
{ Now   20...e4  falls to  21.Bxb8 } 21. Be2 Be6 22. Bc4 Bd7 23. Be2
{ Here   23.Qa3  +=2  ! ±  was good, winning a pawn with the double attack on a7 and c5, with a clear advantage. }
23... f4 24. exf4 exf4 25. Bh4 Bc6
{ Black threatens to create counterplay with 26... Rg8. What should White play now ? }
26. Be7 { Here   26.Nh2  was good. } 26... Rf7
{ It was much better to play   26...Rfe8  to answer  27.Bc4   27.Bd6  27...Ne5 }
27. Bc4 Nd5 28. Bh4 Rf5 { Black could have equalised with   28...Rg8 ! } 29.
Bd3 Rff8 30. Bb1 Rbe8 31. Rxe8
{ Once again White had a safe edge after   31.Qc2  Ndf6   31...Kg8 ?  32.Qh7+  Kf7  33.Ng5+  +-   31...Ngf6  32.Nc4  +-  32.Qg6  +=  /+/-   31.Qc4 !?  was stronger. }
31... Rxe8 32. Ne4 { 32.Qc2  +=2  Ndf6  33.Qg6  was stronger. } 32... Nde3
{ Both players were short of time, which partly explains the inaccurate play. Black therefore played this move to complicate the game, although it was better to play   32...Ne5 !  33.Ned2  Nxf3+  34.Nxf3  Nf6  35.Bxf6  and Black has a clear advantage in this position, with the bishop pair and the half-open g-file. }
33. fxe3 Bxe4 34. Bxe4 Rxe4 35. Qxb7
{ It would have been better to play   35.exf4 !?  Rxf4  36.Rd8+  Rf8   36...Bf8  37.Bg3  37.Rxf8+  Bxf8  38.Qxb7  ±  with a clear advantage to White. }
35... Qg6 { If   35...Rxe3  then  36.Qb8+  Re8  37.Qxf4 } 36. Rd8+
{ Safer was   36.exf4 !? } 36... Kh7 37. Qd5
{ An error. White should have played   37.Rd6 !  Re6  38.Rxe6  Qxe6  39.exf4  Qe3+  40.Kh1  Qxf4  41.Qxa7 }
37... Re6 38. exf4
{ A blunder by Aronian which loses the game. Such serious tactical errors are quite rare among the chess elite but, as we can see, even the great players are human and can make mistakes. It was necessary to play 38. Ne1, with a balanced position. This position will no doubt feature in basic tactics books of the future: it is Black to play and win. }
38... Bd4+
{ Aronian resigned because the back-rank mate is unstoppable, except by giving up the queen, since after }
39. Kh1 Qb1+ 40. Ne1 Rxe1+ 41. Bxe1 { is mate. } 41... Qxe1#
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw a fairly unusual plan for Black with h7-h6 and g7-g5, instead of the normal Leningrad move g7-g6. These pawn advances left Black's kingside slightly weak and White emerged from the opening with an advantage. The position is similar to some variations that can arise from the King's Indian.  In the middlegame Aronian did not play well. Remember that White should not allow the dark-squared bishop to be exchanged for a black knight. White should have played 14. Bg3. White's best plan is to double rooks on the d-file and play on the queenside.  In some variations it is possible to advance with e3-e4. The black position looks menacing on the kingside but White can easily repel the black attack. Time pressure caused both players to make quite a few errors. Aronian had a clear advantage at several points in the game but spoiled things in the last few moves, including the serious tactical error 38. exf4, which allowed Black a simple finish. }
*

