1. d4 f5 2. Nf3
{ An interesting alternative is   2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  g6   3...d6  is better  4.h4 !?  Bg7   4...h6  and now:  5.Nc3   5.c4  d6  6.Nc3  Bg7  7.Nf3  Nbd7  8.Qc2   8.c5  +=  8...c5  9.d5  a6 =  Morozevich-Ivanchuk, Moscow 2009.  5...Bg7  6.Bc4   6.Qf3  +=  6...d6  7.Nge2   7.Qf3  +=  7...e6  8.Qd2  Qe7  9.O-O-O  a6  ∞  Sjberg-Berg, Stockholm 1998  5.h5  Nxh5 ?   5...d6  6.h6  Bf8  7.Nc3  +=  6.Rxh5  gxh5  7.Qxh5+  Kf8  8.Qxf5+  Kg8   8...Bf6  9.Bh6+  9.Nc3  e6  10.Qh5  d6  11.O-O-O  ± }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 d6 4. h3 g6 { The normal line of the Leningrad. } 5. e3
{ Another similar idea to hinder Black from castling is   5.c3  Bg7  6.Qb3 !?  e6  7.Nbd2  Nc6  8.e3  Qe7  9.O-O-O  O-O  10.g4  fxg4  11.hxg4  Nxg4  12.Bg3  which gave White very good compensation and an eventual win in Garcia Palermo-Rodi, Pinamar 2004. }
5... Bg7 6. Bc4
{ This is an unpleasant move against the Leningrad, because it makes it difficult for Black to castle; to accomplish this Black will have to play e7-e6 or d7-d5, neither of which usually forms part of his plan.  Aronian and Grachev chose   6.Be2  which is also playable, although this seems a rather inferior square for the bishop:  O-O  7.O-O   7.Bh2  Kh8  8.O-O  Be6  9.c4  Bg8  10.Nc3  Nbd7  11.Rc1  +=  Grachev-Cherniaev, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013  7...e6  8.Bh2   8.c4  +=  8...Nc6  9.Nbd2  Qe7  10.c3  +=  Aronian-Caruana, Zurich rapid 2014  White has also tried   6.Nbd2  Nc6  7.c3  O-O  8.Qb3+   8.Bc4+  e6  9.O-O  +=  8...Kh8  9.O-O-O !?   9.Bh2  +=  9...Qe8 =  Hodgson-M.Gurevich, Haifa 1989. }
6... e6 { 6...d5  7.Bb3  +=  would be dubious. } 7. g4
{ An interesting and very aggressive idea. Other quieter, and better, options are:   7.O-O  O-O  8.Bh2   8.Nc3  +=  8...Qe7  9.b4 !?   9.Nbd2  9...a5 =  Khruschiov-Fazulyanov, Cheliabinsk 2008   7.Nc3  Qe7  8.Qe2   8.O-O  +=  8...Nbd7  9.a4   9.O-O  +=  9...c6  10.a5  Ne4  11.Bh2  e5 =  Miladinovic-Grivas, Ano Liosia 1995 }
7... Qe7
{ Black declines the pawn, because he would stand worse after   7...fxg4  8.hxg4  Nxg4 ?   8...O-O  9.Nc3  +=  9.Ng5  Nf6  10.Bxe6  ±   7...a6  has also been played, e.g  8.gxf5  exf5  9.Nbd2   9.Rg1  +=  9...Nc6  10.a3  Qe7  11.Qe2  Bd7 =  Moor-Gabrielsen, Oslo 2011. }
8. Nc3
{ or   8.gxf5  exf5   8...gxf5  9.Rg1  +=  9.Nc3  Nbd7  10.Qe2  Nb6  11.Bb3  Bd7  12.O-O-O  O-O-O = }
8... Nbd7
{ If   8...fxg4  then  9.hxg4  Nxg4  10.Qe2  ∞  and White, after castling queenside, will have very good compensation, thanks to the half-open g- and h- files. }
9. gxf5 gxf5
{ The alternative was   9...exf5  with the idea of castling queenside. } 10.
Rg1 Nb6 11. Bb3 Bd7 12. a4
{ White is now planning to dispense with castling.   12.Qe2  O-O-O  13.O-O-O  Rhg8  would lead to equality. }
12... a5
{ It was better to play   12...Nbd5  13.Nxd5  Nxd5  14.Bxd5  exd5  15.Qd2  O-O-O =   12...O-O-O = }
13. Nb5 Bxb5 14. axb5 Nbd5 15. Bg5 b6
{ This is a decisive error. It was better to play   15...Qf7  16.Nd2  Rg8  17.c4  Nb4  18.Qf3  ± }
16. Nh4
{ This simple move wins material with the twin threats of Bxd5 and Nxf5. }
16... Qf7
{ If   16...O-O-O  then  17.Bxd5  exd5  18.Nxf5  or   16...Qd7  17.Nxf5  exf5  18.Qf3 }
17. Nxf5 exf5
{ If   17...Ne4  then  18.Bh4  and again White wins after  exf5   18...Qxf5  19.Bxd5  exd5  20.Rxg7  19.Bxd5  Qxd5  20.Rxg7 }
18. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ After   18...Bxf6  White recovers the piece with  19.Qf3  with a decisive advantage. }
19. Qh5+ Ke7 20. Bxd5 Rae8
{ White has a winning advantage: he is a pawn up, the black king is stranded in the centre and there are bishops of opposite colour, which usually help the attacking side. }
21. Kd2 f4 22. Qg5
{ White proceeds carefully, but it was more forceful to play   22.Bc6  Reg8  23.Qg4 !  fxe3+  24.fxe3  Qe6  25.Qxe6+  Kxe6  26.c4  winning more material. }
22... Bh6 23. Qxf6+ Kxf6 24. e4 Re7 25. Ra4 Bg5 26. Ke2 Rhe8 27. Kf3
{ The game is decided and Black can do nothing to save himself. } 27... Rg7 28.
Rc4 Rge7 29. Rc6
{ White could have won a piece here with   29.e5+ !  since if  dxe5  White wins with   29...Kf5  then  30.Be4+  Ke6  31.Rxg5  wins.  30.Rc6+  Kg7   30...Kf5  31.Be4#  +-  31.Rxg5+  +- }
29... h6 30. h4 Bxh4 31. e5+ Kf5 32. Be4+ Ke6 33. Rg6+ Kd7
{ 33...Kf7  34.Rxh6  Bg5  35.Rh5  Black would lose the bishop. } 34. Bf5+
{ Black resigned, since he will be mated after 34... Kd8 35. Rgxd6+ cxd6 36. Rc8+.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the London System in action against the Leningrad  (Dutch Defence with g7-g6)  . White used the unpleasant idea of 6. Bc4, which prevents Black from castling in the normal way. After Black played 6... e6 White used the aggressive advance 7. g4, although he can also play more conservatively with kingside castling or 7. Nc3, with a slight but stable advantage.  White abstained from castling and gained the advantage after a couple of bad moves by Black, who had equalised after the opening. It is worth noting the simple idea of 16. Nh4, which gave White a decisive advantage, since he not only won a pawn but also had the better position and an attack.  The presence of bishops of opposite colour favours the attacking side and White decided the game on the light squares. }
*

