[Black "Game 36 - Georgiev vs. Vallejo Pons"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nc3
{ The line with 2. Nc3 and 3. Bf4 is a very popular variation against the Dutch, normally resulting in the adoption of a type of Stonewall set-up by Black . The natural move order of the London System would be   2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  e6  4.Nc3  Instead, a more classical approach would be   4.Nf3  d5  5.c4  Bd6   5...Be7  6.Nc3   6.Bxd6  Qxd6   6...cxd6  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.Bc4  Nb6  9.Bb3  +=  7.Nc3  +=  6...c6  7.Bd3  O-O  8.O-O  Qe7  9.c5  Bxf4  10.exf4  Nbd7  11.Qa4  +=  Van Wely-Rakhmanov, Baku 2008.  4...d5  5.Bd3  c6 }
2... d5 3. Bf4 c6
{ This move order is designed to avoid lines with Nb5. The move a7-a6 is also played for the same reason.  If Black plays   3...Nf6  instead, White has two main options:  4.e3   4.Nb5 !  Na6  5.e3   5.c4  e6  6.Nf3  dxc4  7.g3 ?!   7.e3  +=  7...Bd7  8.Nc3  Bc6 =  Grischuk-Nakamura, Monaco  (blind)  2011.  5...e6   5...c6  6.Nc3  Nc7  7.Bd3  g6  8.Nce2  Bg7  9.Nf3  Ne6  10.Be5  O-O  11.O-O  +=  Hillarp Persson-Mohammadi, Tylosand 2012  6.Nf3  c6  7.Nc3  Nc7  8.Bd3  Be7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Ne2  Nce8  11.c4  Nd6  12.c5  Nf7  +=  Zubov-Firman, Alushta 2009  4...a6   4...e6   4...c6  5.Nf3   5.Bd3  5...e6  6.Bd3  c5  7.dxc5   7.O-O  c4  8.Be2  Nc6  9.Ne5  +=  Dzagnidze-A.Muzychuk, Beijing 2013  7...Bxc5  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Ne2  O-O   9...Qd7  10.Nfd4  Bd6  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.c4  +=  A. lAmi-Moynihan, Bunratty 2014  10.c4  and now:  Qb6   10...Nb4  again with several examples:  11.a3   11.Nc3  Nxd3  12.Qxd3  dxc4  13.Qxc4  Qe7  14.Rac1  Bd7  15.Ne5  b5  16.Qb3  Rfc8  17.Nxd7  Qxd7  18.Rfd1  +=  Gelfand-Nakamura, Zurich 2014  11...Nxd3  12.Qxd3  Bd7  13.Ned4   13.Ne5  Bd6  14.Rfd1  Rc8  15.Nxd7  Qxd7  16.Rac1  Rfd8 =  Svetushkin-Sivuk, St Petersburg 2010  13...Rc8  14.cxd5  Nxd5  15.Be5  +=  Svetushkin-Zygouris, Nikea 2011  11.Rc1   11.Nc3  +=  11...Rd8  12.Qb3 ?!   12.a3  12...Qxb3  13.axb3 =  Grigoryan-Panbukchian, Golden Sands 2013 }
4. e3 Nf6 5. Bd3
{ Another option is   5.Nf3  g6 !?   5...e6  6.Bd3  Bg7  7.O-O  Nbd7  8.Ne2  ±  Gelfand-Nakamura, Moscow 2013. }
5... e6 { So now we have the Stonewall against the London System. } 6. Nf3 Be7
{ In the Stonewall Black normally plays Bd6, but since White has his bishop on f4 he decides to avoid this. In such positions, White generally seeks the exchange of Black's good dark-squared bishop, leaving Black with the bad one on c8. However, there have also been games with Bd6:   6...Bd6  7.O-O  O-O   7...Bxf4  8.exf4  +=  8.Ne2  Qe7  9.c4  Ne4   9...Nbd7  10.Rc1  e5  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Nxe5  Bxe5  13.Qb3  +=  Polak-Bozanic, Split 2005  10.Qc2   10.Rb1  Nd7  11.Bxd6  Nxd6  12.Qc2  Ne4  13.b4  +=  Svetushkin-Fernandez, Roquetas de Mar 2014;   10.c5  Bxf4  11.exf4  b6  12.b4  a5  13.a3  +=  Manolache-Samolins, Arteixo 2007.  10...Nd7  11.c5   11.Rab1  g5  12.Bxd6  Nxd6  13.Rfc1  +=  Maletin-Mesropov, Moscow 2012;  11...Bb8  12.b4   12.Bxb8  Rxb8  13.b4  +=  12...g5   12...e5 =  13.Bxb8  Rxb8  +=  Paunovic-Markovic, Budva 1996; }
7. O-O
{ White has also tried   7.h3  O-O  8.O-O   8.Ne2  b6  9.O-O  Ne4  10.c4  Nd7  11.Rc1  Bb7  +=  Sargissian-A.Muzychuk, Antwerp 2009  8...Nbd7   8...Bd7  9.Ne2  Be8  10.Bh2  Bh5  11.Nf4  Bxf3  12.Qxf3  Qd7  13.c4  +=  Gelfand-Beinoras, Kallithea 2008  9.Ne2  h6  10.Bh2  g5  11.c4  ±  Kosic-Schmidt, Munich 2013. }
7... O-O 8. Ne2
{ White repositions the knight, with an eye on the f4-square and also making way for the natural plan of c2-c4, followed by doubling rooks on the c-file. This plan is the most common one in this position. The main difference between this position and the normal Stonewall is the deployment of Whites bishops at f4 and d3. }
8... Ne4
{ Another option is   8...Nbd7  9.c4  dxc4  10.Bxc4  Nb6  11.Bb3  a5  12.a3  Nbd5  13.h3  += }
9. c4
{ 9.Ne5  Nd7  10.c4  g5  11.Nxd7  Bxd7  12.Be5  Be8  13.f4  h6  14.Nc3  Nf6  +=  1/2-1/2 Dziuba,M-Vallejo Pons, F/Oropesa del Mar ESP 1998  (34)   9.h3  is again possible, e.g.  Bd7  10.c4  Be8  11.Qb3  Qb6  12.c5   12.Qc2  +=  12...Qxb3  13.axb3  Nd7  14.Ne5  Nxe5  15.Bxe5  +=  Dizdar-Nordahl, Gothenburg 2005 }
9... Bd7
{ planning Be8,Nd7. In my opinion this plan is too unnatural, black's queenside becomes vulnerable.   9...Nd7  +=2  !?  10.Ne5   10.h3  Qe8   10...a5  11.Bh2  g5  12.Ne5  Nxe5  13.Bxe5  +=  Dizdar-Kobalia, Dresden 2007   10...Bf6  11.Bh2  Qe7  12.Qc2  g5  13.Rac1  ±  Malakhatko-Kuzubov, St. Petersburg 2011  11.Bh2  g5  12.Ne5  +=  I. Sokolov-Haraldsson, Reykjavik 2013.  10...Bf6   10...g5  11.Nxd7  Bxd7  12.Be5  Be8  13.Qc2  Bg6  14.c5  Nf6  15.b4  a6  16.a4  Nd7  17.f4  Bh5  18.Nc3  Nxe5  19.fxe5  Rf7  20.b5  +=  1/2-1/2 Milov,V-Bhend,E/Zurich ,EXT 1993  (48)  11.Qc2  g5  12.Nxd7  Bxd7  13.Be5  g4  14.Kh1 ?!  Bxe5  15.dxe5  Qc7  16.cxd5  exd5  17.f4  gxf3  18.gxf3  Qxe5 !  1/2-1/2 Izeta,F-Ochoa de Echaguen,F/Grand Canaria 1993  (32)  An interesting and thematic line is   9...g5 !?  and now:  10.Be5 !?   10.Bxb8  Rxb8  11.Ne5  Bd7   11...Bd6  12.f4  +=  Ernst-Bosch, Dieren 1998  12.f3  Nf6  13.Qc2   13.Rc1  +=  13...dxc4  14.Bxc4  Nd5  15.Qd2  +=  Meszaros-Farkas, Hungary 2011.   10.Bg3  Nxg3  11.hxg3  +=  10...Nd7  11.h3  Ndf6   11...Nxe5  12.Nxe5  +=  12.Nd2  Bd7  13.f3  Nxd2  14.Qxd2  ±  Guramishvili-Batsiashvili, Tbilisi 2008; }
10. Qb3
{ 10.Qc2  Be8  11.Ne5  g5  12.Bg3  Nd7  13.Nxd7  Qxd7  14.Be5  Bg6  15.c5  Nf6  16.f3  Qd8  17.b4  Nd7  18.Bg3  Rc8  19.Rab1  a6  20.a4  Rf7  21.Rb3  Qf8  22.Qd2  1/2-1/2 Mellano,S-Fraschini,M/Buenos Aires PRENAJ ,EXT 1994  (22) }
10... b6
{ Black could also defend the pawn with   10...Qb6  and now :  11.Qxb6  I think that the best reply is   11.Qc2  +=2  !?  Be8  12.Rac1  +=   11.c5  Qxb3  12.axb3  +=  11...axb6  12.Bc7  Bd8  13.Bxd8  Rxd8  14.Bxe4   14.a3  +=  14...dxe4  15.Ne5  Be8  16.Nc3  Nd7  17.Nxd7  Bxd7 =  0-1 Ishbulatov,S-Boe,M/FSIM B July, Budapest HUN 1998  (46) }
11. Rfc1
{ Whites plan is to double rooks on the c-file, and after exchanging pawns on d5, invade with the rooks if Black recaptures with the c-pawn, or put pressure on c6 if Black takes with the epawn. There is another thematic option for White, which is to play h2-h3, to prevent the exchange of the London bishop, although here this is not essential. }
11... g5
{ A typical plan for Black is to advance his kingside pawns, trying to create counterplay on this wing, because on the queenside he is behind in development. The attack can be dangerous if White plays with insufficient care, although in this precise position it does not look as if it should cause White many difficulties. }
12. Bg3
{ I think that it is better to play   12.Be5  Qe8   12...g4  13.Ne1  ±  13.a3  g4  14.Ne1  Nd2   14...Qh5  15.Nf4  ±  15.Qc2  Nxc4  16.Bxc4  dxc4  17.Qxc4  ± }
12... Nxg3 13. hxg3 Be8
{ This manoeuvre is typical in the Stonewall; the c8-bishop has two possible development routes: via d7-e8-g6  (or -h5)  and to b7. Here Black activates it via e8, but since he has already played b7-b6, the queenside is left weak. }
14. Rc2 Nd7 15. cxd5
{ A precise move; Black must recapture with the c-pawn and White seizes control of the c-file. }
15... cxd5 16. Rac1
{ White has a clear advantage in this position: control of the c-file, possible entry squares at c7 or c6 and tactical ideas against the pawn chain d5-e6-f5. }
16... a6
{ This move is designed to control b5 but it is dubious, not only for tactical reasons, but also because it weakens b6. It was better to play   16...Rb8  17.Ne5  ± }
17. a4
{ There were other options for White here. The best seems to be   17.Rc6 !  but it is also possible to play   17.Bxa6  Rxa6  18.Rc8  Nc5  19.R1xc5  Qd6  20.Rc1  with a healthy extra pawn. }
17... Bf7 18. Rc6 Qb8 19. Qc2 h6
{ Black overlooks Whites reply. It was better to play   19...Qe8  20.Ne5  Nxe5  21.dxe5  Bc5  22.Nd4  although White retains a clear advantage. What should White play now ? }
20. Bxf5
{ Correct ! This sacrifice is crushing and grants White a decisive advantage. The weakness of Blacks castled position and the light squares is key, along with the passivity of the black pieces.   20.Rc7  Be8 }
20... exf5 21. Qxf5 Be8 { 21...Nf6  22.Rxf6  Bxf6  23.Qxf6  wins. } 22. Qxd5+
{ There was a quicker way with   22.Qe6+ !  Rf7  23.Rc8  Qxc8   23...Qb7  24.R1c7  24.Rxc8  Rxc8  25.Ne5  Bb4  26.Nxf7  Bxf7  27.Qxd7  with a decisive advantage. }
22... Kg7 23. Qe6 Bf6 24. e4
{ White has a decisive advantage, with three pawns for the piece, the attack, a weak black king and a strong pawn centre. Black therefore tries to return some material. }
24... Nc5
{ 24...Kh8  +=2  25.e5  Bg7  26.Qh3  Kg8  27.Rxh6  Bxh6  28.Qxh6  Qd8  29.Nxg5   29.e6  Qf6  29...Qe7  30.Rc7  +-  White has 5 pawns for the rook,and strong attack with all pieces.   30.Qe6+  Qxe6  31.Nxe6  Rf7  32.Nc7  Rc8  33.e6  Re7  34.exd7  Bxd7 !   34...Rxd7  35.Nxe8  +-   30.Nf4  Rf5  31.Nge6  +- }
25. dxc5 Bxc6 26. Qxc6
{ It was stronger to interpolate   26.cxb6 !  Qe8   26...Be8  27.Rc7+  Kh8  28.e5   26...Qxb6  27.Rxc6  Qxb2  28.e5  27.Qxc6  Bxb2  28.Rc2  Qxc6  29.Rxc6 }
26... bxc5 27. Rxc5 Qxb2 { 27...Qe8  was better:  28.Ned4  Qxc6  29.Rxc6  ± }
28. e5 { White begins decisive attack. } 28... Be7
{ 28...Qxe2  29.exf6+  Kg8  30.Qb7  +- } 29. Rc2 Qa1+ 30. Rc1 Qa3 31. Ned4
{ The entrance of the white knight at e6 or f5 will prove decisive. } 31...
Rac8 { 31...Kh7  32.Qe4+  Kh8  33.Rc6 } 32. Nf5+ Kf7
{ This results in mate, but White wins anyway after   32...Rxf5  33.Qxc8 } 33.
Qd5+ Kg6 34. Qe6+ Rf6 { 34...Bf6  35.Rxc8   34...Kh5  35.Ng7# } 35. Nxe7+
{ 35. exf6 mates more quickly, but the game continuation also wins after 35Qxe7 36. Qxe7 Rxc1+ 37. Kh2 Rf7 38. Qe8 Kg7 39. e6 Ra7 40. e7. . SUMMARY In this game we have seen the Stonewall Variation, a system that has a very solid reputation. With the London System the idea of playing Bf4 and Nc3 is very popular, instead of the more classical plan with c2-c4, although this is also possible. Whites advantage against this system is based on his bishop on f4 and so Black often avoids playing the natural move Bd6, and instead plays Be7, since in the Stonewall the exchange of the dark-squared bishops usually favours White. In the game, the typical white plan after recycling the knight to e2 is to play c2-c4, doubling rooks on the c-file and exploiting his advantage on the queenside. Whites control of the c-file, combined with some tactical possibilities, allowed him to sacrifice a piece and obtain a decisive advantage, exploiting Blacks weak kingside. Black was left helpless. }
