1. d4 e6 2. Bf4 f5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ White has also tried   4.Be2 !?  d6  5.c4  Be7  6.Bh5+ ?!   6.Nc3  6...Nxh5  7.Qxh5+  g6  8.Qe2  Bf6   8...h5  9.h3  Nd7 =  9.Nc3  O-O  10.h4  ∞  Morozevich-Amin, Almaty 2008 }
4... Be7
{ The main alternative in the Classical Dutch is to play   4...b6  This is a good scheme for Black in many variations of this defence. Once more the idea is to control e4. There are several options now:  5.Be2   5.Nbd2  Bb7  6.Bd3  Bd6 !?   6...Be7  7.h3  O-O  and now:  8.c3   8.g4 !?  Ne4 ?!   8...c5  9.gxf5  exf5  10.Rg1  +=  Bf6   10...d5  11.Ne5  Nd7  12.Nxe4  dxe4  13.Bc4+  ±  Kosic-Stamenkovic, Niksic 1996  11.c3   11.Qe2  +=  11...d6  12.Qe2  Nd7  13.O-O-O  +=  Stefanova-Moser, Plovdiv 2008   8.Qe2  and now:  Ne4   8...c5  9.c3  Ne4  10.O-O-O   10.O-O  +=  10...b5 ?!   10...a5  11.Kb1  a4  12.a3  Na6  ∞  11.Bxb5  Qa5  12.Nb3 ?   12.Kb1  Bd5  13.Nb3  ±  12...Qxa2  13.Kc2  c4 ?   13...Nxc3 !  14.Kxc3  cxd4+  15.exd4  Rc8+  =+  14.Bxc4  Ba3  15.Rb1  Rc8 ?   15...d5  +=  16.Nc5  De Prado-Abella, Spain tt 2006  9.O-O-O   9.Rg1  +=  9...a5  10.g4   10.Rhg1  +=  10...a4  11.gxf5  exf5  12.a3  +=  Teske-Meister, Tegernsee 2008  8...Ne4  9.Rg1  c5  10.g4  cxd4  11.gxf5   11.cxd4  +=  11...Nc5  12.Bb1  dxc3  13.bxc3 =  Khenkin-Meister, Bad Liebenzell 2010  7.Ne5   7.c3  O-O  8.Qc2  Bxf4  9.exf4  c5  10.O-O  Qc7  11.g3  cxd4  12.Nxd4 =  Wesseln-Dgebuadze, Oldenburg 2000;   7.Bxd6  cxd6  8.Qe2  O-O  9.h3  Ne4  10.Rg1  Nxd2  11.Nxd2  Nc6  12.c3  a6  13.g4  +=  Hoang Thanh Trang-Prakash, Chennai 2012;  7...O-O  8.O-O  Nc6  9.a4   9.a3  9...Nb4  10.Be2  Be7  11.c3  Nbd5  12.Bf3  d6  13.Nd3 =  Teske-Teran, Seville 2012  5...Bb7  6.O-O  Be7   6...g6 !?  7.c4  Bg7  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Qc2  Ne4  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  11.Qb3  +=  7.c4   7.h3  O-O  8.c4  h6  9.Nc3  d6  10.Bh2  +=  Izeta-Vaisser, Las Palmas 1995;  7...O-O  8.Nc3  Nh5   8...d6  9.Ng5  Qd7  10.Bf3  c6  11.h4  h6  12.Nh3  d5  +=  Irizanin-Isak, Paracin 2013  9.Ne5   9.Re1  +=  9...Nxf4  10.exf4  d6  11.Bf3  Qc8 ?!   11...c6 =  12.Bxb7  Qxb7  13.Nf3  +=  Stocek-Bigg, Zurich 2005 }
5. h3 O-O 6. Bd3
{ An alternative is to play   6.c4  d6  7.Nc3  and now:  Qe8 ?!   7...Ne4  8.Nxe4   8.Qc2  Nxc3  9.bxc3  b6  10.Bd3  Bb7 =  Sharevich-Lagvilava, Minsk 2004  8...fxe4  9.Nd2  d5  10.Be2  Nc6 =  Piket-Nikolic, Wijk aan Zee 1992  8.Qc2  Qg6   8...b6  +=  9.O-O-O  c6 ?   9...Nh5  +=  10.g4 !  fxg4   10...Ne4  ±  11.Bd3  Goldaracena-Farias, Spain tt 2014; }
6... d6
{ Here we have the Classical set-up of the Dutch versus the London System: Black's plan is based on trying to advance with e6-e5. Whites advantage is that with this set-up he can choose which side to castle: he can play quietly with kingside castling or head for a more complicated game by castling queenside, with the plan of Rg1 and g2-g4. }
7. c4
{ Or   7.Nbd2  Nc6  8.O-O  Kh8  9.Bh2  a6  10.a3  Rb8  11.e4  fxe4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Bxe4  +=  Pezerovic-Komljenovic, Munich 2013   7.O-O }
7... Qe8
{ I think that the idea of   7...Ne4  is better, which is typical of the Classical Dutch. Black's plan would be to follow up with b7-b6 and Bb7 to gain firm control of e4. Play might continue  8.O-O  b6  9.Bxe4  fxe4  10.Nfd2  d5  11.Nc3  += }
8. Nc3 Nc6
{ Now it is too late for   8...b6  9.O-O  Bb7  10.Bh2  Ne4  11.Bxe4  fxe4  12.Nd2  d5  13.Bxc7  ± }
9. O-O
{ It is inferior to play   9.d5  e5 !  10.dxc6  exf4  11.cxb7 ?!   11.exf4  Bd8+  12.Ne2  bxc6 =  11...Bxb7  12.Bxf5   12.O-O =  12...fxe3  13.fxe3  Nh5 =  Zaitseva-Savitskaya, Elista 1998.   13...Bd8  =+ }
9... Bd8
{ This is a normal move in the Classical Dutch: the bishop retreats to d8 to enable the queen to support the e6-e5 advance, and at the same time defends the c7-pawn against a possible Nb5 by White.  If   9...Nh5 ?!  then  10.Bh2  f4  11.Qb1  g6  12.b4  ±  Sharevich-Yakovlev, St Petersburg 2003. }
10. d5
{ Here   10.Bh2  was good, and after  e5  White maintains the advantage:  11.c5   11.Bc2  e4  12.Nd2  a6  13.a3  Rb8  14.b4  b5  15.Bb3  +=  11...e4   11...Kh8  12.cxd6  cxd6  13.Bb5  +=  12.cxd6  exf3  13.dxc7  fxg2  14.Re1 !  Bxc7   14...Be7  15.d5  ±  15.Bxc7  += }
10... exd5
{ An error. Black should play   10...Nb4  11.Bb1  e5  12.Bh2  a5  13.a3  Na6  14.b4  Qg6  += }
11. cxd5 Ne5 { If   11...Nb4  then  12.Bc4  ± } 12. Bc2
{ It seems better to play   12.Nxe5  dxe5  13.Bh2  a6  14.Qb3  with a comfortable advantage. }
12... Bd7
{ Black misses his opportunity. It was better to play   12...Nxf3+  13.Qxf3  Qh5 !  14.Qg3  a6  with equality. }
13. Nd4
{ White now has a clear advantage: he attacks f5 and can force an entry at e6. }
13... Nh5 14. Ne6 { was also good.   14.Bh2  ±  was also good. } 14... Bxe6 15.
dxe6 Nxf4 16. exf4 Nc6
{ It was a little better to play   16...Ng6  17.Ba4  c6  18.Qxd6  ± } 17. Re1
{ Here   17.Ba4  was even better, preventing the black knight from blockading on e7, with a decisive advantage to White. }
17... Ne7 18. Ba4 Qg6 { If   18...c6  then  19.Qxd6  ± } 19. Bd7
{ White's advantage is very clear: he has a strong passed pawn on e6, Black is weak on the light squares and his pieces are passive, especially the bishop on d8, the knight on e7 and the rook on a8. }
19... Qf6 20. Rc1 Kh8 21. Rc2
{ Here White could already win with   21.Nb5  Qxb2  22.Nxc7  Bxc7  23.Rxc7  Qb4  24.Ba4  d5  25.a3  Qxa3  26.Qa1  Qxa1  27.Rxa1  Ng6  28.e7  Rfe8  29.Bxe8  Rxe8  30.g3 }
21... a6 22. Rce2
{ Another good move was   22.Nd5  Nxd5  23.Qxd5  Rb8  24.Rd1  with a clear advantage. }
22... Rb8 23. a4 h6 24. Re3 Kh7 25. b4 Rg8 26. b5 axb5 27. axb5 Ra8 28. Nd5
{ Finally this knight move, which was also possible a few moves ago. White has a decisive advantage. }
28... Qb2 29. Nxe7 Bxe7 30. Qd5
{ Winning material with the double attack on f5 and b7. } 30... Ra2 31. R3e2
Qxe2 32. Rxe2 Rxe2 33. Qxb7 Rc2 34. Bc6 g5
{ Also losing was   34...Bd8  35.g3  Rf8  36.Qc8   36.e7  Bxe7  37.Qxc7  Bf6  38.Qxd6  36...Rc1+  37.Kg2  Re1  38.Qd7  Kh8  39.f3  Kh7  40.Kf2 }
35. Qxc7 Rg7 36. fxg5 Bxg5 37. Qxd6 Be7 38. Qd3 Rc1+ 39. Kh2 Kh8 40. Qxf5 Bd6+
41. g3 Bc5 42. Kg2 Kg8 43. Bd5
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw Blacks final option in the Dutch: the Classical set-up, the main idea of which is to advance with e6-e5. Black has two main development plans: he can opt for b7-b6 and Bb7 or Be7 and d7-d6. The London System works well against this variation and White has the choice of where to play.  Kingside castling is the quieter option, with a solid position and a slight advantage, whereas queenside castling, with the plan of Rg1 and g2-g4, leads to more complex play, with chances of a strong attack.  In the game, White gained a clear advantage by placing his knight on e6, ending up with a strong passed pawn and play on the light squares. Black was left passive and unable to defend. }
