[White "Vs the Dutch"]
[Black "Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter we have been looking at the Dutch Defence against the London System.  In Game 34 we saw a type of Leningrad, with h7-h6 and g7-g5, a rather rare line which resembles some variations of the King's Indian.  In Game 39 we saw the true Leningrad with g7-g6 and White's annoying deployment with Bc4, hindering Black's castling.  In Game 36 we saw the Stonewall, a line with a very solid reputation. White can play an early c2-c4 against it, but White also has the very interesting plan of Nc3  (threatening Nb5)  , followed by Ne2 and c2-c4, which is the most popular. White won, thanks to his control of the c-file.  In Game 37 we saw the Classical Dutch with Be7, d7-d6 and Qe8. There is another option for Black, based on b7-b6 and Bb7. White can choose where to castle and he maintains a slight advantage.  In general, the bishop on f4 considerably disrupts Black's usual plans in the Dutch, since in most variations Blacks idea is to play e6-e5.  In the Stonewall Black usually plays Bd6, but since White's bishop is on f4 and the exchange of dark-squared bishops tends to favour White, Black often plays the bishop to e7, where it is not so well placed. }
