[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4
{ Here we have the Exchange Variation of the Slav Defence. It is a line that we need to learn as White, since we can end up in it via several different move orders, such as 1. d4 c5 2. c3 cxd4 3. cxd4 d5 4. Bf4, or 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c3 cxd4 4. cxd4 d5. It has a drawish reputation, but it has to be handled with care. It is a very comfortable option for White, who is usually able to gain some slight advantages with no risk of losing. The main plan is to play on the c-file and the queenside. White also can play here   4.Nf3  or the most precise move order, which is   4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Bf4 }
4... Nc6
{ Against this move order Black has the option of playing   4...Qb6  5.Nc3  Nf6   5...Qxb2 ?  6.Nxd5  6.e3   6.Rc1  Nc6  7.e3  Qxb2  8.Bd3  ∞  6...Qxb2   6...Nc6  7.Bd3  Bg4  8.Nge2  +=  Grischuk-Kamsky, Moscow 2013  7.Bb5+  Bd7   7...Nc6  8.Nge2  ∞  8.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  9.Nge2  with compensation, Morozevich-Mamedyarov, Tashkent 2012. }
5. e3
{ If   5.Nc3  then  e5 !?  is interesting:  6.dxe5   6.Bxe5  Nxe5  7.dxe5  d4  8.Ne4  Qa5+  9.Nd2  Ne7  10.Ngf3  Nc6 =  Varga-Grigoriants, Hungary 2011  6...d4  7.Ne4  Qa5+   7...Bf5  8.Nd6+  Bxd6  9.exd6  Nf6  10.Nf3  Nh5 =  Maisuradze-Lampert, Gibraltar 2014  8.Nd2  Nge7  9.Ngf3  Nd5  10.g3   10.Bg3  Ne3  11.fxe3  dxe3  =+  Mikhailov-Volkov, Taganrog 2013  10...h6  11.h4 =  Stefanova-Ali, Skopje 2013. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bg4
{ The most popular continuation is   6...a6  7.Bd3 !  Bg4   7...g6  8.h3  Bf5  9.Nf3  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  +=  Kramnik-Aronian, Istanbul 2012  8.Nge2  e6  9.O-O   9.Rc1  Bd6  10.f3  Bh5  11.O-O  Bg6  12.Na4  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Bxf4  14.Nxf4  +=  Bruzon-Yakovenko, Poikovsky 2012  9...Be7  10.Rc1  Bh5   10...O-O  11.Na4  Rc8  12.f3  +=  Aronian-Nakamura, Sandnes 2013  11.Qb3   11.Na4  +=  11...Na5  12.Qa4+  Nc6  13.Bg3 =  Wang Hao-Caruana, Tashkent 2012  Another common sequence is   6...Bf5  7.Qb3  Na5  8.Qa4+  Bd7  which transposes to the game. }
7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+
{ If   8.Bb5+  then  Bd7  9.Qc2   9.Bxd7+  Qxd7  10.Qb5 =  Hertneck-Kramnik, Germany Bundesliga 1993/94  9...e6 = }
8... Bd7 9. Qc2
{ The alternative is   9.Bb5  e6  and now:  10.Bxd7+   10.Rc1  Rc8  11.Nf3  Rc4 !?   11...a6  12.Bxd7+  Nxd7  13.O-O =  12.Qd1 ?!   12.Bxd7+  Nxd7  13.Qc2 =  12...Bxb5  13.Nxb5  Bb4+  14.Ke2  Rxc1   14...O-O  15.Qa4  Bc3  16.Qa3  Bb4  17.Qa4  - Wen Yang-Ni Hua, Danzhou 2013  15.Qxc1  O-O =  Romanov-Elianov, Legnica 2013.  10...Nxd7  11.Nf3  a6  12.O-O  Be7  13.Rfe1   13.Rac1 =  Garcia-Dominguez, Las Tunas 2001   13.Nd2  Rc8 =  Fridman-Balogh, Munich 2013  13...Nc6  14.Qb3   14.Qd1  O-O  15.Na4  Rc8  16.a3 =  Grachev-Yilmaz, Kocaeli 2014   14.h3  O-O  15.Qd1  Nb6 =  Mirzoev-Solak, Denizli 2013  14...Qb6  15.Qd1  O-O  16.Na4  Qa5  17.a3  +=  Kosic-Mihok, Budapest 2011; }
9... Rc8
{ Here   9...e6  is slightly better, as played in several games in the 2014 Gibraltar tournament:  10.Bd3  Be7   10...Nh5  11.Be5  Nc6  12.Qe2  Nxe5  13.dxe5  g6  14.Nf3  Bb4  15.O-O =  Vitiugov-Dreev, Gibraltar 2014  11.h3  Rc8  12.Nf3  Ne4   12...b5  13.a3  O-O  14.O-O =  Li Chao-Rodshtein, Gibraltar 2014  13.O-O  O-O  14.Ne5  Bc6  15.Rac1  b5  +=  Smirnov-Belous, Taganrog 2014   15...Nd6  Svidler-Le Quang Liem, Troms 2013 }
10. Bd3 e6 11. Nf3 b5
{ Making use of the pin on the white queen, Black threatens b5-b4 and consolidates his grip on c4.  Another option is   11...Bb4  12.O-O  O-O  13.Ne5  +=  Nisipeanu-Zhao Zong, Canberra 2014. }
12. Qe2
{ The best move for White is considered to be   12.a3  and now:  Be7   12...Nc4  13.O-O  Be7  and now:  14.Ne5   14.h3  a5  15.Qe2  Nxa3   15...O-O  16.Nxb5  Nxb5  17.Bxb5  +=  I.Sokolov-Giri, Boxtel 2011.  14...Nh5   14...O-O  15.Qe2  +=  Yakovenko-Sjugirov, Yerevan 2014  15.Nxd7  Qxd7  16.Bg3   16.Be5  +=  16...Nxg3  17.hxg3  g6 =  Palac-Svetushkin, Porto Carras 2011;  13.O-O  O-O  14.Ne5   14.Rfc1  14...Be8 =  Ju Wenjun-A. Muzychuk, Beijing 2013; }
12... a6
{ White is better after   12...Nc4  13.O-O  Be7  14.Rac1   14.b3  +=  14...a6  15.b3  Na5  16.Ne5  +=  Naiditsch-Dubov, Wijk aan Zee 2013  Best is   12...b4  13.Nd1  Qb6   13...Nc4  14.b3  Na3 =  14.Ne5  +=  Kosic-Pajkovic, Cetinje 2009 }
13. O-O Be7 14. Ne5 O-O
{ or   14...Qb6  15.Bg5   15.Rac1  +=  15...h6  16.Bxf6  Bxf6  +=  Soors-Cabrera, Fermo 2009 }
15. Rfc1 Be8 16. Rc2
{ White has emerged from the opening with a slight advantage: he is ready to double rooks on the c-file, has a strong knight on e5, and the bishop on d3 it is better than its counterpart on e8. Black is trying to gain a grip on the c4-square, but his pieces are rather passive. }
16... Nd7 { Another option was   16...Nc4  17.Rac1  Bd7  18.Nf3  += } 17. Nf3
{ White avoids piece exchanges.  If   17.Nxd7  then  Bxd7  18.Rac1  Nc4  19.Nb1  Qa5  20.b3  Nd6  21.Rc5  h6 =   21...Nb7  22.Bc7  ±   21...Ne4  22.Bc7  += }
17... Nb6 18. Rac1 Nac4 { It is better to play   18...Nc6  19.a3 } 19. e4
{ White decides to open the centre. However, it was better to play   19.Nb1  +=  with the idea of b2-b3, driving back the black knight, with a slight advantage to White. }
19... dxe4 20. Qxe4
{ It seems better to recapture with the knight:   20.Nxe4 !  Nd5  21.Bd2  += }
20... g6 21. Bh6
{ It is better to play   21.Qe2  Bc6  22.Ne4  Nd5  23.Bh6  += } 21... Bc6 22.
Qe2 Bxf3
{ 22...Re8  23.Be4  Nd6  24.Bxc6  Rxc6  25.Ne5  Rc8  26.Ne4  Rxc2  27.Qxc2  Nd5 = }
23. Qxf3 Re8 24. Be4 Qxd4 25. Bb7 Rcd8
{ This allows White a clear advantage. It was necessary to exert some control over the b5-square with   25...Rc5  e.g.  26.Bxa6  b4  27.Ne4  if White plays   27.Nb5 ?  as in the note to move 27, then Black has the edge after  Qd7  27...Ne5  28.Qe3   28.Nf6+  Kh8 =  28...Qxe3  29.Bxe3  Rxc2  30.Rxc2  Ra8 = }
26. Bxa6 b4 27. Ne4
{ Even better was   27.Nb5  Qd7  28.h4  Bf8  29.Bg5  Be7  30.b3  += } 27... Ne5
28. Qe2 Nd3 29. Rf1
{ Here it was better to play   29.Ra1  ±  indirectly defending the bishop on a6 as well as the pawn on a2. }
29... f5
{ A clear mistake, weakening Black's king and leaving Black in a lost position.  The best try was   29...b3 !?  30.axb3  Nb4  31.Rd2  Qe5  32.Bb5  although White maintains a slight advantage. }
30. Ng3 f4
{ if   30...Nc5  then  31.Bb5  Nbd7  32.Rd1  Qf6  33.h3  g5  34.Bxg5  Qxg5  35.Bxd7  Nxd7  36.Qxe6+  +- }
31. Qxe6+ Kh8 32. Ne2 Qf6 33. Qxf6+ Bxf6 34. Rc6 Bh4 35. Bxd3 Rxd3 36. Nxf4
{ And, faced with the loss of a piece, Black resigned.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@We have seen that from the Benoni or after 1... Nf6 Black can transpose to the Exchange Variation of the Slav Defence. It is a line which a London System player needs to know and which can be reached by transposition.  The Exchange Variation is a very solid line, and although it has a drawish reputation, it is played quite often. Black often relaxes in this type of variation, thinking that any move will do to make a draw, but this is not the case Black needs to play carefully.  White's plan is based on doubling rooks on the c-file and playing on the queenside or in the centre. In this game Black chose a fashionable line with Bg4. White emerged slightly better from the opening and was first to double rooks on the c-file. Black had the c4-square under control, which is important, but after breaking in the centre with e3-e4 White gained the better game and his advantage became decisive after Black blundered with 29... f5. }
