[Black "Game 39 - Naiditsch vs. Movsesian"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 a6 7. Bd3 e6
{ In this game we shall look at the line with e7-e6. In the London System generally, I much prefer White in the variations where Black leaves his queen's bishop shut in with d7-d5 and e7-e6, and this position is no exception. The bishop on d3 is always aimed towards h7. White has options of mounting an attack with Ne5, f2-f4 and g2-g4-g5, followed by bringing the queen to the kingside. In the next game we shall look at lines with Bf5. }
8. Rc1
{ The alternative is   8.Nf3  and now:  Bd6   8...Be7  9.Ne5   9.h3  +=  9...Bd7  10.O-O  Rc8  11.Rc1  +=  De Prado-Zurano, Spain tt 2005.   11.a3  +=  9.Rc1 !?   9.Bxd6  Qxd6 =   9.O-O  Bxf4  10.exf4  Qd6  11.Qd2  O-O  12.Rfe1  Bd7  13.Rad1  Rac8  14.Ne5 =  Graf-Burmakin, Schwbisch Gmnd 2010  9...Bxf4  10.exf4  Qd6  11.Qd2  Bd7  12.O-O  O-O  13.Bb1  +=  Melkumyan-Grabarczyk, Grodzisk 2007 }
8... Bd6
{ Another possibility is   8...Be7  9.h3  O-O  10.Nf3  Bd7  11.O-O  b5  12.Ne5  +=  Qb6   12...Rc8  13.a4  b4  14.Nxd7  Qxd7  15.Nb1  Na5  +=  Bosiocic-Jankovic, Philadelphia 2012  13.Bg5  Be8  14.f4  +=  Rakhmanov-Shvedchikov, Moscow 2012. }
9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. f4
{ White prevents e6-e5 and fortifies this square for his knight. This scheme is like the Stonewall, but with the advantage of having exchanged the bad bishop. The typical plan is Nf3-e5, followed by the pawn advance g2-g4-g5 and then Qh5, or Qf3-h3, with a strong attack. }
10... b5 11. Nf3 Bb7 12. Ne5 O-O 13. O-O Rac8
{ The alternative is to play   13...Ne7  bringing the knight to the kingside to strengthen the defences against White's impending attack, e.g.  14.Qf3   14.a4  b4  15.Nb1  a5  16.Nd2  +=  Rojicek-Ponizil, Czechia tt 2013/14  14...Rac8  15.g4  b4 ?!   15...Nd7  ∞  16.Na4  +=  Shimanov-Ipatov, Moscow 2013. }
14. a3
{ White has also tried   14.Qf3  Na5  15.g4  Nc4  16.g5  Ne4   16...Nd7 =  17.Nxc4  bxc4  18.Nxe4  dxe4  19.Bxe4  +=  Stefanova-Gvetadze, Batumi 2012. }
14... Ne7 15. Qf3 Rc7 16. g4
{ White launches the typical kingside assault. White prefaced this with Qf3 in order to prevent Ne4 a standard plan, as we shall see in other variations where Black plays d7-d5 and adopts a Queen's Gambit Declined set-up. In this type of position the bishop on b7 tends to remain passive and Black has to seek counterplay on the queenside. It was also possible to play   16.f5  exf5  17.Bxf5  Nxf5  18.Qxf5 = }
16... Rfc8 17. Rcd1 b4 18. axb4 Qxb4 19. Rf2
{ The rook defends b2 and can go to g2 or double rooks on the f-file. } 19...
Ne4
{ Black cracks under the pressure and sacrifices a pawn to gain some activity, but this should not be sufficient.  It was better to play   19...Ng6  20.Rdf1  +=  or   19...a5  20.g5  += }
20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Qxe4 Rc1
{ Here it was better to play   22...Qb3  23.Rfd2  Nd5  24.Nd3  += } 23. Rdf1
{ Now   23.Rxc1 !  Rxc1+  24.Kg2  ±  was better. } 23... Rxf1+ 24. Rxf1
{ White could have maintained his advantage with   24.Kxf1  += } 24... Qxb2 25.
f5 exf5 26. gxf5 Qb6
{ The best move was   26...Qe2  with the threat of 27... Rc2, and this would have guaranteed Black the draw:  27.f6  gxf6   27...Rc2 ??  28.Qxc2 !  Qxc2  29.fxg7  28.Nd7  Rc2  29.Nxf6+  Kf8  30.Nxh7+  Kg8  31.Nf6+  Kf8  32.Nh7+  Ke8  33.Nf6+  with a draw by perpetual check, since  Kd8 ?  would lose to  34.Qa8+  Kc7  35.Qa7+  Kc6  36.Qd7+  Kb6  37.Qd6+ }
27. Ng4
{ The right move was   27.f6 !  Ng6   27...gxf6 ??  28.Qg4+  28.Nxf7 !  gxf6   28...Kxf7  29.Qd5+  Kf8  30.fxg7+  Kxg7  31.Qd7+  29.Nh6+  Kh8  30.h4  with a clear advantage to White. }
27... h5 28. f6 Ng6
{ This loses;  he needed to play   28...hxg4  with equality after:  29.Qxg4   29.fxe7  Re8  30.Rf5   30.Rb1  Qc7  31.Rb7  Qc1+  32.Kg2  Qd2+  33.Kg3  Qe1+  34.Kxg4  Qg1+  35.Kf5  Qxh2 =  29...g6  30.fxe7  Re8  31.Qd7  Qb5  32.Qxb5   32.Qd8 ??  Qg5+  32...axb5 = }
29. Qf5
{ Attacking the rook and the pawn. White now has a decisive advantage. } 29...
Qb7 30. Qxh5 Rc2 31. d5 gxf6
{ A blunder that hastens the defeat; I imagine this was caused by time pressure. Black was lost anyway, but he could have put up greater resistance with   31...Qc8  32.fxg7  Rc1  33.Qg5 }
32. Qh6
{ Black must give up his queen to prevent mate with 33. Nxf6.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the line with e7-e6 by Black, without developing the queen's bishop. In general, the variations where Black leaves this bishop shut in with d7-d5 and e7-e6 are very comfortable for White. White exchanged the dark-squared bishops and then played f2-f4, switching to a Stonewall set-up but without the usual bad bishop.  White's plan in such positions is to play Ne5 and g2-g4-g5 and then move the queen to the kingside, either via f3-h3 or moving to h5 directly, to attack the black king. In the game, Black tried to create counterplay on the queenside and in a worse position he hurriedly played Ne4, sacrificing a pawn.  However, White then played badly and let Black equalise, but a further mistake by Black allowed White to win material and mount a strong attack against the black king, forcing resignation. Not all the lines of the Exchange Variation are boring or dead drawn. }
*

