[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Slav"]
[Black "Game 40 - Ivanchuk vs. Nakamura"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6
{ In this move order Black can also play the interesting Winawer Counter-Gambit   4...e5 !?   which can also arise via  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nc3  e5  Let us review White's options here:  5.Nf3   5.e4 !?  a counter-counter-gambit !  dxe4  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.dxe5  Bb4  and now:  8.e6 !?   8.Bxd7+  Nxd7  9.e6 !?   9.Nge2  Nxe5  10.O-O  Qxd1  11.Rxd1  Nf6  12.Bg5 =  9...fxe6  10.Nge2  Nc5  11.O-O  Nf6  12.Be3  with compensation, Vavrak-Saric, Pula 2008  8...fxe6  9.Nh3   9.Qh5+  g6  10.Qe5  Qf6  11.Bf4  a6  =+  Beliavsky-Lautier, Belgrade 1991  9...Nf6  10.Bc4   10.Qb3  Bxb5  11.Qxb4  Ba6  =+  10...Qc7  11.Qb3  Nc6  =+  Chabanon-Khenkin, Genova 1996   5.dxe5  d4  6.Ne4  Qa5+  7.Nd2   7.Bd2  Qxe5  8.Ng3  Nc6  9.Nf3  Qd6  10.a3   10.e3  dxe3  11.Bxe3 =  Bunyatov-Shkuran, Lviv 2015  10...Nf6  11.e4  dxe3  12.Bxe3 =  A.Muzychuk-Stefanova, Monaco 2015  7...Nc6  8.Ngf3  Bg4   8...Nh6  9.g3  Ng4  10.Bg2  Ne3  11.fxe3  dxe3  12.O-O  exd2  13.Bxd2  +=  Guliev-Morozevich, Moscow 1998  9.g3  Bxf3  10.exf3  Qxe5+  11.Qe2  Qxe2+  12.Bxe2  O-O-O  13.Bc4   13.Bd3  g6  14.O-O  Bg7  15.f4  +=  Sarwer-Ebeling, Finland tt 2015/16  13...Bb4   13...Ne5  14.Bb3  +=  14.a3   14.Bxf7  Nh6  15.Be6+  Kb8  16.O-O  +=  14...Bxd2+  15.Bxd2  Ne5  16.Be2  ±  Fridman-Hector, Germany 2010.  5...e4  6.Ne5  f6  7.Qa4+  Nd7  8.Ng4   8.Nxd7  Bxd7  9.Qb3  Bc6  10.Bf4  Bd6 =  Wiedenkeller-Engqvist, Borlange 1992  8...Kf7  ∞  Perelshteyn-Holt, Wheeling 2010; }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bf4 Bf5
{ This is the position that is reached most often. The Symmetrical Variation is considered Black's simplest way to equalise, but that is not always the case.  The move   6...Ne4  is regarded as slightly dubious, but it is played nevertheless and even some strong players, such as Kramnik and Shirov, have employed it. I think this is because some aggressive players dislike symmetrical positions and prefer a more open and complex position, even though it might be a bit worse.  7.e3  Nxc3  8.bxc3  and now:  e6   8...g6  and now there are several good moves for White:  9.h4   9.Bd3  Bg7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Re1  +=   11.Rb1  b6  12.c4  dxc4  13.Bxc4  Bb7  14.Qe2  +=  Banikas-G.Kasparov, Patras blitz 2001   9.Rb1  Bg7  and now:  10.h4 !?   10.c4  O-O  11.Rb5  dxc4   11...Be6 =  12.Bxc4  a6  13.Rd5   13.Rc5  13...Qb6 =  Lakdawala-S.Jones, Los Angeles 2000.  10...Qa5   10...O-O  11.h5  +=  11.Qd2  a6  12.Bd3  +=  Daly-Ferguson, Rotherham 1997  9...h6  10.Ne5  +=  Ubilava-Cifuentes, Benasque 2005  9.Bd3  Bd6  10.Bxd6   10.O-O  O-O  11.Re1  +=  10...Qxd6  11.O-O  O-O  12.e4  dxe4  13.Bxe4  g6 ?!   13...b6  14.Re1 =  14.Qd2  +=  Rezan-Kreisl, Zadar 2012; }
7. Qb3
{ The main line goes   7.e3  e6  with more than 7,000 games. Let us consider a few examples: A very common line leading to a draw is  8.Bd3  The most popular line is   8.Bb5  Nd7  and now:  9.Qb3   9.O-O  Be7  10.Rc1  Rc8  11.Qb3  O-O  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.Na4  Qa5 =  Fressinet-Balogh, Bastia 2010;   9.Qa4  Rc8  10.O-O  a6  11.Bxc6  Rxc6  12.Rfc1  Be7  13.Ne2  Qb6 =  Ivanchuk-Dominguez, Moscow 2009.  9...Be7  10.O-O   10.Rc1  10...g5  11.Bg3  h5  12.h3  g4  13.hxg4  hxg4 =  Rakhmanov-Yakovenko, Plovdiv 2012   8.Qb3  Bb4  9.Bb5  O-O  10.Bxc6  Bxc3+  11.Qxc3  Rc8  12.Ne5  Ng4  13.Nxg4  Bxg4  14.Qb4  Rxc6  15.Qxb7  Qc8  ∞  Kramnik-Anand, Bonn 2008.  8...Bxd3  9.Qxd3  Bd6  10.Bxd6  Qxd6 = }
7... Qb6
{ This is a typical move to parry the attack on b7 but I do not think it is a good one here.   7...Na5  is preferable:  8.Qa4+  Bd7  9.Qc2  e6  10.e3  Rc8  11.Bd3  +=  I.Sokolov-Yu Yangyi, Jakarta 2012.   7...Qd7  is inferior:  8.Ne5   8.e3  +=  8...Nxe5  9.Bxe5   9.dxe5  Ne4  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.e3  +=  9...a6  Sumets-Latreche, Tipaza 2011   7...Qc8  is bad in view of  8.Nb5  ± }
8. Qxb6 axb6 9. e3 e6 10. a3
{ Practice has also seen   10.Nh4  Be4  11.f3  Bb4  12.fxe4   12.Kd1 =  12...Nxe4  13.Bd3  Nxc3  14.bxc3  Bxc3+  15.Ke2  Bxa1  16.Rxa1  ∞  Moradiabadi-Rublevsky, Khanty-Mansiysk 2010. }
10... Be7 11. Be2
{ Why does the bishop go to e2 instead of b5 ? First of all because White keeps the square b5 vacated for the knight; and secondly from e2 the bishop indirectly fights against Black's idea of Nf6-h5  (see the comments on Black's 14th move below)  .  But   11.Bb5  is also played and White was slightly better after  Nd7  12.O-O  O-O  13.Rac1  in Pri-Van Wely, Bastia 2007.   11.Rc1  is also good, e.g.  O-O  12.Be2   12.Nh4  +=  12...Rfc8  13.Nd2  +=  Bauer-Arnold, Biel 2011. }
11... O-O 12. O-O Rfc8 13. Rfc1
{ The main drawback of doubled pawns is their lack of flexibility. Furthermore, here White has also complete control over the b5-square. And finally, the isolated doubled pawns can easily become a target later on. All this gives White hopes to play for advantage.  Here   13.Nd2  +=  was also good. }
13... Nh5 { Here   13...Ne4  was better. } 14. Bg5 Bxg5
{ After   14...f6  White plays  15.Nh4 !  attacking the knight on h5. If then  fxg5   15...Be4 !  16.Bxh5  fxg5  17.Bg4  Kf7  18.Nxe4  gxh4  19.Nc3  White has a slight advantage.  16.Nxf5  exf5  17.Bxh5  g4  with the idea to catch the bishop, White takes the pawn  18.Nxd5  Rd8   18...Bd8  19.Be8 !  19.Nxe7+  Nxe7  20.Rc7  Kf8  21.h3  g6  22.hxg4  gxh5  23.gxf5  and Black is struggling to survive. }
15. Nxg5 Nf6 16. Nf3
{ The immediate   16.Nb5  was good, e.g.  h6  17.Nf3  Rd8  18.Nd2  += } 16...
Bg4 17. Nb5 Bxf3 18. Bxf3
{ Black is close to equality in this position. The piece exchanges are in his favour but he must exercise great care. What should he play now ? }
18... Rd8
{ 18...Na5 !  was the right move:  19.Rc3   19.Bd1  Kf8  20.Nd6  Rc6 =  19...Rxc3  20.bxc3  Kf8  21.Rb1  Ke7 = }
19. Kf1 Kf8 20. Rc3 Ke7 21. Rac1 Rdc8 22. Ke1 Kd7 23. h3 h5 { 23...h6 } 24. h4
{ Ivanchuk fixes the black pawns on light squares, so that in the future they can be attacked by the bishop. White has a space advantage, and he controls the c-file and the b5-square, while Black's doubled pawns are weak. Still, the win is a long way off. }
24... g6 25. g3 Ra5 26. Be2 Ne8 27. Rb3 Rd8
{ 27...Nxd4 ?  doesn't work:  28.Rxc8  Nxb3  29.Rc3  Na1   29...Nc5  30.b4  30.b4  ±  and the a1-knight's future is looking bleak. }
28. f3 Nf6 29. Nc3 Kc7 30. Na2 Ng8
{ According to Ivanchuk this is a bad mistake.   30...Rc8  31.Nb4  Nd7  was better, controlling e5 and defending b6. Still, White can try to open the kingside to gain the advantage. }
31. Nb4
{ White now has a clear advantage. The knight is heading for e5, to create weaknesses. }
31... Ne7 32. Nd3 Raa8
{ If   32...f6  weakening his position, White can play  33.Nf4  with a clear advantage. }
33. Ne5 Rf8
{ After   33...f6  34.Nd3  followed by Nf4 at some point  (and eventually Bf1-h3)  Black will have problems with the pawn e6. }
34. Bd3 f5
{ After this move White is strategically winning. Black has too many pawn weaknesses  (b6, e6 and g6)  .   34...Rad8  was better, but after  35.Kf2  White retains a clear advantage. }
35. Bb5 Rac8 36. Kf2 { 36.Rbc3  Kd6 } 36... Rg8 37. Ba4 Rgf8 38. Rc2 Rfd8
{ 38...Rg8  loses by force:  39.Rbc3  Kd6  40.Nf7+  Kd7  41.Rb3  Kc7  42.Ng5  and Black is unable to protect the e6-pawn. }
39. Rbc3 Rd6 40. b4 Kb8 41. Bxc6 bxc6 42. b5
{ The game is over. Black is losing a pawn and remains with a lot of other weaknesses. }
42... Kb7 43. bxc6+ Kc7 { 43...Nxc6  44.Nxg6  wins. } 44. a4 Rdd8 45. Rb2 Ra8
46. Rcb3 { The target is the b6-pawn, to create an entry for the rooks on b7. }
46... Nc8 { 46...Ra6  47.a5 ! } 47. Ra2 Rg8 48. a5 b5
{ 48...Ra6  fails to  49.axb6+  Rxb6  50.Rxb6  Kxb6  51.Rb2+  with a winning advantage. }
49. Rxb5 Nd6 50. Rb4 Ra6 51. Kg2 g5 52. hxg5 Rxg5 53. Kh3 Rg8 54. Kh4
{ White is going after the weak pawn on h5. } 54... Rh8 55. Rab2 Ra7
{ 55...Rxa5  56.Rb7+ !  Nxb7  57.Rxb7+  Kc8   57...Kd6 ??  58.Rd7#  58.Nd7  and wins. }
56. Rb6 Rha8 57. Kxh5 Rg8 58. a6 Rga8 59. Rb7+ Nxb7 60. axb7
{ Black resigned. There is no defence against 61. Nd7.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the main line of the Slav Exchange with Bf5. White has various options after the usual 7. e3 e6, including 8. Bd3, which is very drawish, and 8. Bb5, the most popular move.  Ivanchuk chose the interesting 7. Qb3, delaying e2-e3. Black has several ways to defend the b7-pawn and chose 7... Qb6, allowing his pawns to be doubled, although the best reply is 7... Na5. In the game, White gained a slightly better position, mainly on account of the doubled pawns and his control of the b5-square and the c-file. Ivanchuk kept improving his position and he exploited his opponents weaknesses very well, finally winning a pawn and the game. }
