1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6
{ If Black plays symmetrically with   2...Bf5  White should play  3.c4 !  right away and now:  the normal   3.e3  e6  4.c4 ?!  is dubious because of  Bxb1 !  5.Rxb1  or   5.Qxb1  5...Bb4+  and White loses castling rights.  3...c6  On the third move Black can also opt for   3...dxc4  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3   5.f3  e6   5...c6  6.e4  Be6 =  Olea-Fernandez, Asturias 2009  6.e4  Bg6  7.Bxc4  +=  Kaunzinger-Stross, Bavaria 2011  5...c6  6.Bxc4  +=  Nbd7 ?   6...e6  +=  7.Qb3  with a double attack on b7 and f7  Qb6   7...e6  8.Qxb7  Rc8  9.Ba6  8.Bxf7+  Kd8  1-0 Romero-Aranda, Caete 1994;   3...e6  and now  4.Nc3  transposes to the game.  if   4.Qb3  then  Nc6  with advantage   4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nc3 =  4.Nc3  e6  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qxb3  7.axb3  Nd7  8.b4  Ngf6  9.e3   9.b5  +=  9...Nh5  10.Bg3   10.Be5  +=  10...Be7 =  Gazik-Chernyshov, Ustron 2013  Another option is   2...c6  3.e3  Bf5   3...e6  4.Nf3  Bd6  5.Bd3  Bxf4  6.exf4  Ne7  7.Nbd2  b6  8.O-O  Ba6  9.c4  +=  Jobava-Ivanov, Sochi 2014;   3...Qb6  and now:  4.b3 !  this must be one of the few times when this move is necessary and good.  White has also tried   4.Qc1 !?  Bf5   4...Nf6  5.Bd3   5.Nf3 !   5.h3 !  are better.  5...Nh5  6.Bg5  h6  7.Bh4  Nd7 =  Sandipan-Komljenovic, Benasque 2014  5.Nf3  Nd7  6.Be2  e6  7.O-O  h6  8.h3  Ngf6  9.c4  +=  Stefanova-Zatonskih, Beijing 2012.  4...Bf5   4...Nf6  5.Bd3  c5  6.Nc3   6.Nf3  +=  is better.  6...Bg4 !?  7.f3 ?!   7.Nxd5  +=  7...Bd7  8.Nge2  e6  Pri-Tregubov, Le Port Marly 2009  5.Bd3   5.Nf3  e6  6.Bd3  Bg6  7.O-O  Nf6  8.c4  Nbd7  9.c5  Qd8  10.b4  +=  Eljanov-Golod, Netanya 2009  5...Bxd3  6.Qxd3  Nf6  7.Ne2  e6  8.O-O  Nbd7  9.c4  +=  Predojevic-Houska, Oslo 2013  4.c4   4.Nf3  e6  5.c4  Bd6 =  Vachier-Lagrave-Caruana, Biel 2010   4.Bd3  Bxd3  5.Qxd3  Nf6  6.Nf3  e6  7.O-O  Bd6  8.Bxd6  Qxd6  9.c4  O-O  10.Nc3  Nbd7 =  Stefanova-Harikrishna, Cap dAgde 2006  4...e6   4...Bxb1 ?!  5.Qxb1  e5  6.Bxe5  Qa5+  7.Kd1  +=  Nd7  8.Bg3  c5  9.Nf3  Ngf6  10.a3  cxd4  11.exd4  Be7  12.c5  Ne4  13.Bd3  f5  14.b4  Qd8  15.Qb3  f4  16.Bxf4  Nxf2+  17.Kc2  Nxh1  18.Qxd5  Berkes-Lupulescu,Dresden 2008  5.Nc3  Nd7  6.Qb3  Qb6  7.c5  Qxb3  8.axb3  a6  9.b4  Rc8  10.Nf3  h6  11.Nd2  g5  12.Bg3  Bg7  13.Nb3  e5  14.Na5  +=  Grachev-Kobalia, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013; }
3. e3 Bf5
{ The Slav set-up against the London System is a defence that has a solid reputation and it is difficult for White to gain any advantage against it. Black plays symmetrically in many lines. We have already seen in the chapter on the Benoni how Black can transpose to the Exchange Variation of the Slav. This defence and its associated patterns of play are very common in many variations of the London System, so it is essential to have a good knowledge of them with white. }
4. c4 c6
{ Alternatives include:   4...Nc6 !?  5.Qb3   5.Nf3   5.Nc3  e6  6.Nf3   6.a3  is better.  6...Bb4  7.Be2   7.Rc1  7...Ne4  8.Qb3  O-O  9.O-O  Bxc3  10.bxc3  Na5 =  Nguyen Ngoc-Le Quang Liem, Cap dAgde 2010  5...e6   5...Na5  6.Qa4+  c6  7.c5  b5 =  6.Qxb7 ?!   6.Nc3 =  6...Nb4  7.Na3  dxc4  8.Bxc7   8.Nb5 !?  Rb8  9.Nxc7+  Kd7  10.Qxa7  Nc6  11.Qa4  Rb4  12.Qa6  Rxb2  =+  8...Qd5 !  9.Qxd5  Nfxd5  10.Bg3   10.Ba5  Nd3+  11.Bxd3  Bxd3  =+  10...Nd3+  11.Bxd3  cxd3 !?   11...Bb4+  12.Kd1  Bxd3  =+  12.Nf3   12.Rc1 =  12...Bb4+  13.Kd1  O-O ?!   13...Rc8  =+  14.Nc4 =  De Prado-Patio, Spain tt 2014.   4...e6  5.Nc3   5.Qb3  Nc6 =  5...Bd6   5...Bb4  6.Qb3   6.Bd3 =  6...Nc6  7.a3  Bxc3+  8.bxc3 =  Stefanova-Koneru, Beijing 2013  6.Bxd6  Qxd6  7.Nf3  c6  8.Be2  O-O  9.O-O =  Shimanov-Mikhailov, St Petersburg 2013. }
5. Nc3 e6 6. Qb3
{ This is the thematic idea when Black moves his bishop from c8; White attacks the weak point b7, just as Black does in other lines with Qb6, attacking b2. The difference is that White is helped by having his bishop on f4, controlling a key diagonal. Now Black has to choose how to defend his b7-pawn; he has various options, such as 6... Qc8, 6... b6 or 6... Qb6. Each of these has its drawbacks and the choice is not easy for Black, since White's threats are more unpleasant than they might appear at first sight. }
6... b6
{ This is not the most popular move but according to the engines it is the best. Let us consider the alternatives:   6...Qb6  The resulting endgame is considered better for White after  7.c5  Qxb3  8.axb3  Nbd7  9.b4  other options at this point are   9.h3  a6  10.b4  Rc8  11.Nf3  Be7  12.Nd2  Bd8  13.Nb3  Bc7  14.Bxc7  Rxc7  15.b5  ±  Grachev-Mohammad, Chennai 2016   9.Nf3  a6  10.h3  Be7  11.b4  O-O  12.Nd2  Rac8  13.Nb3  Bd8  14.Bd6  Re8  15.Na5  Bxa5  16.bxa5  +=  Bortnyk-Nguyen, Bblingen 2015  9...Nh5  and now :  or   9...Be7  10.f3 !  +=  O-O  11.g4  Bg6  12.b5  Lffler-Cardili, Porto Mannu 2013;   9...a6  10.f3   10.b5  cxb5  11.Bxb5  Rc8  12.Ba4  +=  10...Rc8  11.g4  Bg6  12.h4  +=  10.Be5   10.Bc7 !?  is fashionable, and the piece sacrifice after  Rc8  11.Rxa7 !?   11.Be5  +=  11...Rxc7  12.Ra8+   12.b5  ∞  12...Ke7  13.b5  appears to give White compensation  (and in fact he has scored well)  but although this idea is quite interesting I do not think that White gains any advantage with it:  b6   13...cxb5  14.Nxb5  Rc6  15.Na7  Rc7  16.f3   16.Nb5 =  16...Nxc5  17.dxc5  Rxc5  18.g4  Rc1+  19.Kf2  Rc2+ =  Miladinovic-Grbovic, Cetinje 2012   13...e5  14.b6  Nxb6  15.cxb6  Rc8  16.Ra7 =  Noiroux-Hommerson, Belgium tt 2013/14   13...g5 ?!  14.b6  Nxb6  15.cxb6  Rd7  +=  Riordan-Katz, Parsippany 2013  14.bxc6  Rxc6  15.Ra7 ?   15.Bb5 !  Rc7  16.c6  Ndf6  17.f3  ∞  15...Nhf6   15...Kd8  ∓  16.Bb5  Rusev-Mitkov, Sunny Beach 2010  10...f6 ?!   10...Nxe5  11.dxe5  g5  12.h3  +=  and the pawn break on b5 gives White the advantage.  11.Bc7  g5  12.b5  ±  Yermolinsky-Lu, Dallas 2008;   6...Qc8  The move 6Qc8 is played more often, although this does not seem like a good square for the queen  (similar to when White plays Qc1)  ; I think that eventually the queen will be exposed to an attack by an enemy rook along the c-file. Here White has tried  7.h3  as well as   7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.Bg3  Be7  9.Nf3  O-O  10.Be2  +=  Bocharov-Simonian, Bhubaneswar 2010;  Another good option seems to be   7.Rc1  and now:  Nbd7   7...Be7  8.cxd5  Nxd5  9.Bg3   9.Bxb8 ?!  Rxb8  10.e4  Nxc3  11.exf5  Nd5  12.Bc4  O-O  with a slight advantage to Black, De Prado-B.Vega, Linares 2013  instead   9.Nxd5 !  exd5  10.Bd3  +=  is better.  9...O-O  10.Nf3  Nxc3  11.Qxc3  a5  12.a3  +=  Ponomariov-Karjakin, Moscow 2010.  8.cxd5   8.Nf3  Be7  9.Nh4  +=   9.cxd5  exd5 ?!  but   9...Nxd5  is an improvement  10.Nb5  +=  D.Gurevich-Zhou, Moscow 2005  8...Nxd5  9.Bg3  or   9.Nxd5  exd5  10.Ne2  +=  9...N7f6  10.Nf3  Be7  11.Be2  O-O =  Roiz-Bryzgalin, Dagomys 2010  7...Be7  8.Nf3  h6  9.Be2  O-O  10.O-O  Nbd7  +=  Kamsky-Leko, Beijing 2013 }
7. Nf3 Bd6
{ 7...Be7  8.Be2   8.Rc1  +=  8...O-O  +=  Vezzosi-Modena, Arbo 2009. } 8. Ne5
{ This seems best. White has also tried   8.Bg3  O-O  9.Be2  Qe7  10.Ne5  Nfd7  11.O-O =  Nguyen Ngoc-Tologontegin, Guangzhou 2010  and   8.Bxd6  Qxd6  9.cxd5  exd5  10.Be2  Nbd7  11.O-O  h6 =  Dorfman-Cuijpers, Germany Bundesliga B 1999/2000. }
8... dxc4
{ I think that it is better to play   8...O-O  9.h3   9.Be2  +=  9...Ne4  10.cxd5  Nxc3  11.Qxc3 =  Abdel-Sarwat, Windhoek 2007 }
9. Bxc4
{ I think that White has emerged from the opening with a slight advantage, since Black has a weak square at c6 and his queenside development is lagging. }
9... O-O 10. Be2
{ A good move: the bishop retreats from c4 to control g4 and go to f3; at the same time it clears the c-file. }
10... Nd5 11. g4
{ Here the simple   11.Nxd5 !  would give White a pleasant advantage, e.g.  cxd5   11...exd5  12.O-O  +=  12.g4  Be4  13.f3  Bg6  14.Rc1  += }
11... Bg6 12. h4 Nxc3 13. bxc3
{ It was better to recapture with the queen:   13.Qxc3  ± } 13... Bxe5 14. Bxe5
h6 15. Bf3
{ White has a clear advantage: he has the bishop pair and the initiative on the kingside, while Black is nursing a weakness on c6 and has an inactive knight on b8. }
15... Qc8 16. g5 h5
{ If   16...hxg5  then after  17.hxg5  Nd7  18.Bg3  White would maintain a clear advantage, owing to the open h-file. }
17. Qd1 { White is going to win the pawn on h5. } 17... Qa6 18. Bxh5 Bxh5 19.
Qxh5 Qa3 20. O-O
{ A very good move by White: he brings his king into safety and indirectly defends his pawn. }
20... Nd7
{ Why did Black not take the pawn with   20...Qxc3 ?  Because this loses after  21.Bxg7 !  Kxg7  22.Qh6+  Kg8  23.g6  fxg6  24.Qxg6+  Kh8  25.Kh1  and the arrival of the rook on g1 will be decisive. }
21. Bg3
{ Now the sacrifice   21.Bxg7  Kxg7  22.Qh6+  Kg8  23.g6  fxg6  24.Qxg6+  Kh8  is only good enough for a draw, since if  25.Kh1 ?  then  Qe7  and Black wins. }
21... Qxc3 22. Rac1 Qa5 23. Rxc6 Qxa2
{ Black has recovered the material, but stands worse. White commands the open file, Black's knight cannot move and White has the attack, with g5-g6 in the air. }
24. Rfc1
{ Here   24.Rc7 !  Qd5  25.Qg4 !  was stronger, with the idea of e3-e4. White would have a clear advantage. }
24... Qd5 25. Rd6 Qb5
{ It was better to play   25...Qb7  although White would still have a clear advantage after  26.Rdc6  Rfc8  27.Rc7  Rxc7  28.Rxc7  Qd5  29.Qg4 }
26. Qd1 Rfd8 27. Rc7 { Now White gains material and has a won game. } 27... Nf8
28. Rxd8 { Even stronger was   28.Qf3 !  Qe8  29.h5  Rac8  30.Rxa7 } 28... Rxd8
29. Rxa7 Qd5 30. Qc2 b5 31. Qc5 Qf3
{ if   31...Qxc5  then  32.dxc5  or   31...Rd7  32.Qxd5  Rxd5  33.Rb7 } 32.
Qxb5
{ White is two pawns up and to win he just needs to parry a few threats by Black. }
32... Rc8 33. Qf1 Ng6 34. Qg2 Rc1+
{ 34...Qg4  was more tenacious, but after  35.f3  Qf5  36.e4  Qb5  37.Ra2  White is winning. }
35. Kh2 Qh5 36. Qa8+ Kh7 37. Qe4 Kg8 38. Ra8+ Kh7 39. Rf8
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw a Slav Defence set-up by Black against the London System and we reviewed various options for Black on move 2. We saw that after 2... c6 and 3... Qb6 we have one of the few occasions when White should respond with 4. b3 !.  We learned that if Black plays 2... Bf5 White should play an immediate 3. c4. After 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 4. c4 we saw that 4... Nc6 and 4... e6 are interesting. In the game, after White played the main line with 6. Qb3, Black had several ways to defend the b7-pawn. In the game we saw 6b6 but we also analysed 6... Qb6 and 6... Qc8, which are the main alternatives. White emerged from the opening with some advantage, on account of his better development and the weakness on c6 in particular.  White opted to put pressure on both wings and won a pawn. Then, following the brilliant 20.O-O !! White had a clear advantage and shortly afterwards he was able to win without any problems. }
