1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5
{ The Slav set-up against the London System is a defence that has a solid reputation and it is difficult for White to gain any advantage against it. Black plays symmetrically in many lines. We have already seen in the chapter on the Benoni how Black can transpose to the Exchange Variation of the Slav. This defence and its associated patterns of play are very common in many variations of the London System, so it is essential to have a good knowledge of them with white. }
4. c4 c6 { Alternatives include: } 5. Nc3 e6 6. Qb3
{ This is the thematic idea when Black moves his bishop from c8; White attacks the weak point b7, just as Black does in other lines with Qb6, attacking b2. The difference is that White is helped by having his bishop on f4, controlling a key diagonal. Now Black has to choose how to defend his b7-pawn; he has various options, such as 6... Qc8, 6... b6 or 6... Qb6. Each of these has its drawbacks and the choice is not easy for Black, since White's threats are more unpleasant than they might appear at first sight. }
6... b6
{ This is not the most popular move but according to the engines it is the best. Let us consider the alternatives: }
7. Nf3 Bd6 8. Ne5 { This seems best. White has also tried } 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4
{ I think that White has emerged from the opening with a slight advantage, since Black has a weak square at c6 and his queenside development is lagging. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs the Slav"]
[Black "Game 42 - Karjakin vs. Kramnik"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4
{ We already know that White does better to employ the 2. Bf4 move order. }
3... c6
{ 3... c5 would be the best move for Black against this move order. Kramnik opts for a type of Slav Defence. }
4. e3 Bg4
{ The most popular move with this move order. The alternatives are:   4...Qb6  a classical line for Black which Kramnik had already played before:  5.Nbd2 !?   5.Qc1  Bf5  6.c4  e6  7.Nc3   7.c5  7...Nbd7  8.c5  +=  Kamsky-Kramnik, Turin ol 2006  5...Qxb2   5...Nbd7  6.Bd3  6.Rb1 !?   6.Bd3  Qa3   6...Qb6  7.O-O  e6  8.c4  Be7  9.Rb1  Qd8  +=  Annaberdiev-Barsov, Doha 2006  7.Qe2   7.O-O   7.Ne5  e6  8.O-O  ∞  Karaboikis-Kjartansson, Rodas 2013  7...Bg4 ?!  8.O-O  Nbd7  9.h3  Bxf3  10.Nxf3  +=  Van Harreveld-De Vreugt, Enschede 2006  6...Qa3  7.Bd3  ∞   4...Bf5  heading for the Slav, as we saw in the previous game:  5.c4  e6  6.Nc3  here it is better to play   6.Qb3  Qb6  7.c5  Qxb3  8.axb3  +=  Kadziolka-Kulon, Wroclaw 2013  6...Nbd7   6...Be7  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.h3  O-O  9.Be2  Ne4  10.O-O  +=  E.Alvarez-B. Vega,Linares 2013   6...Bd6 =  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  += }
5. c4 Nbd7
{ Other options for Black are:   5...e6  6.Qb3  Qb6  7.c5 !   7.Ne5  Bf5  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  Bxb1  10.Rxb1  Nbd7   10...Nh5 =  11.b4  a6  +=  Pakleza-Dreev, Varosvia 2013  7...Qxb3  8.axb3  Nbd7  9.h3   9.Nc3  Nh5  10.Bg3  Nxg3  11.hxg3  Be7 =  Rder-Iagar, Balaguer 2011   9.Nbd2 !  +=  9...Bf5  10.Nc3  h6  11.b4  Be7  12.b5  O-O  13.bxc6  bxc6  14.Ba6   5...Bxf3 !?  6.gxf3   6.Qxf3  e6  7.cxd5  cxd5  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.Bd3  Bd6  +=  Ravi-Murali,Tirupati 2012  6...dxc4   6...Nbd7  7.Nc3  e6  8.e4   8.Qb3  +=  8...Bb4  9.Qb3  Bxc3+  10.bxc3  dxe4  11.Qxb7  O-O  - Bacrot-Khenkin, Eppingen 2008  7.Bxc4  e6  8.Nc3  Nbd7  9.Qc2   9.Bd3  +=  9...Nb6  10.Be2  Bd6 =  Grachev-Bryzgalin, Ulan Ude 2009. }
6. Nc3
{ I think that it is even better to play   6.Qb3  right away, and now:  Bxf3  7.gxf3  Qb6   7...Nh5  8.Bg3  Qb6  9.Nc3   9.cxd5  Qxb3  10.axb3  cxd5  11.Nc3  e6  12.Nb5  +=  9...e6  10.Qc2  Qa5   10...Be7  11.Be2  g6  12.f4  Ng7  13.O-O-O  Nf5 =  Mirzoev-Sengupta, Calvi 2010  11.a3  dxc4  12.Bxc4  +=  Bagheri-Phtz, Belgium tt 2003/04  8.Nd2  Nh5  9.Bg3  e6  10.c5  Qxb3  11.Nxb3 =  Tu Hoang-Varga, Elista 1998  White has also played   6.Nbd2  Nh5  7.Bg5   7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Nxf4  9.Qxf4 =   7.Be5 !?  7...h6  8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  e6 =  Gomez-Magem, Linares 1995 }
6... e6 7. Qb3
{ 7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.Nxd5  exd5  9.Bd3  Bb4+  10.Kf1  Qe7 =  Ye-Liang, Beijing 2005. }
7... dxc4
{ This capture is a clear mistake: allowing White to capture on b7 is usually bad for Black in the London System and this is no exception. We do not know if Kramnik had prepared this or decided to improvise, but it did not turn out well for him in such an important game.  In this position Black has also played   7...Bxf3  8.gxf3  Qb6   8...Qc8  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  exd5  11.Bh3  +=  Crouch-Baburin, Birmingham 2001  or   8...Nh5  9.Bg3  Nxg3  10.hxg3  Rb8  +=  Wirthensohn-Cherniaev, Scuol 2001  9.c5  Qxb3  10.axb3  a6   10...Nh5  11.Bg3  a6  12.b4  Rc8  13.Bd3   13.f4  Nxg3  14.hxg3  g6  15.Bd3  Bg7  16.g4  +=  Torre-Supriyono, Jakarta 2012  13...g6  14.Ne2  f6  +=  Hulak-Wessman, Novi Sad 1990  11.b4  Rc8  12.Bg3  g6 =  13.Na2  Nh5  14.Nc1  Nxg3  15.hxg3  e5  16.Nb3  Bg7  17.Kd2  h5  18.Bd3  f5  19.f4  exd4  20.Nxd4  Kf7  21.f3  Rce8  22.Rhg1  Rxe3  23.Kxe3  Re8+  24.Kd2  Bxd4  25.Rge1  Rxe1  26.Rxe1  Bf2  27.Ra1  Bxg3  28.Ke3  h4  29.b5  axb5  30.b4  h3  31.Bf1  h2  32.Bg2  Ke7  33.Ra7  Be1  34.Rxb7  Bxb4  35.Kf2  Bxc5+  36.Kg3  Bg1  37.Kh4  Eljanov,P  (2716)  -Najer,E  (2663)  Netanya 2009 0-1  If   7...b6 ?  8.cxd5  Nxd5  9.Nxd5  cxd5  10.Ba6  Hirscher-Welsch, Koblenz 2003   7...Qb6  reaches the lines in the note to move 5e6. Now:  8.h3   8.Nd2  Bf5  9.h3   9.c5  +=  9...Qxb3  10.axb3 =  Pham-D.Nguyen, Ho Chi Minh City 2013;   8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  +=  8...Bxf3  9.gxf3  Qxb3  10.axb3  Bb4 = }
8. Qxb7 Bxf3 9. gxf3 Nd5
{ It appears that Blacks idea was to continue with   10...Bb4  but White responds with  11.Bxc4  ±  when  Nxc3  loses to   11...Bxc3+  12.bxc3  Nxc3  13.Bc7  Qc8  14.Ba6  12.Qxb4  +- }
10. Bg3 N5b6 11. Qxc6 Bb4 12. Qb5 Qe7 13. a3 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 O-O 15. Bxc4
{ Karjakin takes the second pawn. It was also possible to play   15.a4  a5  16.Be2  f5   16...Nd5  17.Kd2  ±  17.Rg1  ± }
15... Nxc4 16. Qxc4 Rac8 17. Qd3 Nb6 18. O-O Rc4 19. Rfb1 Rfc8 20. Rb3 h5 21.
e4 Qg5 22. h4 Qa5 23. Rc1 Qa4 24. Qb1 Nd7 25. Kg2 Nf8 26. Qb2 Qe8 27. Rb7
{ 12.Rc1  ±  was also possible. } 27... a6 28. Qb6 Ng6 29. Qxa6 Qd8
{ White has an extra pawn and can capture a second; his advantage is clear. }
30. Qb5 e5 { White could also play   31.dxe5  Nxh4+  32.Bxh4  Qxh4  33.e6 } 31.
Rh1 Rxc3 32. dxe5 Nf8 33. Qd5 Qe8 34. Ra1 Ne6 35. Qd7
{ White exchanges the queens and simplifies the position to reach a winning endgame. }
35... Qf8 36. Qe7 Qxe7 37. Rxe7 Nd4 38. a4 Nxf3 39. e6 fxe6 40. Rxe6 Nd4 41.
Re5 Ne2 42. Rxh5 Nxg3 43. fxg3 Re3 44. a5 Rxe4
{ Black is trying to blockade the pawns on the light squares and put pressure on c3 with his knight and his rooks, while the bishop on g3 is taking little part in the game. But two pawns is a lot of material and I do not think that Black's compensation is sufficient. }
45. a6 Re7 46. Rb5 Kh7 47. Kh3 { Another option was   21.h4  ± } 47... Ra8 48.
Rb6 Raa7 49. Ra5
{ It was possible to defend the pawn indirectly with   23.Kg2 !  Qa4   23...Rxc3 ?  24.Qd2  24.Rab1  Qc6  25.Bf4  f6   25...Rxc3  26.Rxc3  Qxc3  27.Qa6  26.Bd2  ± }
49... Re3 50. h5 Rd3 51. Kh4 Rd4+ 52. g4 Re4
{ This plan is bad. The knight was very well placed on b6, blocking the b-file and controlling c4 and a4. It was better to move it back there, although after   25...Nb6  White would still maintain a clear advantage. }
53. Kg5 Rf7 { here   26.d5  exd5  27.exd5  Qa6  28.d6  was also strong. } 54.
Rg6 { If   26...Rxd4  then  27.cxd4  Rxc1  28.Qxc1  Qxb3  29.Qc8  Qb6  30.d5 }
54... Ra7 55. Kh4 Rb4 { A third pawn falls. Whites advantage is decisive. } 56.
Rc6 Re4 57. Rb6 Re1 58. Ra4 Re3 59. g5 Ree7 60. Rb8 g6 61. Rb6 gxh5 62. Rab4
Re1 63. Rb7+ Kg6
{ Equivalent to resignation. But if   63...Rxb7  64.axb7  wins. } 64. R4b6+
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw Black's plan of c7-c6, typical of the Slav, but with Bg4 instead of Bf5. Kramnik had played 4... Qb6 previously against Kamsky, but this time he preferred to play something different.  White played in a similar way to the typical plan against the Slav with c2-c4, Nc3 and Qb3; the main difference is that Black is able to exchange on f3 and leave White with a less mobile pawn structure.  In the game Black went wrong with the move 7... dxc4, which left him with a clear disadvantage after 8. Qxb7. It is not usually good for Black to allow White to capture on b7 and this game was no exception.  White emerged with two extra pawns and although Black had some compensation, this was not sufficient. }
*

