[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 { 1...Nf6 } 2. Bf4
{ 2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bf4  a6   3...Bf5   3...c5   2.Nf3  Nf6   2...c5  3.c3 } 2...
Nf6 { 2...c5  3.e4   3.e3 } 3. e3 c5 { 3...Nc6 } 4. c3 Nc6 { 4...Qb6 } 5. Nd2
Qb6 { 5...Bf5   5...cxd4 } 6. Qb3 c4 { 6...Bf5 } 7. Qc2 { 7.Qxb6 } 7... Bg4
{ In this chapter we shall look at: the various systems for Black with 1d5, but without an early e7-e6; the lines with c7-c5, in the style of the Tarrasch Defence, and once again the idea of Qb6, putting pressure on b2, which is one of Black's most popular systems; the Chigorin set-up with Nc6.  As well as looking at ways to combat all these lines, we shall cover some other interesting ideas for White: the Morris Gambit 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e4 !? and a new idea, the Jobava Attack, 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. Nc3 !?, brought into fashion by the strong grandmaster of that name; this line is a cross between the London System and the Richter-Veresov Attack.  It also involves an interesting idea to avoid Black's plan of Qb6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
