[White "Vs ...d5 without early ...e6"]
[Black "Game 43 - Winants vs. Korneev"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e4
{ The Morris Gambit is a sort of Albin Counter-gambit with reversed colours and an extra tempo, since White has already developed the bishop on f4. The Belgian grandmaster Luc Winants is its main exponent. The normal line is 3. e3, which we shall see in the next game.   3.Bxb8 ?!  Rxb8  4.dxc5  e6  5.Qd4  Ne7  6.e3  Bd7   6...Nc6  =+  7.c4  Nc6  =+  Stefanova-Skripchenko, Shenyang 2000  The alternative is   3.Nc3  with several replies that we shall now examine. We shall leave 3Nf6 until later, when we consider the Jobava Attack.  Nc6   3...e6  4.e4  +=  Pri-Doluhanova, Montpellier 2013;   3...cxd4  4.Qxd4  e6  5.e4  Nc6 =  4.e3   4.e4  transposes to the Morris Gambit with the line 3Nc6  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Bf5  6.Bd3  Bxd3  7.Qxd3  e6  8.Nf3  Bd6  9.Ne2   9.Bxd6  Qxd6  10.O-O  Nge7  11.Rfe1  O-O  Knezevic-Sveshnikov, Anapa 1991  9...Nge7  10.c3  Ng6  11.Bg3  Bxg3  12.hxg3  Qd6 =  Miladinovic-Ratkovic, Vrnjacka Banja 2013; }
3... dxe4
{ It is often said that the best way to refute a gambit is to accept it, although we know that often that is not the case. In this position there are several alternatives, and although capturing was always the main move, nowadays there are other lines that are more unpleasant for White. Let us see:   3...Nf6 !?  4.e5  Nfd7  5.Bd3 ?!   5.c3  Nc6   5.c4  e6  6.Nf3  Nc6 =  5...e6   5...Qb6 !  =+  6.c3  Nc6  7.Nf3  Be7  8.O-O =  Dickson-Wagner, England 4NCL 2011.   3...Nc6 !  is very interesting. This idea involves an exchange sacrifice, but Black obtains very good compensation and scores very well. Let us examine White's options here:  4.Nc3   4.exd5  Here  Qxd5  5.Nc3  is considered best, and now:  Qf5 ?!   5...Qe6+ ?!  6.Nge2  Nxd4  7.Be3   7.Qd2  ±  7...a6   7...Nxe2  8.Bxe2  Bd7  9.Bxc5  ±  8.Nxd4  cxd4  9.Qxd4  ±  Romero-Fernandez, Barcelona 2015;   5...Qxd4 !  6.Nd5  and now:  Bd7   6...e5  7.Nc7+  Kd8  8.Nxa8  exf4  9.Nf3   9.Ne2 ?!  Qd6  with a slight advantage to Black, Winants-Adly, Turin ol 2006  9...Qxd1+  10.Rxd1+  Bd7  11.Bb5   11.Bc4  Nh6  12.O-O  Kc8  13.Rfe1 =  Klaric-Sermek, Makarska Tucepi 1995  11...Kc8  12.O-O  f6   12...Nge7 ?!  13.Ng5  Be6 ?   13...Be8  +=  14.Rfe1  ±  Bestard-Argandoa, Gijon 2011  13.a4   13.Rfe1 =  13...Be7  14.Rfe1  Bg4 =  Winants-Michalczak, Dresden 2007.  7.Nc7+  Kd8  8.Qxd4  Nxd4  9.c3   9.Nxa8  Nxc2+  10.Kd2  Nxa1  11.Bd3  g6 =  9...Nc2+  10.Kd2  Nxa1  11.Nxa8  g6 =  6.Be3   6.Bg3  +=  6...cxd4  7.Nb5  Bd7  8.Nxd4  Nxd4  9.Qxd4 =  Winants-Van der Werf, Netherlands tt 2006.  4...cxd4  5.exd5  dxc3  6.dxc6  Qxd1+   6...Qa5 ?  7.b4  ±  7.Rxd1  bxc6  and now:  8.Bc7   8.bxc3  f6  9.Bc7  Bf5  10.Ba6  Kf7  11.Bb7  Re8 =  Reddmann-Svane, Hamburg 2012;  8...Bg4   8...e6 ! =  9.f3  Rc8 ?!   9...Bd7 =  10.Ba5  +=  Hoffmeyer-Hoffmann, Germany tt 2011; }
4. d5 Nf6
{ Another possible scheme is   4...g6  5.Nc3  Bg7  6.Qd2   6.Nxe4  Bxb2  7.Rb1  Bg7  8.Nf3  ∞  6...Nf6  7.O-O-O  O-O  ∞  Winants-Okkes, Netherlands tt 2006/07   4...Qb6  5.Nc3  Qxb2 ?   5...Nf6  6.Qd2  Bd7  7.O-O-O  +=  Steiner-Hatzl, Kflach 2006  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Bd2  ±  Qb4  8.Rb1  Qa5  9.Bxd7+ ?   9.Nxe4  ±  9...Nxd7  10.Rxb7  Qa6 =  Lobron-Nadanian, St Vincent 2000. }
5. Nc3 a6
{ 5...g6  6.Nb5   6.Qd2  Bg7  7.Bh6   7.O-O-O  O-O  7...O-O  8.Bxg7  Kxg7  9.Nge2  Na6  10.O-O-O  Bg4  11.h3  Bxe2  12.Bxe2  Qa5  =+  Sirnik,B-Susnik,M/ Ljubljana 1998  6...Na6  7.d6  Bg4  8.f3  exf3  9.gxf3  Bf5  10.Qd2  =∞  Toupalik, B-Spielmann, R/Prague 1912   5...e6  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.dxe6  fxe6  with compensation. }
6. Qe2
{ A typical position in this gambit. White is attacking e4 and plans queenside castling.   6.a4  e6   6...g6  7.Bc4  Nbd7  8.Nge2  Nb6  9.Ba2  Bd7  10.a5  Nc8  11.Be5  Bg7  12.O-O  Nd6  13.Ng3  O-O  ∞  Daly,H-Bernstein,N/Omaha 1949  7.Bc4  exd5  8.Bxd5  Be7  9.Bxe4  Qxd1+  10.Rxd1  Nxe4  11.Nxe4  O-O  12.Ne2  Nc6  13.O-O  1/2-1/2 Vidmar, M-Perlis, J/St Petersburg 1909  Also interesting are   6.f3 !?  exf3  7.Nxf3  e6  8.dxe6  Qxd1+  9.Rxd1  Bxe6  with a slight advantage to Black  or   6.Nge2  Nbd7  7.Ng3  Nb6  8.Ngxe4 = }
6... Bf5
{ 6...e6  7.O-O-O  Qa5  8.d6  Nc6  9.Kb1  e5  10.Bd2  Nd4  11.Qe1  Qb6  12.Bg5  Be6  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.Nxe4  O-O-O  =+  Winants, L-Tregubov,P/Warsaw 2005  Other options are, returning the pawn with:   6...g6  7.Nxe4  Nxe4  8.Qxe4  Bg7  9.O-O-O  O-O  10.Ne2   10.Bc4 ?!  Bf5  11.Qf3  b5  12.Bf1  Qa5  =+  McShane-Illescas, Gothenburg 2005   10.Qe3  Qa5  11.Kb1  Bf5  12.Bh6  ∞  Berkes-Prohaszka, Zalakaros 2015   10.Nf3  Bf5  11.Qe3  ∞  10...Nd7  11.Qe3  Nf6  12.Nc3   12.Qxc5  Bf5  =+  Bauner-Lederman, Plovdiv 2013  12...b5  13.Qxc5  Bf5  14.Qb4 =  Elianov-Ponomariov, Kharkiv 2008   6...Nbd7  7.O-O-O  g6  8.Nxe4  Nxe4  9.Qxe4  Bg7  10.d6  +=   6...Bg4  7.f3  exf3  8.Nxf3   8.gxf3  Bf5  9.O-O-O  g6  10.Qe3  Nbd7  11.Nge2 =  Danielian-Krivec, Athens 2006  8...g6  9.O-O-O  Bg7  10.h3  Bxf3  11.Qxf3  O-O   11...Nbd7  12.d6  ∞  Pri-Dumitrache, Condom 2012  12.g4  ∞  Grachev-E.Sveshnikov, Jurmala 2012. }
7. O-O-O Nbd7 8. h3 Qb6
{ This move is inferior.  I do not like   8...Qa5 ?!  9.g4  Bg6  10.Kb1  either.  It seems best for Black to play   8...b5  +=2  !?  9.g4  b4  10.Nb1   10.Na4  Bg6  11.Kb1  with a balanced position.  10...e5  11.Bg3  Bg6  12.Bg2  c4  =+ }
9. g4 Bg6 10. f3
{ White gives up trying to regain the pawn and instead opens lines, since he has a lead in development, which not only compensates for the pawn but even grants him some advantage. }
10... e5
{ Black declines the material.  The problem for Black after   10...exf3  11.Nxf3  is his lack of kingside development, while if  O-O-O  12.Bg2   12.Nh4  Ne8  13.Kb1  Nd6  14.Qf3  White maintains excellent compensation. Black has development problems.  12...e6  13.dxe6  Qxe6  14.Qxe6  fxe6  15.Rhe1  += }
11. dxe6 fxe6
{ Another mistake after which there is no way back.   11...Qxe6 !  12.h4  exf3   12...h6  13.Bh3  +-  13.Qxf3  Qxg4  14.Re1+  Kd8   14...Be7  15.Qxg4  Nxg4  16.Nd5  +-  15.Qf2  is better for White. Blacks king is stuck in the centre and will not be able to survive. }
12. fxe4 e5
{ This move weakens the d5-square and delays his development.  It was better to complete development with   12...Be7  13.Nf3  O-O  14.Bg2  although White maintains an appreciable advantage. }
13. Bh2 O-O-O 14. Nf3 Qe6 15. Nh4 Bf7 16. Bg2 c4
{ Black wants to liberate his f8-bishop and free the c5-square, but this move also closes the a2-g8 diagonal. White has a clear advantage in space.   16...g6  +=2  17.g5  Nh5  18.Nd5  Nf4   18...h6  19.Qd2  hxg5  20.Nf3  ±  19.Qf3  Nxg2  20.Nxg2  h6  21.Rhf1  Rh7  22.Nge3  hxg5  23.Ng4  Bd6  += }
17. Kb1 Bc5 18. Nf5 g6 19. Nh6 Be8 { 19...Rhf8 !?  20.Rhf1  Ne8  21.Nd5  ± }
20. Nd5
{ Whites advantage is decisive; he is threatening the pawn on c4 and the black pieces remain passive. }
20... b5 21. Rhf1 Ng8 { 21...Bf8  22.g5  Bxh6  23.gxf6  Kb7  24.Qe1 !  ± } 22.
Nxg8 Rxg8 23. g5
{ Whites plan is Bg2-f3-g4 and Black has no defence against this. } 23... Rf8
{ 23...Bf7  24.Bf3  Qc6  25.Bg4  Be6  26.Bg1  Kb8  27.Bxc5  Bxg4  28.Qxg4  Qxc5  29.Qe6  +- }
24. Bf3 Bf7
{ A blunder which hastens his defeat, but even after the best move   24...Qd6  White still retains a decisive advantage with  25.Bg4  Rxf1  26.Rxf1  Kb7  27.Qe1 }
25. Bg4 Qc6 26. Rf6
{ The game is decided: White has a strong attack and is winning material. }
26... Qb7 27. Bxe5 Bxd5 28. Rxd5 Rfe8
{ A blunder in a position that was desperate in any case.   28...Be7  29.Qe3   29.Qf2 !  Bxf6 ?  30.Qc5+  mating  29...Bxf6  30.Qc5+  +-   28...Rxf6  29.Bxf6  and Black loses a lot of material. }
29. Rxc5+
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the so-called Morris Gambit with 3. e4, which is an interesting alternative to 3. e3. GM Winants has frequently played it.  The idea of the gambit is a sort of Albin with an extra tempo. White wants to castle queenside quickly and benefit from his lead in development. For Black I think that it is best not to take the pawn. The line 3... Nc6 seems best at the moment. Once Black has accepted the pawn it is best to return it with g7-g6 rather than defend it with Bf5.  In the game we saw how White gained a clear advantage thanks to his better development and he won without any problems. White scores very well in the games where Black hangs on to the pawn . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs ...d5 without early ...e6"]
[Black "Game 44 - Sedlak vs. Mihok"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6
{ If   3...Qb6 ?!  then  4.Nc3 !  e6   4...Qxb2  5.Nxd5  5.Nb5 !  +=  If   3...Bf5  then  4.Bb5+  Nc6  5.Nf3  +=  while if   3...cxd4  then  4.exd4  takes us into the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann. }
4. c3
{ An alternative is   4.Nf3  Bg4 !?   4...Nf6  is the normal line  5.c3  e6  6.Qb3   6.h3  6...Qc8   6...Qd7 =  7.Nbd2  Nf6 =  Kramnik-Gelfand, Moscow 2007;   4.Nc3  is possible and similar to the line which we shall see with Nf6. }
4... Qb6
{ Instead,   4...Nf6  would lead to the normal lines of the London System.  An alternative is   4...Bf5 !?  5.Nd2   5.Qb3  Qd7  6.Nd2  c4 =  5...e6   5...Qb6  6.Qb3  c4 ?  7.Qxb6  axb6  8.e4  ±  6.Ngf3  Nf6   6...Bd6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Nd4  +=  and now:  7.Qa4   7.Be2  Be7  8.h3  h6  9.O-O  O-O  10.Ne5  Nxe5  11.Bxe5  Nd7  12.Bg3 =  Klimenko-Solodovnichenko, Russia Internet 2004;   7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Bb5  a6  9.h3  Be7  10.O-O  O-O =  Pri-Gomez, San Sebastian 2008.  7...Nd7  8.Bb5  Qc8  9.Ne5 ?!   9.Nh4  9...Ncxe5  10.Bxe5  a6  11.Bxd7+  Qxd7  12.Qxd7+  Kxd7 =  Sedlak-Korneev, Istanbul 2012;  In the event of   4...cxd4  White can choose between transposing to the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann with  5.exd4  or to the Exchange Variation of the Slav with   5.cxd4  Bf5  which we covered in the chapter on the Benoni.  5...Bf5  6.Nf3   6.Qb3  Qd7  7.Nf3  a6  8.Nbd2  e6  9.h3  h6  10.Be2  Nf6 =  Morozevich-Anand, Monaco  (blindfold)  2003  6...e6  7.Qb3  Qd7  8.Nbd2  Nge7  9.h3  h6 =  Pri-Vaisser, Caen 2011 }
5. Qb3 c4 6. Qc2 Bf5
{ This idea works in some other variations, when the black knight is already on f6, but here it is dubious because White can sacrifice the exchange for a pawn and incarcerate the black queen.   6...Nf6  would be the normal line, and we shall see this in the next game;  another option is   6...e5 !?  7.dxe5  Bf5  8.Qc1  Nge7  9.Nf3  Ng6  10.Bg3  Bc5  11.Be2   11.Nd4  11...O-O  +=  Basha-Gibbons, Antalya 2007  Finally, we shall consider   6...g6  7.Nd2  Nf6  8.e4  in the variation with Nf6. }
7. Qxf5 Qxb2 8. Qxd5 Qxa1
{ 8...Qc1+  is no better:  9.Ke2  Qb2+  10.Kf3   10.Nd2 !  Qxa1  11.Qb5  O-O-O  12.g3  ±  10...Nf6  11.Qxc4  Qxa1  12.Qb3  O-O-O  13.Bb5  Na5  14.Qc2  a6  15.Bd3  Nd5   15...e5 ?  16.Bxe5  Nd7  17.Bf4  Be7  18.Nh3  g5  19.Nxg5  1-0 Miles-Minasian, Ohrid 2001  16.Ne2  Nxf4  17.exf4  Rd6  18.Qa4  Nc6  19.Qb3  +-  Curien-Georgiadis, Switzerland tt 2013  Black is also worse after   8...Nf6  9.Qxc4  Ne4   9...O-O-O  10.Qb3  Qxa1  11.Bb5  Na5  12.Qc2  Ne8  13.Nf3  Nd6  14.Bxd6  Rxd6  15.O-O  a6  16.Na3  1-0 Bauer-Reuss,Schwbisch Gmnd 2012  10.Qb5 !  Qxf2+   10...Qc1+  11.Ke2  Qc2+  12.Kf3  +-  Bogosavljevic-Miladinovic, Vrsac 2007   10...Qxa1  11.Qxb7  +-  11.Kd1  a6  12.Qe2  e5  13.Bg3  +-  Sedlak-Czebe, Subotica 2005  If   8...e6  then  9.Qxc4  Qxa1   9...Qc1+  10.Ke2  Qb2+  11.Nd2  ±  10.Qb3  is much better for White. }
9. Qb5 O-O-O
{ The alternative is   9...a6  10.Qxb7  Nd8  and now  11.Qe4 !  is the right move, with advantage to White  but not   11.Qb4 ??  Rc8 ?   11...e5  -+  12.Nf3 ?  Qxa2  -+  Bistric-Sveshnikov, Bled 1991  or   11.Qxa8  Qxb1+  12.Ke2  e5  13.Bxe5  Qd3+  14.Kf3  Qxf1  15.Bc7  Be7  16.Bxd8  Bxd8  17.Qc6+  with perpetual check, - Kristjansson-E. Sveshnikov, Marianske Lazne 2008. }
10. Qf5+
{ White's idea is to trap the black queen.  The best and most popular move is   10.Bxc4 !  which gives White the advantage. Here are a few examples:  e6   10...e5  is Blacks only chance; now:  11.Bg5 ??   11.Ne2  and now :  Bd6   11...Ba3  12.O-O   12.Bg3  ±  12...Qb2  13.Nxa3   13.Qa4  +-  13...Qxb5  14.Nxb5  exf4  15.Nxf4  ±  Unuk-Sirnik, Sentjur 2013   11...exf4  12.O-O  a6   12...fxe3 ?  13.fxe3  Nf6   13...Nge7 ?  14.Nd2  +-  Hamark-Bellon, Stockholm 2007  14.Nd2  +-  Grachev-Gelfand, Moscow 2008  13.Qb6  Bd6  14.Nd2  Bc7  15.Qb3  Na5  16.Qc2   16.Qb4  Nc6  17.Qa3  ±  16...Qxf1+  17.Kxf1  ±  Cramling-Zatonskih, Beijing 2012  12.O-O  a6  13.Qb3  Na5   13...exf4  14.Nd2  Na5  15.Qc2  Qxf1+  16.Kxf1  ±  14.Be6+ ?!   14.Qa4  +-  14...fxe6  15.Qxe6+  ±  Van der Werf-Krudde, Netherlands tt 2006/07;   11.Bxe5 !  Bb4   11...Nb4 !  12.Bd3  Nxd3+  13.Qxd3  Qxa2  14.Nf3  Qa6  15.Qf5+  Rd7  16.Bg3  +=  12.Bd3  Bxc3+  13.Kf1  Nge7  14.Bxg7  Rhe8  15.Qb3  Nd5  16.Ne2  +-  Hoang Thanh Trang-Das Sayantan, Mumbai 2012  11...f6 ?   11...Bb4 !  -+  12.Ne2  Ba3  13.O-O  +=  Grachev-Ponomariov, Moscow 2008  11.Ne2  Ba3  12.O-O  +-  Qb2  13.Nxa3  Qxa3  14.Rb1  Qe7  15.Qa4   15.e4  Nf6  16.d5  exd5  17.exd5  Nxd5  18.Bxd5  Knig-Vaysberg, Leinzell 2011  15...Qd7  16.Ba6 !  e5  17.Rxb7  Qxb7  18.Qxc6+  1-0 Hamblok-Maddens, Ghent 2013 }
10... e6 11. Qc2 g5
{ An earlier game had continued   11...Na5  12.Nf3  Rd5  13.Be2  Rb5  14.O-O  ±  Ortega-Mazzilli, Palermo 2007.  Black's best line seems to be   11...b5  12.Nf3  Nf6  13.Be2  Nd5  14.O-O  += }
12. Bg3 Na5
{ If   12...h5  then after  13.Nf3  h4  14.Be5  f6  15.Bxc4 !  fxe5  16.O-O  exd4  17.exd4  Black has to sacrifice material to rescue the queen, or be worse in the ending of queen against two rooks. }
13. Nf3 Rd5 14. Be2 Rb5 15. O-O
{ White has completed development and is only the exchange down; in return he has an attack and threats against the black queen. }
15... Nf6 { 15...Qb2  16.Qa4  Be7  17.Nbd2  a6  18.Bxc4  +- } 16. Qa4 Rxb1
{ 16...a6  17.Be5  Be7  18.Bxc4  +- } 17. Qxa5
{ White now has a decisive attack on the black king. } 17... Nd5 18. Qxa7 f6
{ 18...Bg7  changes nothing: White wins with  19.Qb8+  Kd7  20.Qd6+  Ke8  21.Nxg5 }
19. Nd2 Rxf1+ 20. Nxf1 Qxc3 21. Qb8+ Kd7 22. Qxb7+ Kd8 23. Qb8+ Kd7
{ White's attack is decisive, but how should he continue now ? } 24. Bh5
{ Correct ! The bishop threatens a check on e8, followed by mate. } 24... e5
{ This allows mate, but   24...Be7  25.Qxh8  was equally hopeless. } 25. Bg4+
{ Even stronger was   25.Qb7+  Nc7  26.Bg4+  Ke8  27.Qxc7 } 25... Kc6 26. Qa8+
Kd6 27. Qd8+ { 27.Qc8  was mate in four. } 27... Kc6 28. Bd7+ Kd6
{ This allows mate in two, but he would also have lost after   28...Kb7  29.Bc8+  Kb8  30.Be6+  Ka7  31.Bxd5 }
29. Be8+
{ If 29... Ke6 then 30. Qd7 is mate.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the normal line with e2-e3 and a very common variation with Qb6, where Black used the move Bf5, which works in other variations, but not without Black's knight being on f6.  Here White is able to sacrifice the exchange and keep the advantage. Black has problems with his queen, which often remains trapped, or else he has to return some material to save it.  I think that this line is dubious for Black. In the game White gained a decisive attack against the black king. }
*

