{ Hamblok-Maddens, Ghent 2013 } 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. c3 Qb6
{ Again a common idea, trying to punish White's set-up by putting pressure on b2. }
5. Qb3 c4 6. Qc2 Bf5
{ This idea works in some other variations, when the black knight is already on f6, but here it is dubious because White can sacrifice the exchange for a pawn and incarcerate the black queen. }
7. Qxf5 Qxb2 8. Qxd5 Qxa1 9. Qb5 O-O-O { The best and most popular move is }
10. Bxc4 { which gives White the advantage. Here are a few examples: } 10... e6
11. Ne2 Ba3 12. O-O Qb2 13. Nxa3 Qxa3 14. Rb1 Qe7 15. Qa4 Qd7 16. Ba6 e5 17.
