1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6
{ The alternative is   4...Qb6  and now:  5.Qc2   5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2   6.Qxb6  axb6  7.Nd2   7.Na3  Bd7  8.Nf3  e5  9.Bxe5  Bxa3  10.bxa3  Nc6  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.O-O-O  Rxa3  13.Kb2  Ra4 =  7...b5  8.a3  Bf5 =  Welling-Volkov, Oslo 2011  6...g6  7.Nd2   7.b3  Bf5  8.Qd1 =  7...Bf5  8.Qc1  Nc6  9.h3 =  Jovanic-Unuk, Opatija 2014  5...g6   5...Nc6  6.Nd2  g6  7.Ngf3  Bg7   7...Bf5  8.dxc5  Qxc5  9.Qb3  +=  8.h3  O-O  E. Alvarez-Johannessen, Oporto 2012  6.Nd2  Bf5  7.dxc5  Qxc5  8.Qb3  +=  Nguyen-Roque Ho Chi Minh City 2011; }
5. Nd2
{ Or   5.Qb3 !?  c4  6.Qc2  g6  7.b3  Bf5  8.Qb2  Qb6 =  Pri-Perez Candelario, Elgoibar 2006 }
5... Qb6
{ Again this thematic idea.  Black can also play   5...Bf5  and now:  6.Qb3   6.Ngf3  Qb6  and now:  7.Nh4  the favourite move of GM Sedlak   7.Qb3  c4  8.Qxb6  axb6  9.a3   9.Nh4 =  9...b5  10.Rc1  h6  11.h3  Nd7  12.Be2  g5  13.Bh2  Bg7 =  E.Alvarez-Moskalenko, Palma de Mallorca 2010   7.Qc1  e6  8.Be2  Be7  9.a3  O-O  10.O-O  Rac8  11.dxc5 =  Kamsky-Gulko, New York 2006;   7.dxc5  Qxb2   7...Qxc5 ?!  8.Nb3  +=  Curien-Sedina, Switzerland tt 2013  8.Nd4  e5  9.Bxe5  Bg4  10.Rb1  Qa3  11.f3  Nxe5  12.fxg4  Bxc5  ∞  Pri-Flear, San Sebastian 2011.  7...Bd7  8.Qb3  c4  9.Qc2   9.Qxb6 =  9...Nh5  10.Bg3  and now :  g6   10...e6  11.Be2  Nxg3  12.hxg3  Qc7  13.e4  O-O-O  14.Nhf3 =  Elianov-Ponomariov, Moscow 2010;  11.e4  e6  12.Be2  Nxg3  13.hxg3  Qc7  14.Nf1  Ne7  15.Ne3   15.e5  Nc6  16.Ne3  Be7  17.f4  b5  18.Nf3  b4  19.g4  Qa5  20.Kf2  Rb8  21.g5 =  Sedlak-Borisek, Istanbul 2012;  15...b5  16.Nf3  Bg7  17.a3   17.e5  a5  18.a3  Rb8  19.Ng4  Qd8  20.Qd2 =  Sedlak-Svetushkin, Vrsac 2012  17...h5  18.e5  Nc6  19.g4  hxg4  20.Rxh8+  Bxh8  21.Nxg4  +=  Sedlak-Schnider, Lienz 2013  6...Qc8   6...Qd7  and now :  7.dxc5   7.Ngf3  c4  8.Qd1   8.Qb5 !?  e6  9.b3  a6   9...cxb3  10.axb3 =  Nguyen Thi-Bagi, Budapest 2010  10.Qb6  cxb3  11.axb3  Be7  12.b4  Rc8  13.b5 =  De Prado-Andres, Bembibre 2014  8...e6  9.Be2   9.Nh4 =  9...h6   9...b5  10.O-O  Bd6  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.Nh4  Bg6  13.b3  Ne4 =  Berkes-Robson, Paks 2010   9...Be7  10.Ne5  Nxe5  11.Bxe5  O-O  12.g4  Bg6  13.h4  with an initiative to White, Berkes-Shulman, Dresden 2008  10.O-O  Be7  11.Ne5  Nxe5  12.Bxe5  O-O =  Kamsky-Potkin, Khanty-Mansiysk Wch rapid 2013  7...e5  8.Bg3  Bxc5  9.Ngf3  Qe7  10.Bb5  d4   10...Bd6  11.c4  a6  12.cxd5  axb5  13.dxc6  bxc6 =  Perunovic-Hristodoulou, Bansko 2010  11.O-O   11.Bxc6+  bxc6  12.Qa4 =  11...dxe3  12.fxe3  Bxe3+  13.Kh1  ∞  Bogosavljevic-Atalik, Paracin 2012;  7.dxc5   7.c4  e6   7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  e6  9.Rc1   9.Ngf3 =  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Qd7  11.Bb5  Be7  12.Ngf3  O-O =  De Prado-Rey, Ferrol 2013  8.dxc5   8.Ngf3 =  8...Bxc5  9.Rc1 ?   9.Ngf3 =  9...d4  =+  Nguyen Thi-Lu, Ho Chi Minh City 2011  7...e5  8.Bg5   8.Bg3  Bxc5  9.Ngf3  Bd6 =  Stefanova-Munguntuul, Doha 2011  8...Nd7   8...Be6  9.Bxf6  gxf6  Ponomariov-Gelfand, Moscow 2010  9.Qxd5  Nxc5  ∞  Sedlak-Todorovic, Belgrade 2009  Another variation is   5...cxd4  6.exd4  (we have now transposed to the Caro-Kann Exchange Variation)  Bf5   6...g6  7.Be2  Bg7  8.h3 =  Popovic-Ivanisevic, Serbia tt 2007  7.Qb3  and now Black can defend b7 in two ways:  Qd7   7...Qc8  8.Ngf3  e6  9.Nh4  the alternative is   9.Be2  Be7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Nh4   11.Rfe1  a6  12.a4 ?!  Ne4 =  Ringoir-Palac, Troms 2014  11...Bg4  12.f3  Bh5  13.g4  Bg6  14.Bg3  Qd7  15.Rae1 =  Rapport-Korpa, Zalakaros 2014  9...Be4   9...Bg6  10.Nxg6  hxg6 =  Kamsky-Macieja, Achaea 2012  10.Nxe4  dxe4   10...Nxe4  11.Nf3  Bd6  12.Bxd6  Nxd6 =  Sandipan-Kasimdzhanov, Dubai 2014  11.g3   11.f3 !?  11...Be7  12.Ng2  Nd5   12...O-O  13.Be2  Nd5  14.Bd2 =  Sedlak-Ragger, Achaea 2012  13.Bd2  O-O  14.Nf4  Nf6 =  Sandipan-Prasad, Benasque 2014.  8.Ngf3   8.Be2  8...a6  9.Be2   9.Nh4 !?  9...e6  10.h3   10.O-O  Be7  11.Ne5 =  Berkes-Mihok, Mako 2013   10.Nh4   10.Ne5  10...Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Nh4 =  De Prado-Medarde, A Corua 2013; }
6. Qb3 c4
{ If   6...Qxb3  7.axb3  cxd4  8.exd4  +=  The main alternative is   6...Bf5  7.dxc5  Qxb3  8.axb3  e5  9.Bg3  Bxc5  and now:  10.Bb5 !?   10.b4  Bd6  11.b5  Ne7  12.Ngf3  Nd7   12...Ng6  13.h3  O-O  14.Be2  +=  Sean-Nguyen,Kuala Lumpur 2012  13.Nd4  Bg6  14.Be2  O-O =  Sergeev-Cernousek, Rakovnik 2008;   10.Ngf3 !  e4   10...Bd6  11.Bb5  +=   10...d4 ?!  11.b4  dxe3  12.fxe3  Bb6   12...Bxe3  13.Nc4  +-  13.Nc4   13.b5  Ne7  14.Bxe5  +=  13...O-O  14.b5  Ne7  15.Bxe5  +=  Kovacevic-Garcia, Mislata 1993   10...Nd7  11.b4  Bd6  and again there are several options for White:  12.Nd4   12.Be2  f6   12...O-O  13.Nb3  Rfe8  14.O-O =  Kovacevic-Garcia, La Pobla de Lillet 1998  13.O-O  +=  Ipatov-Silva, Barcelona 2011;   12.Bb5  f6  13.Nd4  Nxd4  14.exd4  Ke7  15.dxe5  Bxe5  16.O-O  +=  Delchev-Behling, Forni di Sopra 2014.  12...Nxd4  13.exd4  Ke7   13...f6  14.Nf3  Ke7  15.dxe5  fxe5  16.Bb5  +=  Condie-Crouch, London 1984  or   13...O-O  14.Nf3  +=  14.dxe5  Bxe5  +=  Gogolis-Miskulin, Neos Marmaras 2012  11.Nd4   11.Ne5  +=  11...Nxd4  12.exd4  Bb6  13.Be2  +=  Stefanova-Sebag, Doha 2011;  10...Nd7  11.Ngf3  f6 =  Danielsen-Anwesh, Visakhapatnam 2011; }
7. Qc2
{ The endgame following the exchange of queens is fine for Black:   7.Qxb6  axb6  8.a3  b5  9.Rc1  Bf5  10.h3   10.Ngf3 =  10...e6  11.Ngf3   11.g4  11...h6 =  De Prado-Obregon, Ferrol 2012. }
7... Bg4
{ An interesting move. Several alternatives have been tried here, e.g.   7...g6  8.e4 !  and now:  Nxe4 ?!   8...Qd8  9.Bg5   9.Ngf3  Bg7  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O =  9...b5  10.a4  +=   8...e5 !?  9.dxe5  Ng4  10.Nh3  Bc5  11.O-O-O  +=   8...dxe4  9.Nxc4  Qd8  +=  Soysal-Shetty, Al-Ain 2013  9.Nxe4  dxe4   9...Bf5  10.f3  dxe4  11.fxe4  ±  Pri-Labarthe, Gap 2008  10.Bxc4  +=  Bg7   10...Bf5  11.Qb3  Qxb3  12.axb3  Bg7  13.Be3  +=  Ruiz-Astasio,Linares 2013  11.Be3  Qc7  +=  Bosque-Martin, Benidorm 2011  Also interesting is   7...Nh5 !?  for example:  8.Bg3   8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  g5   9...e5  10.Be2  g5  11.Bxh5  gxh4  12.Ngf3  +=  10.Be2  Ng7  11.Bg3  Bf5  12.e4  Bg6  13.h4  gxh4  14.Rxh4  O-O-O  15.Ngf3  ±  Sedlak-Todorovic, Subotica 2008.  8...Nxg3  9.hxg3  and now :  e6   9...e5  10.e4 !  exd4  11.exd5  dxc3  12.bxc3  Ne7  13.Bxc4  ±  Sedlak-Vasilev; Blagoevgrad 2013;  10.e4   10.b3  +=  10...Bd7  11.Be2  g6  12.Bf3  Ne7  13.Ne2  Bg7  14.Nf4  Qd6 =  Grachev-Potkin, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013 }
8. b3
{ The thematic break on b3, in response to c5-c4 by Black, is usually the best plan for White and in this position it is again the best move. Other moves have been tried, e.g.:   8.Be2  Bxe2   8...Bh5  9.Bxh5   9.b3 !  9...Nxh5  10.Be5  e6  11.Ne2   11.h3  11...Be7  12.Nf3  O-O =  Pri-Huerga, Elgoibar 2007  9.Nxe2  e6  10.Bg5   10.e4  +=  10...Be7 =  Kukov-Kozhuharov, Sunny Beach 2013;   8.h3  Bh5  9.Ngf3  e6  10.Nh4  Qd8  11.g4  Bg6  12.Nxg6  hxg6  +=  Sergeev-Thesing,Predeal 2006;  The normal   8.Ngf3  e6  9.h3   9.Be2  Be7  10.h3  Bf5 =  Rodriguez-Arizmendi, El Sauzal 2010  or   9.b3  Bf5  10.Qc1  Qa5  - Meduna-Stangl, Brno 1993  9...Bf5  10.Qc1  Rc8   10...h6  11.Be2  Rc8  12.O-O  Be7 =  Marzolo-Drazic, Bastia 2000  11.g4 !?  Bg6  12.Nh4  Be7  13.Nxg6  hxg6  Sergeev-Potkin, Warsaw 2011  And even   8.e4  e6  9.f3  Bh5  10.h4  Bg6  11.g4  h5 =  Sean-Sutorikhin, Kecskemet 2013 }
8... cxb3 9. axb3 e6
{ 9...Rc8  is the main alternative, discomforting the white queen, but it is able to move aside without any problems:  10.Qb1   10.Qb2  Bf5 =  10...e6  11.Bd3   11.h3  Bf5  12.Bd3  Bb4  13.Ne2  Bxd3  14.Qxd3  O-O =  11...Be7  12.Ngf3  Bh5  13.b4  +=  Bruno-Suc, Trieste 2013 }
10. Bd3
{ An alternative is   10.h3  Bf5  11.Bd3  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  Be7  13.Ngf3  O-O  14.O-O  and the white position is more comfortable, as he has the better structure and pawn breaks available on c4 or e4. }
10... Be7 11. Ngf3
{ It was better to gain a tempo with   11.h3 !  Bf5  12.Ngf3  += } 11... Rc8
12. Qb2 O-O 13. h3 Bh5
{ The alternative was   13...Bf5  14.Bxf5  exf5  15.O-O  which is better than the game continuation. }
14. O-O
{ White has emerged from the opening with some advantage: more space, the better pawn structure, half-open a-file, pawn breaks available on e4 or c4 and the possible plan of b2-b4 and Nb3. }
14... Bg6 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Rfb1
{ This defends the queen and prepares to play c3-c4. There were several other possibilities for White, such as   16.Bh2   16.Rfc1   16.Rfe1 }
16... Qd8
{ Black has also played   16...a6  17.Rc1  Qd8  18.Ne1  Nh5  19.Be5  Bd6  20.Nd3  Nf6  21.Bxd6  Qxd6  22.c4  +=  Maksimovic-Ioannidis, Plovdiv 2014.   16...a5  += }
17. c4
{ It was better to employ the plan of   17.b4 !  Ne8   17...b6  18.Ra6  ±   17...a6  18.b5  ±  18.Nb3  ± }
17... Bd6
{ 17...a5  was better, e.g.  18.Re1   18.c5  b6 =   18.Rc1  b6  19.Qb1 =  18...b6  19.e4  Bb4 = }
18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. c5
{ Here   19.Ne5  was favourable, e.g.  a6  20.c5  Qe7  21.Nxc6  Rxc6  22.b4  ±  also good was   19.b4  dxc4  20.Nxc4   20.b5  Ne7  21.Rc1  Qd5  22.Ne5  c3  23.Rxc3  Rxc3  24.Qxc3  Qxb5  25.Rxa7  +=  20...Qd5  21.Rc1  ± }
19... Qe7 20. b4 a6 21. b5 axb5 22. Qxb5 Rc7
{ White has a clear advantage in space, with pressure along the open files and against the weak b7-pawn, but it is not easy to turn these advantages into something concrete. }
23. Ra3 Ne4
{ This is a bad move; it was better to play   23...e5  although White is still better after  24.Qb2  Ne4  25.Rb3  Rb8  26.Rb6 }
24. Nxe4 dxe4 25. Nd2 f5 26. Qb2
{ An error. White could have gained a decisive, long-term advantage with   26.Nc4 !  achieving total domination of the position after  Rb8  27.Qb2   27.Nd6  +-  27...Nd8  28.Rb3  Qd7  29.Nd6  Kh7  30.Rb6  Qe7  31.Qa2  Nc6  32.g3  Qd7  33.h4  Qe7  34.Kg2  Qd7  35.Nb5  Rcc8  36.Na7  Nxa7   36...Rc7  37.Nxc6  Rxc6  38.Rxc6  Qxc6  39.Rb6  +-  and e6 falls.  37.Qxa7  +-  and the b7-pawn falls. }
26... Rd8 27. Rb3
{ This allows Black to free his game. White would still have a clear advantage after   27.Nc4  e5  28.Rd1   28.Nd6  exd4  29.exd4  Rxd6  30.cxd6  Qxd6  31.Ra8+  Kh7  32.Rd1  ±  28...exd4  29.exd4  Kh7  30.Ra4 }
27... e5 28. Nc4
{ With Black in time pressure, White complicates the game and avoids the drawish line   28.Rxb7  Rxb7  29.Qxb7  Qxb7  30.Rxb7  exd4  31.exd4  Nxd4 = }
28... exd4 29. Nd6 dxe3
{ It was better to play   29...d3  allowing  30.Nxb7  =+ } 30. fxe3 Rcd7 31.
Qa2 Kh7 32. Rxb7 Rxb7 33. Rxb7 Rd7 34. Rb6 Ne5 35. Rb4
{ 35.Rb8  led to equality after  Rd8  36.Rxd8  Qxd8  37.Qe6  Nc6 } 35... Nd3
{ 35...Qg5  was better, e.g.  36.Qe2  Ra7  ∓ } 36. Rb8 Nxc5
{ A further mistake that gives White a clear advantage; instead,   36...Rd8  37.Rxd8  Qxd8 =  was fine. }
37. Qg8+ Kh6 38. Qh8+ Kg5 39. g3 Kf6 40. Rf8+ Ke6 41. Re8
{ This wins the queen, but Black can obtain good compensation. Another winning attempt was   41.Nxf5  gxf5  42.Re8  ±  However, the best move was   41.Nc4 !  Kd5   41...Qg5 ?  42.Qg8+  Ke7  43.Qf7#   41...Rd6  42.Qg8+  Kd7  43.Rf7   41...Rd1+  42.Kg2  Kd5  43.Rd8+  Kxc4  44.Rxd1  +-  42.Nb6+  Kc6  43.Nxd7  Qxd7   43...Kxd7  44.Ra8  +-   43...Nxd7  44.Ra8  44.Rd8  +- }
41... Kxd6 42. Rxe7 Rxe7 43. Qh7 Re6 44. Qxg7 Nd3 45. h4
{ Black can construct a fortress in this ending, so it was better to play   45.g4  fxg4  46.hxg4  Ne5  47.Qf8+  Re7  48.Qf6+  Kd7  49.g5  Re6  50.Qf4  Nf3+  51.Kf2  Kc6  ± }
45... Ne5 46. Kf2 Ng4+ 47. Ke2 Kc5 48. Qc7+ Kd5 49. Qg7 Kd6 50. Kd2 Re7 51. Qg8
Ne5 52. Qd8+ Ke6 53. Kc3
{ Trying to bring his king into the struggle, but White cannot penetrate the black fortress. }
53... Kf7 54. Qd6 Ng4 55. Qf4 Nf6 56. Qg5 Kg7 57. Kc4 Rd7 58. Kc5 Rd5+ 59. Kc4
Rd7 60. Qf4 Rd3 61. Kc5 Rd8 62. Qc7+ Rd7 63. Qe5 Rd5+
{ Black loses patience and enters the pawn ending that White was seeking. Although the pawn ending should be drawn, it is risky to enter it when short of time. It was safer from from the practical point of view to maintain the fortress with 63... Kf7, when White cannot make progress. }
64. Qxd5 Nxd5 65. Kxd5 g5
{ This is not losing, but it comes close. There was an easy draw with   65...Kf6 !  and now:  66.g4   66.Kd6  Kg7  67.Ke6  Kh6  68.Ke5   68.Kf6  Kh5  -+  68...Kg7 =   66.Kd4  Ke6  67.g4  fxg4  68.Kxe4  g5  69.hxg5  g3  70.Kf3  Kf5  71.Kxg3  Kxg5 =  66...fxg4  67.Kxe4  g5  68.h5   68.hxg5+ ?  Kxg5  -+  68...Kg7  69.Kd3  Kh6  70.e4  Kxh5  71.Ke3  Kh4  72.Kf2  Kh3  73.Kg1  Kh4 = }
66. Ke5 f4
{ And now this is definitely losing. Black could have drawn with the neat idea   66...Kg6  67.h5+  Kh6 !! =   67...Kxh5  68.Kxf5  +-  68.Kxf5  Kxh5  69.Kxe4  Kg4  70.Kd5  Kxg3  71.e4  Kf4  72.e5  g4  73.e6  g3  74.e7  g2  75.e8=Q  g1=Q = }
67. gxf4 g4 { 67...gxh4  68.Kxe4  h3  69.Kf3  wins.   67...gxf4  68.Kxf4  +- }
68. Kxe4 Kh6 69. f5 Kh5 70. f6 Kg6 71. Kf4 Kxf6 72. Kxg4
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the normal line with Nf6 and Nd2. Then after 6c4 by Black, the right move for White is 7. Qc2, since the endgame after 7. Qxb6 is good for Black.  We saw the idea of 7... Bg4 in the game and analysed various alternatives, such as 7... g6 and 7... Nh5. Once again the best move for White was 8. b3 !, the thematic break that should always be kept in mind when Black plays c5-c4.  In the game, white emerged from the opening with some advantage: the better pawn structure, the half-open a-file, possible pawn breaks on e4 or c4 and an alternative plan of b3-b4, which would have been even better than the game continuation.  Both sides made mistakes and in the endgame, after White won the queen for rook and knight, Black should not have lost, since he had a fortress position, but in time pressure he entered the pawn ending, and although this should have been a draw, further errors led to Black's defeat. }
