[Black "Game 46 - Carlsen vs. Wojtaszek"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ In the last few years some of the world's best players, such as Carlsen, Kramnik, Grischuk and Karjakin, have begun to play the London System. Many of them started playing it in rapidplay games but then graduated to using it in important standard play games, such as this one from the European Team Championship. }
2... d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 cxd4
{ In the previous game we saw the variations which arise after 5.. Qb6. After the exchange on d4 we usually transpose to the structure of the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence, which we can also reach via the move order 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3, e.g. 5... Bf5   5...Nf6  6. Nf3  e.g.   5...Bf5  is also fully playable:  6.Qb3  is better: 6... Qd7 7. Nf3 e6 8. Nbd2 Nge7 !?   8...Nf6  transposes to the game;  8...f6 !?  9. Be3 Ng6 10. Bg3 Bd6= De Prado-Suarez, Arteixo 2016  6... Nf6 7. Nbd2 e6 8. Qb3, as in our main game.  Qd7 }
6. exd4 Bf5 7. Qb3
{ White can also play   7.Ngf3  first, and after  e6  then  8.Qb3 } 7... Qc8
{ The most common defence.  Black can also play   7...Qd7  which reaches a practically equal game, but Black often prefers to place his queen out of reach of Whites possible threats based on Ne5 and Bb5; a sample continuation would be  8.Ngf3  a6   8...e6  9.Ne5  Qc8  ∞  9.Be2   9.Nh4 !?  9...e6  10.O-O   10.h3  Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Nh4 =  De Prado-Medarde, A Corua 2013  10...Be7  11.Ne5  Nxe5  12.Bxe5  O-O  13.a4   13.c4  dxc4  14.Nxc4  Nd5  15.Bf3  b5 =  Berkes-Mihok, Hungary tt 2013/14  13...Ne4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4 =  Jacobsen-Annenkov, Jyvskyl 2015.  Here the offer to exchange queens with   7...Qb6  gives White a comfortable advantage after  8.Qxb6   8.Ngf3  e6   8...Qxb3  9.axb3 !  +=  9.Qxb6   9.Nh4  +=  9...axb6  10.Bb5  Nd7  11.O-O  +=  Bocharov-Yapparov, Kazan 2014  8...axb6  9.Ngf3   9.Bb5  +=  9...Nd7  10.Bb5  f6  11.Bg3  +=  Berkes-Czebe, Hungary tt 2009. }
8. Ngf3 e6
{ Previously, in the World Rapidplay Championship in Berlin, Carlsen had faced   8...h6  9.Ne5  g5  10.Bg3  Bg7  11.Be2  O-O  12.O-O  e6  13.Rae1   13.h3  +=  13...Ne4   13...Nxe5  14.Bxe5  Nd7 =  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.Nd3  +=  Bh7  16.Qd1  Ne7  17.Be5  f6  18.Bd6  Re8  19.Bh5  Bg6  20.Bxe7  Bxh5  21.Qxh5  Rxe7  22.f4  Qe8  23.Qf3  f5  24.fxg5  hxg5  25.g4  ±  Carlsen,M  (2850)  -Wagner,D  (2575)  Berlin rpd 2015 }
9. Nh4
{ The critical line; White is trying to exchange the black bishop and gain the bishop pair. Practice has also seen:   9.Ne5  Be7  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  Nxe5  12.Bxe5  Nd7 =  13.Bg3  Nb8  14.a4  Nc6  15.a5  a6  16.Qa4  Qd7  17.b4  Eljanov,P  (2717)  -Motylev,A  (2649)  Berlin blitz 2015  (e5 ! ⇆)  /  18.dxe5  d4   9.Be2  h6   9...Be7  10.O-O  O-O  and now :  11.Rfe1   11.Rac1  Ne4  12.Nxe4   12.Rfe1  h6  13.Nxe4  Bxe4  14.Ne5 =  Kovalevskaya-Kadimova, Moscow 1994  12...Bxe4  13.Qd1  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Qd7  +=  Berkes-Mchedlishvili, Novi Sad 2009;   11.Nh4  Bg4   11...Be4  12.f3  Bg6  13.Nxg6  hxg6  14.Rae1 =  12.f3  Bh5  13.g4  Bg6   13...Ne8  14.Bg3  Qd8  15.Ng2  ∞  14.Bg3  Qd7  15.Rae1  +=  Rapport-Korpa, Zalakaros 2014.  11...a6  12.Qd1   12.a4  Ne4  13.Nxe4  Bxe4  14.Qd1  Qd8 =  Ringoir-Palac,Troms 2014  12...h6  13.Nf1  b5  14.a3  Re8 =  Reich-Ribli, Germany Bundesliga 2014/15   9...Ne4  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  11.h4 !?  h6  12.Nd2  Bh7  13.g4  ∞  Nguyen-Bogner, Khanty-Mansiysk 2010  10.h3   10.Ne5  Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.a4  Nd7  Kamsky-Fressinet, Beijing 2012;   10.O-O  Be7  11.c4 !?  O-O  12.c5  Nd7 =  E.Sveshnikov-J.Alvarez, Dresden 2008  10...Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Rfe1  Bd8   12...a6  13.a4  Nd7  14.Bf1  Re8  15.Rac1  Na5  16.Qa2  Nb6  17.b4  Nac4  18.a5  Nxd2  19.Nxd2  Nd7  20.Nb3  Nb8  21.Nc5  +=  Grachev, B  (2666)  -Motylev,A  (2648)  Sochi rpd 2015  13.a4  Bc7 =  , Grachev,B  (2666)  -Motylev,A  (2648)  St Petersburg rpd 2015   9.h3  h6  10.Be2  Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Rfe1   12.Ne5  a6  13.Rfc1  Ne4  14.Nxc6  Qxc6 =  Trent-Hagen, Aarhus 2015  12...a6   12...Rd8  13.Bf1  Bd6  14.Bxd6  Rxd6 =  Karakehajov-Nikolov, Sofia 2004  13.a4  Nd7   13...Ne4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.Nd2  Bf5 =  Pavlovic-Bogosavljevic, Belgrade 2014  14.Bf1  Re8  15.Rac1 =  Grachev-Motylev, Sochi tt rapid 2015. }
9... Be4
{ The most common response; the main alternative is   9...Bg6  10.Nxg6  hxg6  11.h3   11.Bd3  Nh5  12.Be3  Bd6  13.O-O-O !?  a new and more aggressive idea of Kramniks, instead of   13.g3  Nf6  14.Qd1 !?   14.O-O  +=   14.Nf3  +=  14...O-O  15.f4  +=  Kamsky-Macieja, Achaea 2012  or   13.Nf3  Nf4  14.Bxf4  Bxf4  15.g3  Bd6  16.h4  +=  Elianov-Tkachiev, Moscow 2008  13...a6  14.Kb1  b5  15.Qc2  Na5  16.Nf3  Nc4  17.Bc1  ∞  Kramnik-Sjugirov, Doha 2015.  11...Be7  12.Bd3   12.Nf3  +=  12...Bd8   12...a6  13.a4  Nh5  14.Bh2 =  Gonda-Erds, Budapest 2005  13.Nf3  Bc7  14.Be3  +=  O-O  15.Qc2  a6  16.h4  e5  17.dxe5  Nxe5  18.Nxe5  Bxe5  19.O-O-O  Re8  20.Kb1  b5  21.Bg5  Ne4  22.Bc1  b4  23.Bxe4  dxe4  24.cxb4  Qg4  25.Rhe1  Bf6  26.g3  Rac8  27.Qb3  +=  Grischuk,A  (2774)  -Motylev,A  (2649)  Berlin rpd 2015  Black has also played   9...Bg4  10.h3  +=   10.Bd3  Be7  11.Nhf3   11.h3  Bh5  12.O-O  +=  11...Bh5  12.O-O  Bg6  13.Bxg6  hxg6  +=  Anikonov-Rublevsky, Khanty-Mansiysk 2015  10...Bh5  11.Bd3  Be7  12.O-O   12.Ndf3  h6  13.g4  g5  14.Be5  gxh4  15.gxh5  +=  Sulskis-Galkin, New York 2000  12...Nd7  13.Nhf3  +=  Nisipeanu-Banusz, Austria Bundesliga 2015/16 }
10. Nxe4
{ If   10.f3  then  Bg6  11.g4   11.g3  Qd7  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Bg2 =  E.Sveshnikov-Agrest,Tallinn 2015  11...Be7  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Bd3  Nd7  14.O-O =  E.Sveshnikov-Arngrimsson, Albena 2013. }
10... Nxe4
{ The engines prefer the move   10...dxe4  which is no doubt less logical. On the one hand Black doubles his pawns and weakens his pawn structure, but it is true that he also deprives the g1-knight of its natural position on f3 and at the same time clears the d5-square. The game might continue  11.g3  Be7  12.Ng2  O-O   12...Nd5  13.Bd2   13.Be2   13.O-O-O !?  13...O-O =  Sandipan-Arun, Benasque 2014  13.Be2  Nd5   13...a6  14.O-O  Nd5  15.Rae1   15.f3  +=  15...Nxf4  16.Nxf4  +=  Renner-Levushkina, Germany tt 2013  14.Bd2  Qd7   14...Rd8  15.O-O  Qd7 =  Sedlak-Ragger, Achaea 2012   14...f5  15.O-O  Kh8  16.f3  +=  Sedlak-Ivanov, Aschach 2015  15.f3 !?   15.O-O =  15...exf3  16.Bxf3  Na5  17.Qc2  Rac8   17...Nc4  18.O-O =  Sedlak-Perunovic, Hungary tt 2013/14  18.O-O  Nc4 =  Cruz-Ghosh, Barbera del Valles 2014. }
11. Nf3
{ Here   11.Bd3  has also been played, e.g.  Bd6  12.Bxd6   12.Be3  Nf6  13.g3   13.h3  O-O  14.Qc2 =  G.Pap-P.V.Kiss, Hungary tt 2008/09  13...O-O  14.O-O  Qc7 =  Jovanic-Doric, Croatia tt 2015  12...Nxd6  13.O-O  O-O  14.Nf3   14.Qc2  h6  15.f4  +=  14...Qc7  15.Qc2  h6   15...g6  16.Rfe1  b5  17.Qd2  +=  Sandipan-Kasimdzhanov, Dubai 2014  16.Qe2  Rab8  17.a4  Rbe8 =  Sedlak-Prohaszka, Hungary tt 2012/13. }
11... Bd6
{ It is normally a good idea for Black to exchange this bishop. In a recent game Black played   11...Be7  12.Bd3  O-O  13.O-O   13.Qc2  +=  13...f5  14.Rae1  g5  15.Bc1  g4  16.Nd2  +=  Sandipan-Gunina, Gibraltar 2016. }
12. Bxd6
{ Carlsen improves on a previous game between Kamsky and Wojtaszek himself, where White played   12.Bg3  Nxg3  13.hxg3  Qc7  14.Bd3  h6  15.g4  O-O-O  ∞  16.Kf1  Kb8  17.a4  Rhe8  18.a5  Nxa5  19.Qa4  Nc6  20.b4  Qb6  21.g3  e5  22.b5  Nxd4  23.cxd4  e4  =+  Kamsky,G  (2683)  -Wojtaszek,R  (2737)  Sochi 2015/ Black had no problems whatsoever, therefore he was willing to repeat the line even against Carlsen. }
12... Nxd6 13. Bd3 Qc7
{ 13...O-O  14.Qc2  h6  can transpose into games from the following note. I somehow doubt Carlsen would go in for something wild like  15.g4   15.O-O-O  b5  =+  15...Re8  16.O-O-O  b5  ∞  /=/+ }
14. Qc2
{ This is a new idea of Carlsens;   14.O-O  O-O  would lead to the games mentioned in the notes to Whites 11th move  (Sandipan-Kasimdzhanov and Sedlak-Prohaszka)  . }
14... O-O-O
{ 14...h6  15.O-O   15.O-O-O  b5  =+   15.Qe2 !?  15...Kf8  16.Qe2  ∞ } 15. O-O
h6
{ Preparing to advance his pawns against Whites castled position. The immediate   15...g5 ?  would be too hasty: White would be better after  16.Nxg5  Rdg8  17.Nf3 }
16. a4
{ And Carlsen does the same, so that we have a typical position with castling on opposite wings. There were other good moves available for White, such as   16.Rfe1  +=   16.Rac1  += }
16... Kb8
{ Another option was   16...g5  17.Rfe1  g4  18.Ne5  h5  19.Qc1   19.a5  ∞  19...Kb8  20.Qf4  += }
17. Rfe1 Rc8 18. Qd1
{ A typical Carlsen move; he wants to improve his queen and keep an eye on the kingside.  The most natural move would be   18.Qe2 }
18... Rhe8
{ 18...g5  is not very convincing:  19.Ne5 !?  h5   19...Nxe5  20.Rxe5  +=  20.Qd2  += }
19. Bf1
{ Carlsen continues to make quiet moves. It would be more normal to play   19.Ne5  Nxe5  20.Rxe5  +=  or   19.g3  += }
19... Re7
{ Here   19...f6 !?  was good, to control the e5-square and in the future prepare e6-e5, with equality. }
20. Rc1 Rd8 21. Re2
{ Carlsen decides to improve another piece before playing b2-b4, which was also possible here   21.b4 !? }
21... Ne4
{ It seems better to revert to his initial plan with   21...g5  ⇆  22.b4  g4  23.Ne5  h5  with a complex position. }
22. b4 Ng5 23. Ne1
{ Yet one more move that would probably not occur to other mortals, but is quite normal for Carlsen, who wants to avoid piece exchanges and then prepare his breakthrough on the queenside; he also has the d3-square for the knight. Here   23.Nd2  +=  was also good, as was   23.Nxg5  hxg5  24.a5  += }
23... e5 24. b5
{ This move is very important for establishing Whites advantage. After   24.Nd3  e4  25.Nc5  f5  White is better, but Black has managed to complicate the game and can gain some initiative on the kingside. }
24... Na5 25. Rxe5 Rxe5 26. dxe5 Qxe5
{ It was better to play   26...Nc4  27.f4   27.Nd3  Ne4  28.Qg4  Nxe5  29.Qxg7  Nxd3  30.Bxd3  Nxf2 !  31.Qd4   31.Kxf2 ?  Qf4+  32.Ke2  Qxc1  31...Nxd3  32.Qxd3 =  27...Ne4  28.Qd4  Ncd2  29.Rc2  Nb3  30.Qe3  Nbc5  and Black has compensation, although these lines would have been complicated to see. }
27. c4 Ne6 { 27...d4  28.c5  ± } 28. Nf3 Qf4
{ A mistake;  it was better to play   28...Qe4  29.c5  →  Rc8  30.Bd3  Qg4  31.h3  Qf4  32.g3  Qf6  33.c6  bxc6  34.bxc6  Rxc6   34...Nxc6 ??  35.Ba6  Rc7  36.Qb3+  Ka8  37.Rxc6  +-  35.Rxc6  Nxc6  36.Qb3+  Kc7  37.Qxd5  and White is better, in view of the weakness of the black king. }
29. cxd5 Rxd5
{ 29...Nc7  30.g3  Qd6  31.Rc2  ±   31.Qc2  Nxd5  32.Bh3  with a decisive advantage to White. The control of the light squares and the c-file are key. }
30. Qxd5 Qxc1 31. g3 Qc5
{ This is not good, but the black position was already difficult, even with the best defence:   31...Qc8  +=2  !?  32.Bh3  Nc4  ±  and now White can choose between several moves which give him the advantage:  33.Nd4   33.Bxe6  Qxe6  34.Qd8+  Qc8  35.Qe7  ±   33.a5  Nf4  34.gxf4  Qxh3  35.f5  Qg4+  36.Kh1  ±  33...Nf4  34.gxf4  Qxh3  35.Nf5   35.Qxc4  Qg4+  36.Kf1  Qd1+  37.Kg2  Qg4+  with a draw  35...Qg4+  36.Kh1  ± }
32. Qd7
{ The position is winning for White; the key to the position is the black knight on a5, which is out of play. The white queen is very active, the black king is unsafe and the kingside pawns are weak; in contrast, the bishop on f1 defends the white king. }
32... Qf8 { If   32...Qc7  then  33.Qe8+  Qd8   33...Nd8  34.Ne5  34.Qxf7  +- }
33. Ne5 Nc5 34. Qd5 Kc7
{ Here   34...f6 ?  fails to the tactical shot  35.Qxc5 !  Qxc5  36.Nd7+  Kc7  37.Nxc5  winning a piece. }
35. Nxf7
{ White has won an important pawn and the black king remains in danger. In addition, the knight on a5 is still out of play. }
35... Nxa4 36. Qe5+ Kb6 37. Nd6 Nc5 38. Ne8
{ Black resigned. White threatens mate on c7 and Black has no good defence.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw Black's option of an early exchange on d4, transposing to the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann. White put pressure on b7 with 7. Qb3 and Black defended with 7... Qc8, instead of the alternative 7... Qd7, which is also playable.  Carlsen shortly improved on a previous game between Kamsky and Wojtaszek himself by exchanging with 12. Bxd6, instead of playing 12. Bg3. Black played in a risky manner with 14... O-O-O. It was surely better to wait to see where White was going to castle.  Carlsen manoeuvred to improve his pieces, perhaps with unnecessary caution, but when Black tried to free his position with 23... e5 he was worse, once Carlsen played 24. b5. White gradually increased his advantage with the help of some inaccuracies on Black's part and he gained a decisive advantage, thanks to his greater piece activity.  The situation of the black knight on a5 and the weakness of the black king contributed to the outcome of the game. }
*

