1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ In the last few years some of the world's best players, such as Carlsen, Kramnik, Grischuk and Karjakin, have begun to play the London System. Many of them started playing it in rapidplay games but then graduated to using it in important standard play games, such as this one from the European Team Championship. }
2... d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 cxd4
{ In the previous game we saw the variations which arise after 5... Qb6. After the exchange on d4 we usually transpose to the structure of the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence, which we can also reach via the move order 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3, e.g. 5Bf5  (5Nf6)  6. Nf3 }
6. exd4 Bf5 7. Qb3 { Black can also play } 7... Qd7
{ which reaches a practically equal game, but Black often prefers to place his queen out of reach of White's possible threats based on Ne5 and Bb5; a sample continuation would be }
8. Ngf3 a6 9. Be2 e6 10. h3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nh4
{ De Prado-Medarde, A Corua 2013 } *

