1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ In this game we shall see the main problem for White of playing Nf3 before Bf4. But there is an alternative for White if he still wants to play 2. Nf3, yet avoid the unpleasant line that Black has available against routine play. Black can also begin with 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...c5  3.c3  Nc6  4.dxc5 !  Black often discounts this capture, although it is usually good for White  e6  5.b4  a5  6.b5  Na7  7.e3   7.a4  Bxc5  8.Bb2  Nf6  9.e3  O-O  10.Nbd2 =  Cacco-Astengo, Italy-ch sf 1998  7...Bxc5  8.Nbd2  += }
3. c3
{ This is the correct move order for White if he wants to prevent the unpleasant line explained in the note to White's fourth move. Another option is   3.c4  is reserved for the match against Topalov.   3.Bf4  c5  4.dxc5 !?  e6   4...Nc6  5.Nbd2  e6  6.Nb3  Ne4  7.e3  Nxc5 =  Bitoon-Paragua, Tagaytay City 2013  5.e3  Bxc5  6.Be2  O-O  7.O-O  Nc6  8.c4 =  Biolek-Lintchevski, Pardubice 2013. }
3... c5
{ An alternative is   3...Bf5  4.Qb3  and now:  b6   4...Qc8  5.Bf4  e6  6.c4   6.e3  Be7  7.c4  O-O  8.Nc3  c6  9.h3  Nbd7  10.Be2 =  Sergeev-Dziuba, Karvina 2013   6.Nbd2 =  6...c6  7.Nc3   7.e3  7...Nbd7  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.Rc1  +=  Taleb-Tan, Kuala Lumpur 2005.  5.Bg5  e6  6.Nbd2  Be7  7.e3  O-O =  Gritsak-Bacrot, Ciudad Real 2007; }
4. dxc5
{ The normal London System continuation would be   4.Bf4  Nc6  5.e3  Qb6  6.Qb3  c4  but the difference, now that both sides knights are developed  (on f3 and f6)  , is that White runs into a problem if he plays the normal  7.Qc2  owing to the reply  The endgame after   7.Qxb6  axb6  is considered fine for Black: Now if  8.Nbd2  Black is in time to get rid of his doubled pawn with   8.Na3 !  Ra5  9.Bc7  Bf5  10.Bxb6  Ra6  11.Bc7   11.Bc5  Ne4  12.Nb5  Kd7  13.Be2   13.Nh4  Bg6  14.Nxg6  hxg6  15.Na3  b6  16.Bb4  Nxb4  17.cxb4  e5  Vlahov-Loncar, Croatia tt 2010  13...Ra5  14.a4  Nxc5  15.dxc5  e6  16.Nfd4 =  Schumacher-Percze, cr 2002.  11...Kd7  12.Nb5  e6  13.Bf4   13.Be2  Be7  14.Bd1  Rha8  15.a4  Na7 =  Legky-Cvetkovic, Vrnjacka Banja 1989  13...Ra5   13...Be7  14.Ne5+  Nxe5  15.dxe5  Nh5  16.Nd4 =  14.a4  Bc2  15.Ne5+  Nxe5  16.dxe5  Ne4 =  Kovacevic-Rausis, Las Palmas 1995;  8...b5  9.a3  b4  10.cxb4  Nxb4  11.Rc1  Nc6  and I think Black has the better prospects, with the plan of b5-b4, for instance  12.Be2  e6   12...Bf5  13.Nh4  Bd7  14.O-O  h6  15.Nhf3  =+  Ragonese-Korneev, Porto San Giorgio 2011  13.O-O  Be7  14.Ne5  O-O =  Milovic-Blagojevic, Cetinje 2012;  7...Bf5 !  Here this move works. White cannot capture on f5 this time and has to play  8.Qc1  which is a move that we should avoid with white, if possible. It is curious that there are quite a lot of games with this position, yet it does not offer any advantage to White. Even Kamsky and some other strong players have played this position, but I think that it is best avoided, because Black stands very well after  Nh5 !  This move, which has not been played much, is the recommendation of the Houdini engine, which awards Black the advantage. An important game continued  The more common move, also good for Black, is   8...e6  9.h3   9.Nbd2  Be7  10.Be2  O-O  11.b3  =+  Georgiev-Artemiev, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013  9...Be7  10.Nbd2  Qd8  11.Ne5   11.Be2 =  11...O-O  12.Be2  Nxe5  13.Bxe5  =+  Telljohann-Adams, Gibraltar 2013  9.Bg3  e6   9...Nxg3  10.hxg3  h6  10.Nbd2  Nxg3  11.hxg3  h6  12.Be2   12.e4  Bh7  13.Be2  Be7  14.exd5  exd5 =  Rozhko-Volkov, Taganrog 2013  12...Be7   12...Bd6  =+  13.Bd1  Qc7  14.Bc2 =  Kamsky-Carlsen, Moscow 2007. }
4... g6
{ Playing in gambit style. The normal continuation would be to regain the pawn with   4...e6  5.b4  a5  6.e3   6.Nbd2  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  8.cxb6  Qxb6  9.a3  Bxb4  10.Rb1  Bxd2+  11.Bxd2  Qa7  with a complex position  6...axb4  7.cxb4  b6  and in this position White can head for a type of Abrahams-Noteboom variation of the Slav with reversed colours, which gives rise to complex positions. In spite of Houdini's preference for Black in this line, I think it is perfectly playable for White.  8.a4   8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  10.a4  bxc5  11.b5  Bd6  12.O-O  O-O  13.Bb2  ∞  Cifuentes-Bauer, San Sebastian 2009  8...bxc5  9.b5   9.bxc5  Bxc5  10.Bb2 =  9...Bd6  10.Bb2  Nbd7  11.Nbd2  O-O  12.Be2  Bc7  13.Qc2  ∞  Kulicov-Derjabin, Alushta 2004; }
5. g3
{ Kamsky often plays the Schlechter Variation of the Slav with black and here he chooses a similar system with white. There were other interesting options, such as:   5.b4  Bg7  6.Bb2  O-O  7.Nbd2  a5  8.a3  Nc6  9.e3  Rogers-Morris, Adelaide 2007;   9.b5  +=   5.e4  is also interesting  Nxe4   5...dxe4  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  7.Ng5  +=  6.Bb5+  Bd7   6...Nc6  7.Ne5  ±  7.Qxd5  Bxb5  8.Qxe4  Nd7  9.Be3  Bg7  10.Nbd2  ∞  Another good move is   5.Bf4  Bg7  6.Nbd2  O-O  7.e3  and now:  Nbd7   7...a5  8.a4   8.Qa4  Bd7  9.Bb5  Qe8 =  Varga-Almasi, Budapest 2000  8...Na6  9.Bxa6  Rxa6  10.Be5  +=  Torre-Srivachirawat, Ho Chi Minh City 2009.  8.Nb3  a6  9.Be2  Re8  10.Ne5  Ne4 ?   10...a5  +=  11.Nxf7  +-  Nxc3   11...Kxf7  12.Qxd5+  e6  13.Qxe4  +-  12.Nxd8  Nxd1  13.Ne6  1-0 Epishin-Bankmann, Schwbisch Gmnd 2013; }
5... Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O
{ 6...a5  7.O-O  Na6  8.c4  +=  Udani-Mok, Kuala Lumpur 2010. } 7. O-O
{ We have reached a position from the symmetrical QPO line   1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  g6  3.g3  Bg7  4.Bg2  O-O  5.O-O  d5  6.c3  with the risky 6. ..c5 ?! 7. dxc5. It is not clear now how Black is going to regain the pawn.  It is inferior to play   7.Nbd2  Qc7  8.Nb3  e5  9.Bg5   9.O-O =  9...Be6  10.O-O =  Dokutchaev-Kanep,Joensuu 2013 }
7... Nc6
{ Or else:   7...Ne4  8.Ng5 !   8.Be3  Na6  9.Nbd2  Naxc5  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Qb3  e6  12.Rfd1  +=  1-0 Orel,O  (2335)  -Licina,A  (2125)  /Bled 1994/TD  (19)  8...Nxg5  9.Bxg5  h6  10.Be3  ±  e6  11.Qd2  Kh7  12.Na3  Nc6  13.Rad1  Qe7  14.Nb5  ±  1-0 Fominykh,M  (2308)  -Shlakich,A  (2105)  /Moscow 2006/CBM 115 ext  (46)   7...Na6  8.b4  Ne4  9.Nd4   9.a3 !?  b6   9...Nxc3  10.Nxc3  Bxc3  11.Ra2  Bg7  12.Rd2  Nc7  13.e4  e6  14.exd5  Nxd5  15.Qb3  +=  1-0 Fiorito,F  (2450)  -Pierrot,J  (2385)  /Trelew 1995/EXT 1997  (28)  10.Nd4  e6  11.c6  +=  Qf6  12.Bb2  e5  13.Nf3  Qxc6  14.c4  Qxc4  15.Bxe5  +=  1/2 Sahl,B  (2375)  -Riemersma,L  (2420)  /Lyon 1990/EXT 1997  (56)  9...e5   9...Nc7  10.Bb2  a5  11.a3   11.Nd2  +=  11...Ne6  12.e3  N6g5  13.f3  +=  0-1 Boguszlavszkij,J  (2280)  -Bagonyai,A  (2364)  /Zalakaros 2003/EXT 2005  (88)  10.Nb5   10.Nb3  Be6  11.Bb2  b6  12.cxb6  Qxb6  13.N1d2  Nd6  14.e4  dxe4  15.Nxe4  Nxe4  16.Bxe4  Rac8  ⇆  1/2 Urban,K  (2468)  -Brzeski,M  (2260)  /Wroclaw 2008/CBM 125 Extra  (21)  10...Be6  11.Nd2  Nxd2  12.Qxd2  ±  Qd7  13.a4  b6  14.cxb6  axb6  15.Bb2  Rac8  16.Rfd1  Rfd8  17.e3  ±  1-0 Brestian,E  (2429)  -Mitter,G  (2261)  /Austria 1999/EXT 2002  (30)   7...a5 !?  Perhaps relatively best.  8.c4   8.Na3  Na6  9.Nb5  Nxc5  10.a4  Bd7  11.Be3  Bxb5  12.axb5  Qd6 =  1/2 Efimov,I  (2470)  -Vezzosi,P  (2305)  /Sestola 1992/EXT 2000  (72)  8...Na6  9.Nc3  dxc4  10.Ne5 !?   10.Qxd8  Rxd8  11.Ne5  Nxc5  12.Be3  Nfe4  13.Nxe4  Nxe4  14.Nxc4  Nd6  15.Rfd1  Be6  16.Nxd6  Rxd6  17.Rxd6  exd6  18.a4  Rc8  19.Bxb7  Rb8  20.Bc6  Rxb2 =  1/2 Zisman,P  (2255)  -Mikhalevski,V  (2499)  /Ramat Aviv 2000/CBM 077  (41)   10.c6  Nb4   10...Qc7  11.Qa4   11.Nd4  ±  11...Nb4  12.cxb7  Bxb7  13.Bf4  Qb6  14.Ne5  Bxg2  15.Kxg2  Rfc8 =  1-0 Froehlich,P  (2397)  -Smerdon,D  (2393)  / Canberra 2004/EXT 2005  (64)  11.Ne5   11.Qxd8  Rxd8  12.c7  Rd7  13.Bf4  Nh5  14.Ne5  +=  11...Nxc6  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.Nxc4  Be6  14.Nb6  Ra6  15.Nba4  Nd5  16.Nxd5  1/2 Basin,L  (2350)  -Maryasin,B/Minsk 1987/EXT 1999  10...Nxc5  11.Be3  Nfe4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Nxc4  Nd6  14.Nxd6  Qxd6  15.Qxd6  exd6  16.Rad1  +=   7...Qc7  8.b4  e5  9.Bb2   9.c4  +=  9...Rd8  10.Nbd2  Bf5 =  E.lAmi-Bok, Haarlem 2013 }
8. Qb3
{ White puts pressure on d5 and b7 and prepares Rd1, but I dislike this move, because it gets in the way of playing b2-b4. I think that   8.Na3 !?  is better, e.g.  e5   8...Qa5  9.b4  +=  9.Nb5  +=  Be6  10.b4  Ne4  11.Bb2  f5  12.Nd2  a6  13.Nxe4  fxe4  14.Nd6  ±  0-1 Fridman,D  (2569)  -Rakhmanov,A  (2473)  /playchess.com INT 2006/EXT 2007  (50)   8.Nbd2 !?   8.Nd4 !? }
8... Qa5
{ but it was better to play   8...e5 !  9.Bg5  Qe7  10.Qa3  Bf5  11.Nbd2 = } 9.
Qa3 Qc7 10. Bg5 { Here   10.Nd4  +=  looks more natural. } 10... Ne4
{ 10...h6 !  is better, e.g.  11.Bxf6  Bxf6  12.Nbd2  Bf5  and Black has compensation. }
11. Be3 e5 12. Nbd2 f5
{ A seemingly dangerous advance but White's position is solid, and Black's compensation for the pawn is insufficient. }
13. Rad1 Nf6
{ It was bad to play   13...f4 ?!  14.gxf4  exf4  15.Bd4  ±  or   13...Be6 ?  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Ng5  ±   13...a5 !?  M.Notkin }
14. b4 Re8 { 14...Ng4  15.Qb3 !  Ne7  16.Bg5 } 15. Nb3
{ White has completed his development and maintains a slight advantage with his extra pawn. Black has a strong centre at present, but his queenside development is lagging. }
15... Ne4 16. b5 Ne7 17. Qc1 b6
{ This is an error which gives White a clear advantage, but it was not easy suggest anything good for Black here. If   17...Bd7  18.a4  a6  19.c6 !?  bxc6  ∆  20.b6  ±   17...a6  18.b6  ± }
18. Ng5
{ An excellent move to bring the g2-bishop into the game and exploit some tactical ideas. }
18... bxc5 { 18...Nxg5  19.Bxg5  e4  20.c4  +- } 19. c4
{ Even better was   19.Nxe4 !  fxe4   19...dxe4  20.c4  +-  20.Nxc5  ± } 19...
d4 20. Nxe4 fxe4 { 20...dxe3  21.Nd6  +- } 21. Bg5
{ Another option was   21.Bxe4  Bb7  22.Bxb7  Qxb7  23.Bg5  with a clear advantage. }
21... Bb7 22. Bxe7
{ Here it was better to play   22.Qa3  ±  and it would not be easy for Black to defend the pawn on c5. }
22... Rxe7 23. Qc2 Rf8 { 23...e3  24.Bxb7  Qxb7  25.Nxc5  ± } 24. Bxe4
{ White wins a pawn and is left with a good knight against a bad black bishop. }
24... Bc8 25. Kg2 { It was better to recycle the knight with   25.Nd2  ± }
25... Bh6 26. Rd3 Kg7 27. Rf3 Rd8 28. h3 Be6 29. a4 a5
{ A bad move, creating a new weakness and making the b-pawn passed. It was better to wait with   29...Rc8  ± }
30. Bc6 Qb6 31. e4
{ It was more sensible to wait a while before making this advance and instead play   31.Nc1  ±  with the idea of going to d3. }
31... dxe3
{ This is a serious strategic error, rare in a player as strong as Karjakin: he loses his passed pawn and opens the f-file for White's rooks. The game is now decided. Instead   31...Rc8  ±  was better. }
32. fxe3 Kg8 33. e4 Rd6 34. Bd5 Bxd5 35. cxd5 Rc7 36. Rc3 Rf6 37. Rxf6 Qxf6 38.
Nxc5 Rf7 39. Qe2 Bd2 40. Rf3 Qg5 41. Ne6
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we learned about the drawback of using the move order with 2. Nf3 instead of 2. Bf4.  In the critical line with 5Qb6 and 6c4 the white queen should not retreat to c2, because now 7Bf5 works. But the ending after 7. Qxb6 is fine for Black.  Thus if White wants to use the 2. Nf3 move order, Kamsky's idea of 3. c3 is interesting, so that when Black plays c7-c5, White can capture with dxc5. Karjakin decided to play 4g6 !? and gambit the pawn, instead of the normal 4e6, which could lead to complex positions similar to the Abrahams-Noteboom line in the Slav, but with colours reversed.  Kamsky opted for the solid 5. g3, although he had other interesting options, such as 5. b4, 5. e4 or 5. Bf4.  In the game it was not easy for Black to regain the pawn and in the middlegame White gained a clear advantage. Then after errors on both sides White emerged the winner. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs ...d5 without early ...e6"]
[Black "Game 48 - Winants vs. Albzour"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6
{ Black can also choose the move order   2...Nc6  3.e3 !  f6 ?!   3...Nf6  transposes to the game  4.Bd3 !  +=   4.c4  e5 !?  5.cxd5 !  Qxd5   5...exf4  6.dxc6  fxe3  7.fxe3  bxc6  8.Nf3  +=  6.Nc3  Bb4  7.dxe5  +=  Jugelt-Shteinberg, Dresden 2009  4...Be6   4...e5 ?  5.Qh5+  ±  5.Nf3  Bf7  Macedo-Santiago, Recife 2012  6.O-O  += }
3. e3 Nc6
{ The Chigorin Defence against the London System.  If   3...Bg4  then  4.Be2   4.Nf3  e6  5.c4  c6  6.Qb3   6.Nc3  Nh5  7.Bg3  Nd7  8.Bd3 =  Georgiev-Liiva, Puhajarve 2013  6...Qb6  7.c5   7.Nc3  Nbd7  8.Nd2  Bf5  +=  Pham Le-Nguyen, Ho Chi Minh 2013  7...Qxb3  8.axb3  Nbd7  9.Nbd2  +=   4.f3 !?  Bf5  5.c4   5.Nc3 !?  5...c6   5...e6  6.Nc3  Bb4  7.Qb3  Nc6  8.a3  Bxc3+  9.Qxc3 =  Carlsen-Polgar, Rishon-Le-Zion 2006  6.Nc3  e6  7.Qb3  b6   7...Qb6  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  Be7  10.b4  +=  8.g4  Bg6  9.h4  h6   9...h5  10.g5  Ng8  11.cxd5  exd5  ±  McShane-Jansa, Tegernsee 2003  10.Nh3  Be7  11.O-O-O !?   11.Bg3  Nbd7  12.Nf4  Bh7  13.O-O-O  O-O  14.g5  +=  11...a5  12.cxd5  exd5  13.Bd3  Bxd3  14.Rxd3  +=  Winants-Wiedenkeller, Neum 2000.  4...Bxe2  5.Nxe2  e6 = }
4. Nf3
{ 4.Nc3 !?  is a line that deserves practical tests:  Bg4  5.Qd2  e6  6.f3  ∞ }
4... Bg4
{ This is the move most in the spirit of the Chigorin. Other options are:   4...Bf5  5.Bb5  Bd7  6.O-O  e6  +=  Landa-Balducchi, Ajaccio 2007;   4...e6  5.Nbd2  Bd6  6.c3  Nd7  7.Bxd6   7.Qb3  +=  7...cxd6  8.e4  dxe4  9.Nxe4  Nf6  10.Bd3  +=  Bogdanovski-Sipila, Warsaw 2013   4...Nh5 !?  is an interesting idea, for instance:  5.Bg5   5.Bg3  Nxg3  6.hxg3  Bg4  7.Bb5  +=   5.c3 ?!  g6 ?!   5...Nxf4 =  6.Bg5  f6  7.Bh4  +=  Paunovic-Arribas, Elgoibar 2013.  5...h6  6.Bh4  g5  7.Nfd2  Nf6   7...Bf5  8.Qxh5  Bg6  9.Qg4  gxh4  10.c3  +=   7...Ng7  8.Bg3  Nf5  9.c4  Nxg3  10.hxg3  Bg7  11.cxd5  Qxd5  12.Nc3  +=  Yedidia-Curdo, New England 1997  8.Bg3  +=  Akkozov-Khouseinov,Tashkent 2011; }
5. Bb5
{ This move is interesting. The idea is to threaten to damage Black's pawn structure with Bxc6 and after h2-h3 gain the bishop pair or else occupy e5 with the knight. Black cannot now advance e7-e5 in the future.  White has also tried   5.c4  e6  6.Nc3  Bb4  7.Rc1  Ne4   7...O-O =  8.Bd3  f5  9.Qb3  +=  Ibrahimov-Eidivadi, Mashhad 2010.   5.h3  Bxf3  6.Qxf3  e6  7.a3 = }
5... h6
{ If   5...Bxf3 ?!  then  6.Qxf3  e6  7.Nd2  Bd6  8.Bg5  a6  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  10.e4  +=  Bauer-Marie, Vandoeuvre 2008.  It seems best to play   5...e6  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  a6  8.Ba4   8.Bxc6+  +=  8...Be7  9.c3  b5  10.Bc2  +=  Oblitas-Morante, Sullana 2012. }
6. h3
{ Here it was good to play   6.c4 !  dxc4   6...e6  7.Qa4  ±  7.Nbd2  += } 6...
Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e6 8. c4 a6
{ It was better to complete development with   8...Bb4+  9.Nc3  O-O  10.O-O  although I prefer White. }
9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O
{ It was even better to play   10.c5 !  restricting the f8-bishop and closing the queenside, with a substantial advantage to White: he is going to be able to play Nc3, b2-b4 and a2-a4, followed by bringing a rook to b1 to prepare the break on b5. }
10... Bd6 11. Rc1 Rb8 12. b3 O-O 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Nc3 Rc8 15. Na4
{ The pawn on a6 is weak and the one on c7 is backward. White commands the half-open c-file, whereas Black is unable to make use of the b-file. }
15... Ne4 16. Rc6 Qf6
{ This loses material without compensation.  It was better to play   16...a5  17.Rac1  Qd7  18.R1c2  ± }
17. Bxd6 Qxf3 18. gxf3 Nxd6 19. Rxa6
{ The game is very straightforward for White, with an extra pawn and the better position. }
19... Rfd8 20. Rc1 Nf5 21. Rac6 { Winning a second pawn and the game. } 21...
Nh4 { 21...Rd7 ?  22.Nb6 } 22. f4 Nf3+ 23. Kg2 Nh4+ 24. Kf1 Nf3 25. Ke2 Nh4 26.
Rxc7 Rxc7 27. Rxc7 f6 28. Nc5 Re8 29. a4 e5 30. dxe5 fxe5 31. fxe5 Rxe5 32. a5
d4 33. a6 Nf5 34. Rc8+ Kh7 35. a7 dxe3 36. fxe3 Rxe3+ 37. Kd2 Rxh3 38. a8=Q
Rh2+ 39. Kc1
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@We have seen the Chigorin Defence, with Nc6, against the London System. This setup for Black is less effective here, because, having developed the bishop on f4 and played e2-e3, Blacks thematic move Bg4 presents fewer dangers to White.  In the game White emerged from the opening with the better game, especially after the dubious moves 5... h6 and 8... a6. Black was left with weak pawns on the queenside and once more White exploited the c-file to win the game. }
*

