[White "Vs ...d5 without early ...e6"]
[Black "The Jobava Attack"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now we shall analyse a line which has become quite fashionable and which is a cross between the Richter-Veresov  Attack with Nc3 and the London System with Bf4.  The strong grandmaster Baadur Jobava has been playing it regularly. Other strong grandmasters, such as Naiditsch, Rapport and Prié, have also included it in their repertoires. Grandmaster Henrik Danielsen also recommends using this line in the normal London System against the idea of ...c7-c5.  Even the Houdini engine often gives 2. Nc3 as the best move. Theory has moved on from the days when playing c2-c4 was the only approved idea for White in the Queen's Pawn Openings and nowadays in many lines it is fine to develop the knight first. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs ...d5 without early ...e6"]
[Black "Game 49 - Jobava vs. Savchenko"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ White can also use the move order   2.Bf4  d5  3.e3  c5  4.Nc3  In the traditional line, this move, recommended by grandmaster Danielsen, is also fashionable:  Nc6 ?   4...a6  5.dxc5  e6  6.Na4  Bxc5  7.Nxc5  Qa5+  8.c3  Qxc5  9.Nf3  Nc6  10.Bd3  +=   4...Qb6  5.Nb5  Na6  6.dxc5  +=   4...cxd4  5.exd4   5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Bb5  Bd7  7.Bxc6  Bxc6  8.Nf3  e6  9.O-O  Be7 =  5...a6   5...Nc6 ?!  6.Nb5  +=   5...Bg4  6.f3  Bf5  7.Nb5  Na6  +=   5...Qb6  6.Nb5  +=  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.Ne5  with a slight advantage to White according to Danielsen; I think that this position is playable for White but I do not think that he has any real advantage:  e6   7...Bf5  8.g4  Nxe5  9.gxf5  Nc6  10.Qd3  g6  11.O-O-O  +=  Hector-Andersen, Vxj 2013  8.Nxc6   8.Qd2  ∞  8...bxc6  9.Na4  Bd6 =  Heinzel-Leutwyler, Austria undesliga B 2013  5.Nb5  ± }
2... d5 3. Bf4
{ This is the fashionable line employed by grandmaster Jobava, a cross between the RichterVeresov and the London System. }
3... a6
{ 3...e6  a very solid and popular alternative  4.e3  and now:  Be7   4...Bd6  5.Nf3   5.Bd3  b6  6.Bg5 !?  Bb7  7.Qf3  h6  8.Qh3  Nbd7  9.Nb5 =  Harikrishna-Rakhmanov, Linares 2014  5...O-O  6.Bd3  c5  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.O-O   8.a3  Nc6  9.O-O  Bd6  10.Bxd6  Qxd6  11.e4  Rd8  +=  Pri-Lillo, Spain tt 2013  8...Nc6  9.e4  dxe4  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  +=  Jobava-Malakhov, Warsaw 2013;   4...Bb4  and now:  5.Nge2   5.Bd3  c5  6.dxc5  Nbd7  7.Nge2  O-O   7...Nxc5  8.a3  Nxd3+  9.Qxd3  Ba5  10.O-O-O  O-O  11.Bg5  h6  12.h4  Bd7  13.g4  Bc6  14.Rh3  e5 ?   14...Re8  ∞  15.Qf5  ±  Jobava-Shalamberidze, Ureki 2014.  8.O-O   8.Bd6  Re8  9.Bb5  a6  10.Bxd7  Nxd7  11.Qd4  Qa5 =  Jobava-Korneev, Sochi 2014.  8...Nxc5  9.Rc1  Bd7  10.a3  Nxd3  11.cxd3  Be7 =  Demidov-Panarin, Sochi RUS-tt rapid 2015;  5...O-O  6.a3  Bd6  7.Qd2   7.g3  b6  8.Bg2  Bb7  9.O-O  c5 =  Jobava-Caruana, Wijk aan Zee 2015   7.Ng3  c5  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Bd3  Nc6  10.O-O  Bd6 =  Navara-Wojtaszek, Berlin Wch rapid 2015  7...c5  8.O-O-O  Nc6 =  Jobava-Kravtsiv, Al-Ain 2013;  5.Bd3   5.Nf3  a6  6.Bd3  Nbd7  7.Ne5   7.e4 !?  7...c5  8.a3  Nxe5  9.Bxe5  c4  10.Be2  b5 =  Ganguly-Arizmendi, Linares 2014  5...c5   5...O-O  6.Nf3  c5  7.dxc5  Nc6   7...Bxc5  8.O-O  Nc6  9.e4  dxe4  10.Nxe4  Be7 =  Stefanova-Lagno, Khanty-Mansiysk 2014  8.O-O  Nd7  9.e4  d4 =  Wei Yi-Zhao Jun, Jiaxing 2014  6.dxc5  O-O   6...Bxc5  7.Nb5  +=  7.Nf3  Nbd7  8.b4  +=  Jobava-Andreev, Al-Ain 2013;  Black has also tried   3...c6  4.e3  g6   4...Qb6  5.Rb1  Bf5  6.Nf3  e6  7.Bd3  +=  Ibarra-Perez Candelario, Navalmoral 2012  5.Nf3   5.Be2  Bg7  6.h4  Qb6  7.a3  Nbd7  8.Nf3  O-O  ∞  Pri-Dominguez, Spain tt 2013   5.h3  Bg7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.Bd3  +=  Jrgens-Lomineishvili,Germany Frauenbundesliga 1998/99  5...Bg7  6.h4  h5  7.Ne5  Nbd7  8.Qd2  O-O  9.O-O-O  ∞  Romero-Crnkovic, Pula 2012;  Practice has also seen   3...g6  4.Qd2   4.e3  Bg7  5.Be2  O-O  6.Nf3  c5  transposes to the Barry Attack, which we examined in Chapter 2.  4...c6 !?   4...Bg7  5.Bh6  O-O  6.Bxg7  Kxg7 =  Cabrera-Dvirnyy, Spain tt 2014  5.f3  b5  6.a3  Bg7   6...Nbd7  7.e4  Nb6  8.e5  Ng8  9.Bd3  e6  10.Nh3 =  Boguszlavszkij-Szegi, Kisber 2011  7.Bh6  Bxh6  8.Qxh6  Qd6  9.e3  e5  10.Bd3  Nbd7  11.Nge2  +=  Jobava-Winants, Troms 2014. }
4. e3 g6
{ One month before this game, Jobava had faced   4...e6  5.Nf3  c5  6.a3   6.Qd2  6...Nc6  7.h3  b5  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Bd3  Bb7  10.O-O  Bd6  11.Re1 =  Jobava-Zhao Xue, Wijk aan Zee 2014. }
5. h4 Bg7 6. h5
{ This position resembles a Barry Attack, but one in which White has not yet developed his kingside knight or bishop. Jobava goes straight for the attack. Normal moves in the Barry would be   6.Be2   6.Nf3 }
6... Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5
{ White has sacrificed the exchange and has good compensation. Now kingside castling for Black would be dangerous, since White is going to castle queenside and has the better development. This sacrifice is similar to one played against the Leningrad Dutch. }
8... c6 9. Nf3 h6 10. O-O-O Nd7 11. Qh2 Nf8 12. Bc7 Qd7 13. Be2
{ Here   13.Na4  Ne6  14.Be5  was interesting; White has good compensation. }
13... Ne6 14. Be5 b5 15. Rh1 f6 16. Bg3 Ng5 17. Ne1
{ White avoids exchanges, because Blacks king is still in the centre and Black is behind in development. White can keep quietly improving his pieces, since his compensation is long-lasting. }
17... O-O 18. Nd3 Qf5 19. Bf4 a5 20. Nc5 Qh7 21. g4
{ White is now better: the bishop on g7 is passive, as is the black queen; Whites knight on c5 is very strong and he threatens 22. Bd3. }
21... Qg6 22. Bc7 b4 { If   22...Qf7  then  23.f4  Ne6  24.Bb6  += } 23. N3a4
e5 24. Nb6 Ra7 25. Bd6 Re8 26. f4 Nf7 27. g5
{ Opening lines; this is better than   27.Bb8  Rae7  28.f5  Qg5 = } 27... Nxd6
{ Black makes a mistake; he needed to play   27...fxg5  28.Nxc8  Rxc8  29.Bxe5  Nxe5  30.dxe5  += }
28. Bh5 Qf5 29. gxh6 Ree7
{ This loses; it was essential to play   29...exf4  30.Bxe8  Nxe8  31.hxg7  Rxg7  32.Nxc8  Qxc8  33.Qxf4  ± }
30. hxg7 Rxg7 31. fxe5 fxe5 32. Nxc8 Nxc8
{ If   32...Qxc8  then  33.dxe5  Nf7  34.Bxf7+  Kxf7  35.Qh5+  Kf8  36.Qh6  and Whites attack is decisive. But how should White continue now ? }
33. Bg6
{ An excellent move that accomplishes the task in brilliant fashion: White clears the h-file. }
33... Qxg6
{ 33...Rxg6  loses to  34.Qh8+  Kf7  35.Rh7+  Rg7  36.Rxg7+  Kf6  37.Qf8+  Rf7  38.Qxf7# }
34. Qh8+ Kf7 35. Rf1+ { Black must give up his queen with } 35... Qf6
{ since   35...Ke7  36.Qf8#  .   @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@We have seen an alternative line, one that is interesting and fashionable, the so-called Jobava Attack. The Georgian grandmaster has employed it regularly, as have some other strong grandmasters.  The line is a cross between the Richter-Veresov with  2.Nc3  and the London System with  2.Bf4.  There are quite a lot of games available, but ones by strong grandmasters have only appeared in the last few years.  Ideas involving  Nc3  (without c2-c4)  are now quite common in the London System and often this move is the top recommendation of the Houdini engine. In this game Black responded with  3...a6  , to prevent the idea of  Nb5  , and we also analysed other options for Black.  Jobava played very aggressively against Black's fianchetto and sacrificed an exchange at a very early stage. The positions with g7-g6 resemble the Barry Attack. Jobava obtained very good compensation and his position got better and better.  Then, when he already had the advantage, following an error by his opponent, he finished off the game brilliantly with  33.Bg6  !. }
*

