{ The Jobava Attack . Now we shall analyse a line which has become quite fashionable and which is a cross between the Richter-Veresov Attack with Nc3 and the London System with Bf4. The strong grandmaster Baadur Jobava has been playing it regularly. Other strong grandmasters, such as Naiditsch, Rapport and Pri, have also included it in their repertoires. Grandmaster Henrik Danielsen also recommends using this line in the normal London System against the idea of c7-c5. Even the Houdini engine often gives 2. Nc3 as the best move. Theory has moved on from the days when playing c2-c4 was the only approved idea for White in the Queens Pawn Openings and nowadays in many lines it is fine to develop the knight first. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4
{ This is the fashionable line employed by grandmaster Jobava, a cross between the RichterVeresov and the London System. }
3... a6 4. e3 g6 5. h4 Bg7 6. h5
{ This position resembles a Barry Attack, but one in which White has not yet developed his kingside knight or bishop. Jobava goes straight for the attack. Normal moves in the Barry would be }
6... Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5
{ White has sacrificed the exchange and has good compensation. Now kingside castling for Black would be dangerous, since White is going to castle queenside and has the better development. This sacrifice is similar to one played against the Leningrad Dutch. }
8... c6 9. Nf3 h6 10. O-O-O Nd7 11. Qh2 Nf8 12. Bc7 Qd7 { Here } 13. Na4 Ne6
14. Be5 { was interesting; White has good compensation. } *

