1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 Bf5
{ In the previous game we saw 3... a6, and we shall see 3... c5 in the next game. }
4. f3
{ The most popular response;  The alternative is   4.e3  e6  5.Nf3  Be7  6.Ne5  h6  7.g4  Bh7  8.Bd3  c6   8...Bxd3 =  9.Bxh7  Nxh7  10.Qf3  +=  Rapport-Pajeken, Reykjavik 2014. }
4... e6 5. g4
{ The alternative   5.Qd2  Be7  6.O-O-O  Nc6  7.Qe1 ?!  Bg6  8.Nh3  O-O  9.Nf2 ?!  Nh5  10.Be3  Nb4  ∓  was played in Naiditsch-Harikrishna, Wijk aan Zee 2014. }
5... Bg6 6. h4 h6
{ The advance   6...h5  has also been played:  7.g5  Nfd7  8.e3  and now:  c5   8...a6  9.Bd3  Bxd3  and now:  10.cxd3   10.Qxd3  c5   10...g6 ?!  11.e4  c6  12.Nge2  Bg7  13.O-O-O  +=  Vidovic-Grachev, Croatia tt 2014  11.g6 !?   11.O-O-O  is playable, with a balanced game  11...f6  12.Nge2   12.O-O-O  12...Nc6  13.a3  Qb6  14.Bh2  O-O-O  15.O-O-O =  Ipatov-Kantans, Troms 2014.  10...Nc6   10...c5  11.dxc5  Bxc5  12.d4  Be7  13.Nge2  Nc6 =  Juhasz-Nikolova, Budapest 2015  11.g6 ?!   11.Nge2 =  11...fxg6   11...f6  =+  12.Bg5  Be7  13.f4  Nf6  =+  Jobava-Nakamura, Khanty-Mansiysk 2015;  9.Bd3   9.Nb5  Na6  10.c3  9...Bxd3  10.Qxd3  Nc6  11.g6   11.O-O-O  11...f6  ∞  Boguszlavszkij-Lukacs, Budapest 2010; }
7. e3
{ White's idea is reminiscent of play in the Caro-Kann: he gains space on the kingside with g2-g4 and h2-h4-h5, and then exchanges the bishops on d3. }
7... c5
{ The thematic idea to break the white centre. There are several alternatives for Black here:   7...c6  and now:  8.Bd3   8.h5  Bh7  9.Bd3  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  Bd6  11.Nge2  Bxf4  12.exf4 !?   12.Nxf4  O-O  13.O-O-O =  12...Nbd7  13.Qe3   13.O-O-O !?  13...Qe7  14.Nc1 =  Jobava-Salgado, Yerevan 2014, a game in which Jobava won an interesting endgame.  8...Bxd3  9.Qxd3   9.cxd3 !?  Bd6  10.Nge2  Bxf4  11.Nxf4  Nbd7  12.Kf2 =  Rapport-Sachdev, Gibraltar 2014  9...Bd6  10.O-O-O   10.Nge2  Na6  11.O-O-O  Bxf4  12.Nxf4  Qa5  13.g5  ±  Colovic-Nikolic, Serbia tt 2013  10...Qe7  11.Nge2  Nbd7  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.e4 !  dxe4  14.fxe4  Nxg4 ?!   14...e5  15.g5  hxg5 ?   15...Ng4 !  16.Qf3  h5  16.hxg5  Rxh1  17.Rxh1  Ng8  18.d5  ±  Nabaty-Samblic, Malinska 2014  15.e5 ?   15.Qf3 !  h5  16.e5  Qe7  17.Ne4  ±  15...Qe7 ?   15...Ndxe5 !  16.dxe5  Qxd3  17.cxd3  Nf2 =  16.Ne4 ?!   16.Qf3 !  ±  16...O-O-O  +=  Thorfinnsson-Nordenbaek, Ballerup 2014;   7...Bd6  8.h5   8.Nh3  Nc6  9.Qd2   9.Bd3  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  e5 =  9...e5  10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Bxe5  Bxe5  12.O-O-O  c6  13.Nf4 =  Nabaty-Gomez Esteban, Benasque 2012   8.Bd3  Bxf4  9.exf4  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  Qd6 =  Isik-Sengul, Kocaeli 2014  8...Bh7  9.Bd3  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  a6   10...Nc6  11.Nge2  Qd7  12.O-O-O  O-O-O  13.Bxd6  cxd6  14.Nf4 =  Vorontsov-Vignesh, Moscow 2014  11.Nge2  c5  12.dxc5  Bxc5  13.O-O-O  Nc6 =  Stefanova-Dzagnidze, KhantyMansiysk 2014;   7...a6  and now:  8.Bd3   8.h5  Bh7  9.Bd3  Bxd3   9...c5  10.Nge2  Bxd3  11.cxd3  cxd4  12.Nxd4  Nbd7 =  Jobava-Hovhannisyan, Yerevan 2014.  10.Qxd3   10.cxd3  Bd6  11.Nge2  Nc6  12.Qd2  Qe7  13.O-O-O  ∞  Jobava-Nepomniachtchi, Dubai 2014  10...c5  11.dxc5  Bxc5  12.Nge2  Nc6  13.Nd4  Nazaretyan-Zakharov, Russia tt 2015;  8...Bxd3  9.Qxd3   9.cxd3  Bd6  10.Nge2  Bxf4  11.Nxf4  Qd6 =  Zavgorodniy-Kanarek, Katowice 2014  9...c5  10.Nge2   10.Nce2  Nc6  11.c3  Bd6  12.O-O-O  ∞  Nakamura-Nepomniachtchi, Dubai 2014   10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.O-O-O  Nc6  12.Nge2  Qa5  13.Kb1  ∞  Bortnyk-Munguntuul, Moscow 2015   10.O-O-O !?  is also playable here  10...Nc6  11.O-O-O  c4  12.Qd2  ∞  Putka-Neiksans, Jurmala 2016; }
8. h5
{ 8.Bd3  has also been played, e.g.  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  Nc6  10.Nge2  cxd4  11.exd4 =  Boguszlavszkij-Turzo, Budapest 2009. }
8... Bh7
{ Having played c7-c5, Black is on the verge of having a good position. What should White play now ? }
9. Nb5
{ This knight move is thematic in several lines, as in the Dutch. White's idea, in addition to gaining a tempo, is to bolster his centre with c2-c3 and redeploy his knight. It also forces Black to develop his knight to a bad square, from which it does not move for the rest of the game. }
9... Na6 10. c3 Be7 11. Bd3
{ Another possibility is   11.dxc5  Bxc5  12.b4  Be7  13.Bd3  Bxd3  14.Qxd3  O-O  15.Ne2 = }
11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nd7
{ Black delays castling; if   12...O-O  13.g5  and White has the attack. } 13.
Ne2 O-O { But now Black castles, because he has the g5-square under control. }
14. a4
{ An idea for White here is to play   14.Kf2  connecting the rooks. We have seen several examples of how White can place his king here without any problems. }
14... Bf6 15. Bd6 Re8 { It was better to play   15...Be7 = } 16. f4
{ Again   16.Kf2 !  seems good. } 16... Nb6
{ It was to better to deprive White of the right to castle with   16...Bh4+  forcing  17.Kf1   17.Kd1  with a complex position and chances for both sides. }
17. g5 hxg5 18. h6 g6
{ The best defence.  If   18...gxh6  19.Rxh6  wins  or   18...gxf4  19.hxg7  Bh4+  20.Kf1  Qf6   20...Kxg7  21.Rg1+  Kh8  22.Be5+  Bf6   22...f6  23.Qg6  23.exf4  21.Be5  Qh6  22.Nxf4 }
19. fxg5 Bxg5 20. h7+ Kg7
{ if   20...Kh8  21.Be5+  Bf6   21...f6  22.Nd6  Rf8  23.Bf4  ±  22.Nd6  with a clear advantage to White. }
21. Be5+ f6
{ It was better to defend with   21...Bf6  22.Nd6  Bxe5  23.dxe5  although White maintains the advantage. How should White continue now ? }
22. Nd6
{ 22.Nf4 !  Bxf4  23.Rg1 !!  a difficult but important move  would have been decisive; the attack on the black king is unstoppable, e.g.  g5   23...fxe5  24.Qxg6+  Kh8  25.Qg7#  24.exf4 !  fxe5   24...Kh8  25.Rxg5  +-  25.Rxg5+  Kh8   25...Qxg5  26.fxg5  +-  26.Qg6  Qe7  27.Nd6 !  the knight always lands on d6 to put the icing on the cake  Rf8  28.O-O-O  with unstoppable mate in five:  exd4  29.Qg8+  Rxg8  30.hxg8=Q+  Rxg8  31.Rh1+  Qh7  32.Nf7#  that would have been a wonderful finish, wouldnt it ? }
22... Rh8
{ It was better to play   22...fxe5 !  23.Nxe8+  Qxe8  24.h8=Q+  Qxh8  25.Rxh8  Rxh8  26.O-O-O  += }
23. Nf4 { Now it seems that Jobava has finally seen the winning idea } 23...
Bxf4 24. Bxf4
{ Alas, no; he fails to see   24.Rg1 !!  g5  25.exf4  fxe5  26.Rxg5+  winning in even simpler fashion than in the variation given above. }
24... g5 25. O-O-O
{ 25.Ke2  also gives White a decisive advantage after  Nc4  26.Rh6 !  Kxh6  27.Nf7+  +- }
25... Nc4 { It is time to realise White's advantage. How should he continue ? }
26. Rh6
{ Very spectacular, although not the best; there was a simpler win with   26.Nxc4 !  dxc4  27.Qc2  cxd4  28.Rxd4 !  Qe7  29.Qh2  e5  30.Qh6+  Kf7  31.Qh5+  Kf8   31...Kg7  32.Bxg5  fxg5  33.Qh6+  Kf7  34.Rf1+  Ke8  35.Qh5+  32.Bxg5  Rxh7   32...fxg5  33.Rf1+  33.Qxh7   33.Bh6+  33...Qxh7  34.Rxh7  fxg5   34...exd4  35.Rh8+  35.Rdd7  +- }
26... Kxh6
{ 26...Qe7  27.Qg6+  Kf8  28.Be5 !!  Nxe5   28...fxe5  29.Rf1+   28...Qg7  29.Qxf6+  Qxf6  30.Rxf6+  Kg7   30...Ke7  31.Rf7+  Kd8  32.Bf6#  31.Rf7+  Kg6  32.Rg7+  Kh5  33.Nf7  with unstoppable mate   28...Nxd6  29.Bxd6  Qxd6  30.Qxf6+  +-  29.dxe5  Qg7  30.Qh5  fxe5  31.Rxe6  with a decisive advantage. }
27. Nf7+ Kg7 28. Nxd8 Raxd8
{ White is winning: he has an edge in material, the black king is still very weak, the black knights are out of play and the pawn on h7 is a nuisance. }
29. b3
{ There was a simpler win starting with   29.e4 !  Rxh7   29...gxf4  30.Rg1+  Kf7  31.exd5  exd5  32.Qg6+  Ke6  33.Qg4+ !  Kd6  34.Qxf4+  Ke6   34...Kc6  35.Qxf6+  Nd6  36.Qxd8  Rxd8  37.Rg8  +-  35.Qg4+  Kd6  36.Qg7  30.exd5  exd5  31.Bxg5  fxg5  32.Qf5  with a decisive attack, for example:  Rf8  33.Qxg5+  Kh8  34.Qxd5  Nb6  35.Qe5+  Rg7  36.Rg1  Rff7  37.Qe8+  Kh7  38.Rh1+  Kg6  39.Qe4+  with mate in a few moves. }
29... Nb6 30. Rg1 Rxh7 31. e4
{ 31.Bxg5 !  was also winning, e.g.  fxg5  32.Rxg5+  Kh8  33.dxc5  Nd7   33...Nxc5 ??  34.Qd4+  34.c6 }
31... Kh8 { 31...cxd4  32.e5  +- } 32. e5 gxf4
{ This hastens Black's defeat, but there was no defence; if   32...Nd7  33.exf6  +-  or   32...cxd4  33.exf6  +- }
33. Qg6 Rf8 34. exf6
{ And Black resigned, in view of the unstoppable mate after } 34... Nd7 35. f7
Nc7 { 35...Rhxf7  36.Rh1+  Rh7  37.Rxh7#   35...Rfxf7  36.Qg8# } 36. Qg8+ Rxg8
37. Rxg8#
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we continued to study the Jobava Attack. We analysed the reply 3Bf5, which is one of the most popular. White's plan consists of gaining space on the kingside by advancing his pawns against the black bishop, similar to what happens in the Caro-Kann, and then exchange bishops on d3.  Black played 7c5, but in that position he has other interesting options as well, such as 7a6, 7Bd6 or 7c6. White employed the plan of Nb5 and then gained a strong attack against the black king. He won material with the pretty 26. Rh6, although he missed good chances to finish the struggle sooner with the idea of Nf4 and Rg1 !!.  Jobava exposed the black king by sacrificing material and finished the game with a mating attack. Both players made mistakes, but these are excusable, since this game was played in the World Rapidplay Championship in Dubai. Nevertheless, the game has some very good points and is well worth analysing. It is a good illustration of the dangers facing Black. }
*

