[White "Vs ...d5 without early ...e6"]
[Black "Game 51 - Rapport vs. Sutovsky"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5
{ We shall conclude our survey of the Jobava Attack by examining this very thematic black option. }
4. e3
{ The normal move.  Here   4.e4 !?  is interesting, e.g.  Nxe4   4...dxe4  5.d5  transposes to the Morris Gambit, which we looked at earlier;  5.Nxe4   5.dxc5 =  5...dxe4  6.d5 !?   6.dxc5 =  6...Nd7  7.Ne2  g6  8.Nc3  Bg7  9.Qd2  f5 ?!   9...Nf6  10.O-O-O  ∞  Boguszlavszk ij-Flumbort,Hungary tt 2010/11  10.Nb5  Ne5  11.d6 !  O-O ?   11...exd6  +=  12.Bxe5  Bxe5  13.Qd5+  1-0 Boguszlavszkij-Wang, Budapest 2012. }
4... cxd4
{ 4...a6  5.dxc5  Nc6  6.a3   6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Be2  e6  8.Na4  Ne4 =  Stripunsky-Perelshteyn,Ledyard 2014  6...e5  7.Bg5  d4  8.exd4   8.Bxf6  gxf6   8...Qxf6  9.Nd5  +=  9.Na4  +=  8...exd4   8...Nxd4 =  9.Ne4  +=  Nakamura-Fressinet, Dubai 2014   4...e6  5.Nb5  Na6  and here there are several options for White:  6.c3 !   6.h3  Be7  7.Nf3  Ne4  8.c3  c4  9.a4  +=  Stefanova-Kosteniuk, Khanty-Mansiysk 2014   6.Nf3  Be7  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.a3  +=  Agdestein-Johannessen, Oslo 2010;   6.a4  Be7  7.c3  O-O  8.h3  Bd7  9.Nf3  +=  Short-Amonatov, Bangkok 2012  6...Qb6 ?!   6...Be7  7.dxc5   7.a4  +=  7...Bxc5  8.Nf3  O-O  9.Bd3  Be7 =  Hoang Thanh Trang-Kravtsiv, Chennai 2012  7.a4  Bd7  8.Nf3  ±  transposing to the variation with c7-c5 and Qb6 which we analysed in the chapter on the Benoni and which gives White a clear advantage, as in Iotov-Inkiov, Sunny Beach 2014; }
5. exd4 a6 6. Nf3
{ At this point various moves have been tried:   6.Be2  Nc6  7.Nf3  Bg4  8.O-O  e6  9.Ne5   9.h3  Bh5  10.Re1  Bd6  11.Bxd6  Qxd6 =  Colovic-Ivanov, Novi Sad 2016  9...Bxe2  10.Nxe2  Nxe5   10...Be7 =  Vaisser-Postny, St Quentin 2014  11. Bxe5 Nd7 =  Kovacevic-Kuljasevic, Croatia tt 2010;   6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Be3  Bg4  8.f3  Bh5  9.Nge2  e6  Danov-Arnaudov, Albena 2014;   6.Qd2  Nc6  7.a3   7.O-O-O  e6  8.Qe3  b5  9.Nf3 ?!  b4  10.Na4  Qa5  =+  Colovic-Vrbljanac,Valjevo 2011  7...e6  8.Nf3  Bd6  9.Bd3  h6  10.O-O =  Hoang-Akshat, New Delhi 2012   6.Nce2  Nc6  7.c3  g6  8.Nf3  Bg7  9.Nc1  O-O  10.Be2  Ne4 =  Shimanov-Geller,Moscow 2014. }
6... Bg4
{ Another option is   6...Nc6  and now:  7.h3   7.Ne5  and now:  e6   7...Bd7  8.Qd3  Rc8  9.a3  g6  10.Be2  Bg7  11.O-O =  Bauer-Abel, Berlin Wch blitz 2015;   7...g6  8.Qd2  Bg7  9.Be2  Be6  10.h4  Rc8  11.h5  ∞  Bromann-Stenner, Germany tt 2016;   7...Bf5  8.g4  Nxe5   8...Be6  9.h3   9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.g5  +=   9.Bg2  h6  10.O-O  g5  11.Bg3 =  Petrusic-Pucovski, Novi Sad 2016  9...g6  10.Qd2   10.Bg2  +=  10...Bg7  11.Bg2  Rc8  12.O-O-O  +=  Bauer-Kirszenberg, Le Port Marly 2012  9.gxf5  Nc6  10.Qd3 =  Hector-Andersen, Vxj 2013.  8.Nxc6   8.Be2  Bd6  9.O-O  Qc7  10.Re1  O-O =  Bortnyk-Gavrilov, Schwbisch Gmnd 2016  8...bxc6  9.Na4  Bd6  10.Bxd6  Qxd6  11.Bd3   11.Be2  O-O  12.O-O  Nd7  13.c4 =  Romanov-Wagner, Berlin Wch rapid 2015  11...O-O  12.O-O  e5  13.dxe5  Qxe5  14.Qf3  Rapport-Bu Xiangzhi, Tsaghkadzor 2015   7.Qd2 !?  Bf5  8.Bd3  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  e6 =   7.a3  Bg4  8.Be2  Bxf3  9.Bxf3  e6  10.Be3  Be7  11.O-O  Qc7  12.Qe2 =  Bortnyk-Santos, Manacor 2016  7...e6   7...g6  8.Ne5   8.Be2  Bg7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Ne5 =  Williams-Hawkins, Coventry 2015  8...Bg7  9.Qd2 =  Danielsen-Gagare, New Delhi 2012   7...Bf5  8.Bd3   8.Be2  e6  9.O-O  Bd6  10.Bxd6  Qxd6 =  Milanovic-Wagner, Berlin Wch rapid 2015  8...Bxd3  9.Qxd3  e6  10.O-O   10.g4 ?!  Bd6  11.Be3 ?!  Rc8  12.g5 ?!  Nb4  ∓  Khotenashvili-Stefanova, Beijing 2014  10...Bd6  11.Bg5  O-O   11...h6  12.Bh4  O-O  13.a3  Rc8 =  Miladinovic-Dizdarevic, Belgrade 2010  12.Rae1  Be7  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.Nd1  b5  15.Ne3 =  Kovalev-Mirzoev, Minsk 2015  8.Bd3  Bd6 =  Kovalev-Blbaum, Berlin Wch rapid 2015 }
7. h3
{ Best;   7.Be2  Nc6  8.Ne5  Bxe2  9.Nxe2  e6   9...g6  10.c3  Bg7  11.Ng3  Rc8  12.O-O  O-O =  Stefanova-Khotenashvili, Lopota 2014  10.c3  Bd6   10...Rc8  11.O-O  Bd6  12.Nd3  O-O =  Boguszlavszkij-Kislik, Heviz ch-HUN 2011  11.Nd3  O-O =  Miladinovic-Jankovic, Rogaska Slatina 2009. }
7... Bxf3
{ Better than   7...Bh5 ?!  8.g4  Bg6  9.Ne5 !  Nc6   9...Ne4 ?!  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  11.f3  Bg6  12.h4  ±  Heinzel-Platzgummer, Austria undesliga B 2013/14  10.h4 !  Qb6  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Na4  Qa5+  13.c3  += }
8. Qxf3 Nc6
{ Here Black has also tried   8...e6  9.O-O-O  Bd6  10.Bxd6  Qxd6  11.g4  Nc6  12.g5  Nd7  13.h4  Ne7   13...b5  14.h5  O-O  15.Kb1  +=  Vojinovic-Burrows, Caleta 2015  14.h5  O-O-O  +=  Ferreira-Illingworth, Troms 2014. }
9. O-O-O
{ A normal move, and better than   9.Ne2  e6  10.c3  Qb6  11.Rb1  Rc8 =  Fries-Agrest, Sweden 2014. }
9... e6 10. g4
{ The typical plan for White, after castling queenside, is to start a pawn storm on the kingside. However, since Black has not castled yet he has more options. }
10... Bb4
{ Sutovsky's move was a novelty at the time. Black has also played:   10...Qa5 ?!  11.g5  Nd7  12.Kb1  +=  Semiev-Seliverstov, Moscow 2015   10...b5  11.g5  Nd7  12.h4  Be7  +=  Korley-Flaquer, Arlington 2015   10...Qb6 ?!  11.g5  Nd7  12.Qe3  O-O-O ?!  13.h4  ±  Bauer-Bindrich, Biel 2008;   10...Bd6 !  seems best. Nikolic employed it against Rapport himself, one month after the Sutovsky game:  11.Be3   11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.h4 =   11.g5  Bxf4+  12.Qxf4  Nh5  13.Qe3  Qd6  14.h4   14.Be2  - Georgescu-Berescu, Rumania tt 2014  14...Na5  with equality  11...Qa5   11...b5 !?  12.g5  Nd7  13.Kb1  Nb6  ∞  12.Kb1  Rc8  13.g5  Nd7  with equality in Rapport-Nikolic, Palic 2014, although Rapport managed to win;   10...Rc8  11.Kb1  Bb4  12.Ne2  Ne4  13.Ng3  Qb6  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Qe3  +=  BerczesPeczely, Zalakaros 2014. }
11. Ne2
{ White avoids exchanges and also decides to redeploy his knight.  It was possible to play   11.g5  Bxc3   11...Ng8  12.Qxc3  Ne4  13.Qe3  O-O  14.Kb1  with a balanced position. }
11... Qa5 { 11...O-O   11...Bd6  were also good moves. } 12. Kb1 Ne4 13. Nc1
{ Rapport continues with his plan of redeploying his knight. The young Hungarians play is very original and it is obvious that he likes to play positions that are unusual and sharp. Here   13.Qe3  was also good. }
13... Bd6
{ 13...Qb6 !  14.Nb3  a5  15.a4  O-O  16.h4 =  seems a better defence. } 14.
Nb3 Qc7 15. Be3 O-O { Better was to delay castling with   15...a5 = } 16. Rg1
{ It looks better to complete development with   16.Bd3  f5  17.Rhg1  when White has the initiative; he is going to open the g-file, although Black has counterplay and possibilities of defence. }
16... b5 { Again   16...a5 !  17.a4  Na7 =  was better. } 17. Bd3 f5
{ This is an error.  It was better to sacrifice a pawn, either with   17...a5 !  18.Bxe4  dxe4  19.Qxe4  a4  or   17...Ne7  18.Bxe4  dxe4  19.Qxe4  Nd5  with good compensation in either case. }
18. gxf5 exf5
{ Here   18...Rxf5  was slightly better, although after  19.Qg2  Nb4   19...Bh2  20.Rge1  ±  20.Bxe4   20.Nc5  Bxc5  21.Bxe4  dxe4  22.dxc5  ±  20...dxe4  21.Qxe4  Re8  White would have a clear advantage. }
19. Bh6 { White's attack is very dangerous. } 19... Rf7 20. Bxg7
{ A piece sacrifice to open Blacks castled position: White will either recover his material or obtain a strong mating attack. }
20... Rxg7 21. Qxf5 Kh8
{ The best defence;  other moves lose in simpler fashion, such as   21...Ne7  22.Qe6+  Kh8  23.Rxg7  Kxg7  24.Rg1+  Ng6   24...Kh8  25.Bxe4  dxe4  26.Qf6#  25.Qxd5   21...Qf7  22.Bxe4  dxe4  23.Qxe4  Rc8  24.Rxg7+  Kxg7   24...Qxg7  25.Qe6+  25.Qg4+  with a winning advantage. }
22. Rxg7 Qxg7 { 22...Kxg7  23.Bxe4  dxe4  24.Rg1+ } 23. Qxd5 Nxf2 24. Qxc6 Rf8
{ After the tactical skirmishing, White has emerged with two extra pawns and a decisive advantage. }
25. Rc1
{ It was even better to sacrifice the exchange and eliminate Blacks queenside pawns with   25.Qxa6 !  Nxd1  26.Qxd6  Nf2  27.Bxb5 }
25... Nxd3 26. cxd3 Qg3 27. a3 Bf4 { 27...Qxd3+  28.Ka2  Bf4  29.Nc5 } 28. Rd1
Qxh3 29. Nc5 Be3 30. Qe4 Qf3 31. Qe5+
{ Rapport shows good judgement in avoiding the exchange of queens: he wants to attack, because the white pieces are more active and the black king is more exposed, whereas the white king is in no danger. }
31... Kg8 32. Re1 Bf2 33. Re4 { The rook joins in the attack ! } 33... Qf5 34.
Qc7 Kh8 35. Ne6 Rg8 36. d5
{ It was slightly better to play   36.Qc3  Qd5  37.Nf4  Qd7  38.d5+  Qg7  39.Qb3 }
36... Bh4 37. Qc5 Bf6 38. Ka2 h5
{ This hastens the defeat, although Black would also be lost after   38...Be5  39.Re2 }
39. Rf4 Qg6 { 39...Qe5 ?  40.d4 } 40. d6 Bg7 41. Qf5 Kh7 { 41...Qxf5  42.Rxf5 }
42. d7 Qxf5 43. Rxf5 Kg6 44. Rf8
{ A neat finish; the d-pawn cannot be prevented from queening.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw Black play 3... c5, followed by exchanging pawns on d4 and then the plan of Bg4 and Bxf3, which is considered solid for Black.  Sutovsky then played the novelty 11... Bb4, although 11... Bd6 seems better, as Nikolic played soon after. White castled on the queenside and advanced his kingside pawns a typical plan. Rapport showed originality in playing Nc3-e2-c1 and Be3, preventing piece exchanges.   However, Black had everything under control until he made a serious error with 17f5 ?. White then opened the g-file and, after a piece sacrifice on g7, obtained a strong attack and a decisive advantage.  White could have concluded the game more quickly, but in the endgame the advance of White's d-pawn proved decisive. }
*

