1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d5 6. Nbd2 Bd6
{ The alternative is 6... Be7, which we shall look at further on. } 7. Bg3
{ The normal response, with the idea of opening the h-file, if Black captures on g3, or playing f2-f4 in the future.  Practice has also seen:   7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Bd3  Qe7  9.e4  dxe4  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  e5 =  Harikrishna-Zaragatski, Vlissingen 2013;   7.Bxd6  Qxd6  8.Bb5   8.Bd3  O-O  9.O-O  e5  10.dxc5  Qxc5  11.e4  Bg4  12.Qc2 =  Abasov-Idani, Al-Ain 2013  8...Bd7  9.O-O  O-O  10.a4   10.Qb3  a6  11.Bxc6  Bxc6  12.Qa3  Nd7 =  Nguyen-Caruana, Biel 2010  10...a6   10...Rac8  11.Qb3  Rfd8  12.Qa3  +=  Moreno-Georgiev, Jaen 2011  11.Bxc6  Bxc6  12.Ne5  Nd7 =  Kveinys-Kryvoruchko, Cappelle-la-Grande 2008. }
7... O-O
{ Exchanging on g3 is also playable:   7...Bxg3  8.hxg3  Qd6  9.Bb5   9.Qc2  h6  10.Bb5  Bd7 =  Kovacevic-Dizdarevic, Sarajevo 1982  9...Bd7  10.Bxc6   10.Qe2   10.O-O  10...Bxc6  11.Ne5  Nd7   11...Bb5  12.Qb3  +=   11...O-O  12.g4  Nd7  13.Qc2  +=  Kamsky-Dlugy,New York 1989   11...h6  12.g4  +=  12.Nxd7   12.f4  Nxe5  13.fxe5  Qe7  14.Qg4  f5  15.Qh5+  Kd7  ∞  Kamsky-Potkin, Khanty-Mansiysk Wch blitz 2013  12...Bxd7  13.Nf3  h6  14.Ne5  cxd4  15.exd4  Qe7  16.Qg4  +=  Abdulla-Ghosh, Calcutta 2014. }
8. Bd3
{ This is one of the key positions in this variation. Black has several options at this point, while White must prevent Black from playing e6-e5. }
8... Qe7
{ We shall see the move 8... b6 in another game.  Here   8...Qc7 ?!  is dubious, owing to  9.dxc5  Bxg3  10.hxg3  e5  11.e4  +=  Markus-Papp,Sarajevo 2013.  An alternative is   8...Re8  when White can play  9.Ne5 !  and now:  cxd4   9...Qc7  10.f4   10.Nxc6  Qxc6  11.Nf3  Nd7 =  10...Nd7 ?   10...Ne7  11.Qf3  Nf5  12.Bf2  ∞  11.Bxh7+  ±   9...Bxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.f4 !?  This move involves a pawn sacrifice:  Instead of 11. f4 !? the normal move would be   11.Nf3  and now:  Qc7   11...Nf8  12.h4   12.O-O  +=  12...f5  13.h5  +=  Danielsen-Skytte, Borup 2010   11...f6  12.exf6  Nxf6  13.Ne5  +=  Torre-Bitoon, Manila 2011;   11...a6  12.O-O  b5  13.a4   13.e4  Bb7  14.exd5  exd5  15.Re1  +=  13...Rb8  14.axb5  axb5  15.Qe2  +=  Pri-Flear, Narbonne 2007.  12.O-O  g6   12...h6  13.e4  +=   12...Ndxe5 ??  13.Nxe5  Nxe5  14.Qh5  +-  13.Bb5   13.Re1  Ndxe5  14.e4  =∞  13...a6  14.Bxc6  bxc6  15.e4  Rb8  16.b3  a5  17.Qd2  Ba6  18.Rfe1  +=  11...c4  12.Bc2  Qb6  13.O-O  Qxb2   13...Qxe3+  14.Kh1  =∞  14.Rc1  Nc5   14...f5 ?!  15.exf6  Nxf6  16.Bh4  =∞  Mitkov-Shulman,Bolingbrook 2005   14...Qxa2  15.Bh4   15.e4  =∞  15...Qa3  16.Rf3  g6  17.Rh3  =∞  Moradiabadi-Nasri, Jakarta 2011  15.Rf2   15.e4 !  =∞  15...Qa3  16.Bh4  Nd3   16...b6  =+  17.Bxd3  cxd3  =∞  Cvetnic-Tinture, cr Belgium 2002.  10.exd4  Bxe5  11.dxe5  Nd7  12.Nf3   12.f4  Qb6  13.Nb3  Qe3+  14.Qe2  Qxe2+  15.Bxe2  +=  12...f6  13.exf6  gxf6  +=  Vaisser-Buhmann, France tt 2013;  Finally let us examine the continuation   8...a6  when White can again play various moves :  9.Ne5 !  White has also tried   9.Qe2  Re8  10.Ne5  Ne7  11.Ndf3  Rf8  12.dxc5  Bxc5  13.O-O  +=  Elianov-Malakhatko, St Petersburg 2012   9.O-O  Bxg3  10.hxg3  c4   10...cxd4  11.exd4  b6  12.Qc2  Bb7  13.Ne5  g6 =  11.Bc2  b5  12.e4 =  Zilberman-Kataev, Ramat Aviv 2004  9...Ne7   9...Bxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.Qb1  f5   11...h6 =  12.f4  c4 =  Heinzel-Martin, Nuremberg 2011;   9...Qc7  10.f4  Nd7  11.O-O  f6   11...g6  12.Qg4  f5  13.Qh3  Kg7  14.Bh4  +=  Tuerlinckx-Bennett, Prague 2012   11...cxd4  12.exd4  Qb6  13.Ndf3 !  Nf6   13...Qxb2 ?  14.Bxh7+ !  Kxh7  15.Ng5+  Kg8  16.Nxd7  ±  14.Qe2  +=  Banoci-Skrabakova, Tatranske Zruby 2011  12.Bxh7+ !?  White can also try   12.Qh5  f5  13.Bh4  Nf6  14.Qf3  Bd7  15.Bxf6  Rxf6 =   12.Nxc6  bxc6  13.e4 =  The sacrifice looks interesting; it is thematic in some lines and although it gives no advantage here, it certainly complicates the game and makes it difficult for Black to defend:  12...Kxh7  13.Qh5+  Kg8  14.Ng6  Re8   14...cxd4  15.exd4  Rd8  16.Nf3  =∞   14...Rd8  15.Nf3   15.e4 !  was good, e.g.  f5   15...cxd4  16.exd5  Nf8   16...Ne7  17.Nxe7+  Bxe7  18.dxe6  +=   16...exd5  17.Qxd5+  Kh7  18.Qh5+  Kg8  19.Ne4  ±  17.dxc6  Nxg6  18.Qxg6  dxc3  19.Ne4  Be7  ∞  16.e5  Be7  17.Nf3  and White is a bit better in this position.  15...Nf8  16.Qh8+  Kf7  17.Ng5+ ?  De Prado-D. Perez, Ferrol 2012   17.Ngh4 !  Ke8  18.Ng5 !  Ne7  19.Qxg7  fxg5  20.fxg5  Bxg3  21.Rxf8+  Kd7  22.hxg3  Rxf8  23.Qxf8  Qxg3  24.Nf3   17.Nge5+ !  Ke8   17...Bxe5  18.fxe5  f5  19.Bh4  Ke8  ∞  20.Ng5   17...fxe5  18.fxe5  +-  18.Bh4  fxe5  19.fxe5  Be7  20.Qxg7  when White has good compensation;  Here  15.e4  was good, e.g.   15.Ne5  Re7  16.Ng6  Re8 =   15.Qh8+  Kf7  16.Qh7  Rf8   16...Ne7  17.Ne5+  +=  17.Nf3  15...Ne7   15...f5  16.e5  Be7  17.Nf3  +=  and White is a bit better in this position.   15...cxd4  16.exd5  Nd8   16...exd5  17.Qxd5+  Kh7  18.Nc4  ±  17.Ne4  ±  16.e5  Nxg6  17.exd6  Qc6  18.Qxg6  Nf8  19.Qd3  10.f4  b5  11.Bh4  Nf5 = }
9. Ne5 Nd7
{ Another option is   9...Bxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  and now:  11.Nf3   11.f4  f6   11...c4  12.Bc2  b5  13.Nf3  +=  E.Alvarez-Trepat, San Sebastian 2010  12.Nf3  b6   12...fxe5  13.fxe5  +=  13.h4   13.O-O  +=  13...f5  14.c4   14.h5  14...dxc4  15.Bxc4  +=  Gochelashvili-Sanzhaev, Izhevsk 2010.  11...f6   11...f5  12.Bf4   12.exf6  +=  12...c4  13.Bc2  Nc5 =  Bauer-A. Sokolov, Flims 2012  12.exf6  Nxf6  +=  Kovacevic-Izeta, Albacete 1992 }
10. Nxd7
{ The start of a sequence that took Black by surprise. Other moves have also been tried, such as   10.h4  cxd4  11.exd4  Bxe5  12.dxe5  Ndxe5  13.Bxe5  Nxe5  14.Bxh7+  Kxh7  15.Qh5+  Kg8  16.Qxe5 =  Prié-Luther, Arvier 2007   10.f4  f6  and now White has several options, including:   10...f5  11.O-O  Nf6  12.Bh4  Qc7  13.h3  Ne4  14.Nxe4   14.g4 ?!  Bxe5   14...Qb6  =+  15.fxe5  cxd4  16.exd4 =  Yemelin-Orlov, St.Petersburg 2013  14...fxe4  15.Be2  Ne7 =  Grachev-Zakhartsov, Pardubice 2007  11.Bxh7+ ?!  This sacrifice is dubious here:   11.Nxd7  Bxd7  12.O-O   12.Qh5  g6  13.Qh6  b5  14.O-O  b4  =+  Kosic-Caruana, Budapest 2007  12...e5 ?  13.fxe5  fxe5  14.Qh5  +-  g6  15.Bxg6  hxg6  16.Qxg6+  Kh8  17.Qh6+  Kg8  18.Bh4  Qe6  19.Bf6  1-0 Gongora-Del Valle, Alcudia 2010.   11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.O-O  e5   12...f5  13.Qa4  Nb6  14.Qa5 =  Summerscale-Berry, London 2011  13.fxe5  fxe5  14.Rxf8+  Nxf8  15.dxe5  Bxe5 =  Rozhko-Kovalchuk, Taganrog 2013.  11...Kxh7  12.Qh5+  Kg8  13.Ng6  Qe8  and now :  14.Nf3   14.Qh8+  Kf7  15.Nxf8  Qxf8  ∓   14.f5 !?  Bxg3+  15.hxg3  exf5  16.O-O-O  Ne7  17.Nxe7+  Qxe7  18.Qxf5  g6  19.Qxg6+  Qg7  20.Qh5  f5  ∓  14...Ne7  15.f5 ?   15.Nfh4  Nxg6  16.Nxg6  Kf7 ?   16...f5  ∓  17.O-O  f5  =+  Herzog-Kozio, Ortisei 2013  15...exf5  16.Nfh4   16.Bxd6  Nxg6  17.Bxf8  Qxe3+  +-  16...Nxg6  17.Nxg6  Qxe3+  +-  Blatny-Iotov,Kusadasi 2006; }
10... Bxd7
{ This natural move is dubious.  If Black had foreseen what was going to happen he would have played   10...Qxd7  with the following variations:  11.Bxd6   11.Qh5  g6  12.Qh6  cxd4  13.Bxd6   13.exd4 =  13...Qxd6  14.Nf3  Qe7  15.exd4  e5  16.dxe5  Bg4 =  Sedlak-Tadic, Jahorina 2012;   11.Nf3  h6  12.Ne5   12.dxc5  Bxc5  13.O-O  +=  12...Bxe5  13.dxe5 =  Sean-Gupta, Kecskemet 2013;   11.O-O  b6  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.f4 =  Grischuk-Hammer, Stavanger 2015;   11.dxc5 !  Bxc5  12.Nf3  Qe7   12...Bd6  13.e4  Bxg3  14.hxg3  dxe4  15.Bxe4  +=  Pakleza-Theodorou, Rethymno 2014  13.e4 ?!   13.O-O !  +=  13...f5  ∞  Heberla-Zajic, Plovdiv 2015  11...Qxd6  12.dxc5  Qxc5  13.Bxh7+  here this sacrifice is only sufficient for a draw  Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Ne4  g6  16.Qg5  Qe7 !  17.Nf6+  Kg7  18.Nh5+  Kh7  19.Nf6+  Kg7  20.Nh5+  Kg8  - Heberla-Fier, Plovdiv 2013; }
11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5
{ This whole series of exchanges, which would appear to favour Black, is justified by the discovery on the next move. Black is now almost lost.  In this position he should acquiesce to the loss of a pawn and play   12...Qe7  13.b4   13.Nb3  +=   13.O-O  a5  14.a4  e5  +=  Karlik-Jasny,Czechia tt 2013/14  13...b6 ?  14.cxb6 ?   14.Nb3  ±  14...axb6  =∞  Grachev-Ponkratov, Khanty-Mansiysk Wch blitz 2013. }
13. Bxh7+
{ This sacrifice was discovered by an unknown reader of ChessPublishing who called himself AlanG, and further analysed by GM Prié; the analysis engines have difficulty in finding it, but once it is pointed out to them they award White a clear advantage. }
13... Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 Qc4
{ In one of my own games Black played   15...Qb5  which is similar after  16.Ng5  Rfd8   16...Rfe8 !?  17.Qxf7+  Kh8  18.Qh5+   18.Qxd7  Re7  19.Qd6  Qxb2  20.O-O  +=   18.Rd1 !?  Qxb2  19.O-O  Qxc3  20.Qxd7  +=  Pham Le-Zatonskih, Istanbul 2012  18...Kg8  19.O-O-O  ±  17.Qxf7+  Kh8  18.Qh5+  Kg8  19.Qh7+   19.O-O-O !  +-  19...Kf8  20.Qh8+  Ke7  21.Qxg7+  Kd6  22.Nf7+  Kc7  23.Nxd8  Rxd8  24.O-O-O  ±  De Prado-Rey, Spain tt 2013. }
16. Ng5 Rfd8
{ 16...Qd3  17.e4  1-0 E.Alvarez-Pellicer, Padron 2011 Black could have played on, but he is losing after  Rfd8  18.Rd1  Qc4  19.Qxf7+  Kh8  20.Qg6  Kg8  21.f4  There is no salvation after   16...Rfe8  17.Qxf7+  Kh8  18.Qxd7  ±  either. }
17. Qxf7+ Kh8 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Qf7+
{ Here   19.Rd1 !  also works, as played by Kamsky in 2014 against the strong grandmaster Shankland. Strong players are still falling into this trap ! The game continued  e5   19...d4  20.Qf7+   20.exd4  20...Kh8  21.h4  Qd5  22.O-O  Qf5  23.Qxf5  exf5  24.Nf7+  Kg8  25.Nxd8  Rxd8  26.exd4  +-  Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son-Kanep, Khanty-Mansiysk 2010   19...Qxa2  20.O-O  Qxb2  21.f4  Qc2  22.f5 !  exf5  23.Rxd5  with a decisive attack;   19...Be8  20.Qh7+  Kf8  21.Qh8+  Ke7  22.Qxg7+  Kd6  23.b3  Qh4  24.g3  Qh5  25.Ne4#  20.Qf7+  Kh8  21.e4 !  Ne7   21...Bg4  22.f3  Bc8  23.Rxd5  +-  22.Qxe7  Bb5  23.Rd2  Qxa2  24.Qf7  Qa1+  25.Rd1  Qxb2  26.Qh5+  Kg8  27.Qh7+  Kf8  28.Qh8+  Ke7  29.Qxg7+  Kd6  30.Rxd5+  Kc6  31.Qf6+  1-0 Kamsky-Shankland,Sturbridge 2014. }
19... Kh8 20. h4
{ A very good move: White defends the knight and makes way for the rook via h3-f3. }
20... Ne5
{ 20...Be8 ??  21.Qf8#  1-0 Tosic-Ratkovic, Paracin 2012   20...Re8  21.Qxd7 }
21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. O-O-O
{ The king is tucked away, the rooks are connected and the rook on the d-file is particularly active. }
22... Qxa2 23. Qh7+ Kf8 24. Qh8+ Ke7 25. Qxg7+ Kd6 26. Ne4+ Kc6 27. Qxe5 Qa1+
{ Here   27...dxe4  fails to  28.Rd6+  Kc7  29.Ra6+  with a decisive advantage. }
28. Kd2 Qxb2+ 29. Ke1 b6
{ Now   29...dxe4  loses to  30.Rd6+  Kc7  31.Rd2+  +-  The first game Pri played with this line, against Bonn in Rochefort 2008, ended with   29...Rac8  30.Nd6  Rc7  31.Nc4  Qc2  32.Qd6+  1-0 }
30. Nd6
{ With the threat of 31. Nf7 and 31. Qd6+. White has an extra pawn, and a rather dangerous one at that, since the h-pawn is flying towards h8. }
30... Qa3 31. c4
{ Another very accurate move. In this game Prié's play is at a high level, even if this line was part of his home preparation. }
31... Qb4+
{ Black loses his queen after   31...Qxd6  32.cxd5+  exd5  33.Rc1+  Qc5  34.Rxc5+ }
32. Rd2 Qc5
{ Black is mated after   32...Qb1+  33.Ke2  Qxh1  34.cxd5+  Kc7  35.Ne8+  Kb7  36.Qc7+  Ka6  37.Ra2+  Kb5  38.Nd6+  Kb4  39.Qc4# }
33. h5 { According to Prié, his preparation extended to here ! } 33... Be8 34.
cxd5+ exd5 35. Nf5
{ The pawn is flying and the black king is not safe. White should win this, of course, but Prié now made some inaccuracies and eventually the players agreed a draw: }
35... Kb7 36. h6 Ba4 37. Qg7+ Rd7 38. Qa1 Bb5 39. h7 Qc4 40. h8=Q Rxh8 41. Qxh8
d4 42. Qh5 Rd5 43. e4 Rd7 44. e5 Ka6 45. Qd1 Qe6 46. Qc2 Qxe5+ 47. Re2 Qb8 48.
Qa2+ Kb7 49. Qe6 Qf8 50. Nd6+ Rxd6 51. Qe7+ Qxe7 52. Rxe7+ Kc6 53. Rxa7 Re6+
54. Kd1 Bc4 55. Re1 Rf6 56. f3 Rg6 57. Rg1 Re6 58. Ra1
{ Now it is getting complicated and I did not want to lose control in time trouble  (Prié)  . }
58... Kc5 59. Re1 Rg6 60. Rg1 Re6 61. Re1 Rg6 62. Rg1 Re6
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we have seen one of the key positions of Blacks defensive scheme with Bd6. On the eighth move there are several options for Black.  In this game, which is very famous, Black chose the line with 8... Qe7, with the plan of Nd7, to dislodge the white pieces from the strong square e5. White started a series of exchanges that appeared to favour Black, until White made the spectacular sacrifice 13. Bxh7+ !!, which refutes the variation.  The sacrifice had been deeply investigated by Prié in his home analysis and he played well for much of the game, with some excellent moves, before making some inaccuracies and eventually agreeing a draw in time trouble. Even today strong players continue to fall into this trap. }
*

