1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d5 6. Nbd2 Bd6
{ The alternative is 6... Be7, which we shall look at further on. } 7. Bg3
{ The normal response, with the idea of opening the h-file, if Black captures on g3, or playing f2-f4 in the future. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ This is one of the key positions in this variation. Black has several options at this point, while White must prevent Black from playing e6-e5. }
8... Qe7 { We shall see the move 8b6 in another game. } 9. Ne5 Nd7 10. Nxd7
{ The start of a sequence that took Black by surprise. Other moves have also been tried, such as }
10... Bxd7 { This natural move is dubious. } 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5
{ This whole series of exchanges, which would appear to favour Black, is justified by the discovery on the next move. Black is now almost lost. }
13. Bxh7+
{ This sacrifice was discovered by an unknown reader of ChessPublishing who called himself AlanG, and further analysed by GM Prié; the analysis engines have difficulty in finding it, but once it is pointed out to them they award White a clear advantage. }
13... Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 Qc4 16. Ng5 Rfd8 17. Qxf7+ Kh8 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19.
Qf7+ Kh8 20. h4
{ A very good move: White defends the knight and makes way for the rook via h3-f3. }
*

