1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bg3
{ Via another move order, White has tested the idea of a quick Ne5 after   5.c3  c5  6.Nbd2  Nc6  7.Ne5  This immediate knight leap promises White no advantage, as Hou Yifan demonstrated against Giri . Black continued with   7.Bg3  7...Qc7  8.Ndf3  O-O  9.Bd3  b6  10.Nxc6  Qxc6 =  Giri-Hou Yifan, Wijk aan Zee 2016. }
5... c5 6. Nbd2 { The usual move order is   6.c3 } 6... Nc6 7. c3 O-O
{ The alternative is   7...Qc7  8.dxc5  Bxg3  9.hxg3  and now:  e5   9...O-O  10.Qc2  h6   10...e5  11.e4  d4  12.cxd4  ±  11.b4  a5  12.Qb2  +=   9...a5  10.c4  Ne5  11.cxd5  Nxf3+  12.Nxf3  Qxc5  13.dxe6  Bxe6  14.Qa4+  Bd7  15.Qd4  ±  Grischuk-Sethuraman, Berlin Wch blitz 2015  10.b4   10.Bb5  10...Bf5  11.Qb3   11.Bb5  O-O  12.O-O  a6  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.Nb3  +=  11...O-O  12.Bb5  a6  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.O-O  Bd3  15.Rfe1  e4 =  Georgievski-Markovski, Skopje 2012; }
8. Bd3
{ The usual move in this position: the bishop is usually placed on the b1-h7 diagonal, aiming towards Black's castled position and with possible sacrifices on h7 in mind. Recently, however, we have begun to see the move   8.Bb5  as played by Carlsen and Grischuk. The idea is to put pressure on the knight on c6 and control the e5-square. Black has various options in reply:  a6   8...Qc7  9.dxc5  Bxg3  10.hxg3  e5  11.Qc2   11.Qa4  e4  with compensation, Ortega-Ceresoli, Bratto 1996  11...e4  12.Nd4  +=  Ni-Tari, Gibraltar 2016;   8...Bxg3  9.hxg3  Qb6   9...Qd6  10.Bxc6  bxc6 =  Nogueiras-Todorovic, Internet 2005  10.Bxc6  bxc6  11.Qc2  Rb8  12.Rb1  cxd4   12...g6  13.Ne5  Nd7  14.O-O  Nxe5  15.dxe5  Ba6  16.Rfe1 =  Kamsky-Balakrishnan, Philadelphia 2015  13.cxd4  Ba6  14.Ne5  Rfc8  15.b4  +=  Kamsky-Sevian, Chicago 2015   8...Qe7  9.Bxc6   9.O-O  Bxg3  10.hxg3  Bd7 =  Kayumov-Elianov, Dubai 2014  9...bxc6  10.Qa4  Bxg3   10...cxd4  11.cxd4  Bd7 ?!   11...Bxg3  12.hxg3  Rb8 =  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.O-O  +=  Nogueiras-Kunte, Mallorca 2004  11.hxg3  cxd4  12.cxd4  Rb8 =  Raznikov-Li, Dallas 2016;   8...Ne7  9.dxc5   9.Bd3  cxd4   9...Ng6  10.Ne5  b6  11.h4  Bb7  12.h5  Ne7  13.Qf3  ∞  Kamsky-Li, Rockville 2015   9...a6  10.e4  dxe4  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.Bxe4  +=  Winants-Decoster, Belgium tt 2015/16  10.exd4  b6  11.O-O   11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.O-O  +=  11...Bb7  12.Re1   12.Bxd6  +=  12...Bxg3  13.hxg3  Nc8 =  Kamsky-Azarov, Las Vegas 2015.  9...Bxc5  10.Bd3  b6  11.O-O  Bb7 =  Kramnik-Nakamura, Zurich 2016;  9.Bxc6   9.Bd3 !?  b6  10.e4  Be7  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.O-O =  Grischuk-Karjakin,Berlin Wch blitz 2015  9...bxc6  10.Ne5   10.Bxd6  Qxd6  11.O-O =   10.Qa4  Bxg3   10...cxd4  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.cxd4  a5  13.O-O  Ba6  14.Rfc1  Bb5  15.Qc2 =  11.hxg3  +=  Vuilleumier-Tari, Reykjavik 2016  10...Qc7  11.Nd3  c4  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.Nc5  e5  14.b3 =  Carlsen-Karjakin, Berlin Wch blitz 2015; }
8... b6
{ Recently we saw a good win by Carlsen against   8...a6  as played by Yu Yangyi in the tiebreak of the Qatar Open. White won in brilliant style with a kingside attack after  9.Ne5   9.e4  +=  9...Ne7  10.O-O  b6  11.Bh4 !?   11.Bf4  11...Nf5  12.Bg5   12.Nc6 !?  Qc7  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.Qh5 !  Bb7   14...Qxc6  15.g4  +=  15.Kh1  Bxc6  16.g4  Kh8  17.gxf5  Rg8 =  12...h6  13.Bf4  Bb7  14.h3  Be7  15.a4  Nd6  16.f3  Nd7  17.Qe2  Nf6  18.Bh2  Qc8  19.Rac1  a5  20.g4  Qd8  21.Qg2  Nd7  22.f4  Rc8  23.Rce1  cxd4  24.exd4  Ba8  25.g5  hxg5  26.fxg5  Nxe5  27.Bxe5  Nc4  28.Nf3  Nxe5  29.Rxe5  Bd6  30.Re2  g6  31.Qg4  Kg7  32.h4  Rh8  33.Rxe6 !  fxe6  34.Qxe6  Qe8  35.Qxd6  Rc6  36.Qe5+  Qxe5  37.Nxe5  Rxh4  38.Rf7+  Kg8  39.Ra7  Rc8  40.Bxg6  Bc6  41.Bf7+  Kf8  42.Ng6+  1-0 Carlsen-Yu Yangyi, Doha blitz 2015. }
9. e4
{ A new attempt to improve White's play.  The main line is   9.Ne5  Bb7  and now there are two main ideas:  10.O-O  perhaps the best move, according to the current state of theory. Black now has three options:   10.f4  Once again, White's old standard plan. Karjakin played this line not long ago:  Ne7 !  Once again Black employs the fashionable plan of Nc6-e7-f5, Be7 and Nd6, which promises a good position.  11.Qf3   11.Qc2 ?!  c4  12.Be2  Nf5  13.Bf2  =+  Andreikin-Karjakin, Baku 2015   11.Qb1  Ng6   11...g6  12.Bf2   12.Bh4  Nf5  =+  12...cxd4   12...a5  13.O-O  Ba6 =  Izoria-Brattain,Internet 2015  13.exd4  Nh5  14.g3  f6  15.Nef3 =  Grischuk-Wang, Beijing 2014.  12.O-O   12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Bh4  cxd4  14.cxd4  Bb4  15.Qd1  Sandipan-Kryvoruchko, Dubai 2014  12...Nh5  13.Be1  cxd4  14.cxd4  Nf6  15.a3  Rc8  Kamsky-Dreev, Khanty-Mansiysk Wch blitz 2013;  11...Nf5  12.Bf2  Be7 !  13.g4  it is more prudent to play   13.O-O  Nd6  14.dxc5   14.Qh3  c4  15.Bc2  Nfe4 =  Burghoff-Galanov, cr Email 2011   14.Bh4  Nfe4  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  =+  Pezerovic-Postny, Bad Wiessee 2013  14...bxc5  15.Qh3  Qc7 =  Bhme-Zidu, cr Email 2013  13...Nd6  14.g5  Nfe4  15.O-O-O !?  White generally does not castle queenside in such lines, since Blacks attack tends to strike first  White has also played   15.h4  Nxd2  16.Kxd2  Ne4+  =+  Mitkov-Borges, Toluca 2009   15.Qh3  Nf5   15...cxd4  16.exd4  g6  =+  16.Ndf3  Qc8  =+  Blatny-Zilka, Ostrava 2014  15...c4 ?!   15...cxd4 !  16.exd4  b5  =+  seems better, Sodomski-Fedorov, cr Email 2011  16.Bc2  it is also possible to play   16.Bxe4  dxe4  17.Qe2  b5  18.h4 =  the main difference being that here the c-file is closed and so White is fine  16...b5  17.Qh3   17.Nxe4  dxe4  18.Qg2 =  seems better  17...b4 !  now the black attack strikes first  18.Nxe4  dxe4  19.Be1  Bd5 ?!   19...bxc3  20.Bxc3  Nb5 =  Petrusic-Derakhshani, Novi Sad 2016;   19...a5 !  =+  20.Rg1 ?   20.cxb4 !  ∞  20...b3  ∓  Karjakin-Adams,Wijk aan Zee 2016.  10...Rc8  when White has tried:   10...Qc7  11.f4  and now:   11.Nxc6  Bxc6   11...Qxc6 =  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.Nf3  c4  14.Bc2  b5  15.Ne5  Pezerovic-Werle, Bad Wrishofen 2016.  11...Ne7   11...Nd7  12.Qh5 !?   12.Qe2 =   12.Bh4 =  12...f5  13.Qe2  Nf6  14.Bh4  Ne4 =  Georgiev-Rauk, Puhajarve 2013  12.Qb1   12.Qf3  Nf5  13.Bf2  Be7  14.Rad1  Rac8 =  Astasio-Barrenechea, Elgoibar 2015   12.Bh4 ?!  Ne4  13.Bxe7  Qxe7  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Be2  =+  Kayumov-Salgado, Dubai 2014   12.Qc2  Ng6  13.Rae1  a6  14.Ndf3  b5 =  Hoang-Kochetkova, Rijeka 2010  12...Ng6   12...g6  13.Bh4  Ne8  14.Qe1  f6  15.Nef3  Ng7  =+  Gholami-Krush, Doha 2015  13.Nxg6  hxg6  14.Bh4 =  Kosic-Urkedal, Reykjavik 2015;   10...Ne7  and now White has various options:  11.f4   11.a4  Ne4  12.Bxe4  dxe4  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.Ndc4 =  Sandipan-Vaibhav, Bhubaneswar 2014;   11.Qe2  a6  12.Rad1  Qc7  13.f4  Ne4 =  Lubbe-Ducarmon, Netherlands tt 2015/16;   11.Qb1  g6   11...a5  12.Re1  Qc7  13.a4  g6 =  Saleh-Ehlvest, Dubai 2015  12.Bh4   12.f4  Nf5  13.Bf2  Be7  14.g4  Nd6  15.Bh4 =  Reyes-Torre, Quezon City 2014;   12.Nef3  Nf5  13.Be5  Be7  14.h3 =  Kamsky-Arun, Rockville 2015.  12...Kg7   12...Nh5 =  13.e4 ?!   13.f4  ∞  13...cxd4  14.Bxf6+   14.cxd4  Bb4  15.Bxf6+  Kxf6  16.Ndf3  Kg7  =+  14...Kxf6  15.Ng4+  Kg7  16.e5  h5  ∓  Zherebtsova-Iljiushenok, Moscow 2015;   11.Qf3  Ng6   11...Qc7  12.Bf4  Ng6  13.Nxg6  hxg6 =  Gelle-Samu, Hungary 2012  12.h4 !?   12.Rad1 =   12.Nxg6 =  12...Bxe5 ?!  13.dxe5  Nd7  +=  Meier-Donchenko, Internet 2012.  11...Ne4  12.Bh4  f6  =+  11.Qe2   11.a4  Ne7   11...Qe7  12.f4 =  Michna-Zawadzka, Porto Rio 2015  12.Bh4   12.a5 !?  12...Ng6  13.Nxg6  hxg6 =  Michna-Zatonskih, Germany Frauenbundesliga 2015/ 16;   11.Nxc6  Bxc6  12.Qe2   12.Bxd6  Qxd6 =  12...c4  13.Bc2  b5 =  Reich-Zelcic, Schwarzach 2014.   11.f4  (considered best)  Ne7 !  (initiating the manoeuvre Ne7-f5, Be7 and Nd6, to control the e4-square, which enables Black to render the position harmless. This variation has become very popular for Black)  12.Qb1   12.Qf3  Nf5  13.Bf2  Be7  14.Qh3   14.Ng4  Nxg4  15.Qxg4  Nd6  =+  Dlugy-Zhigalko, Berlin Wch rapid 2015   14.dxc5  bxc5  15.Qh3 =  14...Ne4  15.Rad1  Qc7  16.g4  Nfd6 =  Pham-Perena, KhantyMansiysk 2010   12.Bh4 ?!  Ne4  13.Bxe7  Qxe7  =+  Milanovic-Nabaty, Belgrade 2015  12...Rc7  13.Bh4  Ng6  14.Bg5  Qa8 =  Kamsky-Korobov, Antalya 2013.  11...Qc7  12.f4   12.Nxc6  Qxc6  13.Bxd6  Qxd6 =  12...Ne7  13.Qf3  Nf5  14.Bf2  Be7 =  Kosic-Korobov, Reykjavik 2015; }
9... Be7
{ Taking on e4 gives White the advantage after   9...dxe4 ?!  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  Bb7  12.dxc5 !   12.Qa4  Qc7  13.dxc5  bxc5  +=  Burmakin-Iturrizaga, Barcelona 2013  12...Bxc5  13.Qa4  Rc8  14.Rd1  Qe8 ??   14...Qf6  15.O-O  ±  Sedlak-Prusikin, Bavaria 2014  We have reached a typical attacking position for the player of the London System. How should White continue here ?  15.Bxh7+ !  Once again there is a thematic sacrifice on h7 and it wins: if  Kxh7  16.Qh4+  1-0 Grachev-Gorodetzky, Minsk 2015. There is no defence against mate after 17. Ng5. }
10. e5
{ Trying to gain space. This is, without doubt, White's most ambitious move here. In general, the engines evaluate the black position as advantageous, but several strong grandmasters continue to play this move, even in longplay games, which leads me to think that in practical play the position is complex and playable for both sides. White has also played:   10.dxc5  bxc5  11.O-O  Qb6 =  Burmakin-Urkedal, Manacor 2016;   10.Qc2  h6   10...c4  11.Be2 =  11.O-O  cxd4  12.e5  Nh5  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.cxd4 =  Van Foreest-Admiraal, Wijk aan Zee 2016;   10.O-O  with equality;  The latest treatment of this position by London System specialist Gata Kamsky gave him a good position from the opening:   10.Ne5  Nxe5   10...Bb7  11.Nxc6  Bxc6  12.e5  Ne4  13.Bf4 =  11.dxe5 !  Nxe4  12.Nxe4  dxe4  13.Bxe4  Qxd1+   13...Rb8 =  14.Rxd1  Rb8  with a slight advantage to White, Kamsky-Nakamura, Saint Louis 2016. }
10... Nh5
{ The most common response in this position, hitting the white bishop on g3.  If Black plays   10...Nd7  the position resembles the French Defence and White would have excellent attacking possibilities on the kingside. }
11. a3
{ A recent idea. White plays in a similar way to the Advance Variation of the French and prepares counterplay with b2-b4. One of the greatest specialists of the London System in the world, Gata Kamsky, has tried other moves here, but without good results:   11.Qe2  Bd7  12.a3  a5  13.O-O  c4  14.Bc2  b5  =+  Kamsky-Goryachkina, Gibraltar 2016   11.O-O  Bd7  12.Re1  Nxg3   12...Rc8  13.a3   13.Nf1  13...Nxg3  14.hxg3  f5  =+  Kamsky-Nakamura, Saint Louis 2015  13.hxg3  a5  14.a3  a4  15.Nf1  b5  16.Ne3  b4  =+  Kamsky-M. Muzychuk, Gibraltar 2016. }
11... a5 12. Qe2 Ra7
{ At the time, this move of Nakamura's was a novelty. Previously Black had played   12...Nb8  13.Ng5  Bxg5  14.Qxh5  g6  15.Qe2 =  Kamsky-Taborsky, New York 2015   12...g6  13.O-O  f5  14.exf6  Bxf6  15.Qe3  ∞  Berkes-Demuth, Cappelle-la-Grande 2016   12...c4  13.Bc2  b5  14.Ng5 !  Bxg5  15.Qxh5  g6  16.Qe2  +=  Kramnik-Zhigalko, Berlin Wch rapid 2015, with good attacking chances; closing the queenside is dangerous. The rook move is a normal idea in the Orthodox set-up; the rook is activated along the second rank Jorge Luis Fernandez. }
13. O-O
{ An alternative would be   13.Nf1  to develop the knight to e3, e.g.:  g6   13...c4  14.Bc2  b5  and now:  15.h4   15.Ng5  Bxg5  16.Qxh5  g6  17.Qe2  Be7   17...f5 !?  is interesting, e.g.  18.exf6  Bxf6  19.Ne3   19.f4  b4  20.axb4  axb4  21.Rxa7  Nxa7  22.Ne3  Qa5  23.Ng4  bxc3  24.Nxf6+  Rxf6  25.bxc3  Qxc3+  26.Qd2  19...e5  20.dxe5  Nxe5  21.Rd1  Rd7  22.O-O  with equal chances  18.h4  h5  19.Bf4  +=  15...Nxg3  16.Nxg3  f6  17.Bxh7+   17.Ng5  fxg5  18.Qh5  g6  19.Bxg6  Bc5  20.hxg5   20.Bc2   20.Bb1  Nxd4  21.hxg5  Qc7  22.cxd4  Bxd4  and Black wins  20...hxg6  21.Qh8+  Kf7  22.Qh7+  Ke8  23.Qxg6+  Raf7  and Black wins  17...Kxh7  18.Ng5+  fxg5  19.hxg5+  Kg8  20.Rh8+  Kf7  21.Qh5+  g6  22.Rh7+  Ke8  23.Qxg6+  Kd7  and Black wins;  14.h3  Nxg3  15.Nxg3  c4  16.Bc2  b5  17.h4  b4  with complex play;   13.Ng1  g6 !  and Black is better. }
13... c4 { Once White has castled, Black closes the queenside. } 14. Bc2 b5 15.
h4
{ White needs to seek counterplay on the kingside, since Black is winning the battle on the queenside. }
15... g6
{ Inexplicably, Black does not exchange the bishop. It looks natural to play   15...Nxg3 !  16.fxg3  b4   16...f5  17.g4  g6   17...fxg4  18.Ng5  Bxg5  19.hxg5  Rxf1+  20.Rxf1  Qxg5  21.Qf2  Qe7  22.Qf4  with compensation  18.g3  b4  with initiative  (Jorge Luis Fernandez)  .  17.axb4  axb4  18.Nxc4 !?  Ba6   18...dxc4  19.Qe4  ±  19.Rxa6  Rxa6  20.Ne3  when White has a pawn for the exchange and attacking chances  (Qa8 =+) }
16. Bh2
{ An interesting pawn sacrifice; White preserves his bishop and prepares to dislodge the black knight. Now White's kingside attack can begin. }
16... Bxh4 17. g4
{ Tempting, but surely premature.  Another way to play for White, and perhaps sounder, was   17.Nxh4  Qxh4  18.Nf3  Qd8   18...Qg4  19.Qe3  f5  20.exf6  Rxf6  21.Ne5  +=   18...Qe7  19.Qe3  f5  20.exf6  Nxf6  21.Qg5  ∞  19.g4  Ng7  20.Qe3  with good compensation. The h-file is dangerous.   20.Kg2  +=  Jorge Luis Fernandez }
17... Ng7 18. Nxh4
{ It seems natural to eliminate the dark-squared bishop, but it was better to play   18.Qe3 !  which threatens moves like 19. g5, trapping the bishop, or 19. Qh6. After  Be7  19.Kg2  f5  20.exf6  Bxf6  21.Bg3  with the plan of Rh1, White has very good compensation, as well as an attack along the h-file.   21.Rh1  e5 !  22.dxe5  Be7  23.Bg3  Ne6  24.Qh6  Bc5  ∞  Jorge Luis Fernandez }
18... Qxh4 19. Kg2 f5
{ The other option was   19...h5  20.Rh1 !?   20.f3  Qg5  21.Bg3  ∞  20...Qxg4+  21.Qxg4  hxg4  22.Bd1  b4  23.Bxg4  bxa3  24.bxa3  Rb7  25.Bf4  f6   25...f5  26.Bf3  with compensation  26.exf6  Rxf6  27.Bg5  Rf8  28.Nf3  Rb3  29.Rh6  Rxc3  30.Rxg6  Kf7  31.Rh6  and White has compensation. }
20. exf6 Qxf6 21. Bd6
{ A dubious move;  the simple   21.Nf3 !  was good, e.g.  e5   21...Raf7  22.Ne5  +=  22.Nxe5  Nxe5  23.Bxe5  Qg5  24.f3  with equality. }
21... Rff7 22. f4
{ White wants to prevent e6-e5, but for this it was better to play   22.Qe3  e5   22...Qd8  23.Be5   23.Bc5  e5  =+  23...Nxe5  24.dxe5  d4  25.cxd4  Rad7  26.f3  Bb7  =+  23.dxe5   23.Bxe5 ?  Nxe5  24.Qxe5   24.dxe5  Qh4  25.f3  Nh5  24...Qxe5  25.dxe5  Bxg4  23...Qd8  24.f3  Ne6  =+ }
22... e5
{ A good freeing move by Black: his bishop enters play and joins in the counterattack on the kingside. }
23. dxe5
{ 23.fxe5 ?  Qg5  ∓   23.Bxe5 ?  Nxe5  24.dxe5  Qh4  25.Rh1  Qxg4+  26.Qxg4  Bxg4  27.Kg3  Bf5  ∓ }
23... Qh4 24. f5
{ White cannot defend g4 and so he hurries to complicate the play.  If   24.Rh1  then  Qxg4+  25.Qxg4  Bxg4  26.Kg3  Bf5  ∓ }
24... gxf5
{ The right move was   24...Nxf5 !  25.Bxf5  not   25.gxf5 ?  gxf5  26.Rg1  Rg7+  27.Kf3  f4  with a decisive attack for Black  or   25.e6  Rg7  26.Bxf5  gxf5  27.Rf4  Rg6 !  ∓  25...gxf5  26.Nf3  Qxg4+  27.Kf2  Rg7  28.Rg1  Qf4  29.Qe3 !  Qxe3+  30.Kxe3  when Black has the advantage, but White has drawing chances, thanks to his control of the dark squares. }
25. Rh1 Qd8
{ Here   25...Qg5 !?  was interesting, e.g.  26.Nf3  Qf4  not   26...Qxg4+ ?  27.Kf2  +=  with the idea of Rg1, and White would have a dangerous attack  27.Rh4  Ne6  28.gxf5  Qxh4  29.Nxh4  Nf4+  30.Kf2  Nxe2  31.Kxe2  ∞  here White has very good compensation. }
26. Qe3 d4
{ A good move by Black, clearing the long diagonal h1-a8 in order to revive his bishop. }
27. cxd4 Ne8
{ But Nakamura follows it up erroneously.  Instead,   27...Bb7 !  was good, e.g.  28.d5   28.Kf2 !?  is interesting, for instance  Ne7  29.d5  Bxd5 !  30.Qxa7  fxg4+  31.Kg1  Bxh1  32.Kxh1  Nd5  33.Bxh7+ !  Kxh7  34.Qxf7  Qh4+  35.Kg1  Qg3+  36.Kh1  Qh3+  37.Kg1  Qg3+  with a draw; a fantastic variation, very difficult to see during the game.  28...Nd4 !  29.Qxd4  Ne6 !  30.Qe3  Bxd5+  31.Kh3 !?   31.Kf2 !  f4  32.Qh3  Qb6+  33.Kf1  Qd4  Black has very good compensation and the result should be a draw after  34.Rd1  Qxb2  35.Be4  Ng5  36.Qh4  Nxe4  37.Nxe4  Bxe4  38.Qd8+  Kg7  39.Qg5+  Kh8  40.Qd8+  Kg7  41.Qg5+  31...f4  32.Qf2  Rg7  33.Rhg1  f3 !  and again it seems that the most likely result will be a draw by perpetual check:  34.Kh2  Qg5  35.Nxf3  Qf4+  36.Qg3  Qh6+  37.Qh3  Qf4+  38.Qg3 = }
28. Rh6
{ In time pressure both players slip up and the advantage keeps changing hands. Now it is Grischuk's turn to miss the best move:   28.Bc5 !  Rac7  29.Nf3  Rg7   29...fxg4 ?  30.Ng5  +-  30.Rag1  ±  Rxg4+   30...fxg4  31.Qh6  gxf3+  32.Kf2  +-  31.Kf2  Rcg7   31...Rxg1  32.Rxg1+  Rg7   32...Kh8  33.Qh6  Rg7  34.Rxg7  Nxg7  35.Ng5  +-  33.Qh6  Qc7   33...Rxg1  34.Qf8#  34.Rxg7+  Qxg7   34...Nxg7  35.Ng5  +-  35.Qxc6  +-  32.Rxg4  Rxg4   32...fxg4  33.Qh6  +-  The move   28.d5 !?  was also good, e.g.  Nxd6   28...f4  29.Qc5  Nxd6  30.Qxc6  ±  29.dxc6  Ne8  30.Nf3  += }
28... Rg7 29. Rg1 Rad7
{ It was better to play   29...Rxg4+ !  30.Kf1  Rxg1+  31.Qxg1+  Rg7  32.Qe3  Ne7  and once again Black is better. }
30. d5
{ Here   30.Kf1 !  was good, e.g.  Nxd6  31.exd6  Qf8   31...Rxd6  32.Rxd6  Qxd6  33.Qe8+  Qf8  34.Qxc6  +-  32.d5  Nd8  33.gxf5  ± }
30... Ne7 31. Bxe7 Rdxe7 32. Qd4 Bb7
{ Here it was better to play   32...Rxg4+  33.Kf1  Reg7  34.Rxg4  Rxg4  35.Qf2  Qxd5  36.Bxf5  Bxf5  37.Qxf5  Qg2+  38.Ke1  Qg1+  39.Nf1  Qd4  ∓ }
33. Kf2 Qxd5 34. Qxd5+ Bxd5 35. Bxf5 Rxe5 36. Re1
{ After these exchanges the position levels out. } 36... Rxe1 37. Kxe1 b4 38.
axb4 axb4 39. Be6+
{ White should draw without difficulty after   39.Nf1 !  c3  40.bxc3  bxc3  41.Ne3  Re7  42.Kf2  Bb3  43.Rb6 = }
39... Bxe6 40. Rxe6 Nc7 { 40...Kf7 !  41.Rc6  Rxg4  42.Nxc4  Rh4 } 41. Rc6 Nd5
42. Rxc4
{ And the draw was agreed, in view of 41. Rc6 Nd5 42. Rxc4 with an easy draw. Black had a better option in 40... Kf7 ! 41. Rc6 Rxg4 42. Nxc4 Rh4; even though this should also end in a draw, Black should have chosen this continuation. A great fighting game, very complicated, and one in which both sides had winning chances. And some people say that the London System is boring !  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@We have seen a game in which White tried the idea of 9. e4, instead of the more usual 9. Ne5, which recently Black has been countering successfully with the manoeuvre Nc6-e7-f5, Be7 and Nd6, in order to control e4, as in the game between Karjakin and Adams from Wijk aan Zee 2016.  To combat this particular line White has also been testing 8. Bb5, instead of 8. Bd3, as can be seen in the annotations. The idea of e4-e5 is reminiscent of some positions from the Advance Variation of the French Defence.  In the game White sacrificed a pawn on the kingside and complicated the play, since Black had the upper hand on the queenside. White obtained very good compensation and attacking chances along the half-open h-file, but then in time pressure and in a very complex position, the advantage changed hands several times. Finally it all ended in a very hard-fought and entertaining draw. }
