1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bg3 c5 6. Nbd2 Nc6 7. c3 O-O 8. Bb5
{ as played by Carlsen and Grischuk. The idea is to put pressure on the knight on c6 and control the e5-square. Black has various options in reply: }
8... a6 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Ne5 Qc7 11. Nd3 c4 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Nc5 e5 14. b3
{ Carlsen-Karjakin, Berlin Wch blitz 2015; } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs ...d5 with early ...e6"]
[Black "Game 54 - Kamsky vs. Goganov"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3
{ An interesting alternative for White is to delay the development of the king's knight and play an early f2-f4 after   4.Nd2  Nc6  5.c3  e6  6.Bd3  Bd6  7.Bxd6   7.dxc5  Bxc5 =  7...Qxd6  8.f4  White is trying to set up the attacking formation known as the Stonewall Attack, but having first exchanged his bad bishop. Now:  Bd7   8...cxd4  9.cxd4  O-O   9...Qb4  10.Rb1  Ne4  11.Bxe4  dxe4  12.a3  Qa5  13.Ne2  +=  Moran-Harper, Bridgetown 2009   9...Nb4  10.Be2   10.Bb1 =  10...Qb6  11.Qb3  Bd7  12.a3  Nc6  13.Qxb6  axb6  +=  Kovacevic-Beliavsky, Plovdiv 1983  10.a3  Ne7  11.Ngf3  Qb6  12.Qb3  Qxb3  13.Nxb3  b6 =  Kramnik-Grandelius, Stavanger 2016.  9.a3  O-O  10.Ngf3  cxd4  11.cxd4  Ne7  12.O-O   12.Ne5  Qb6  13.Qb3  +=  Romero Holmes-Zambrana, Bogota 2010  12...Bc6  13.Ne5  Nd7  14.Qh5  f5  +=  Kamsky-Wang Yue, Beijing blitz 2013; }
4... Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ An interesting move order, directed against the thematic Qb6. } 5... e6
{ Whites idea against the annoying   5...Qb6  is to play  6.dxc5 !  Qxc5   6...Qxb2  7.Rb1  Qc3   7...Qxa2  8.Bb5  with compensation  8.Bb5  e6   8...Qxc5  9.O-O  with compensation,Genga-Palm, cr Email 2013  9.O-O  Be7  10.Ne5  Qxc5  11.c4  with compensation, Bhme-Bttner, Email 2013  7.a3   7.Be2  Bf5  8.c3  Qb6  9.Qb3  +=  Torre-Abelgas, Olongapo City 2015  7...Bf5   7...Bg4  +=  8.c4  e6  9.b4  Qb6  10.c5  ±  Kramnik-Cheparinov, Berlin Wch blitz 2015. }
6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
{ We looked at the alternative   8.Bb5  in the previous game. } 8... b6 9. Qe2
{ Gata Kamsky applies an interesting idea, which is not new, however. In the previous game we saw the move   9.e4  and we are also familiar with the traditional move   9.Ne5 }
9... Bb7 10. Rd1
{ A quiet move, awaiting events and delaying castling.  Practice has also seen here   10.dxc5 ?!  bxc5  11.e4  Be7  12.e5 ?  Nh5  =+  Sandipan-Karjakin, Dubai 2014  Castling is also possible:   10.O-O  Qc7  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.e4   12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.e4 =  12...Bxg3  13.hxg3  =+  Radjabov-Leko, Beijing 2014  as well as the normal   10.Ne5  Qc7  11.f4  Ne7  12.Qf3  Nf5  13.Bf2  Be7  14.Qh3  Ne4  15.g4  ∞  Agrest-Cuenca, Sweden tt 2015/16. }
10... Re8
{ and   10...cxd4  11.exd4  Ne7  12.O-O  Nf5  13.Be5  +=  Maksimenko-Schwabeneder, Austria Bundesliga 2015/16. }
11. e4
{ But this is a new idea at this point. Kamsky decides to play e3-e4 under more favourable conditions.  In another game White had played   11.dxc5  Bxc5   11...bxc5  =+  12.e4  a5   12...Nh5 =  13.Bh4  Be7  14.e5  Nd7  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.O-O =  Sandipan-Travesset, Benasque 2014 }
11... Be7 { 11...e5 !?  12.dxc5  Bxc5  13.O-O  += } 12. e5
{ This is a move which, in general, the engines dislike, but it is a natural one, since it gains space.   12.O-O =  is also playable. }
12... Nh5 13. a3
{ To control the b4-square, as in the previous game between Grischuk-Nakamura. The main differences are that the rook on e8 does not seem to be very well situated and White has not castled yet. These differences are important, as we shall soon see. }
13... c4
{ Closing the queenside does not look the best option.  Perhaps Black should have played   13...a5  with the idea of Qc8 and Ba6,  or   13...Rc8  with a complex position and possibilities for both sides. }
14. Bb1 g6 15. Nf1
{ Kamsky takes the opportunity to improve his pieces and he still delays castling.   15.h4  was also interesting }
15... b5 16. Ne3 a5 17. Ng4
{ As a result of White's precise knight manoeuvre, he now has the advantage. The knight reaches a more active square and menaces the enemy's castled position. }
17... b4 18. Qe3
{ Another good and thematic move, to bring the queen to the kingside. Black is focusing on the queenside, while White is directing his forces towards the black king. }
18... bxc3 19. bxc3 Rb8
{ The black bishop has to wait patiently on e7, because otherwise the dark squares on Black's kingside would be vulnerable to a future Bh4 by White, followed by an eventual g2-g4. Thus, capturing the pawn would lose: after   19...Bxa3 ?  20.Nh6+  Kg7   20...Kf8  21.Bh4  Be7  22.g4 !  Bxh4  23.gxh5  with a decisive advantage; White threatens 24. Qf4, among other things  21.Bh4  Be7  22.Bxe7  Nxe7   22...Qxe7  23.g4  +-  23.g4  White wins a piece.  or   19...Kh8  20.Bf4  Bxa3  21.Bh6  ±  with a strong attack and advantage to White. }
20. Bf4
{ Kamsky handles the attack with great precision; he now improves the bishop, to include it in the attack. }
20... Bc8
{ The exchange   20...Nxf4  21.Qxf4  would leave White with a strong attack and a practically decisive advantage. It is curious how the black knight is the king's main defender. White would quickly play h2-h4 and Qh6. }
21. Bg5
{ It is normal to want to exchange the dark-squared bishops, but it also was good to play   21.Nh6+  Kg7  22.h4  with a strong attack for White. }
21... Rb3
{ It was better to defend with   21...Kh8  but White is better after  22.h4 }
22. h4 { Again   22.Nh6+  was playable, with great advantage to White. } 22...
Qb6
{ Another mistake, removing this powerful piece from the king's security zone.  I do not think that it would have saved Black, but   22...Rf8  was better, e.g.  23.Nh6+  Kh8   23...Kg7  24.g4  f6  25.gxh5  fxg5  26.hxg6  hxg6  27.Nxg5  Nxd4  28.Qxd4  Kxh6  29.Qg4  ±  24.g4  Ng7  25.Bxe7  Qxe7   25...Nxe7  26.Ng5  Qe8  27.h5  26.Ng5  Nd8  and now:  27.Nxh7 !?   27.Bc2  Rb2   27...Rxa3  28.h5  +-   27...a4  28.Nxh7  +-  28.Qc1  Ra2   28...Rxc2  29.Qxc2  +-  29.Nxh7  Rxc2  30.Qxc2  Kxh7  31.h5  with a decisive attack.   27.h5  ±  27...Rxb1   27...Kxh7  28.h5  +-  28.Nxf8  Rxd1+  29.Kxd1  Qxf8  30.h5  ± }
23. Bc2
{ Here White could play   23.Nd2 !  Rxa3  24.Bxe7  Nxe7  25.Nh6+  Kg7   25...Kf8  26.g4  Ng7  27.Qf4  +-   27.h5  +-   27.Nf3  +-  26.g4  with a decisive advantage. }
23... Rxa3
{ Here   23...Bf8  was a better defence, but after  24.O-O   24.Bxb3  cxb3  ±  24...Rxa3  25.Bf6  White would again have a decisive attack. }
24. Bxe7 Nxe7 { 24...Rxe7  then  25.Qh6  wins, with the threat of 26. Ng5. }
25. Qh6
{ Finally White's attack is decisive. There is no good defence against the threat of 26. Ng5. }
25... Nf5 26. Bxf5 exf5 27. Ng5 Nf6 { 27...Be6  28.Qxh7+  Kf8  29.Nh6 } 28. Ne3
{ With the unstoppable threat of 29. exf6 and 29. Nxd5; this is stronger than   28.Nxf6+  Qxf6  29.Qxh7+  Kf8  30.f4  Qg7  ± }
28... f4 29. Nxd5 Qd8 30. O-O
{ It is very satisfying and creates a sensation of aesthetic beauty to win by castling so late, and indeed on the very last move of the game. With this move White forces resignation. If }
30... Qxd5 { 30...Nxd5  31.Qxh7+  Kf8  32.Qxf7# } 31. exf6
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw a new idea of Kamsky's, 9. Qe2 and 10. Rd1, in one of the critical and currently most popular lines of the London System.  Kamsky's idea is to delay castling and then to play in a similar fashion to the course of the game between Grischuk and Nakamura. The dubious 13... c4 is worth highlighting; Black should not close the queenside. Kamsky's manoeuvre Nd2-f1-e3-g4, followed by Qe3/Bf4, gave him a great advantage and very good attacking chances against the black king.  Finally Black's counterplay on the queenside proved futile and White won with a mating attack. A good game and a model for how to conduct White's attack in this type of position. }
*

