[White "Vs ...d5 with early ...e6"]
[Black "Game 55 - Carlsen vs. Tomashevsky"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6
{ Here we have a London System which is heading towards a Queen's Indian ? } 4.
e3 Bb7 5. h3
{ As I am sure many players of the London System are aware, this is a slight inaccuracy in the move order; the move h2-h3 should be played only after Black has played Be7. }
5... Be7
{ The move   5...Bd6 !  is the way to punish White for the premature 5. h3; now White must exchange on d6, since the move Bg3 is not available with the pawn on h3:  6.Bxd6  cxd6  7.c4  d5  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Rc1 =  Pri-Eingorn, France tt 2007. }
6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O c5 8. c3 Nc6
{ The usual choice would be   8...cxd4  9.cxd4   9.exd4  9...Nc6   9...d6  followed by Nbd7,is the most popular, in the style of the Queen's Indian  10.a3 }
9. Nbd2 d5
{ But Tomashevsky switches to the main line of the Queen's Gambit set-up, with Be7, instead of continuing in Queen's Indian fashion. In particular I think that it is better for Black to play d7-d6, since this is a more flexible set-up. The systems with d7-d5 are particularly hard on the b7-bishop and although they can be more solid, I think that they considerably reduce Blacks possibilities of active play.  The normal alternative was   9...cxd4  10.exd4  d6  or   9...d6 }
10. Qe2
{ An interesting move; White controls the f1-a6 diagonal and supports a possible e3-e4. Practice has also seen:   10.a4  Bd6  11.Bg5   11.Bxd6  Qxd6 =  11...h6  12.Bh4  Be7  13.Ne5  Nxe5  14.dxe5  Nd7 =  Kamsky-Almasi, Beijing 2011   10.Bh2  Bd6  11.Ne5  Qc7  12.f4  Nd7  13.g4  f6  14.Nxd7  Qxd7  15.Nf3  ∞  Sanikidze-Petriashvili, Ureki 2015;   10.Re1  Nh5  11.Bh2  Bd6  12.dxc5  bxc5  13.Bxd6  Qxd6 =  Lelenko-Yloenen, cr Email 2013;  The knight move   10.Ne5  is normal; e5 is one of the key squares in these set-ups:  Nxe5   10...Nd7  11.Nxc6  Bxc6  12.a4  a5  13.Qe2  Nf6  14.Nf3  Bb7  15.Bb5  Qc8 =  Vachier-Lagrave-Caruana, Biel 2010.  11.Bxe5   11.dxe5  Nd7   11...Ne4 !?  12.Qg4  Re8  13.Nf3  f5 ?!   13...Qc7 =  14.exf6  Bxf6  +=  Lazic-Postny, Lodi 2006  11...c4  12.Bc2  b5  13.Re1  Ne4 =  Zuluaga-Leitao, Mar del Plata 2012 }
10... Bd6
{ 10...Rc8  11.Rad1  Nh5  12.Bh2  c4  13.Bc2 =  Grachev-Frolyanov, Sochi 2015   10...h6  11.Rad1  Bd6  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.e4  Qc7   13...dxe4 ?  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Qxe4  ±  Sergeev-Leniart, Katowice 2014  14.e5  Nd7  15.Qe3  a5  16.Bb1  Ba6  17.Rfe1  Rfc8  ∞  Kamsky-Castellanos, Cappelle-la-Grande 2016. Gata Kamsky managed to win a good game with a kingside attack. }
11. Rfe1
{ This move is a new one in over-the-board games; two Email games are the only others played with this line. White has also tried:   11.Ne5  Qc7  12.Ndf3  Ne7 =  Yurtseven-Sanal, Antalya 2013   11.Bxd6  Qxd6  and now:  12.e4   12.Ba6  Bxa6  13.Qxa6  e5  14.dxe5  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.a4 =  Ravi-Babujian, Hyderabad 2013;   12.dxc5  Qxc5   12...bxc5 !?  looks interesting, e.g.  13.e4  Nd7  14.exd5  exd5  15.Rfe1  Nf6 =  Potkin-Kurnosov, Moscow 2010  13.Ba6  Bxa6  14.Qxa6  e5  15.Rfd1  Pirard-Hautot, Belgium tt 2014/15  12...dxe4  13.Nxe4  Nxe4  14.Qxe4  f5  15.Qe3  cxd4  16.cxd4  Rf6  ∞   11.Bg5  h6  12.Bh4  Be7  13.Bg3  Nd7   13...a5  14.Rfe1  Qc8  15.Rad1  Ba6 =  Umetsubo-Leitao, Joao Pessoa 2013  14.Rad1  Re8  15.a3  a5  16.e4  Qc8  17.Rfe1  +=  V.Georgiev-Quesada, Merida 2006;   11.Rfd1  Re8  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.e4  Qf4  14.e5  Nd7  15.Nf1  f6  16.exf6  Nxf6  17.Bb5 =  Sergeev-Zelbel, Austria Bundesliga B 2013/14. }
11... Ne7
{ In the Email games mentioned Black had played   11...Bxf4  12.exf4  cxd4  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.cxd4  Qd6  15.g3   15.Qe3  Rac8  16.a3  Rfe8  17.Rac1 =  Carvalho-Damigo, cr Email 2008  15...Rac8  16.Rac1  Qd7  17.Kg2 =  Leimgruber-Dmitriev, cr Email 2013.  We can infer that Carlsen was relying on this type of structure to put pressure on the black position, thanks to his better bishop. How, though ? Perhaps it is better to play   17.Nf3  immediately and answer  Ne4  with  18.Ng5 !? }
12. Rad1
{ White maintains the tension. If   12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.e4  then  dxe4  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Bxe4  Bxe4  16.Qxe4  cxd4  17.Rad1  with a balanced game. }
12... Ng6
{ 12...Bxf4  13.exf4  Rc8  14.Nf1  Qc7  15.g3 =  White is more comfortable, with his greater control of the dark squares. }
13. Bxg6
{ A decision with the Carlsen stamp on it. It is unusual for White to exchange this bishop, which is usually his most dangerous piece, aiming towards h7. Carlsen rules out any attack  (seemingly)  and plans to leave himself with a good knight vs. a bad bishop, with a view to the endgame. This knight will be strong on e5 because after the exchange on g6 it can hardly be evicted by f7-f6. }
13... hxg6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Ne5 g5
{ A questionable move, since it is not usually good to move the pawns in front of the castled position. Obviously Black was afraid of f2-f4 or h3-h4, bolstering the knight on e5, and is trying to prevent that.  An alternative was   15...Qe7  with a balanced game. }
16. f4
{ But Carlsen plays the move f2-f4 anyway.   16.Qf3  +=  was also possible. After Black's dubious advance with 15... g5 Carlsen is once again thinking about an attack ! }
16... gxf4 17. Rf1
{ The key to the previous idea: White brings the rook to the f-file, where it will be much more dangerous, although logically Carlsen had to calculate thoroughly the consequences of the capture on e3.  if   17.exf4  cxd4  18.cxd4  Rac8 = }
17... Nd7
{ In the event of   17...fxe3  White would play  18.Rxf6 !  was Carlsen's plan when he played 16. f4. This sacrifice promises a strong initiative, and although is does not win by force it presents difficulties to the defender:  gxf6 ?  loses after   18...cxd4  19.cxd4  exd2  20.Rf4 !  f6  21.Ng6  Rfc8  22.Qxd2  White is better and has attacking chances;   18...exd2  19.Rxd2  Qe7   19...gxf6  20.Qg4+  Kh7  21.Rf2 !  20.Rf4  Qg5  21.Rg4  Qh6  22.dxc5  bxc5  23.Qf2  d4  24.cxd4  Rad8  25.Rh4  Qg5  And here White has an elegant combination:  26.Qxf7+ !  Rxf7  27.Rh8+  Kxh8  28.Nxf7+  Kg8  29.Nxg5  Rxd4  30.Rxd4  cxd4  31.Nxe6  with a very advantageous endgame.  19.Qg4+  e.g.:  Kh7   19...Kh8  20.Rf1 !  exd2  21.Rf4  again with a mating attack after  d1=Q+  22.Qxd1  Qxe5   22...Rg8  23.Qh5+  Kg7  24.Rg4+  Kf8  25.Qxf7#   22...fxe5  23.Qh5+  Kg7  24.Rg4+  Kf6  25.Qg5#  23.dxe5  Rg8  24.Qh5+  Kg7  25.Rxf6  with unstoppable mate once again.  20.Rf1 !  fxe5   20...f5  21.Qh4+  Kg7  22.Qg5+  Kh7  23.Rf4  and mate  or   20...e2  21.Qxe2  fxe5  22.Qh5+  Kg8  23.Qg5+  Kh7  24.Rf6  21.Rf6 !  exd2  22.Qh5+  Kg7  23.Qg5+  Kh7  24.Rh6# }
18. Qh5 { Another option was   18.Nxd7  Qxd7  19.Rxf4  f6  20.Rh4  += } 18...
Nf6
{ if   18...fxe3 ?  then  19.Nxf7  +-  but   18...cxd4 !  was fine, e.g.  19.Nxd7   19.exd4  Nxe5  20.dxe5  Qc5+  21.Rf2  Ba6 =  19...Qxd7  20.exd4  with no more than a very slight advantage to White. He has pressure along the f-file and threats along the h-file; Black's defence is difficult, but possible: he should play  f6 !  after   20...Qd6  the knight manoeuvre  21.Nf3 !?  f6  22.Nh4  is interesting  21.Rxf4  Ba6 !? }
19. Qh4 Qd8
{ If   19...fxe3  then once more  20.Rxf6 !  wins, for example:  exd2   20...gxf6  21.Qg4+  Kh8  22.Rf1 !  +-   20...Qd8  21.Ng4  +-   20...Qe7  21.Ng4 !  exd2  22.Rxd2  +-   22.Nh6+ !  gxh6  23.Rxd2  +-   23.Rg6+  fxg6  24.Qxe7  +-  23...Rfe8  24.Rd3  and wins  21.Rxd2  gxf6  22.Rd3  +- }
20. Rxf4 Ne4
{ It is understandable that Black wanted to exchange queens and simplify, but now he is going to be clearly worse in the endgame, since a white rook will invade the seventh rank.  It was necessary to exchange on d4 first, thanks to a strategic detail:   20...cxd4 !  21.exd4  Ne4  and now if White continues as in the game with  22.Nxe4  Instead, White can keep an edge with   22.Qg4  f5  23.Qg6  Rf6  24.Qh5  since the e5-knight is better than the b7-bishop;  22...Qxh4  23.Rxh4  dxe4  the d-file remains closed to Whites rook. nevertheless, Black would still be in the game. }
21. Nxe4 Qxh4 { 21...dxe4 ?  22.Qh5 !  f6  23.Ng6  +- } 22. Rxh4 dxe4 23. dxc5
bxc5 24. Rd7
{ This is the difference; because Black failed to exchange on d4 first, White will now be able to occupy the seventh rank; furthermore Black's pawns are weak. }
24... Rab8 25. b3 a5 26. Rc7 a4
{ Desperation; but passive defence with e.g.   26...Ba8  27.Rf4  Rb7   27...f5  28.Rh4  +-  with the idea of Ng6 and Rh8 mate  28.Rxc5  would leave White with a comfortable advantage. }
27. bxa4 Ba8 28. a5 Rb7 29. Rxc5 Ra7 30. Nc4
{ And here Tomashevsky decided to resign, in view of the futility of any defence. Of course, he could have carried on for a while, for example with }
30... Rd8 31. Rf4 { 31.Nb6  f5  32.Rf4  Kf7  33.Rf2  Rd3  34.Re2  +- } 31... f5
32. Rf2
{ but the result would be the same.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw a variation where Black plays Be7 instead of Bd6, arising from a different move order. The game began as a Queen's Indian   subsequently Black decided to play  9...d5  . Black ended up playing Bd6 just the same, losing a tempo; this is hardly noticeable in a closed position, but still, if Black wants to play Bd6 it is preferable to do so directly.  Carlsen employed a very interesting idea, exchanging his good bishop on d3 for the knight on g6. There are few players who would have made such a move. Then he found a way to open the position on the kingside by sacrificing with f2-f4 and Rf1. White had in mind a decisive exchange sacrifice on f6.  Tomashevsky defended himself as best he could, until he made an error, failing to exchange pawns on d4 before offering the exchange of queens. Carlsen exploited this mistake by going into a very superior endgame.  He was able to invade the seventh rank and soon won two pawns, after which his opponent resigned. }
*

