[White "Vs ...d5 with early ...e6"]
[Black "Game 55 - Carlsen vs. Tomashevsky"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6
{ Here we have a London System which is heading towards a Queen's Indian ? } 4.
e3 Bb7 5. h3
{ As I am sure many players of the London System are aware, this is a slight inaccuracy in the move order; the move h2-h3 should be played only after Black has played Be7. }
5... Be7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O c5 8. c3 { The usual choice would be } 8... cxd4 9.
cxd4 Nc6 10. a3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vs ...d5 with early ...e6"]
[Black "Game 55 - Carlsen vs. Tomashevsky"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6
{ Here we have a London System which is heading towards a Queen's Indian ? } 4.
e3 Bb7 5. h3
{ As I am sure many players of the London System are aware, this is a slight inaccuracy in the move order; the move h2-h3 should be played only after Black has played Be7. }
5... Be7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. Nbd2 d5
{ But Tomashevsky switches to the main line of the Queen's Gambit set-up, with Be7, instead of continuing in Queen's Indian fashion. In particular I think that it is better for Black to play d7-d6, since this is a more flexible set-up. The systems with d7-d5 are particularly hard on the b7-bishop and although they can be more solid, I think that they considerably reduce Blacks possibilities of active play. }
10. Qe2
{ An interesting move; White controls the f1-a6 diagonal and supports a possible e3-e4. Practice has also seen: }
10... Rc8 11. Rad1 Nh5 12. Bh2 c4 13. Bc2 { Grachev-Frolyanov, Sochi 2015 } *

