1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 d5 5. c3 Bd6
{ Here the thematic   5...Qb6  is playable, e.g.  6.Qb3  Nc6  7.Nbd2  Be7  8.h3  O-O  9.Be2  Bd7  10.O-O   10.Qxb6  axb6  11.Bc7  Bd8 =  Grachev-Kamsky, Moscow 2008  10...Rfd8 ?   10...Rfc8  11.Rfe1  Be8   11...h6  12.Bh2  +=  12.Rad1   12.Bd3  c4  13.Qxb6  axb6  14.Bc2 =  E.Alvarez-Lobo, Gijon 2005  12...Qa5 ?!  13.Qxb7   13.dxc5  +=  13...c4 =  Vysochin-Rublevsky, Internet 2004  11.Qxb6  axb6  12.Bc7 !  +=  De Prado-Lorenzo, Ferrol 2013.  Another option is   5...Nc6  6.Nbd2  cxd4  7.exd4  Nh5 !?  8.Bg5   8.Be3  +=  8...Be7  9.h4 !?   9.Bxe7  Qxe7  10.Bb5  +=  9...h6  10.Bxe7  Qxe7  11.Ne5  +=  De Prado-Espieira, Spain tt 2014. }
6. Bg3 O-O
{ Another option here is   6...Nc6  7.Bd3   7.Nbd2  7...Bxg3  8.hxg3  Qd6  9.Nbd2  b6  10.Qe2  Bb7  11.O-O-O  O-O-O  12.e4  +=  De Prado-Wegerle, Portugal tt 2010. }
7. Nbd2 b6
{ The normal move order would be   7...Nc6  8.Bd3  b6  Here the main move is  9.Ne5   9.O-O  Bxg3  10.hxg3  Bb7  11.a3  Qd6  Eljanov-Gelfand, Moscow 2008  But on the ninth move   9.e4 !?  is interesting, for example:  dxe4 ?!   9...Be7 !?  10.dxc5   10.e5  Nh5  11.Qe2  Bb7  12.Qe3  Rc8  13.a3 =  10...bxc5  11.O-O  Bb7 =  Sarapu-Rogers, Auckland 1992;  Another idea is   9...Bxg3  10.hxg3  h6  11.e5  Ng4  12.Qe2 =  10.Nxe4  Nxe4   10...Be7  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.Nxf6+  Bxf6  13.Qc2  g6  14.O-O  +=  11.Bxe4  Bb7  12.Qa4   12.dxc5 !  Bxc5  13.Qa4  Rc8  14.Rd1  Qe7  15.O-O  +=  12...Qc7  13.dxc5  bxc5   13...Bxg3  14.hxg3  f5  15.Bxc6  Bxc6  16.cxb6  axb6  17.Qc4  +=  14.Bxd6   14.Qc4  +=  14...Qxd6 =  Burmakin-Iturrizaga, Barcelona 2013;  9...Bxe5 ?!   9...Qc7  10.f4  Ne7   10...Bb7  11.Bh4  Ne8  12.O-O  f5  13.Rf3  +=  Sedlak-Drozdovskyij, Ajaccio 2006  11.Bh4  Ne8  12.Bxe7  Bxe7  13.Qh5  f5  14.g4  ∞  Sedlak-Sargissian, Valjevo 2012  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.O-O ?!   11.f4 !  +=  is better, e.g.  f5  12.exf6  Nxf6  13.O-O  Bodiroga-Katzir, Rijeka 2010   11.Nf3  Bb7  12.O-O  h6  13.e4 =  11...Ndxe5  12.Bxe5  Nxe5  13.Bxh7+  Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Qxe5  f6  16.Qg3 =  De Prado-Portela, Spain tt 2014; }
8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Ne5 Nc6
{ The line with b7-b6 and Bb7 is considered the best for Black, forgetting about playing e6-e5 and focusing on controlling the e4-square. }
10. O-O
{ The alternative is   10.f4  Ne7  and now:  11.Qf3   11.Qb1  Ng6  12.O-O =  Kamsky-Dreev, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013.  11...Nf5  12.Bf2  Be7  13.O-O   13.g4 !?  Nd6  14.g5  Nfe4 =  Mitkov-Borges, Toluca 2009   13.Ng4 ?!  Nxg4  14.Qxg4  Nd6  =+  Pakleza-Jaracz, Chorzow ch-POL 2013  13...Nd6 =  14.Bh4   14.Qh3 =  14...Nfe4  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  =+  Pezerovic-Postny, Bad Wiessee 2013; }
10... Qc7
{ An alternative is   10...Rc8  11.f4   11.Nxc6  Bxc6  12.Qe2  c4  13.Bc2  b5 =  Reich-Zelcic, Schwarzach 2014  11...Ne7  12.Qb1 !  this is a thematic idea, not only in the London System but also in some other openings, such as the Torre Attack or the Colle: the queen puts pressure on h7 to provoke a weakness in Black's kingside position, after which the queen goes back; in addition, the queen controls e4.  Practice has also seen   12.Qf3  Nf5  13.Bf2  Be7  14.Qh3  Ne4  15.Rad1  Qc7  16.g4  ∞  Pham Le-Perena, Khanty-Mansiysk 2010  12...Rc7  13.Bh4  Ng6  14.Bg5  Qa8  15.f5 ?  Kamsky sacrifices a pawn without justification;  he should have played   15.Qe1  with a complex position; I am not convinced of the value of placing the queen on a8 behind the bishop and I think that White has chances on the kingside;  White could also consider   15.Bxf6  gxf6  16.Ng4  f5  17.Nf6+  Kh8  18.Qe1  ∞  15...Nxe5  16.dxe5  Bxe5  ∓  Kamsky-Korobov, Antalya 2013  Another typical option is   10...Ne7  and now:  11.Qc2   11.Qf3  Ng6  12.h4  Bxe5  13.dxe5  Nd7  14.Bxg6   14.Qh5  +=  14...hxg6  15.Qg4  Meier-Donchenko, Internet 2012;   11.f4 ?!  Ne4  Alcaraz-Defrance, Le Touquet 2011   11.Rc1  Ne4  12.Bxe4  dxe4  +=  Colas-Adamson, Las Vegas 2013.  11...Rc8  12.Rae1  c4  13.Be2  b5  Torre-Berkes, Istanbul 2012 }
11. f4 Nd7
{ 11...Ne7  12.Qc2   12.Qf3  Ne8   12...Nf5  13.Bf2  Be7  14.a4 =  13.Bh4  f5  14.Qh3  Nf6  ∞  12...Ng6  13.Rae1  a6  14.Ndf3  b5  15.Ng5  ∞ }
12. Qh5 f5 13. Qe2 Nf6 14. Bh4 Ne4 15. Nxe4 { 15.Rad1 } 15... fxe4 16. Bb5 Nxe5
17. fxe5 Be7 18. Bg3 { 18.Qg4  Bxh4  19.Qxh4 } 18... Bc6 19. a4 c4 20. Qg4 Qd7
21. h4 Rxf1+ 22. Rxf1 a6
{ 22...Bxb5  23.axb5  Rf8   23...Qxb5 ?  24.Qxe6+  +-  24.Rxf8+   24.Bf4  Rf5 =  24...Kxf8 = }
23. Bxc6 Qxc6 24. h5 Rf8 25. Bf4 Qd7 26. Qd1
{ 26.h6  g6  27.Bg5  Rxf1+  28.Kxf1  Bxg5  29.Qxg5  Kf8  30.Ke2  Qe7 = } 26...
Qe8 27. g4 Qc6 28. Kg2 Ra8 { 28...Qd7 = } 29. g5 g6 30. Qg4 b5
{ 30...gxh5  31.Qxh5  Qe8  32.Qg4  Qg6  33.Rh1  Bf8 = } 31. hxg6 hxg6 32. Rh1
{ 32.axb5  axb5  33.Qh4  Kf7  34.Qh7+  Ke8  35.Qxg6+  Kd7  36.Qh7  +- } 32...
Kf7 { 32...bxa4  33.Qh4  Kf7  34.Qh7+  Ke8  35.Qxg6+  Kd7 = } 33. axb5 axb5 34.
Qh3 { 34.Qh4  Rg8  35.Bg3  Bf8  36.Rf1+  Ke8  37.Qf4  Qd7  38.Qf6 } 34... Rg8
35. Rf1 Rg7
{ 35...Rf8  36.Qh7+  Ke8  37.Qxg6+  Kd7  38.Qh5  +-   35...Ke8  36.Qh7  +-   35...Bf8  36.Qh7+  Rg7  37.Qh8  Ke7  38.Bg3  Qe8  39.Rf6  +- }
36. Qh8
{ and Black resigned, since there is no good defence against the discovered check with 37. Bg3.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw some alternatives for Black, such as ... Qb6 and taking on d4. Black chose the line with ...b7-b6 and ...♗b7, which is the most solid, since it forgets about advancing with ...e6-e5 and fights for control of the e4-square, blocking White’s attack. The best plan for Black involves ...♘c6-e7- f5-d6. In the game, when Black closes the position with 12...f5, White should try to attack with the plan of ♔h1, ♖g1 and g2-g4, with good prospects. The exchange on e4 and then the exchange of light-squared bishops favoured Black, who equalised the game.  White tried to attack on the kingside, but only an error on Black’s part allowed White to mount an attack and win. }
