[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c3 d5 4. Bf4 Nc6
{ Another possible move order is   4...Nf6  5.e3  Be7  6.Nbd2  b6  7.Bd3  Bb7  8.Ne5  O-O  9.Qf3   9.h3  Ne4  10.Qh5  f6  11.Ng4  g6  12.Qh6  ∞  De Prado-Piay, Spain tt 2010  9...Nbd7  10.Rd1   10.Qh3  Re8  11.Ndf3  Nxe5  12.Nxe5  c4  13.Bc2  +=  Stefanova-A.Rodriguez, Madrid 1997  10...Nxe5  11.dxe5  Ne8  12.Qh3  +=  Ortega-Drei, Senegallia 1996 }
5. e3 Nf6 6. Nbd2 Be7
{ I think the variation with Be7 is inferior to the one with Bd6. } 7. Bd3
{ There are some better options for White in this position, such as:   7.h3  O-O  8.Bd3  Qb6   8...b6  9.O-O  Bb7  10.Qe2  Bd6  11.Bxd6  Qxd6 =  Potkin-Kurnosov, Moscow 2010  9.Rb1  when this move is possible there is no need to play Qb3  Bd7  10.O-O  cxd4   10...Rac8  11.Ne5  Nxe5  12.dxe5  Ne8  13.c4  +=  Miladinovic-Seitaj, Ohrid 2009  11.exd4  Rfd8  +=  Hebden-Britton, London 2013;   7.Ne5 !  is the best line to prevent the variations where Black plays Nh5;  O-O  8.Bd3  Qb6   8...Bd7  9.Qf3  Rc8  10.Qh3  +=  Annaberdiev-Seitaj, Bled 2002  9.Rb1  Bd7  10.O-O  Rad8  +=  Cuno-Chuikov, cr ICCF 1996;   7.h4 !?  is a suggestion of Pris;  O-O  8.Bd3  Ng4 ?   8...h6  9.Ne5  ∞  9.Bxh7+ !  Kxh7  10.Ng5+  Bxg5 ?   10...Kg8  11.Qxg4  e5  12.Qh5  +=  11.hxg5+  Kg6  12.Qxg4  Rh8  13.Rh6+ !  1-0 Bruno-Opacic, Verona 2005. }
7... O-O
{ Here the thematic move   7...Nh5  was interesting, harassing the bishop;  8.Be5   8.Bg3  Nxg3  9.hxg3  h6  10.Ne5   10.Qe2  b6  11.Bb5  Bd7  12.Bxc6  Bxc6  13.Ne5  Rc8 =  Kosic-Dehlinger, Munich 2013   10.g4  Bd7  11.dxc5  Bxc5  12.g5  Qb6  13.Nb3 =  Kosic-Savic, Herceg Novi 2001  10...Nxe5  11.dxe5  Bd7  12.Qg4  Bf8  ∞  Kamsky-Yakovenko, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013  8...Nxe5   8...f6  9.Bg3  g6   9...Nxg3  10.hxg3  f5  11.g4  +=  10.O-O  O-O  11.a3  a6  12.b4  c4  13.Bc2  Nxg3  14.hxg3  f5 =  Danielsen-Sai, New Delhi 2011  9.Nxe5   9.dxe5  g6 =  Winants-Michiels, Belgium tt 2004/05  9...Nf6  10.O-O  O-O  11.f4  +=  Safin-Sareen, Sangli ch Commonwealth 2000;  Another thematic option is   7...Qb6  although it is not so good here, for instance:  8.Rb1   8.Qb1  Bd7  9.h3  Rc8  10.O-O  cxd4  11.exd4  +=  Larsen-Garcia Padron, Las Palmas 1976  8...h6  9.h3  O-O  10.O-O  Bd7  +=  Bosch-Shreyansh, Dieren 2009.   7...c4  is playable, e.g.  8.Bc2  b5  9.Ne5   9.O-O   9.e4  9...Bb7  +=  Lukov-Colin, Paris 2003. }
8. O-O
{ This is the classical line of the London System. In another game we shall look at the so-called Pereyra Attack with   8.Ne5 !  as an alternative to capturing on e5 there is  Bd6 ?!  although moving the bishop again looks dubious:  9.Bg3  Qc7  10.f4  Rb8   10...Nd7  11.O-O  f5  12.Bh4  +=  Yemelin-Orlov, St Petersburg 2013  11.O-O  b5  12.Bh4  Be7  13.Qf3  b4  14.Qh3  g6  15.Ndf3  Nd8  16.Bxf6  Bxf6  17.Ng5  ±  De Prado-Stanoev, Arteixo 2007.  It is also possible to play   8.h4 !?  and   8.h3  which is more precise, preventing Nh5. }
8... b6
{ I think that Black does better to play   8...Nh5 !  for instance:  9.Qe2 ?!   9.Bg3  c4  10.Bc2  Nxg3  11.hxg3  b5  12.e4 =   9.dxc5  Nxf4  10.exf4  Bxc5  11.Nb3  Bd6  12.g3 =  Takemoto-Pham, Jakarta 1993  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  Nxf4  11.exf4  Qb6  12.Nb3  a5  =+  Tu-Ardiansyah Vung, Tau 2001; }
9. Qb1
{ An interesting idea that we mentioned earlier and which is played in other openings, such as the Torre Attack or the Colle: White tries to put pressure on h7 and control e4.  An alternative is   9.Ne5  Bb7   9...Nxe5  10.dxe5  +=  10.Ndf3   10.Bg3 !?  with the idea of f2-f4  10...Rc8  +=  Bartha-Juhasz, Budapest 2013. }
9... Bb7 10. Ne5 Qc8
{ A rather strange move. The idea is to play Ba6 in the future, but it was better to play   10...Rc8  11.Bg3  h6  12.f4  or   10...h6  11.h3  or   10...Bd6  with a balanced position. }
11. Bg3
{ White wants to employ the typical plan of the Stonewall with f2-f4. There were other good options, such as   11.Re1   11.a4  or   11.h3 }
11... g6
{ I think that it was better to play   11...h6  but after  12.f4  White has the initiative. }
12. f4 Nh5 13. Be1 { 13.Bf2  was a little better. } 13... cxd4
{ If   13...f6 ?  then  14.Nxg6  hxg6  15.Bxg6  Ng7  16.Bh7+  Kh8  17.Rf3  Bd6  18.Rh3  Ne7  19.Rh6  and Whites attack is decisive.  Instead,   13...Ng7  was a better defence and after  14.Qd1  the position is unclear. }
14. exd4 Nxe5 15. fxe5
{ The white position is superior: she has the half-open f-file and the possibility of attacking on the kingside, while the bishop on b7 and the queen on c8 are both passive. }
15... Ba6 16. g4 Ng7 { If   16...Bxd3  then  17.Qxd3  Ng7  18.Bg3  += } 17. Nf3
Ne8
{ Again   17...Bxd3  18.Qxd3  h5  19.h3  and   17...h5  18.h3  Bc4  19.Bd2  are better for White. }
18. Bd2 f5
{ After   18...Bxd3  19.Qxd3  Qc4  20.Qxc4  dxc4  21.Bh6  Ng7  22.Nd2  b5  23.Ne4  White remains with a decisive advantage: she threatens to play 24. Nf6+ and double rooks on the f-file. }
19. exf6 Nxf6 20. Bh6 Re8
{ There was no salvation.  If   20...Nxg4  then  21.Bxf8  Bxf8  22.Bxg6 !  Bxf1   22...hxg6  23.Qxg6+  Bg7  24.Ng5  +-  23.Bxh7+  Kh8  24.Qg6  Bh6  25.Rxf1  +- }
21. Bxg6
{ A thematic sacrifice that decides the game; finally the queen enters Blacks castled position from b1. }
21... Bxf1
{ If   21...hxg6 ??  then  22.Qxg6+  Kh8  23.Qg7#  More tenacious was   21...Ne4  22.Bxe4  dxe4  23.Qxe4  Bxf1  24.Rxf1  Bd6   24...Bf6  25.Ng5 !  Bxg5  26.Rf7 !!  with unstoppable mate  25.Ng5  Re7  26.Rf8+  Qxf8  27.Bxf8  Rxf8  28.Nxe6  Rfe8  29.d5  +- }
22. Bxh7+ Kh8 { Again it is mate after   22...Nxh7  23.Qg6+  Kh8  24.Qg7# } 23.
Ne5
{ Black resigned, in view of the unstoppable mate.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the line for Black with Be7 instead of Bd6. White used the traditional plan with Bd3, O-O and then the interesting idea of Qb1, followed by the Stonewall Attack with Ne5, Bg3, f2-f4.  In the opening White should prevent the lines with Nh5 by Black with moves such as 8. h3 and 8. Ne5, which is the best move. In the game Black weakened his kingside and the plan with Qc8 and Ba6 was dubious.  Finally White gained a decisive attack on the kingside, concluding with the sacrifice 21. Bxg6 !. }
*

