1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The idea of Bd6 can be employed even earlier; after   2...d5  3.Bf4  the move  Bd6  offering the exchange of bishops, is an interesting option, e.g.  4.Bxd6   4.e3  c5   4...Bxf4  5.exf4  Ne7  6.Bd3  b6  7.c3  a5  8.Ne5  Ba6  9.Qh5  g6  10.Qe2  Bxd3  11.Qxd3 =  Gareev-Luther, Turin ol 2006  5.c3   5.Bxd6  Qxd6  6.dxc5  Qxc5  7.c4  +=  5...Nc6  6.Bg3  Nge7  7.Bd3  b6  8.Nbd2  Bb7  9.Qe2  h6 =  Grachev-Naer, Moscow 2014;   4.Bg3  Ne7  5.e3   5.Nc3 !?  5...Nf5  6.Bd3   6.c4  Nxg3  7.hxg3  Nd7  8.Qc2  h6  9.Nc3  c6  +=  Heberla-Luther, Dresden 2011   6.Bxd6 =  6...Nxg3  7.hxg3  Nd7  8.Nbd2   8.c3  Qe7  9.Nbd2  Nf6  10.Ne5  Bxe5  11.dxe5  Nd7  +=  Lang-Hammes, Germany tt 2012   8.c4  c6  9.Nc3  h6  10.e4  dxe4  11.Nxe4  Bb4+  12.Kf1  Be7  13.Qe2  +=  Margvelashvili-Priyadharshan, Lubbock 2013  8...Nf6  9.Qe2  Bd7  10.Ne5  Qe7  11.O-O-O  +=  De Prado-Graa, Spain tt 2005.  4...Qxd6  5.Nbd2  Nf6  6.e3  Nbd7  7.c4  O-O =  Torre-Antonio, Tagaytay City 2013; }
3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 Bd6
{ Black offers the early exchange of bishops, which in theory favours him. } 5.
Bg3
{ There are other options, although this is the main one.   5.Bxd6  cxd6  6.c4   6.Nbd2  O-O  7.c4  dxc4  8.Bxc4  d5  9.Bd3  Nc6  10.O-O  Bd7  11.a3  - Strikovic-Ilincic, Vrnjacka Banja 1998   6.c3  O-O  7.Nbd2  Nc6  8.Be2  e5  9.O-O  a6  10.h3  h6  - Mikadze-Khukhashvili, Anaklia 2011  6...O-O   6...dxc4  7.Bxc4 =  7.Nc3  dxc4  8.Bxc4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  10.Qe2  Nbd7  11.h3  Rc8  12.Ba6  +=  Pri-Mohota, Creon 2007   5.Bd3  is also playable, for instance:  Bxf4  6.exf4  O-O  7.O-O  c5  8.dxc5  Qc7  9.Qd2  Qxc5 =  And finally   5.Ne5  O-O  6.Bd3   6.Nd2  c5  7.c3  Nc6  8.Bg3  Bxe5  9.dxe5  Nd7  10.f4  f6  11.exf6  Nxf6 =  Mirzoev-Velten, Bugibba 2012  6...c5  7.c3  Nc6  8.Nd2  Qc7  9.Ndf3 =  Derbenev-Kharchenko, St Petersburg 2011. }
5... Ne4
{ Black wants to exchange the g3-bishop for his knight and keep his d6-bishop.  Another option is   5...Bxg3  6.hxg3  Nbd7  7.Nbd2   7.c4  b6  8.cxd5  exd5  9.Nc3  Bb7  10.Bd3  +=  Alonso-Mindeguia, Bergara 2012  7...Qe7  8.c3   8.c4  c6  9.Qc2  h6  10.Be2 =  H.Nguyen-Medina, Tagaytay City 2013  8...e5  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.Nxe5  Qxe5  11.Qa4+  c6  12.Bd3 =  Sedlak-Ascic, Bosnjaci 2006;  Black can also play   5...O-O  6.c4  with this move order it is a good idea to transpose to the Queen's Gambit;   6.Nbd2  b6  7.c3  c5  8.Bd3  Ba6  9.Bxa6  Nxa6 =  Danielian-Koneru, Moscow 2011  6...c5 !?  7.cxd5   7.Nc3  Nc6  8.cxd5  exd5  9.Be2  Bg4  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.O-O  +=  Kir. Georgiev-Rakhmanov, Khanty-Mansiysk Wch blitz 2013;  it seems best to play   7.dxc5 !  Bxc5  8.Nc3  +=  7...Nxd5  8.Bc4   8.dxc5  +=  8...Nc6  9.Bxd5  exd5 =  Kamsky-Ivanchuk, Beijing 2013 }
6. Nbd2
{ An alternative is   6.c4  c6  7.Nc3  Nxg3  8.hxg3  Nd7  +=  Piankov-Schrter, Leipzig 2011. }
6... Nxg3 7. hxg3 Nd7
{ Practice has also seen   7...h6  8.e4   8.c4  8...dxe4  9.Nxe4  Be7  10.c3  Nd7  11.Bd3  c5  12.Qe2  cxd4  13.Nxd4  Nc5  14.Bb5+  Bd7 ?   14...Nd7  +=  15.Nxc5  Bxc5  16.Nxe6  +-  Yemelin-Aleksandrov, St Petersburg 2013,   7...c5  8.c3   8.dxc5 !?  Bxc5  9.c4  8...Nc6  9.Bd3  Qe7  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.e4  Bd7  12.Qe2  h6 =  Labeckas-Kalvaitis, Vilnius 2013. }
8. c3 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. Nf3
{ An earlier game had continued   11.Be2  g6  12.Bg4  f5  13.Bf3  c6  14.a4  O-O  15.Nb3  Qf6  16.a5  Be6 =  Kovacevic-Diaz, Vrnjacka Banja 1988. }
11... Bf6 12. Qc2 g6 13. O-O-O
{ It is typical for White, after the exchange on g3, to castle queenside and exploit the half-open h-file or else open the centre, and although the engines do not see any advantage, I think that White is slightly better. }
13... c6 14. e4 Qa5
{ The quieter   14...O-O  is playable, and if  15.Bc4  then  Qb6 !  16.exd5  cxd5  17.Bxd5  Bf5  18.Be4  Bxe4   18...Be6  19.Kb1  Rad8  =∞  19.Qxe4  Qxf2  with equality. }
15. exd5 cxd5
{ Black could also play   15...Qxa2  16.Qe4+  Kf8  17.Bd3  ∞  or   15...O-O  ∞ }
16. Qb3 { Black has a weakness on d5 and his king is still in the centre. }
16... Be6
{ It was better to sacrifice a pawn with   16...O-O  17.Rxd5  Qc7  =∞ } 17.
Bb5+ Kf8 18. Nd4 Rd8 19. Be2 { 19.Nxe6+  fxe6  20.Bd3  +=  was better. } 19...
Bc8 20. Kb1 Kg7 21. g4 Rd6 22. Qc2 h6 23. Qd2
{ White keeps improving his pieces; he has a strong knight on d4, while Black has a permanent weakness on d5. Whites position is preferable. }
23... Rdd8 24. Rh3 Qc7 25. f4 Qc5 26. Rd3
{ There were better options, such as   26.f5  +=  or   26.Rdh1 } 26... b6 27.
Ka1 a5 28. Bf3 { White lines up all his pieces against the d5-pawn. } 28... a4
{ Here   28...Ba6  was good, e.g.  29.Re3  Rhe8 =  30.Rxe8  Rxe8  31.Bxd5  Bxd4  32.Qxd4+  Qxd4  33.cxd4  Be2  34.Re1  Rd8  35.Rxe2  Rxd5  36.Rd2  f5 ! =  and Black should draw this ending. }
29. Nc2 Be6 30. a3 Qc4
{ After defending well, Black now goes wrong.  It was better to sacrifice the pawn with   30...d4 !  31.Nxd4   31.cxd4  Qb5  32.Rc3  Bb3  33.Bc6  Qa5  =∞  31...Bc4  32.Re3  Rd6  33.Be2  Bd5  and Black has compensation. After the text move Black loses the pawn without any compensation. }
31. Ne3 Qc8 32. Nxd5 Bxd5 33. Rxd5 Qc7
{ More tenacious was   33...Rxd5  34.Qxd5  Rd8  35.Qb5  Rxd1+  36.Bxd1  ± } 34.
g5 Be7 35. Qd4+ { Black resigned, in view of } 35... f6
{ 35...Kh7  36.Rh1  h5  37.f5  +- } 36. gxh6+ Kxh6 37. f5 g5 38. Rxd8 Rxd8
{ 38...Bxd8  39.Qxa4  +- } 39. Rh1+ Kg7 40. Qg4
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw Black playing an early Bd6 to exchange the bishops. We also saw the plan of Ne4, to take on g3 with the knight and retain the d6-bishop. We also analysed capturing on g3 immediately. In this type of variation, White usually castles queenside, exploits the half-open h-file, and opens the centre.  In the game, White gained the advantage, owing to the weakness of the d5-pawn, although he did not choose the best plan. Black defended very well until the error with 30... Qc4; he could have equalised by sacrificing the pawn with 30... d4 !, but after 31. Ne3 the d5-pawn fell anyway and White won without any problems. }
