{ @@HeaderStart@@The Pereyra Attack@@HeaderEnd@@  To conclude this chapter on the lines with d7-d5 and an early e7-e6, we are going to look at a complete game with the so-called Pereyra Attack.  This system is named after the Argentinean Manuel Pereyra Puebla, whom we mentioned in the introduction to this book; this attack is characterised by delayed castling, an early Ne5 and the advance h2-h4, with the idea of sacrificing with Bxh7+ or breaking with g2-g4. }
1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bd3 O-O 6. Ne5
{ The Pereyra Attack differs from the London System in that White does not castle and instead plays an early Ne5 and h2-h4, preparing to sacrifice on h7; alternatively he tries to attack the black king by bringing the queen to the kingside, or even by advancing with g2-g4. }
6... Nbd7
{ The knight can go to c6, but after taking on e5 it just transposes, e.g.   6...c5  7.c3  Nc6  8.Nd2  Nxe5 }
7. Nd2 c5 8. c3 a6
{ If   8...b6 ?!  then  9.Nc6  Kveinys-Nemcova, Cappelle-la-Grande 2014;  Another option is   8...c4 !?  9.Bc2  Nxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.h4 !?   11.O-O  +=  11...f6  12.Nf3  f5  13.Ng5   13.Nd4  +=  13...Bxg5 ?!  14.hxg5  +=  Matovic-Takac, Topusko 2012;  The main line is   8...Nxe5  9.dxe5  Nd7  10.h4 !  This is preparation for bringing the other knight to g5, opening the h-file and sacrificing on h7. Now:  f6   10...f5  closing the b1-h7 diagonal to prevent the sacrifice on h7, is the best defence:  11.exf6   11.g4 !?  Qc7   11...g6 ?!  12.gxf5  exf5  13.Qf3  +=  Hribar-Kukovec, Ljubljana 1995;   11...c4  12.Bc2  Nc5  13.gxf5  exf5  +=  Tkacheva-Dagaeva, St Petersburg 1999;   11...fxg4  12.Qxg4  ±  12.Nf3  fxg4  13.Ng5  Nxe5 ??   13...Bxg5  14.hxg5  g6  15.Qxg4  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  Qxe5  17.Qh4  Rf7  18.O-O-O  =∞  14.Bxh7+  Kh8  15.Bxe5  Qxe5  16.Qxg4  +-  Valero-Garcia, Valencia 2005;   11.Nf3  Qb6   11...h6  12.h5  Nb6  13.g4  fxg4  14.Nh2  +=  12.Rb1  c4  13.Bc2  Nc5  14.g4 !?   14.h5   14.Bg5  14...fxg4  15.Nd4  h5  16.f3  Nd3+   16...gxf3  17.Qxf3  Nd3+  18.Bxd3  cxd3  19.Qxh5  +=  17.Bxd3  cxd3  18.fxg4  +=  T.A. Petrosian-Skatchkov, Yerevan 2004.  11...Nxf6   10...c4  11.Bxh7+ !!  The thematic sacrifice in the Pereyra: White gains a clear advantage  (there are some long lines, but Blacks defence is difficult)  .  Kxh7  12.Qh5+  Kg8  13.Nf3  f6   13...Re8  14.Ng5  +-  14.Ng5 !  White sacrifices a second piece to open the h-file.  fxg5  15.hxg5  and now:  Rf5 ?   15...Bxg5 !  16.Bxg5  Qb6   16...Qc7  17.Qh7+  Kf7  18.Rh4  Nxe5  19.Bf4  Nd3+  20.Qxd3  cxd3  21.Bxc7  ±   16...Qe8  17.Qh7+  Kf7  18.Rh4  +-  17.O-O-O   17.Qh7+  Kf7  18.Rh4  Nxe5  19.Rf4+  Ke8  20.Qxg7  Nd3+ =  17...Nxe5   17...Rxf2  18.Rd2  Rxd2  19.Qh7+  Kf8  20.Rf1+  Nf6  21.b4 !  +-   17...Rf5  18.Rd4  Nf8  19.f4  +-  18.Rh4  Qc5   18...Qd6  19.Qh7+  Kf7  20.Bf4  Ke8  21.Qxg7  +-  Nd3+  22.Rxd3  Rxf4  23.Rxf4  cxd3  24.Rf7  19.Qh7+  Kf7  20.Bh6  Ke8  21.Bxg7  Rxf2   21...Nf7  22.Rg4  Kd7  23.Bxf8  Qxf8  24.Rg8  Qe7  25.Rg7  Ke8  26.Rd4  +-  22.Qh8+  Kd7  23.Bxe5  Qf8   23...Qxe3+  24.Kb1  +-  24.Qxf8  Rxf8  25.Rxc4  +-  16.Qh7+  Kf7  17.g6+  Ke8  18.Qxg7  Qb6   18...Bf8  19.Rh8  Qe7  20.Qh6  Kd8  21.g4  Kc7  22.gxf5  Bxh6  23.f6  Qc5  24.Bxh6  +-  19.Rh8+  Bf8  20.g4  Rxf4  21.exf4  Qxb2  22.Qf7+  Kd8  23.g7  Qxa1+  24.Ke2  Qxa2+  25.Kf3  Qa3  26.gxf8=Q+  Nxf8  27.Rxf8+  Qxf8  28.Qxf8+  with a decisive advantage;  11.Qh5 !   11.Nf3  c4  12.Bxh7+ !?  Kxh7  13.Ng5+  Kg8  14.Qh5  fxg5  15.hxg5  Bxg5  16.Bxg5  Qe8  17.Qh7+  Kf7  18.Rh4  1-0 Gonzalez-Sanchez, Spain tt 1993  11...f5   11...g6  12.Bxg6  hxg6  13.Qxg6+  Kh8  14.Qh6+  Kg8  15.Rh3  +-  12.g4 !  g6   12...c4  13.Bc2  g6  14.Qh6  +=  13.Qh6  and White had a strong attack in Bogoevski-Tuzi, Struga 2013; }
9. h4
{ The key move of the Pereyra Attack. White's idea is to support the other knight coming to g5 and to open the h-file;  the normal move here would be   9.O-O  += }
9... Nxe5
{ instead,   9...cxd4  10.exd4  Re8  11.Ndf3  +=  Nf8 ?   11...h6  12.Ng5  +-  was Vassallo-Garcia, Lisbon 2000. }
10. dxe5 Nd7
{ 10...Ne8  does not prevent the sacrifice:  11.Bxh7+ !  Kxh7  12.Qh5+  Kg8  13.Nf3  f6  14.Ng5  fxg5  15.hxg5  Rf5  16.Qh8+  Kf7  17.g6+  Kxg6  18.g4  +-  In the light of what is coming, the lesser evil would be   10...Ne4  11.Nxe4  dxe4  12.Bxe4  ± }
11. Bxh7+
{ Once again the thematic sacrifice on h7; yet some say that the London System is boring or drawish. }
11... Kxh7 12. Qh5+ Kg8 13. Nf3 Re8
{ The lines are similar to those given in the note at move 8, except that here Black has played a7-a6, which is even worse than c5-c4. The other defensive try was   13...f6  although this would not save the game after  14.Ng5  fxg5  15.hxg5  Bxg5   15...Rf5  16.Qh7+  Kf7   16...Kf8  17.Qg6  +-  17.g6+  Ke8  18.Qxg7  Nf8  19.Qh8  +-  16.Bxg5  Qb6   16...Qc7  17.f4  c4  18.O-O-O  Qc5  19.Qh7+  Kf7  20.f5  +-  17.Qh7+  Kf7  18.Rh4  Nxe5   18...Qxb2  19.Rf4+  Nf6  20.Rxf6+  +-  19.Rf4+  Ke8  20.Qxg7  Nd3+   20...Nf7  21.Bh6  Qd6  22.Qg6  Bd7  23.O-O-O  Qe7  24.Bxf8  Qxf8  25.Rh1  Ke7  26.Qf6+  Ke8  27.Rh7  +-   20...Qd6  21.Rxf8+  Qxf8  22.Qxe5  +-  21.Kf1  Qd6  22.Qg6+  Kd7  23.Qxd3  ± }
14. Ng5 Bxg5
{ If   14...Nf8  then  15.Qxf7+  Kh8  16.h5  Bxg5  17.h6 !  gxh6   17...Bxh6  18.Bxh6  18.Bxg5  Qxg5  19.Qxe8  Qg7  20.Rh3  +- }
15. hxg5 Kf8
{ The black king tries to escape, but will not find any safe hiding place. }
16. g6 Ke7
{ If   16...fxg6  then  17.Qxg6  +-  while if   16...Qa5  then  17.Qg5  f6  18.exf6  Nxf6  19.Bd6+  Kg8  20.Qh4  +- }
17. gxf7 Rf8 18. Bg5+ Nf6 { How should White continue the attack here ? } 19.
Qg6
{ An excellent move, not rushing to regain material and making way for the rook. }
19... Rxf7 20. Rh7
{ The complement to the previous move; Black is lost.  Another winning line was   20.exf6+  gxf6  21.Rh7  Kd6   21...Qf8  22.Qxf6+   21...Rxh7  22.Bxf6+  Kd6  23.Bxd8  Rh1+  24.Kd2  Rxa1  25.Qf7  +-  22.Bf4+  e5  23.Rxf7  exf4  24.O-O-O  +- }
20... Qf8
{ If   20...Qg8  then  21.exf6+  Kd6  22.Bf4+  Kc6  23.fxg7  Bd7  24.Be5  and there is no defence against 25. Rh8. }
21. exf6+ Kd6
{ If   21...gxf6  then  22.Qxf6+  or   21...Kd7  22.fxg7  Qg8  23.Qxf7+  Qxf7  24.g8=Q }
22. fxg7 Qg8 23. Bh6
{ There is no defence against 24. Rh8. An excellent game by White, and all the more meritorious in that the player was only twelve years old. I had taught him the sacrifice, but after Black's 13... Re8 he found all the moves on his own.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@To conclude the chapter on the QGD Orthodox Defence set-up with d7-d5 and an early e7-e6, we looked at the so-called Pereyra Attack against Blacks system with Be7.  White's plan consists of playing Ne5 and h2-h4 and preparing the Bxh7 sacrifice, or else attacking Black's castled position with g2-g4 or Qh5.  In the game, Black, after playing 8... a6, then exchanged on e5 and allowed the thematic sacrifice 11. Bxh7 !!, which gave White a decisive advantage. Black has two defences once White has played Nf3: one is to play f7-f6, but this fails to prevent the attack with Ng5, sacrificing a second piece; the other defence is to play Re8, as in the game, but this also gives White a winning attack.  The game is very instructive for the way White concluded the struggle with quiet moves, such as 19. Qg6 ! and 20. Rh7 !. }
*

