{ The Pereyra Attack . To conclude this chapter on the lines with d7-d5 and an early e7-e6, we are going to look at a complete game with the so-called Pereyra Attack. This system is named after the Argentinean Manuel Pereyra Puebla, whom we mentioned in the introduction to this book; this attack is characterised by delayed castling, an early Ne5 and the advance h2-h4, with the idea of sacrificing with Bxh7+ or breaking with g2-g4. }
1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bd3 O-O 6. Ne5
{ The Pereyra Attack differs from the London System in that White does not castle and instead plays an early Ne5 and h2-h4, preparing to sacrifice on h7; alternatively he tries to attack the black king by bringing the queen to the kingside, or even by advancing with g2-g4. }
6... Nbd7 7. Nd2 c5 8. c3 { The main line is } 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. h4
{ This is preparation for bringing the other knight to g5, opening the h-file and sacrificing on h7. Now: }
10... f5
{ closing the b1-h7 diagonal to prevent the sacrifice on h7, is the best defence: }
11. Nf3 Qb6 12. Rb1 c4 13. Bc2 Nc5 14. g4 fxg4 15. Nd4 h5 16. f3 Nd3+ 17. Bxd3
cxd3 18. fxg4 { T.A. Petrosian-Skatchkov, Yerevan 2004. } *

