[White "Vs other defences"]
[Black "Game 60 - Kamsky vs. Kazhgaleev"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 Nh5
{ Attacking the bishop on f4 is always a possible idea for Black. In this case it seems to me to be too early. }
3. Bg5
{ It is possible to play   3.Bd2  but the bishop is not well placed on this square, and after 2... g6  (it is not necessary to retreat the knight)  Black's previous move would be justified. }
3... h6 4. Bh4 g5 5. e3
{ This move is very important to safeguard the bishop; it is possible here because White has not yet played Nf3. }
5... Nf6
{ The knight returns home empty-handed, and having weakened his kingside. If Black insists on pursuing the bishop with   5...Ng7  6.Bg3  Nf5  then  7.Be5  gives White the advantage, since  f6 ??  8.Qh5# }
6. Bg3 d6
{ Practice has also seen   6...Bg7  7.Nc3  c5  8.dxc5 !?   8.Nge2  +=  8...Qa5  9.Qd4   9.Qd2  Qxc5  10.O-O-O  +=  9...Nh5  10.Qc4  Nxg3  11.hxg3  +=  To-Balint, Budapest 2014. }
7. Nd2 Bg7 8. c3
{ 8.Bd3  Nc6  9.Ngf3  Nh5  10.c3  Nxg3  11.hxg3  +=  Solovjev-Gajsin, Ekaterinburg 2008. }
8... Nc6 9. Bd3 e5 10. Ne2
{ The knight's development on e2 is more flexible, since on f3 it would always be exposed to the advance with e5-e4.  White has also played   10.Qc2  Qe7  11.O-O-O  Be6  12.h4  g4 =  Ponomariov-Andreikin, Moscow 2010,  and   10.Ngf3  Qe7  11.Qc2  Bd7  12.O-O  O-O-O  ∞  Baumann-Riemer, Internet 2003. The control of the f5-square should give White the advantage. }
10... Qe7
{ Another option was   10...Nh5  11.Qc2   11.h3  Nxg3  12.Nxg3  +=   11.O-O  +=  11...Be6  12.O-O-O  Qd7  13.f3  O-O-O  14.Bf2  ∞  Bhm-Hommeles, Netherlands tt 1997  (by transposition)  . }
11. h3 e4
{ I usually dislike this advance for Black, since on e4 the pawn can become weak and also the diagonal of White's dark-squared bishop is lengthened. It was better to play a waiting game, first developing the queen's bishop   11...Be6   11...Bd7  and waiting to see which side White is going to castle. }
12. Bc2 Bf5 13. b4 Bg6 14. Qb1
{ Putting pressure on the e4-pawn and also supporting the advance on the queenside. }
14... O-O 15. Bh2 Rae8 16. b5
{ Gaining space on the queenside;   16.a4  +=  and   16.O-O  +=  were also good. }
16... Na5 17. a4 b6 18. Qa2 Rc8 19. Nc4
{ A good move, to eliminate the a5-knight and allow the future opening of the a-file. }
19... Nxc4 20. Qxc4 d5 21. Qa2
{ Here   21.Qc6 !  was good, e.g.  Qe6  22.Bb3  Qxc6  23.bxc6  Bf5  24.a5  Rfd8  25.axb6  axb6   25...cxb6  26.c7  +-  26.Kd2  with advantage to White. }
21... c5 22. bxc6 Rxc6 23. Bb3 Rd8 24. O-O Bf5 25. c4
{ A typical move to shed the weakness on c3. In addition White gains a passed pawn in the centre and the bishop on h2 will be able to cooperate better with the rest of the white pieces. White is going to fight for control of the c-file. }
25... Be6 { if   25...dxc4  then  26.Bxc4  Be6  27.Rac1  += } 26. Rac1
{ 26.cxd5  Bxd5  27.Rfc1  +=  was also good. } 26... Qb4 27. cxd5 Rxc1 28. Rxc1
Nxd5 29. Bg3
{ This bishop exerts its power all along its diagonal and White has gained a comfortable advantage.  However, at this point the move   29.g4 !  was stronger, to prevent Black from defending his e4-pawn with f7-f5. }
29... Rd7 30. Rc8+ Kh7
{ It was better to play   30...Bf8  although after  31.Bc4  Kg7  32.Qc2  White has a clear advantage. }
31. Kh2
{ Here White could gain a decisive advantage with   31.Nc3 !  Nc7   31...Nxc3  32.Bxe6 !  fxe6   32...Nxa2  33.Bf5#  33.Qxe6  32.Bxe6  Nxe6  33.Qc2  f5  34.Bb8 !  with the idea of g2-g4, and White should win. }
31... f5
{ 31...Qe7  was a better defence, but White keeps the advantage with  32.Qc2  f5  33.Qc6 }
32. Nc3 Qa5
{ Again if   32...Nxc3  then  33.Bxe6 !  is winning, since if  Nxa2  then  34.Bxf5# }
33. Qc2
{ There were other options here, such as   33.Nxd5  Bxd5  34.Bb8  Kg6  35.g4  ±  The best move was   33.Nb5 !  Qb4  34.Rc6  Qe7   34...Bg8  35.Bd6  +-  35.Bd6  Qf7  36.Ba3  Bf6  37.Rxe6 !  Qxe6  38.Nc3  Nxc3  39.Bxe6  Nxa2  40.Bxf5+ !  Kg7  41.Bxd7  and wins. }
33... Bf7 { 33...Nb4  34.Qb1  Bxb3  35.Qxb3  Nd5  36.Be5  +- } 34. Nxe4
{ 34.Nb5 !  was another winning idea. } 34... Bg6
{ This move loses, but there is no defence anyway.  Capturing with   34...fxe4  fails to  35.Qxe4+  Bg6  36.Qe6  Nf6  37.Be5  h5   37...Qa6  38.Rb8  Rb7  39.Qc8  +-  38.Bxf6  Qf5  39.Bxg5  Qxg5  40.Qxd7  with a decisive advantage.   34...Nb4  35.Qb1  Bxb3  36.Qxb3  Qd5   36...fxe4  37.Qg8+  Kg6  38.Qe6+  Bf6   38...Kh7  39.Qxe4+  +-  39.Be5  Nd5  40.Rg8+  Kh7  41.Qe8  and mate in a few moves.  37.Nxg5+  hxg5  38.Qxb4  +- }
35. Qc6 f4
{ Everything loses:   35...fxe4  36.Qxd7  +-   35...Rf7  36.Bxd5  +-   35...Re7  36.Bxd5  fxe4  37.Bg8+  +- }
36. Qxd7 Bxe4 37. Rh8+
{ This wins, although White could mate more quickly with   37.Qf7  fxg3+  38.fxg3  Ne7   38...Qd2  39.Qg8+  Kg6  40.Qe8+  Kf5   40...Kh7  41.Qxe4#   40...Kf6  41.Rc6+  Kf5  42.g4#  41.g4+  Kf6  42.Rc6#  39.Rg8 !  Nxg8  40.Qxg8+  Kg6  41.Qe8+  Kh7   41...Kf6  42.Qe6#   41...Kf5  42.Qe6#  42.Bg8+  Kh8  43.Bf7+  Bf8  44.Qxf8+  Kh7  45.Qg8# }
37... Kg6
{ if   37...Kxh8  38.Qe8+  Kh7  39.Qxe4+  Kg8  40.Qe8+  Bf8   40...Kh7  41.Bc2#  41.exf4  gxf4  42.Bxf4  with mate in a few moves. In all these variations we can observe the bad position of the black queen, totally out of play and unable to defend the black king. }
38. Qe8+ Kf5 39. Qxe4+
{ The most attractive finish, although not the quickest, which was   39.Rf8+ !  Bxf8   39...Nf6  40.Be6#   39...Bf6  40.Qxe4+  Kxe4  41.Bc2#  40.Qf7+  Nf6  41.Be6#  Black resigned, in view of }
39... Kf6 { 39...Kxe4  40.Bc2# } 40. Re8
{ with mate in four moves.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw the outlandish idea 2... Nh5, harassing the bishop on f4. Although this is a common idea for Black, here it is too early. Black's move e5-e4 is not the best and White played very well on the queenside with some precise moves, such as b2-b4 and Qb1, and he gained the advantage after the pawn break 25. c4 !.  White's control of the centre and the c-file led to a strong attack against the black king. The game contained some good tactical details, with sacrifices and variations involving a mating attack, and the final queen sacrifice was the icing on the cake. }
