1. d4 g6 2. Nf3
{ With this move order, Black must always be prepared for   2.e4  Another option is   2.Bf4 }
2... Bg7 3. Bf4
{ Again   3.e4  is an option. I want to show an example from a real game between two masters, which ended in explosive fashion after  d6  4.Bc4  Nd7 ??   4...Nf6  5.Qe2  +=  is a comfortable variation for White  5.Bxf7+ !  In Ibragimov-Zhelnin, Moscow 1998, Black resigned here, in view of  Kxf7  6.Ng5+  Ke8   6...Kf8  7.Ne6+  +-   6...Kf6  7.Qf3#  7.Ne6  This is possibly the shortest win in a standard-play game between 2500+ masters. }
3... d6 4. e3 Nd7 5. h3 e5
{ This is Black's idea, to play a quick e7-e5 and transpose to variations of the King's Indian, but having avoided the main line, in which it is difficult to play e7-e5 under good conditions. }
6. dxe5
{ The first few times I came up against this line I always exchanged on e5, because it freed the d4-square for the f3-knight, in case Black advanced with e5-e4. Later I discovered that it is also good to play   6.Bh2  as we shall see in the next game. }
6... dxe5 7. Bh2 Ne7
{ Another option is   7...Qe7  8.Nc3  Ngf6 ?!   8...c6  is better, e.g.  9.Qd2  Ngf6  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  +=  9.Bc4 ?!  the right move is   9.Nb5 !  O-O  sacrificing the pawn is best; if   9...Qc5 ?  then  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Qd4  Qxd4  12.exd4  ±  10.Nxc7  Rb8  11.Be2  and although Black has some compensation I prefer White  9...O-O  10.O-O  e4 !   10...c6  11.a4  a5  12.Qd2  h6  13.Rfd1  +=  De Prado-Redondo, Spain tt 2013  11.Nd4 ?!   11.Nd2  c6  12.Nb3  Ne5 =  11...Ne5  12.Bb3 ?!   12.Be2   12.Qe2  were both better  12...a6   12...c5  =+  13.a3  c5  14.Nde2  Rd8  =+  De Prado-P.Fernandez, Ferrol 2013. }
8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bc4
{ 9.Qd2  +=  followed by O-O-O, was a good plan for White here. } 9... a6 10.
a4
{ It is essential to prevent Black from expanding on the queenside and to provide a retreat for the c4-bishop on a2. }
10... b6
{ Or   10...Nc6  11.O-O  Re8  12.a5  +=  Shvedchikov-Tseshkovsky, Arbo 2010. }
11. O-O Bb7 12. e4
{ This move is typical, blocking the diagonal of the b7-bishop, controlling d5 and hindering a future advance of the black pawns with f7-f5. The position now looks like a king's pawn opening. }
12... c6
{ This is already a clear mistake: it leaves the b7-bishop passive and weakens the d6-square. The idea of b6-b5 is not unpleasant to White. It was better to play   12...Nc6  13.Nd5  with advantage to White, but still with everything to play for. }
13. Ng5
{ The idea is to play Ne6 and also f2-f4, putting pressure on f7. Houdini considers that it was even better to play   13.Qd2 !  b5  14.Rfd1 !  Nf6   14...bxc4  15.Qxd7  15.Qe3  Qc8  16.Ba2  b4  17.Nb1  c5  18.Nbd2  which the engine considers to give White a decisive advantage, e.g.  Nd7   18...Nc6  19.Qxc5  +-  19.Nc4  Qc7  20.Nd6  h6  21.Nxb7  Qxb7  22.Rd6  +- }
13... Nc8
{ 13...b5  then  14.Ne6 !  fxe6  15.Bxe6+  Kh8  16.Qxd7  Qxd7  17.Bxd7  ± } 14.
Qd2
{ Whites idea is to line up his queen and a rook on the d-file.   14.f4 !  was also good, e.g.  Qe7  15.fxe5 !  and now:  Qc5+ ?   15...Nxe5  16.Bxe5  Qxg5   16...Bxe5  17.Rxf7  Rxf7  18.Nxf7  Bxc3  19.bxc3  Qc5+  20.Qd4  Qxd4+  21.cxd4  Kg7  22.Rf1  +-   16...Qxe5  17.Rxf7  Qc5+  18.Kh1  Qxc4  19.Rxf8+  Bxf8  20.Qd7  Ne7  21.Qxb7  +-  17.Bxg7  Kxg7  18.Qd4+  f6  19.Qd7+  Kh8  20.Rad1  ±  16.Kh1  +-  Qxc4   16...Nxe5  17.Bxe5  Qxe5   17...Qxc4  18.Bxg7  Kxg7  19.Qd7  Rb8  20.Nd5  cxd5  21.Rxf7+  +-   17...Bxe5  18.Rxf7  +-  18.Rxf7  +-  17.Qxd7  Ra7  18.e6  Ba8  19.Rxf7  Rxd7  20.Rxf8+  Bxf8  21.exd7  +- }
14... Qe7
{ If   14...b5  then  15.Rfd1  or   15.Ne6  fxe6  16.Bxe6+  Kh8  17.Qxd7  Qxd7  18.Bxd7  b4  19.Nd1  ±  15...bxc4  16.Qxd7  Qxd7  17.Rxd7  Ra7  18.a5  ± }
15. Rad1 Nf6
{ If   15...Nc5  then  16.b4  Bh6   16...Ne6  17.Nxe6  fxe6  18.Qd7  +-  17.f4  Bxg5  18.fxg5  +- }
16. Bb3 b5
{ If   16...c5  then  17.Nxf7  Rxf7  18.Bxf7+   18.Qd8+  Bf8  19.Qxe7  Nxe7  20.f4  ±  18...Qxf7   18...Kxf7  19.f4  19.f4 !  Qe8   19...exf4  20.Qxf4  and White wins  20.Qd8  Ne7  21.Qc7  Bc6  22.fxe5  Nxe4  23.Nxe4  Bxe4  24.Rd7  Bf8  25.Rxf8+  Kxf8   25...Qxf8  26.Rxe7  +-  26.e6  +- }
17. Nxf7
{ Once again it was better to play   17.f4 !  b4   17...exf4  18.Qxf4  b4  19.Ne2  h6  20.Nxf7  Rxf7  21.Bxf7+  Qxf7   21...Kxf7  22.e5  22.Rd8+  Kh7  23.e5  Qe7  24.exf6  Qxd8  25.fxg7  +-  18.Ne2  exf4  19.Qxf4  h6  20.Nxf7  Rxf7  21.Bxf7+  Qxf7  22.e5  +- }
17... Rxf7
{ If   17...c5  then  18.Nd8+   18.Nxe5+  c4  19.Nxc4  bxc4  20.Bxc4+  Kh8  21.Rfe1  +-  18...c4  19.Nxb7  Qxb7  20.Ba2  +- }
18. Qd8+
{ Once again   18.f4 !  was stronger:  Nd5   18...Nb6  19.Bxf7+  Qxf7  20.fxe5  Nc4  21.Qe1  +-   18...exf4  19.Qxf4  Nd5  20.exd5  Rxf4  21.d6+  Kh8  22.dxe7  Rxf1+  23.Kxf1  Nxe7  24.Rd7  +-  19.exd5  Qc5+  20.Kh1  cxd5  21.Nxd5  Kh8  22.Nc7  Qxc7   22...Rxc7  23.Qd8+  Bf8  24.fxe5  +-  23.Bxf7  Qxf7  24.Qd8+  Qg8  25.Qxg8+  Kxg8  26.Rd8+  Kf7  27.Rd7+  with a decisive advantage; }
18... Bf8
{ If   18...Qxd8  then  19.Rxd8+  Bf8  20.Bxe5  +-  or   18...Ne8  19.Qxe7  Nxe7  20.Rd7  Nd5  21.exd5  Rxd7  22.dxc6+  Rf7  23.cxb7  +- }
19. f4 { Finally White plays this move, opening the f-file. } 19... bxa4
{ This hastens the defeat, but Black was in a very difficult position anyway.   19...Qxd8  20.Rxd8  exf4  21.Rxf4  Nd6  22.Rxf6  Rxd8  23.Bxd6  Rdd7  24.e5  +-  The best defence was possibly   19...Nd5  20.Qxe7  Ncxe7   20...Ndxe7  21.fxe5  +-  21.axb5  axb5  22.fxe5  Rxf1+  23.Kxf1  Rd8  24.exd5  Nxd5  25.Ke2  Kg7  26.Ne4  +-   19...exf4  20.Rxf4  Nd6  21.Qxe7  Bxe7  22.Rxf6  Bxf6  23.Bxd6  Kg7  24.e5  Bd8  25.e6  +-  Finally, if Black plays   19...Qc5+  then  20.Kh1  Ne7   20...Nd6  21.Qxf6   21.Bxf7+  Kxf7  22.Qc7+  Kg8  23.Rxd6  Bxd6  24.Qxb7  ±  21...Nc4  22.Qxe5  Qxe5   22...Nxe5  23.fxe5  +-  23.fxe5  Rxf1+  24.Rxf1  ±  21.Bxf7+  Kxf7  22.Qc7  +- }
20. Qxe7 Bxe7 21. Bxf7+ Kxf7 22. fxe5 Ke6 23. exf6 Bxf6 24. Rxf6+
{ And Black resigned, in view of } 24... Kxf6 25. Rd7 Ra7 26. Bb8 Ra8 27. Rxb7
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw a line for Black with g7-g6, Bg7, d7-d6 and Nd7, in order to play a quick e7-e5. White can always play e2-e4 and transpose to a Pirc or Modern Defence.  In this game we saw the exchange 6. dxe5, although it is also possible to play 6. Bh2. In the game Black chose a passive plan with 9... a6 and 10... b6 and White stood better after he played 12. e4 !. Then, after the bad reply 12... c6, White gained a clear advantage and had several ways to finish the game.  Black's main problem was his lack of development and White won thanks to his control of the d-file, the opening of the f-file and the pressure on f7, which proved decisive. }
