1. d4 d6 2. Bf4
{ Another possible move order is   2.Nf3  Nd7  3.e4 !  and now:  g6   3...e5  4.Bc4  transposes to the Philidor, when the best lines for Black are  exd4   4...c6  5.O-O  +=  Black should avoid   4...Ngf6 ?  5.dxe5  Nxe5   5...dxe5  6.Ng5  +-  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Qxd8  Bb4+  9.Qd2  Bxd2+  10.Nxd2  ±  and   4...Be7 ?  5.dxe5  dxe5   5...Nxe5  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Qh5  6.Qd5  +-  5.Qxd4  +=   3...Ngf6 ?  4.e5  ±  4.Nc3  Bg7  5.Bc4  += }
2... Nd7 3. Nf3 g6 { If   3...c6  then  4.e4  Qc7  5.e5 !  dxe5  6.dxe5  += }
4. e3
{ Again the analysis engines prefer 4. e4 or   4.Nc3  transposing to the Pirc or the Modern Defence:  Ngf6   4...Bg7  5.Qd2 !?  and now:   5.e4  Ngf6  6.Be2  O-O  7.O-O  e5 !  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Be3 =  5...c6   5...c5  6.e4 !   6.dxc5  Nxc5  7.e4  Bg4  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Bxd7+  Nxd7 =  Pri-Vandenbussche, Belgium tt 2012/13   6.O-O-O  cxd4  7.Nxd4  a6 =  Asensio-Arribas, Llucmajor 2013  6...cxd4  7.Nxd4  Ngf6  8.Bh6  O-O  9.Bxg7  Kxg7  10.O-O-O  ∞  6.e4   6.O-O-O !?  Qc7  7.Kb1  b5  8.e4  e5  9.dxe5  dxe5  10.Bg3  ±  Pri-Beeckmans, Belgium tt 2012  6...e5   6...b5  7.e5  d5  8.Bd3  ±  Domenech-Mouhamad, Chateaux 2013  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Be3   8.Bg5  +=  8...Ngf6  9.O-O-O  +=  De Prado-A.Rodriguez, Spain tt 2008;  5.e4  Nh5   5...Bg7  6.Be2  +=  6.Be3  +=  Colovic-Todorovic, Vrnjacka Banja 2012;  Perhaps   4.e4  is better, and now:  Ngf6   4...Bg7  5.e5 !?  and now:  dxe5 ?!  If   5...Nb6  then  6.Nc3  +=  or   5...c5  6.c3  +=  The best idea is   5...Nh6 !  6.Nc3   6.Qd2  Ng4  7.exd6  cxd6  8.h3  Ngf6  9.Be2 =  6...Nf5   6...Ng4  7.Qe2  ±  7.Bc4   7.exd6  cxd6  8.Qd2  ∞  7...c5   7...O-O =  8.Ng5  e6   8...O-O ?  9.Nxf7  Rxf7  10.e6  +=  9.Bxe6  fxe6  10.Nxe6  Qa5   10...Qe7  11.Nd5  +-  11.O-O  cxd4   11...dxe5  12.dxe5  +=  12.b4  Qxb4  13.Nd5  Qc4  14.Nec7+  Kf7   14...Kf8  15.exd6  +=  15.e6+  Kg8  16.Qd3  Qxd3  17.cxd3  +=  6.dxe5  e6  7.Nc3  Ne7  8.Qd2  O-O  9.O-O-O  c6   9...Nc6  ±  10.Bg5 !  +-  5.Nc3   5.e5 !?  Nd5  6.Bd2  5...Bg7   5...c5 ?  6.dxc5  Nxc5  7.e5  ±  6.Qd2 !?   6.h3  c5  7.e5  Nh5  8.Bh2  cxd4  9.Qxd4  dxe5  10.Qe3  O-O  11.Rd1  =∞  6...c5   6...O-O  7.O-O-O   7.Bh6  Bxh6  8.Qxh6  c5  9.O-O-O  cxd4  10.Nxd4  a6  ∞  7...c5  8.dxc5  Nxc5  9.e5  Nfe4  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Qe3  d5  12.Kb1 !  +=  7.dxc5  Nxc5  8.e5  Nfe4   8...Nce4  9.Qd3  dxe5  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8  11.Bxe5  +=  9.Nxe4  Nxe4  10.Qb4 !  dxe5   10...d5  11.Bb5+  Bd7  12.Rd1  +=  11.Nxe5  Nd6  12.Bb5+  Kf8  13.O-O-O  += }
4... Bg7 5. h3 e5 6. Bh2
{ In the previous game we saw 6. dxe5, although the text move is more popular. }
6... Nh6
{ Black has also tried   6...Qe7  7.Be2  Ngf6   7...Nh6  8.c4  f5  9.Nc3  c6  +=  Bodiroga-Krasenkow, Rijeka 2010  8.c4   8.O-O  O-O  9.Re1   8.a4  8...Ne4  9.O-O  O-O =  Pantev-Chatalbashev, Plovdiv 2014,  or   6...Ne7  7.dxe5 !  dxe5  8.Nc3  +=  as in the previous game. }
7. Be2
{ 7.c3  O-O  8.Be2  f5  9.O-O  Nf7  10.Na3  a6  11.Nc4  Qe7 =  Akbaev-Bologan, KhantyMansiysk 2013;   7.c4  O-O   7...exd4  8.Nxd4   8.exd4 =  8...O-O  9.Nc3  Nc5 =  Rombaldoni-Rotstein, Livigno 2011  8.Nc3  Nf5  9.Be2  Re8  10.O-O  exd4  11.exd4  Nf8  12.d5  Nd7  E. Alvarez-Strikovic, Oporto 2012;  White's best continuation here is   7.dxe5  Nxe5   7...dxe5  8.Nc3  +=  8.Nxe5  Bxe5   8...dxe5  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  10.Nc3  +=  9.Nc3  Bxh2   9...O-O  10.Qd2  10.Rxh2  O-O  11.Qd2  += }
7... O-O 8. O-O f5 9. c4
{ It is better to play   9.Bc4+  Nf7   9...Kh8  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.Nc3  +=  10.a4  += }
9... g5
{ This is a typical idea in the King's Indian. Black employs a similar plan in the main line of the Mar del Plata variation. Here the engines dislike this move and award a clear advantage to White, although in practice it is not so easy for him.  Another option is   9...f4 !?  10.exf4  exd4   10...exf4  11.Nc3  ±  11.Nxd4   11.Nbd2  11...Qf6  12.Nb5   12.Nb3  Qxb2  13.N1d2  Nc5 =  12...Qxb2  13.Nxc7  Rb8  14.Qd5+ ?   14.Nd2  Qxa1  15.Qxa1  Bxa1  16.Rxa1  =∞  14...Nf7  ∓  Kleiser-Neubauer, Zwettl 2012  Black has also played   9...Nf7  10.Nc3  g5  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Qc2  ±  Mrkonjic-C. Foisor, Timisoara 2008. }
10. dxe5 dxe5
{ 10...Nxe5  is better, e.g.  11.Nc3  Nxf3+  12.Bxf3  +=  or   10...g4  11.hxg4  fxg4  12.Nd4  Nxe5  13.Nc3  += }
11. Nc3 c6 12. Qc2
{ In another game against the same opponent a couple of months earlier, I chose the natural reply   12.Qd6  which is also good; White gained a decisive advantage, although the game eventually ended in a draw. When I came to analyse the game later, Houdini indicated that 12. Qc2 was better, with a clear advantage to White, so I opted to play it in this game.  g4 ?   12...Nf7  13.Qa3  +=  13.hxg4 ?!   13.Nxe5 !  gxh3   13...Nxe5  14.Bxe5  gxh3  15.gxh3  ±  14.Nxd7  Qxd7  15.Qxd7  Bxd7  16.gxh3  ±  13...Nxg4  14.Bg3  Qe8  15.Nh2  Nxh2  16.Bxh2  ±  De Prado-Strikovic, A Corua 2013. }
12... Qe7 13. a3
{ The idea is to play b2-b4 and c4-c5, but the correct plan in this position is to control the d-file as quickly as possible.  So   13.Rad1 !  is better, e.g.  Kh8   13...g4  14.hxg4  Nxg4  15.Bg3  ±  14.Rd2   14.a3  ±  14...a5  15.Na4  g4  16.hxg4  fxg4  17.Ne1  +=  Yurtseven-Berkes, Skopje 2013. }
13... g4 14. hxg4 Nxg4
{ If   14...fxg4 ?!  then after  15.Nd2  ±  White can exploit the weakened e4-square. }
15. Bg3 Ndf6 16. Bh4 { A good alternative was   16.Rad1  += } 16... Kh8 17. b4
{ This move loses the advantage.  It is better to play   17.Rfd1  e.g.  Rg8  18.e4 !  f4  19.Rd2  Bh6  20.Rad1  Qg7  21.Rd8  Be6  22.Rxa8  Rxa8  23.Qd3  Rg8  24.Qd6  ±  Nxf2 ?   24...Ne3  25.Bxf6  Qxf6  26.fxe3   24...Bc8  25.c5  ±  25.Kxf2  Qxg2+  26.Ke1  +- }
17... Rg8 18. c5 Bh6 19. Bc4 Be6 20. Bxe6 Qxe6 21. Qa2
{ 21.e4  would lead to equality after  fxe4   21...f4  22.Rfd1  +=  22.Nxe4  Qf5  23.Rae1  Qxf3  24.gxf3  Ne3+  25.Ng3  Nxc2  26.Bxf6+  Bg7  27.Bxg7+  Rxg7  28.Rxe5 = }
21... Qe8 22. Rad1
{ Another inaccurate move;   22.g3  Qg6  23.Rae1 =  was better. } 22... e4 23.
Nh2 Qe5
{ It was better to play   23...Qh5 !  24.Bxf6+   24.Nxg4  Nxg4  25.Bg3  Rg7  ∓  24...Nxf6  25.Ne2   25.g3  f4  26.exf4  Bxf4  27.Ne2  Be5  ∓  25...Rg6  26.Qc4  Rag8  27.Ng3  Rxg3  28.fxg3  Bxe3+  29.Kh1  f4  30.gxf4  Bxf4  31.Rxf4  Qxd1+  32.Qf1  ∓ }
24. Bxf6+ Qxf6 { And here   24...Nxf6  25.Ne2  Nd5  =+  was better. } 25. Nxg4
Rxg4 26. Ne2
{ Now White is fine; the knight will defend the kingside well from e2 or g3. }
26... a5
{ Here   26...Rag8  was better, with equal chances, e.g.  27.g3  Qh4  28.Rd2  Qh3  29.Qf7  Rxg3+  30.Nxg3  Rxg3+  31.fxg3  Qxg3+  32.Rg2  Bxe3+  33.Rff2  Bxf2+  34.Kf1  Qd3+  35.Kxf2  Qd2+  36.Kg3  Qg5+ = }
27. Rd6
{ I saw the variation   27.Qa1  Bg7  28.Qxf6  Bxf6  29.Rd7  Rg7  30.Rfd1  axb4  31.axb4  where White is in no danger of losing, but I thought that this move was better and I played to win  Here the move   27.bxa5 !  was good, for instance:  Rxa5 ?   27...Rag8  28.g3  Qh4  29.Kg2  Qh5   29...Bxe3 ?  30.Qb2+  R4g7   30...R8g7  31.fxe3  Rxg3+  32.Nxg3  Qxg3+  33.Kh1  +-  31.fxe3  +-  30.Nf4  Qh4  and now:  31.Ne2   31.Qb2+ !  Bg7  32.Qd2  Be5  33.Qe1  with a slight advantage to White.  31...Qh5  32.Rh1  Rxg3+  33.Nxg3  Rxg3+  34.Kxg3   34.fxg3  Qf3+  35.Kh2  Qh5+  36.Kg2 =  34...Qg4+  35.Kh2  Qh4+  36.Kg2  Qg4+ =  28.Rd6  Qg5  29.Qf7  Rxg2+  30.Kh1  Rg4  31.Qe8+  Qg8  32.Qxg8+  Kxg8  33.Rxh6  +- }
27... Qg5 28. g3 axb4 29. Qb2+
{ 29.Qb3 !?  was interesting:  bxa3  30.Ra1  Rg8  31.Rxa3  Qh5  32.Qb2+  Bg7  33.Qa2  Be5  34.Ra8  Rxa8  35.Qxa8+  Rg8  36.Rd8  Qf7  37.Rxg8+  Qxg8  38.Qxb7  += }
29... Bg7 30. Qxb4 Be5 31. Qxb7
{ It was correct to sacrifice the exchange with   31.Rfd1 !  Bxd6   31...Qh4  32.Qxb7  Rag8  33.Kf1  Qh3+   33...Qh1+  34.Ng1  +=  34.Ke1  Bxd6   34...Qh1+  35.Kd2  ±  35.cxd6  +=  32.cxd6  Rd8  33.Qxb7  Qg7  34.d7  ± }
31... Rg8 32. Rd7
{ It was essential to play   32.Rb1 !  and now:  Bxg3  ends in a draw after   32...Bxd6 ?  33.cxd6  h5  34.Qc7  h4  35.Rb8  Qf6   35...hxg3 ?  36.Rxg8+  Qxg8  37.d7  gxf2+  38.Kxf2  Rg2+  39.Kf1  +-  36.d7  ±   32...Qh4 !  33.Qb8 !  A good move that guarantees the draw for White:  Bxg3   33...Bxd6  34.Qb2+  R4g7  35.cxd6  ±   33...Rxb8  34.Rxb8+  Kg7  35.Rb7+  Kf8  36.Rb8+  Kf7  37.Rb7+  with a draw by perpetual check.  34.fxg3  Rxg3+  35.Nxg3  Qxg3+  36.Kf1  Qf3+  37.Ke1  Qxe3+  38.Kd1  Qf3+  with a draw by perpetual check;  33.Nxg3  Rxg3+  34.Kf1 !  Qh5 =   34...Rg1+  35.Ke2  Qh5+  36.Kd2  ± }
32... Qh6 33. Kg2
{ This loses.  It was essential to try to save the position an exchange down by playing   33.Rfd1  Bxg3 !  34.Rxh7+   34.Nxg3 ??  Rxg3+  +-  34...Qxh7  35.Qxh7+  Kxh7  36.Nxg3  f4   36...Rxg3+  37.fxg3  Rxg3+  38.Kf2 =  37.exf4  Rxf4  38.Re1  and Black is clearly better but White has some drawing chances. }
33... Rh4 34. Rg1 Rh2+ 35. Kf1 Rb8
{ The move I had missed. Now White has to sacrifice the queen to prevent the check on b1, but the position remains lost. }
36. Qxb8+ Bxb8 37. Rd8+ Kg7 38. Rxb8 Qe6 39. Rb7+ Kf6 40. Rb6 Qa2
{ White resigned.  @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we saw that when when Black plays d7-d6, Nd7 and g7-g6 White has options of playing Nc3 and e2-e4, transposing to the Pirc or Modern Defence.  Remaining within the pattern of the London System, we looked at White's most popular alternative, which is 6. Bh2   instead of  6.dxe5  , which we covered in the previous game  . Black employed a typical King's Indian plan with 6... Nh6 and advanced his pawns with 8... f5 and 9... g5.  In theory this favours White, who obtains a clear advantage with either 12. Qd6 or 12. Qc2, as played in the game. White's plan is based on occupying the d-file as soon as possible. The black attack looks more dangerous than it actually is. White defended well and gained the advantage.  In the game, after mistakes by both sides, an interesting position was reached, which White should not have lost. }
*

