[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c6
{ Another, more normal, move order for playing the Old Indian Defence is   2...d6  3.Bf4  Nbd7  4.c3  e6  and now:  5.h3   5.Nbd2  Qe7  6.Bg3  h6  7.e4  Nh5  8.Bd3  g6  9.Qe2  Bg7  10.e5  Nb6  11.Ne4  Nxg3  12.fxg3  Bd7  13.O-O =  Hebden-Rowson, Edinburgh 2009.  5...g6   5...Be7  6.e3  O-O  7.Be2  Re8  8.O-O  Bf8  9.Bh2  b6  10.Qc2  Bb7  11.Rd1  +=  Petrovic-Blagojevic, Novi Sad 1996  6.e3  Bg7  7.Be2  b6  8.a4  a6  9.Na3  Bb7  10.O-O  O-O =  Rebane-Kir.Georgiev, Puhajarve 2013; }
3. Bf4 d6 { Here we have an Old Indian set-up against the London System. } 4.
h3
{ There are other options, such as:   4.e3  Nh5  5.Bg5  h6  6.Bh4  g5  7.Nfd2  Nf6  8.Bg3 =  White can also play   4.c3  g6  5.h3  Qb6  6.Qc1  Bg7  7.a4  Na6  8.Nbd2  +=  Bellon-Gonzalez, Las Palmas 1999;  Another perfectly good alternative is   4.Nc3  Qa5  5.Qd2  b5   5...Nbd7  6.h3  e5  7.Bh2  +=  6.Ne4   6.a3  +=  6...Qxd2+  7.Nexd2 =  Caceres-Salinas, Talcahuano 2012;  Finally there is also   4.Nbd2  Nh5  5.Be3  g6   5...Nf6  6.h3  +=  6.g3  Bg7  7.c4  O-O  8.Bg2 = }
4... Qb6
{ An interesting move that we have already seen in many other variations. Alternatives include:   4...g6  5.e3  Bg7  6.Be2  O-O  7.O-O  Nbd7  8.c4  Ne8  9.Nc3  Nc7  10.Bh2  b6  11.b4  Bb7  12.Qb3  +=  Grachev-Movsesian, Moscow 2010;  But perhaps the best is   4...Bf5  5.Nbd2  Nbd7  6.e3  +=  Frank-Moyano, cr 1997;  A typical Old Indian line would be   4...Nbd7  5.e3   5.Nbd2  Qa5  6.c3  g6  7.e3   7.e4  +=  7...Bg7  8.Be2  O-O  9.O-O  +=  Heinzel-Schnhof, Duisburg 2000  5...Qc7  6.Be2  e5  7.Bh2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.a4   9.c4  +=  9...b6  10.Nbd2  +=  Sitnikov-Petrov, Donetsk 2010 }
5. b3
{ It is not good to play   5.Qc1  c5  6.e3  cxd4  7.exd4  Nc6 =  The best move is to offer the pawn with   5.Nbd2 !  Qxb2  taking the pawn is critical; the alternatives are inferior:   5...Nd5  6.Nc4 !  Qb4+  7.Bd2  Qxc4  8.e4  Qa4  9.a3 !  ±   5...Bf5  6.Nc4  Qc7  7.e3  +=   5...c5  6.e3  +=  6.e4 !  Qc3   6...Qb6  7.Rb1  Qc7  8.Bc4  +=  is similar to the Vaganian Gambit that we saw in the chapter on the Benoni; White has a lot of compensation for the pawn  7.Bd3  Nbd7  8.O-O  e5  9.Bh2  exd4  10.Nc4  += }
5... c5
{ and   5...Nbd7  6.e3  g6   6...Qa5+  7.c3  +=  7.Bh2  Bg7  8.Bd3  O-O  9.O-O  += }
6. dxc5
{ If   6.d5 !?  then  g6  7.c4  Bg7  8.Nc3  Bf5  9.Rc1 =  It seems better to play   6.e3  e.g.  Nc6  7.c3   7.d5  Nb4  8.Nc3  Bf5  9.Rc1  Qa5  10.Bb5+  Kd8  11.O-O  Nbxd5  12.Nxd5  Qxb5  13.c4  =∞  7...g6  8.Bc4  Bg7  9.O-O  O-O = }
6... Qxc5 7. c4 g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Rc1 Bf5
{ Another option was   9...O-O  10.Qd2   10.e4  Nxe4  11.Nxe4  Qf5  =+  10...Nc6  11.e4  b6  12.Be2  Bb7 = }
10. Be3 Qa5 11. Bd2 Qd8 12. Nd4
{ Here   12.Ng5 !?  was playable, e.g.  h6   12...O-O  13.e4  13.e4  hxg5   13...Bc8  14.Nf3  +=  14.exf5  gxf5  15.Bxg5 = }
12... Be4 13. e3
{ If   13.Nxe4  then  Nxe4  14.e3  Nc6  15.Qc2  Nxd2  16.Qxd2 =  or   13.f3  Bc6   13...Nc6  14.e3  Nxd4  15.exd4  Bc6  16.Be3  +=  14.e3  O-O  15.Be2 = }
13... Nc6 14. Nde2
{ It was better to play   14.f3 !  Nxd4   14...e5  15.Ndb5  Bf5  16.e4  +=  15.exd4  Bc6  16.d5  Bd7  17.Be3  += }
14... Bd3 15. Nf4 Bxf1 16. Kxf1 O-O
{ Black has emerged in very good shape from the opening, after White failed to play the correct move 5. Nbd2. }
17. g3 e6 18. Kg2 d5 { 18...a6  19.Qe2  Qe7  20.h4  h6 =  was better. } 19.
cxd5 exd5 20. Qf3 d4
{ Black could have defended the pawn indirectly with   20...Re8 !  21.Nfxd5  Nxd5  22.Qxd5  Qxd5+  23.Nxd5  Rad8  24.Rc5  Re5  25.e4  Rxe4  26.Be3  Bd4 = }
21. Ncd5
{ It was better to take, because in the endgame this pawn will cause White problems:   21.exd4  Nxd4  22.Qxb7  Rb8  23.Qxa7  Ra8  24.Qb7  Rb8  25.Qa6  Nxb3  26.axb3  Qxd2  27.Rhd1  Qb2 = }
21... Nxd5 22. Qxd5 Qe7 23. Rhe1 Rad8 24. Qc5 Qd7 25. e4 Ne5 26. Red1
{ Here   26.Qxa7 !?  was interesting, e.g.  g5  27.Nd5  Nd3  28.Rc7  Nxe1+  29.Bxe1  Qb5  30.Bb4  Rfe8  31.Ne7+  Kh8  32.Qxb7  Qxb7  33.Rxb7  d3  34.Bd2  with good compensation. }
26... b6 27. Qc7 { It was better to play   27.Qd5  with equality. } 27... Qb5
28. Qxa7
{ This is losing. White could stay in the game with   28.Rf1  Rfe8  29.f3  ∞ }
28... g5
{ With this move Black decides the game: the white king is weak and the pawn on d4 is strong. }
29. Qa4
{ This loses a piece, but if   29.Nh5  Qe2 !  -+  or   29.Nd5  Qd3  -+ } 29...
Qxa4 30. bxa4 gxf4 31. gxf4 Nd3
{ Black keeps his extra piece and although White has two pawns for it, that is not enough here. }
32. Rc6 Nb2 33. Rb1 Nxa4 34. f5
{ More tenacious was   34.e5  f6   34...Ra8  35.Rb4  Rfd8  36.Rcc4  Nc5  37.Rxd4  Rxd4  38.Rxd4  ∓  35.e6  Rfe8  36.Rb4  Nc5  37.f5   37.Rbxb6  Ne4  38.Bb4  d3  -+  37...Bf8  38.Rbxb6  Rd5  -+ }
34... Rfe8 35. f3 Ra8 36. Kh1 Nc5 37. Rg1
{ If   37.Rcxb6  Nd7  38.R6b3  Rxa2  -+ } 37... Kh8 38. Rc7 Rf8 39. Bf4 Rac8
40. Re7 Rce8 41. Rc7 Nd3 42. Bd6 Rg8 43. Rxf7 Be5 44. Rxg8+ Rxg8 45. Rd7
{ This allows mate, but there was no defence. If   45.Bxe5+  Nxe5  46.Rc7  Nxf3  47.Rc1  d3  -+ }
45... Nf2#
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY@@HeaderEnd@@In this game we looked at the Old Indian Defence with d7-d6, c7-c6, Nf6 and Nbd7 against the London System.  White chose to play 4. h3, although there are other options such as 4. c3, 4. e3, 4. Nc3 or 4. Nbd2. After 4... Qb6, attacking the b2-pawn, White played 5. b3, but the best is 5. Nbd2, sacrificing a pawn, which gives White the advantage.  Black equalised the game and in the middlegame, after the critical 20... d4, White should have taken the pawn, with equality, but then after a couple of mistakes White was lost, thanks to the strength of Black's d4-pawn and the weakness of the white king. }
*

