1. d4 b5
{ The Polish Defence ! We shall complete our theoretical survey by looking at some irregular openings for Black against 1. d4:   1...e5  The Englund Gambit does not have a very good reputation;  2.dxe5  Nc6   2...d6  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.Bg5  transposes  3.Nf3  Qe7   3...d6  4.Bg5  Be7   4...Qd7  5.exd6  Bxd6  6.Nc3  +=  5.Bxe7  Qxe7  6.exd6  cxd6  7.Nc3  +=   7.e3  +=  4.Bg5   4.Nc3  Nxe5  5.e4  d6  6.Be2  Nxf3+  7.Bxf3  Be6  8.O-O  ±  Kvon-Saidov, Tashkent 2011  4...Qb4+  5.Nc3  Qxb2  6.Bd2  Bb4  7.Rb1  Qa3  8.Nd5  Bxd2+  9.Qxd2  Kd8  10.e4  ±  St.Hansen-Toll, Rynia 2013   1...a6  A few strong grandmasters, such as the French grandmaster Christian Bauer, play this irregular defence. Against 1. e4, 1a6 is called the St. George, but in response to 1. d4 it does not appear to have a name; perhaps it should be called the Bauer Defence. White can play:  2.e4   2.Bf4  d5  3.e3  Nf6  4.Nf3  Bg4  5.c4  dxc4   5...c6  6.Nc3  +=  Gibiec-Velicka, Pribram 2000  6.Bxc4  e6  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Nc6  9.Nc3  +=  Cebalo-Feletar, Belisce 1999;   2.c4  b5  3.cxb5   3.e4 !  Bb7  4.d5   4.Nd2  +=  4...e6  5.Nf3  +=  Fluvia Potatos-Shengelia, Banyoles 2007  3...axb5  4.e4  Bb7   4...b4  5.Bxb5  Bxe4  6.Nf3  Nf6  7.Nc3 =  Gajewski-Bauer, France tt 2013.  2...b5   2...e6  3.c4   3.Nc3  d5  transposes to a good French for White  3...d5  4.exd5  exd5  5.Nc3  Bb4  6.Nf3   6.cxd5  Qxd5  7.Nf3  +=  6...Nf6  7.Bd3  O-O  8.O-O  dxc4  9.Bxc4 =  Meier-Bauer, Biel 2012  3.Bd3   3.a4   3.Nf3  3...Bb7  4.Nf3  e6  5.O-O  Nf6  6.Qe2  ±  Grachev-Pridorozhni, Olginka 2011;   1...b6  The English Defence This often transposes to the Queen's Indian, the Réti Reversed or the Dutch, or, if White plays an early e2-e4, to Owens Defence.  2.e4   2.Bf4  Bb7  3.Nf3   3.Nd2  f5  4.e3  Nf6  5.Ngf3  e6  6.h3  Be7  7.g4  ∞  Kosic-Hoang Thanh Trang, Budapest 2006   3.e3  f5  4.Nf3  e6  3...e6   3...Nf6  4.e3  e6  5.Nbd2  Be7  6.h3  reaches the normal line of the Queen's Indian against the London System  4.e3  f5  5.Bd3  Nf6  6.O-O   6.Nbd2  Bd6  7.Bxd6  cxd6  8.Qe2  O-O  Barnaure-Miezis, Dubai 2004  6...Be7  7.c4  O-O  8.Nc3  d6  9.h3  +=  Walaszczyk-Szromba, Polanica Zdroj 2004;   2.Nc3  Bb7  3.e4  Nf6  4.Bd3  e6  5.Nge2  d5  6.e5  Nfd7  7.Nf4  g6  8.Qg4  +=  Oral-Gawehns, Hamburg 1999.  2...Bb7  3.Bd3  e6  4.Nf3  c5  5.c3  Nf6  6.Qe2   6.e5 !  Nd5  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Be4  +=  Ni Hua-Khairullin, Khanty-Mansiysk 2011  6...d5  7.e5  Nfd7  8.O-O  Be7 =  Moiseenko-Bauer, Bilbao 2004;   1...Nc6  The Lundin Defence  2.d5  Ne5  and now:  3.f4   3.e4  e6  and now:  4.dxe6   4.f4  exd5 !?   4...Ng6  5.Nc3  +=  5.fxe5   5.Nc3  +=  5...Qh4+  6.Ke2  Qh5+  7.Kd2  Qh6+  8.Kc3  Qc6+  9.Kd2  Qh6+  10.Kd3  Qa6+  11.Kd2  Qh6+  12.Ke1  Qh4+  13.Kd2  Qf4+  14.Kc3  Qxe5+  15.Qd4  Bb4+   15...Qxe4  =∞  16.Kd3  dxe4+  17.Qxe4  Qxe4+  18.Kxe4  Nf6+  +=  Erds-Rapport, Hungary tt 2011/12  4...dxe6   4...fxe6  5.Nc3  b6  6.Nf3  Nxf3+  7.Qxf3  Bb7  8.Qh5+   8.Qg3  +=  Spacek-Gross, Trier 1997  8...g6  9.Qe5  Nf6  10.Bb5  c6  11.Be2  +=  Volkov-Savchenko, Moscow 2006  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.f4  Ng6  7.Nf3  +=  Karpov-Berlandier, Cannes Internet simul 1998;   3.Nc3  e6  4.e4  exd5  5.exd5   5.f4 !  Bb4   5...Ng6  6.Qxd5  +=   5...d4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  7.Qc4  +=  6.Nge2  Ng6  7.Qxd5  Nf6  8.Qd3  +=  5...Bc5  6.Ne4  Qe7  +=  Van Wely-Zagema, Dortmund 1992;   3.Bf4 ?!  Ng6  4.Bg3  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5 =  Bacrot-Bauer, Ajaccio 2007  3...Ng6  4.e4  e5  5.dxe6  fxe6  6.Nf3  b6  7.Bd3  Bb7  8.Qe2  +=  Another irregular defence is   1...c6  2.Bf4  Qb6  3.Nf3   3.b3 =   3.Nc3  Qxb2  4.Bd2  =∞  3...Qxb2  4.Nbd2  Nf6  5.Rb1  Qxa2  6.e4  += }
2. Nf3
{ The engines consider the best move here to be   2.e4 !  Bb7   2...c6  3.Nf3  e6  4.a4  b4  ±  Cheparinov-Pesotsky, Bastia 2011  3.Nd2   3.Bd3  Nf6  4.Qe2  c5  5.dxc5  Na6  6.Nf3  Nxc5 =  Wojtaszek-Pakleza, Warsaw 2010  or   3.Bxb5 !  Bxe4  4.Nf3  transposing to the game  3...a6  and now:  4.a4   4.Ngf3  e6  5.Bd3  Nf6   5...c5  6.dxc5  Bxc5  7.a4  Nf6   7...Nc6  +=  8.O-O  bxa4 ?   8...Qc7  ±  Cosma-Scekic, Subotica 2002  9.e5  Ng4  10.Rxa4  +-  Leitao-Dominguez, Menden 2009  6.O-O  c5  7.c3  Nc6  +=  Karjakin-Popov, Panormo 2002;   4.Bd3  e6  5.a4  c5  6.dxc5  Bxc5  7.Ngf3  +=   4.b3 !?  the alternatives above are better  e6  5.Bb2  d6  6.Ngf3  Nd7  7.c4  +=  Dreev-Kossobudzki, Warsaw 2013.  4...b4  5.c4   5.Ngf3  +=   5.Bd3  +=  5...bxc3  6.bxc3  ±  Lputian-Alexandria, Biel 1997;  Another option is   2.Bf4  intending to play a London System set-up. For instance,  Bb7  3.e3  Nf6  4.h3  e6  5.Nf3  a6  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.c3  Ne7  8.Nbd2  Ng6  9.Bh2  +=  Cebalo-Vasiukov, Condino 2009. }
2... Bb7
{ Or   2...Nf6  3.Bg5   3.Nbd2  Bb7  4.e4   3.Bf4  Bb7  4.e3  +=  3...Bb7  4.Nbd2  a6  5.c3  e6  6.e4  h6  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  +=  Wang Yue-Ponkratov, Zurich 2010. }
3. e4
{ Other options are:   3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  e6  5.O-O  c5  6.c3 =  Yakovenko-Pridorozhni, Khanty-Mansiysk Wch blitz 2013;   3.Bf4  Nf6  4.e3  +=   3.e3  a6  4.Bd3  d6  5.a4  b4  6.O-O  Nd7  7.e4  +=  Sambuev-Howell, Ottawa 2007. }
3... Bxe4 { If   3...a6  then  4.Bd3  ± } 4. Bxb5 Nf6 5. O-O e6
{ If   5...c6  then  6.Ba4  d5  7.Ne5  Qb6  8.c4  ±  or   5...Bb7  6.c4  e6  7.Nc3  += }
6. c4 Be7 7. Nc3 Bb7
{ White is better, with a space advantage. The position is a reversed Sokolsky Opening   1.b4  e5  2.Bb2  Bxb4  3.Bxe5  with an extra tempo for White. }
8. d5
{ White gains more space;   8.Ba4  O-O  9.Bc2  d6  10.Re1  +=  or   8.Re1  +=  are more common. }
8... O-O 9. Bf4
{ Here   9.Ba4  has been played more often, e.g.  Na6   9...Bb4  10.Bg5  Bxc3  11.bxc3  h6  +=  Speelman-Hodgson, London 2007  10.Re1   10.a3  Nc5  11.Bc2  a5  12.Be3  exd5  13.cxd5  +=  Wojtkiewicz-Bronstein, Reykjavik 1994  10...Bb4  11.Bg5  Nc5  12.Bc2  Bxc3 ?   12...h6 =  13.bxc3  d6  14.Bh4  h6  15.Nd4  exd5 ?  16.Nf5  +-  Eingorn-Semeniuk, USSR 1984. }
9... Na6
{ Let us examine a few alternatives:   9...c6 ?  10.d6 !  cxb5  11.dxe7  Qxe7  12.Bd6  ±   9...d6  is better:  10.Re1   10.Nd4  e5  11.Nf5  exf4  12.Re1  +=  10...c6  11.dxc6  Nxc6  12.Bxc6  Bxc6  13.Nd4  Bb7  14.Ndb5  Ne8 =  Piasetski-Ramirez, Alajuela 2014;   9...Bd6  10.Bg5   10.Bxd6  cxd6  11.Qd4  e5  12.Qe3  +=  10...h6  11.Bh4  g5  12.Bg3  +=  Velikanov-Gubanov, Kolomna 2012;   9...Re8  10.Re1  Bf8  11.Nd4   11.a3  +=   11.dxe6  +=  11...c6  12.dxc6  Nxc6 =  Mackle-Arkell, Paignton 2011. }
10. Re1 Qc8 11. Nd4 Bb4 12. Bg5
{ Exploiting the shortage of black pieces on the kingside. } 12... Ne8
{ It was better to play   12...Bxc3  13.Bxf6  Bxd4   13...gxf6  14.bxc3  +-   13...Bxb2  14.Qg4  +-  14.Bxd4  ± }
13. Re3
{ The most human and natural move, preparing an attack on the black king. But White could have won here with the move   13.Qa4 !  e.g.  Bxc3  14.Bxd7  Nc5  15.Bxc8  Nxa4  16.Bxb7  Rb8  17.bxc3  Rxb7  18.Be7  +- }
13... c6 14. Bxa6 Bxa6 15. Qh5 f6
{ If   15...Bxc4  then  16.Rh3  h6  17.Bxh6  +-  or   15...g6  16.Qh4  Bxc3  17.bxc3  c5  18.Rh3  h5  19.Nf3  ± }
16. Rh3
{ Whites attack is unstoppable now; Blacks pieces are situated too far away from their king. }
16... fxg5
{ If   16...Bxc3  then  17.Qxh7+  Kf7  18.Rxc3  fxg5  19.dxe6+  dxe6  20.Nf3  Ke7  21.Re1  and the black king will not survive. }
17. Qxh7+ Kf7 18. Qh5+ { Here   18.dxe6+  dxe6  19.Ne4  was also winning. }
18... Kg8
{ If   18...Ke7  then  19.Qxg5+  Kf7  20.Qh5+  Ke7  21.Qh4+  Nf6   21...Rf6  22.dxe6  dxe6  23.Ne4  +-   21...Kf7  22.dxe6+  dxe6  23.Ne4  +-  22.dxe6  dxe6  23.Re1  Kf7  24.Nf3  and wins. }
19. Qh7+ Kf7 20. Ne4 Bxc4 21. Qh5+ Ke7
{ 21...Kg8  22.Nxg5  with unstoppable mate  or   21...g6  22.Qh7+  Ng7  23.Rf3+  +- }
22. Qxg5+ Kf7 23. Qh5+ Ke7 24. Qg5+ Kf7 25. dxe6+ dxe6 26. Nf3
{ The knight regroups, threatening to land the decisive blow on e5. } 26... Kg8
27. Qh4 Rxf3 28. Qh7+ Kf8 29. Rxf3+ Ke7 30. Qh4+
{ And Black resigned, in view of } 30... Nf6
{ 30...Kd7  31.Rf7+  Be7  32.Qxe7# } 31. Nxf6 gxf6 32. Qxc4
{ @@HeaderStart@@SUMMARY:@@HeaderEnd@@In this final game we have examined various irregular, or not very common, replies for Black to 1. d4.  Against most of these we can employ a specific series of moves, which, as we explained, are simply the best. Nevertheless, we can also try to play a London System just the same.  The majority of these irregular defences do not pose a problem if White is at least minimally prepared. In the main game we saw the Polish Defence with 1... b5, which is normally played using the move order 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 b5. White decided to exchange the b5-pawn for the one on e4 and then, after playing c2-c4, he gained a good advantage in development. Black played rather passively and White exploited this to mount a strong attack against the black king, including a piece sacrifice.  This was a very good victory by Kramnik, playing aggressively against Carlsen, who rarely loses in this manner. }
*

