1. Bxh6
{ Attacking the black king. This sacrifice should win. But it was essential to calculate accurately what happens if Black does not capture the piece right away and plays 18e5 instead. }
1... e5
{ The hardest thing for me to calculate was how to respond to the annoying   18...Kh8  White has to find  19.Bf4 !!  and then if  e5  20.Qe2 !!  this is the hidden idea; the queen goes to h5, with a mating attack, e.g.  exd4   20...exf4  21.Ng5 !  g6  22.Nge6  Bxe6   22...Qc8  23.Bxg6  23.Bxg6  Ng7  24.Nxe6  Qd7  25.Qg4  and Black has to give up a lot of material to prevent mate  21.Ng5  g6  22.Bxg6  Ng7  23.Nf7+  Rxf7  24.Bxf7  and Whites advantage is decisive: he has a rook and two pawns  (with more to follow)  and an attack, for two passive pieces  Taking the piece does not save Black:   18...gxh6  19.Bh7+  Kh8  20.Qg6  Bxc5  21.Qxh6  Qe7  22.Bb1+  Kg8  23.Rxc5  Bxa4 ?  24.Nxe6 }
2. Bh7+ Kh8 3. Qg6 Rf7 { 20...gxh6  21.Bg8   20...Rg8  21.Bf4 !! } 4. Bf4 exf4
{ 21...exd4  22.Nh4 !!   22.Qh5 ?  Bg4 !  22...Bg4  23.Qxf7  Kxh7  24.Qg6+  Kg8  25.Qxg4  +- }
5. Qh5
{ This wins, but the pretty   22.Nh4 !!  was more direct, e.g.  f5   22...Bg4  23.Ndf5  23.Qh5  Bxh4  24.Bg6+  Kg8  25.exf4 !!  Nf6  26.Bxf7+  Kf8  27.Qh8+  Kxf7   27...Ke7  28.Rfe1+  28.Qxd8 }
5... Bg4 6. Qxf7 Kxh7 7. Nh4 { 1-0 in 29 moves  (see Game 31)  . } *

