1. Bxh7+
{ The piece sacrifice is interesting; although it brings no objective advantage, it complicates the game and in a practical game Blacks defence is difficult.   12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Qh5+  Kg8  14.Ng6  Rd8  Another option was   14...Re8  15.e4  Ne7  16.e5  Nxg6  17.exd6  Qc6  18.Qxg6  Nf8  19.Qd3  +=  If   14...cxd4  then  15.exd4  Rd8  16.Nf3  with compensation.  15.Nf3   15.e4 !  cxd4   15...f5  16.e5  Be7  17.Nf3  +=  16.exd5  Nf8   16...Ne7  17.Nxe7+  Bxe7  18.dxe6  +=   16...exd5  17.Qxd5+  Kh7  18.Qh5+  Kg8  19.Ne4  ±  17.dxc6  Nxg6  18.Qxg6  dxc3  19.Ne4  Be7  is unclear.  15...Nf8  16.Qh8+  Kf7  17.Ng5+ ?  This move is a bad one.  White could have continued with   17.Ngh4 !  Ke8  18.Ng5 !  Ne7  19.Qxg7  fxg5  20.fxg5  Bxg3  21.Rxf8+  Kd7  22.hxg3  Rxf8  23.Qxf8  Qxg3  24.Nf3  with good compensation: two pawns for the piece, including a passed pawn on g5, and the black king still in the centre.  Even better was   17.Nge5+ !  Ke8   17...Bxe5  18.fxe5  f5  19.Bh4  Ke8  20.Ng5  ∞   17...fxe5  18.fxe5  +-  18.Bh4  fxe5  19.fxe5  Be7  20.Qxg7  Despite being two pieces down White has full compensation here, as Blacks king and other pieces are blocked in. White has many threats and is going to regain material.  17...Kxg6  Black is winning now, however he lost in 23 moves. }
