1. b3
{ Correct; in such positions this is the thematic break, which should be memorised. }
1... b5
{ 16...cxb3  17.Qxb3  gives White a clear advantage, due to the weakness of Black's b-pawn.  It was better to play }
2. bxc4 { 17.axb5 ?! =  Drawn in 51 moves,  (see Game 12)  . } 2... bxc4 3. Rb1
{ and White is better, owing to his control of the b-file, especially since his bishop on f4 prevents the black rooks from going to b8 to contest the b-file. To add to Black's woes, he has no lightsquared bishop to prevent White from putting a rook on b1; the other white rook can go to e1 and support e4, which will undermine Blacks pawn on c4. }
*

