1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nd2 Be7 5. Bd3 O-O 6. Ngf3 c5 7. c3 b6 8. Ne5
Bb7 9. Qf3 Nc6 10. Qh3 g6
{ 10...h6  11.Nxc6 !?  Bxc6  12.g4  Ne4  13.f3  Nxd2  14.Kxd2  cxd4  15.Bxh6  dxc3+  16.bxc3  g6  17.Bxf8  Qxf8  ∞ }
11. Bh6 Re8 12. f4 { And here we have reached a familiar position. } 12... Nd7
{ 12...Nxe5  13.fxe5  Ne4   13...Nd7  seems more tenacious for Black, although equally inadequate  14.Bxe4  dxe4  15.O-O  Bg5  16.Bxg5  Qxg5  17.Rxf7  and White wins. }
13. O-O f5 14. Ndf3 Ncxe5 { 14...Nf6 ?  15.Ng5 } 15. fxe5
{ A Stonewall with White's queens bishop outside the pawn chain. Blacks well-known counter-Stonewall  (f7-f5)  confronts White with the necessity of attacking by advancing with his g-pawn  (g2-g4)  at an opportune moment.. }
15... Bf8
{ Defensive needs force Black to make this exchange, but now he is left with his bad bishop, while White still has his good bishop. }
16. Ng5 Bxh6 17. Qxh6 Nf8
{ The defence of his delicate position requires accuracy on the part of the English master Penrose. After   17...Qe7  White would immediately execute the thematic advance  18.g4 !  with a strong attack that Black cannot repel with  Qg7 ?  because of  19.Qxg7+  Kxg7  20.Bb5  Rad8  21.gxf5  gxf5  22.Nh3  with a decisive positional advantage to White. }
18. Rf3 Re7 { 18...Qe7  was a better defence. } 19. g4
{ The standard advance. Grandmaster Vlastimil Hort had no doubts about evaluating White's attack as decisive from this point on }
19... Rg7 20. Raf1 Qd7 21. Kh1 Qe7 22. h4 Bc8
{ 22...a6 ?!  23.gxf5  exf5  24.Bxf5 !  gxf5  25.Rxf5  followed by Rf7, wins. }
23. Rg3 a5 24. Rfg1 Ra7 25. Nh3 Qd8 26. Nf4 c4 27. Be2 Raf7 28. gxf5 exf5 29.
Bf3 { Not   29.Nh5 ?  Qxh4+ } 29... Be6 30. Qg5 Qxg5 { 30...Qd7  31.h5 } 31.
Rxg5 Rd7 32. h5 Kf7 { 32...h6  33.Rxg6 } 33. R1g2 Ke8 34. hxg6 hxg6 35. Kg1 Kd8
36. Bh5 Rh7 37. Bxg6 Rh3 38. Nxh3
{ Black resigned. This game was published in Chess Informant 7/102, annotated by GM Vlastimil Hort. }
